{"title_page": "Campaign for Homosexual Equality", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2015}}\n{{Infobox non-profit\n| name = Campaign for Homosexual Equality\n| image = File:CHE logo.png\n| caption = CHE logo\n| type =\n| tax_id =\n| registration_id =\n| founded_date = 1969 \n| founder = Allan Horsfall and Colin Harvey\n| location = [[London]], [[United Kingdom]]\n| coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LON|display=inline,title}} -->\n| origins = [[Homosexual Law Reform Society]]\n| key_people =\n| area_served =\n| services =\n| focus =\n| mission =\n| revenue =\n| expenses =\n| endowment =\n| num_volunteers =\n| num_employees =\n| num_members =\n| affiliations =\n| subsid =\n| motto =\n| formerly = Committee for Homosexual Equality\n| website = {{URL|www.c-h-e.org.uk}}\n}} \nThe '''Campaign for Homosexual Equality''' ('''CHE''') was a membership organisation in the United Kingdom with a stated aim from 1969 to promote legal and social equality for lesbians, gay men and bisexuals in England and Wales, active in the mid 1970s when it became involved in controversy by campaigning for an age of consent of 12 and support of a pro-paedophile group, its membership was horrified at the association and significant numbers left.<ref name=\"BBC_PIE\">{{cite web |last1=de Castella |first1=Tom |title=How did the pro-paedophile group PIE exist openly for 10 years? |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-26352378 |website=BBC |publisher=BBC |accessdate=23 September 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"dango1\">{{cite web |title=DANGO RECORDS |url=http://www.dango.bham.ac.uk/record_details.asp?id=863&recordType=ngo |website=Database of Archives of Non-Government Organisations (DANGO) |publisher=University of Birmingham |accessdate=13 June 2019}}</ref> It is no longer active.<ref name=CHEhome>{{cite web|url=http://www.c-h-e.org.uk/ |title=Campaign for Homosexual Equality |publisher=Campaign for Homosexual Equality |date=22 February 2015 |accessdate=25 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Swarthmore Centre Rainbow Plaque.jpg|thumb|right|One of fifteen sponsored memorials on Leeds Rainbow Plaque Trail, in aid of [[Leeds Pride]], commemorating the Swarthmore Centre as safe space in 1971 where the group met.<ref name=\"leeds\">{{cite web |title=Rainbow Plaque Trail |url=https://leedscivictrust.org.uk/whatwedo/heritage/blue-plaques/leeds-rainbow-plaques/ |website=[[Leeds Civic Trust]] |accessdate=29 September 2019}}</ref>]]\n\nIn 1969 the Committee for Homosexual Equality (CHE) was formed with aims to becoming a national body for England and Wales, meeting at the Swarthmoor Centre in Leeds in 1971<ref name=leeds/> and later in the same year changed its name to the Campaign for Homosexual Equality (CHE).<ref>{{cite news | title=An alternative to sexual shame: Impact of the new militancy among homosexual groups | work=The Times | date=28 August 1971 | last=Brittain | first=Victoria | location=London | page=12}}</ref> [[London Friend]] was set up in London in 1972 intended to provide counselling.<ref name=\"FriendAwards\">{{cite news |last1=Duffy |first1=Nick |title=London LGBT charity honoured with Queen\u2019s Award for Voluntary Service |url=https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2016/06/02/london-lgbt-charity-honoured-with-queens-award-for-voluntary-service/ |accessdate=15 June 2019 |agency=Pink News |publisher=Pink News |date=2 June 2016 |ref=FriendAwards}}</ref> In 1972, CHE members took part in the first London Pride at Hyde Park, followed by a march to Trafalgar Square, nominally to protest at the [[age of consent reform|age of consent]], then age 21.<ref name=1RAL2>{{cite web | title= History of lesbian, gay and bisexual equality\n|url= http://www.stonewall.org.uk/at_home/history_of_lesbian_gay_and_bisexual_equality/default.asp | work= | publisher= Stonewall | year= 2009 | accessdate=7 May 2009}}</ref> by 1973 it held the first national gay rights conference in [[Morecambe]].<ref>{{cite news | title=Homosexuals seek revision of discriminatory laws | work=The Times | date=9 April 1973 | last=Chartres | first=John | location=London | page=2}}</ref> CHE was, in this period, claiming 5,000 members and some 100 local groups.<ref name=isbn0704331756>{{cite book| author = Weeks, Jeffrey| title = Coming out: homosexual politics in Britain, from the nineteenth century to the present| url = https://archive.org/details/comingouthomosex00week| url-access = registration| publisher = Quartet Books| location = London| year = 1977| isbn = 0-7043-3175-6|page=[https://archive.org/details/comingouthomosex00week/page/210 210]}}</ref> \n\nIn 1974, CHE appeared alongside London Friend in a documentary titled ''Speak for Yourself'' produced by [[London Weekend Television|London weekend Television]], at which time the organisations offices were in at 22 Great Windmill Street, London and Friend at 47 Church St, London NW8. The organisations were working closely together through social events, CHE at the time had 4000 members and was involved in campaigns and politics whereas Friend was a counselling service.<ref name=\"bfi74\">{{cite web |title=Speak for yourself, Gay's The Word |url=https://player.bfi.org.uk/free/film/watch-homosexual-equality-1974-online |website=British Film Institute |publisher=London Weekend TV 1974 |accessdate=15 June 2019}}</ref> It organised a national Homosexual Equality Rally in London.<ref name=2RAL1>Addison, Paul, & Jones, Harriet. (2008). ''A Companion to Contemporary Britain, 1939-2000''. Chichester: John Wiley & Sons. p.394. {{ISBN|0-470-99619-6}}</ref> The rally was supported by the women's movement and people from ethnic minorities.<ref name=\"hunt et al\">Hunt, Lynn; Thomas R. Martin; et al. (2008). ''The Making of the West: Peoples and Cultures, Vol. C Since 1740''. Boston: Bedford/St. Martin's.</ref> Where earlier actions had concentrated on legal protection from criminal persecution, this rally was part of gay and lesbian people starting to establish a distinct sexual identity.<ref name=\"hunt et al\"/> Those who turned out for the rally did so to support the extension of constitutional rights and universal values to lesbian and gay people.<ref name=\"hunt et al\"/> CHE and London Friend shared offices and had close links until 1974,<ref name=bfi74/> it was separated from CHE in 1975.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.c-h-e.org.uk/history.shtml |title=The history of CHE |publisher=c-h-e.org.uk |date=10 October 2014|accessdate=25 March 2015}}</ref> Membership numbers fell away from 1977 as the group leadership supported a paedophile organisation and proposed an age of consent of 12.<ref name=BBC_PIE/>At a fringe meeting of the organisation held in Coventry in 1978 a new separate international organisation was formed, named [[International_Lesbian,_Gay,_Bisexual,_Trans_and_Intersex_Association|ILGA]].<ref name=\"ILGA1\">{{cite web |last1=Paternotte |first1=David |title=The history of ILGA: 1978/2012 |url=https://ilga.org/ilga-history |website=ILGA |publisher=ILGA |accessdate=16 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, the organisation received a substantial bequest from a former member, Derek Oyston of Gateshead.<ref>Ross Burgess. [http://www.c-h-e.org.uk/derek-oyston.shtml \"CHE > Derek Oyston\"]. ''c-h-e.org.uk''. Retrieved 21 October 2015.</ref> In early 2009 the organisation were campaigning to prevent cases of historic child sex abuse being prosecuted if raised more than five years after the young person gained [[age of majority]].<ref name=\"5yr_limit\">{{cite news |last1=Green |first1=Jessica |title=Campaign for Homosexual Equality disaffiliated from Liberty |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604091957/http://www.pinknews.co.uk/news/articles/2005-13280.html |accessdate=23 September 2019 |agency=PinkNews |publisher=WayBackMachine |date=2009}}</ref>\n\n[[Chris Smith, Baron Smith of Finsbury|Lord Smith of Finsbury]] became a vice-president of the in February 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.c-h-e.org.uk/news.shtml|title=CHE > In the news|website=www.c-h-e.org.uk}}</ref> In 2010 the organisation commissioned a book titled Amiable Warriors: A Space to Breathe, 1954 - 1973, by Peter Scott-Presland to write their own account of the organisations history.<ref>''Amiable Warriors'' Volume One, Chapter 2; [http://www.amiable-warriors.uk/ \"Celebration of the life of Allan Horsfall\"], ''Campaign for Homosexual Equality''.</ref> \n\nThe organisation received the 2014 Alan Turing Memorial Award as part of the Homo Heroes Awards ceremony organised by the [[Lesbian and Gay Foundation]].<ref>[http://www.mancunianmatters.co.uk/content/081071040-i-need-homo-hero-manchesters-lgbt-stars-honoured-awards \"I need a (Homo) Hero! Manchester's LGBT stars honoured in awards\"]. ''mancunianmatters.co.uk''. Retrieved 21 October 2015.</ref> From 2015 the organisation has stated on its page that it \"no longer has the resources to offer assistance to individuals experiencing discrimination, whether in the UK or elsewhere.\"<ref name=CHEhome/>\n\n==Controversies==\nIn May 1974, CHE suggested an age of consent of 12.<ref>Waites, Matthew (2005, op.cit., pp. 132 and 243, Note 6.6)</ref><ref>Gay News, no. 46, 9 May 1974, p.3 \u2013 'CHE Report angers reformers'.</ref>\n\nIn 1975, CHE's conference support for the [[freedom of speech]] of the pro-paedophile group [[Paedophile Information Exchange]] caused controversy in the media, with accusations of support for paedophilia in the press.<ref name=BBC_PIE/><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://spotlightonabuse.files.wordpress.com/2013/03/g26875.jpg |title=Child-lovers win fight for role in Gay Lib |date=26 August 1975 |newspaper=The Guardian |location=London |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6cQUV2eKD?url=https://spotlightonabuse.files.wordpress.com/2013/03/g26875.jpg |archivedate=20 October 2015 |df=dmy }}</ref> In 1976, CHE wanted to hold its annual conference at Scarborough but was turned down by the Council. In 1977 CHE approached Llandudno but was once again turned away and at its Nottingham conference that year again passed a further motion supporting the Paedophile Information Exchange.<ref>{{Cite news |title= Britain's Apologists For Child Abuse |url= https://web.archive.org/web/20170912151710/http://standpointmag.co.uk/node/6193/full |work= Standpoint |accessdate= 12 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=Paedophile talks backed by homosexuals |date=30 August 1977 |newspaper=The Times |location=London |url=https://spotlightonabuse.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/paedotalks.jpg |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6ciXLICuc?url=https://spotlightonabuse.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/paedotalks.jpg |archivedate=1 November 2015 |df=dmy }}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title = Lost Freedom: The Landscape of the Child and the British Post-War Settlement|url = https://books.google.com/books?id=e8doAgAAQBAJ |publisher=OUP |date=28 November 2013 |isbn = 9780191665097 |first= Mathew |last= Thomson}}</ref> CHE continued its campaign in support of the Paedophile groups chairman [[Tom O'Carroll]]'s who had been removed from his post at the [[Open University]].\n\nIn April 2009, [[Liberty (pressure group)|Liberty]] terminated CHE's affiliation over concerns \u201cIn particular, your motion on child sex abuse is also clearly contrary to the objectives of Liberty, as listed in Article 2 of Liberty\u2019s constitution.\u201d other concerns were regarding the nature and size of the CHE membership, governance structures, constitution, electoral process, policy-making process, financial transparency, recent issues and commitment to the objectives of Liberty\".<ref name=\"LIBERTY\">{{cite news |url= http://www.pinknews.co.uk/news/articles/2005-13280.html |title= Campaign for Homosexual Equality disaffiliated from Liberty |work=Pink News |date=16 July 2009 |accessdate=30 January 2011 |last=Green |first=Jessica}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|LGBT}}\n* [[LGBT rights in the United Kingdom]]\n* [[List of LGBT rights organizations]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.c-h-e.org.uk/ CHE official web site]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080611051323/http://www.manchester.gov.uk/site/scripts/documents_info.php?documentID=398 History of Gay Rights campaigning in Manchester]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080509155319/http://www.gaymonitor.co.uk/chehistory1.htm Unofficial history of CHE] by Ray Gosling\n* [http://archives.lse.ac.uk/TreeBrowse.aspx?src=CalmView.Catalog&field=RefNo&key=HCA%2FCHE Catalogue of the papers of the Campaign for Homosexual Equality] at the [https://web.archive.org/web/20070618035533/http://www.lse.ac.uk/library/archive/Default.htm Archives Division] of the [[London School of Economics]]\n* [http://archivecat.lancashire.gov.uk/calmview/Record.aspx?src=Catalog&id=DDX+3085 Archive catalogue of the Lancaster and Morecambe CHE Branch]\n{{LGBT topics in the United Kingdom}}\n{{LGBT|state=collapsed|rights=expanded}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Campaign For Homosexual Equality}}\n[[Category:LGBT history in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:LGBT political advocacy groups in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:1964 establishments in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 1964]]\n[[Category:Political organisations based in London]]\n[[Category:Pedophile activism]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2015}}\n{{Infobox non-profit\n| name = Campaign for Homosexual Equality\n| image = File:CHE logo.png\n| caption = CHE logo\n| type =\n| tax_id =\n| registration_id =\n| founded_date = 1969 \n| founder = Allan Horsfall and Colin Harvey\n| location = [[London]], [[United Kingdom]]\n| coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LON|display=inline,title}} -->\n| origins = [[Homosexual Law Reform Society]]\n| key_people =\n| area_served =\n| services =\n| focus =\n| mission =\n| revenue =\n| expenses =\n| endowment =\n| num_volunteers =\n| num_employees =\n| num_members =\n| affiliations =\n| subsid =\n| motto =\n| formerly = Committee for Homosexual Equality\n| website = {{URL|www.c-h-e.org.uk}}\n}} \nThe '''Campaign for Homosexual Equality''' ('''CHE''') was a membership organisation in the United Kingdom with a stated aim from 1969 to promote legal and social equality for lesbians, gay men and bisexuals in England and Wales, active in the mid 1970s when it became involved in controversy by campaigning for an age of consent of 12 and support of a pro-paedophile group, its membership was horrified at the association and significant numbers left.<ref name=\"BBC_PIE\">{{cite web |last1=de Castella |first1=Tom |title=How did the pro-paedophile group PIE exist openly for 10 years? |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-26352378 |website=BBC |publisher=BBC |accessdate=23 September 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"dango1\">{{cite web |title=DANGO RECORDS |url=http://www.dango.bham.ac.uk/record_details.asp?id=863&recordType=ngo |website=Database of Archives of Non-Government Organisations (DANGO) |publisher=University of Birmingham |accessdate=13 June 2019}}</ref> It is no longer active.<ref name=CHEhome>{{cite web|url=http://www.c-h-e.org.uk/ |title=Campaign for Homosexual Equality |publisher=Campaign for Homosexual Equality |date=22 February 2015 |accessdate=25 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Swarthmore Centre Rainbow Plaque.jpg|thumb|right|One of fifteen sponsored memorials on Leeds Rainbow Plaque Trail, in aid of [[Leeds Pride]], commemorating the Swarthmore Centre as safe space in 1971 where the group met.<ref name=\"leeds\">{{cite web |title=Rainbow Plaque Trail |url=https://leedscivictrust.org.uk/whatwedo/heritage/blue-plaques/leeds-rainbow-plaques/ |website=Leeds Civic Trust |publisher=Leeds Civil trust |accessdate=29 September 2019}}</ref>]]\n\nIn 1969 the Committee for Homosexual Equality (CHE) was formed with aims to becoming a national body for England and Wales, meeting at the Swarthmoor Centre in Leeds in 1971<ref name=leeds/> and later in the same year changed its name to the Campaign for Homosexual Equality (CHE).<ref>{{cite news | title=An alternative to sexual shame: Impact of the new militancy among homosexual groups | work=The Times | date=28 August 1971 | last=Brittain | first=Victoria | location=London | page=12}}</ref> [[London Friend]] was set up in London in 1972 intended to provide counselling.<ref name=\"FriendAwards\">{{cite news |last1=Duffy |first1=Nick |title=London LGBT charity honoured with Queen\u2019s Award for Voluntary Service |url=https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2016/06/02/london-lgbt-charity-honoured-with-queens-award-for-voluntary-service/ |accessdate=15 June 2019 |agency=Pink News |publisher=Pink News |date=2 June 2016 |ref=FriendAwards}}</ref> In 1972, CHE members took part in the first London Pride at Hyde Park, followed by a march to Trafalgar Square, nominally to protest at the [[age of consent reform|age of consent]], then age 21.<ref name=1RAL2>{{cite web | title= History of lesbian, gay and bisexual equality\n|url= http://www.stonewall.org.uk/at_home/history_of_lesbian_gay_and_bisexual_equality/default.asp | work= | publisher= Stonewall | year= 2009 | accessdate=7 May 2009}}</ref> by 1973 it held the first national gay rights conference in [[Morecambe]].<ref>{{cite news | title=Homosexuals seek revision of discriminatory laws | work=The Times | date=9 April 1973 | last=Chartres | first=John | location=London | page=2}}</ref> CHE was, in this period, claiming 5,000 members and some 100 local groups.<ref name=isbn0704331756>{{cite book| author = Weeks, Jeffrey| title = Coming out: homosexual politics in Britain, from the nineteenth century to the present| url = https://archive.org/details/comingouthomosex00week| url-access = registration| publisher = Quartet Books| location = London| year = 1977| isbn = 0-7043-3175-6|page=[https://archive.org/details/comingouthomosex00week/page/210 210]}}</ref> \n\nIn 1974, CHE appeared alongside London Friend in a documentary titled ''Speak for Yourself'' produced by [[London Weekend Television|London weekend Television]], at which time the organisations offices were in at 22 Great Windmill Street, London and Friend at 47 Church St, London NW8. The organisations were working closely together through social events, CHE at the time had 4000 members and was involved in campaigns and politics whereas Friend was a counselling service.<ref name=\"bfi74\">{{cite web |title=Speak for yourself, Gay's The Word |url=https://player.bfi.org.uk/free/film/watch-homosexual-equality-1974-online |website=British Film Institute |publisher=London Weekend TV 1974 |accessdate=15 June 2019}}</ref> It organised a national Homosexual Equality Rally in London.<ref name=2RAL1>Addison, Paul, & Jones, Harriet. (2008). ''A Companion to Contemporary Britain, 1939-2000''. Chichester: John Wiley & Sons. p.394. {{ISBN|0-470-99619-6}}</ref> The rally was supported by the women's movement and people from ethnic minorities.<ref name=\"hunt et al\">Hunt, Lynn; Thomas R. Martin; et al. (2008). ''The Making of the West: Peoples and Cultures, Vol. C Since 1740''. Boston: Bedford/St. Martin's.</ref> Where earlier actions had concentrated on legal protection from criminal persecution, this rally was part of gay and lesbian people starting to establish a distinct sexual identity.<ref name=\"hunt et al\"/> Those who turned out for the rally did so to support the extension of constitutional rights and universal values to lesbian and gay people.<ref name=\"hunt et al\"/> CHE and London Friend shared offices and had close links until 1974,<ref name=bfi74/> it was separated from CHE in 1975.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.c-h-e.org.uk/history.shtml |title=The history of CHE |publisher=c-h-e.org.uk |date=10 October 2014|accessdate=25 March 2015}}</ref> Membership numbers fell away from 1977 as the group leadership supported a paedophile organisation and proposed an age of consent of 12.<ref name=BBC_PIE/>At a fringe meeting of the organisation held in Coventry in 1978 a new separate international organisation was formed, named [[International_Lesbian,_Gay,_Bisexual,_Trans_and_Intersex_Association|ILGA]].<ref name=\"ILGA1\">{{cite web |last1=Paternotte |first1=David |title=The history of ILGA: 1978/2012 |url=https://ilga.org/ilga-history |website=ILGA |publisher=ILGA |accessdate=16 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, the organisation received a substantial bequest from a former member, Derek Oyston of Gateshead.<ref>Ross Burgess. [http://www.c-h-e.org.uk/derek-oyston.shtml \"CHE > Derek Oyston\"]. ''c-h-e.org.uk''. Retrieved 21 October 2015.</ref> In early 2009 the organisation were campaigning to prevent cases of historic child sex abuse being prosecuted if raised more than five years after the young person gained [[age of majority]].<ref name=\"5yr_limit\">{{cite news |last1=Green |first1=Jessica |title=Campaign for Homosexual Equality disaffiliated from Liberty |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604091957/http://www.pinknews.co.uk/news/articles/2005-13280.html |accessdate=23 September 2019 |agency=PinkNews |publisher=WayBackMachine |date=2009}}</ref>\n\n[[Chris Smith, Baron Smith of Finsbury|Lord Smith of Finsbury]] became a vice-president of the in February 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.c-h-e.org.uk/news.shtml|title=CHE > In the news|website=www.c-h-e.org.uk}}</ref> In 2010 the organisation commissioned a book titled Amiable Warriors: A Space to Breathe, 1954 - 1973, by Peter Scott-Presland to write their own account of the organisations history.<ref>''Amiable Warriors'' Volume One, Chapter 2; [http://www.amiable-warriors.uk/ \"Celebration of the life of Allan Horsfall\"], ''Campaign for Homosexual Equality''.</ref> \n\nThe organisation received the 2014 Alan Turing Memorial Award as part of the Homo Heroes Awards ceremony organised by the [[Lesbian and Gay Foundation]].<ref>[http://www.mancunianmatters.co.uk/content/081071040-i-need-homo-hero-manchesters-lgbt-stars-honoured-awards \"I need a (Homo) Hero! Manchester's LGBT stars honoured in awards\"]. ''mancunianmatters.co.uk''. Retrieved 21 October 2015.</ref> From 2015 the organisation has stated on its page that it \"no longer has the resources to offer assistance to individuals experiencing discrimination, whether in the UK or elsewhere.\"<ref name=CHEhome/>\n\n==Controversies==\nIn May 1974, CHE suggested an age of consent of 12.<ref>Waites, Matthew (2005, op.cit., pp. 132 and 243, Note 6.6)</ref><ref>Gay News, no. 46, 9 May 1974, p.3 \u2013 'CHE Report angers reformers'.</ref>\n\nIn 1975, CHE's conference support for the [[freedom of speech]] of the pro-paedophile group [[Paedophile Information Exchange]] caused controversy in the media, with accusations of support for paedophilia in the press.<ref name=BBC_PIE/><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://spotlightonabuse.files.wordpress.com/2013/03/g26875.jpg |title=Child-lovers win fight for role in Gay Lib |date=26 August 1975 |newspaper=The Guardian |location=London |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6cQUV2eKD?url=https://spotlightonabuse.files.wordpress.com/2013/03/g26875.jpg |archivedate=20 October 2015 |df=dmy }}</ref> In 1976, CHE wanted to hold its annual conference at Scarborough but was turned down by the Council. In 1977 CHE approached Llandudno but was once again turned away and at its Nottingham conference that year again passed a further motion supporting the Paedophile Information Exchange.<ref>{{Cite news |title= Britain's Apologists For Child Abuse |url= https://web.archive.org/web/20170912151710/http://standpointmag.co.uk/node/6193/full |work= Standpoint |accessdate= 12 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=Paedophile talks backed by homosexuals |date=30 August 1977 |newspaper=The Times |location=London |url=https://spotlightonabuse.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/paedotalks.jpg |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6ciXLICuc?url=https://spotlightonabuse.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/paedotalks.jpg |archivedate=1 November 2015 |df=dmy }}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title = Lost Freedom: The Landscape of the Child and the British Post-War Settlement|url = https://books.google.com/books?id=e8doAgAAQBAJ |publisher=OUP |date=28 November 2013 |isbn = 9780191665097 |first= Mathew |last= Thomson}}</ref> CHE continued its campaign in support of the Paedophile groups chairman [[Tom O'Carroll]]'s who had been removed from his post at the [[Open University]].\n\nIn April 2009, [[Liberty (pressure group)|Liberty]] terminated CHE's affiliation over concerns \u201cIn particular, your motion on child sex abuse is also clearly contrary to the objectives of Liberty, as listed in Article 2 of Liberty\u2019s constitution.\u201d other concerns were regarding the nature and size of the CHE membership, governance structures, constitution, electoral process, policy-making process, financial transparency, recent issues and commitment to the objectives of Liberty\".<ref name=\"LIBERTY\">{{cite news |url= http://www.pinknews.co.uk/news/articles/2005-13280.html |title= Campaign for Homosexual Equality disaffiliated from Liberty |work=Pink News |date=16 July 2009 |accessdate=30 January 2011 |last=Green |first=Jessica}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|LGBT}}\n* [[LGBT rights in the United Kingdom]]\n* [[List of LGBT rights organizations]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.c-h-e.org.uk/ CHE official web site]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080611051323/http://www.manchester.gov.uk/site/scripts/documents_info.php?documentID=398 History of Gay Rights campaigning in Manchester]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080509155319/http://www.gaymonitor.co.uk/chehistory1.htm Unofficial history of CHE] by Ray Gosling\n* [http://archives.lse.ac.uk/TreeBrowse.aspx?src=CalmView.Catalog&field=RefNo&key=HCA%2FCHE Catalogue of the papers of the Campaign for Homosexual Equality] at the [https://web.archive.org/web/20070618035533/http://www.lse.ac.uk/library/archive/Default.htm Archives Division] of the [[London School of Economics]]\n* [http://archivecat.lancashire.gov.uk/calmview/Record.aspx?src=Catalog&id=DDX+3085 Archive catalogue of the Lancaster and Morecambe CHE Branch]\n{{LGBT topics in the United Kingdom}}\n{{LGBT|state=collapsed|rights=expanded}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Campaign For Homosexual Equality}}\n[[Category:LGBT history in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:LGBT political advocacy groups in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:1964 establishments in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 1964]]\n[[Category:Political organisations based in London]]\n[[Category:Pedophile activism]]\n", "name_user": "Rcsprinter123", "label": "safe", "comment": "link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Campaign_for_Homosexual_Equality"}
{"title_page": "Matsya", "text_new": "{{short description|fish form of the Hindu god Vishnu}}\n{{other uses}}\n{{EngvarB|date=March 2017}} \n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2017}}\n{{Infobox deity<!--Wikipedia:WikiProject Hindu mythology-->\n| type        = Hindu\n| image       = Matsya avatar.jpg\n| caption     = Half-human and Half-Fish depiction of [[Vishnu]]\n| name        = Matsya\n| Devanagari  = \u092e\u0924\u094d\u0938\u094d\u092f\n| affiliation = [[Vishnu]] (first [[avatar]]) \n| weapon      = None\n| abode = [[Kuru Kingdom]], [[Patala]]\n| mantra  = 'I shall invoke god Matsya moving in the sea. O Matsya Deva, the sustainer of the lives of the world, O infallible, kindly come' ([[Vishnudharmottara Purana]], Adhyaya 106)\n| consort = None \n| god_of= \n| children= None\n| symbols= Three dots (e.g. on a long, crystalline-coloured [[salagrama]])\n| festivals = Matsya Jayanti: Pancami (fifth day) in the bright half of the month of [[Chaitra]]\n}}\n{{Vaishnavism}}\n{{Hindu scriptures and texts}}\n'''Matsya''' ({{lang-sa|\u092e\u0924\u094d\u0938\u094d\u092f}}, lit. ''fish'')<!--Do not remove, WP:INDICSCRIPT doesn't apply to WikiProject Hinduism--> is an [[avatar]] of the [[Rigvedic deities|RigVedic]] god [[Vishnu]]. Originating in the White [[Yajurveda|YajurVeda]] ([[Shatapatha Brahmana]]), Matsya is most commonly associated in post-Vedic literature such as the [[Puranas]] with the legends of rescuing [[Shraddhadeva Manu|Vaivasvata Manu]] from the [[Flood myth|deluge]], and rescuing the [[Vedas]] stolen by various [[Asura|Asuras]]. Matsya is listed as the first incarnation of the [[Dashavatara]], the ten principal avatars of Vishnu. \n\nMatsya iconography sometimes is [[Zoomorphism|zoomorphic]] as a giant fish with a horn, or [[Anthropomorphism|anthropomorphic]] in the form of a human torso connected to the rear half of a fish.<ref>Rao p. 127</ref>{{sfn|Bonnefoy|1993|pp=79-80}}\n\n==Etymology==\n'Mastya' is derived from 'matsa' (\u092e\u0924\u094d\u0938) meaning 'Fish',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://spokensanskrit.org/index.php?mode=3&script=hk&tran_input=matsa&direct=au&anz=100|title=Sanskrit Dictionary for Spoken Sanskrit: 'matsa'|last=|first=|date=|website=spokensanskrit.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-05}}</ref> itself derived from the root 'mad' (or 'mat', \u092e\u0924), meaning 'religion', 'counsel', 'knowledge', and 'religious doctrine'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://spokensanskrit.org/index.php?tran_input=mATha&direct=se&script=hk&link=yes&mode=3|title=Sanskrit Dictionary for Spoken Sanskrit|website=spokensanskrit.org|access-date=2020-01-05}}</ref>  The term 'Matsya' also appears in the ''[[Rigveda]]''.<ref name=mmwmatsya/> It is related to ''maccha'', which also means fish.<ref name=mmwmatsya>Monier Monier-Williams, Sanskrit-English Dictionary and Etymology, Oxford University Press, pages 776-777</ref> R. Franco states that [[Etymology|etymologically]], 'Matsa' means 'gay [joyous] one' or 'Fish', and is derived from (square brackets '[ ]' as per the original author):\n\n* '''<nowiki/>'Mad'''', meaning 'to be excited by joy', 'to savor food and drink [ad] to the absolute limit of their flavour [m]', and 'to get drunk', and\n* '''<nowiki/>'sa'''', meaning 'effect of the action [a] of binding to [s]', 'union', 'with', 'similar', or 'together'..<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=KphVAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA383&lpg=PA383&dq=sanskrit+'mad'+the+gay+one#v=onepage&q=sanskrit%20'mad'%20the%20gay%20one&f=false|title=Comparative etymological Dictionary of classical Indo-European languages: Indo-European - Sanskrit - Greek - Latin|last=Franco|first=Rendich|date=2013-12-14|publisher=Rendich Franco|isbn=|location=|pages=383, 555\u2013556|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe Monier-Williams [[Sanskrit]] Dictionary agrees with Franco.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sanskritdictionary.com/?q=matsya%22&lang=sans&iencoding=iast&action=Search|title=Sanskrit Dictionary:'Matsya'|last=|first=|date=|website=sanskritdictionary.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sanskritdictionary.com/?q=matsa&iencoding=iast&lang=sans|title=Sanskrit Dictionary: 'matsa'|last=|first=|date=|website=sanskritdictionary.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-05}}</ref> According to the [[Nirukta]], an ancient ancillary text to the [[Vedas]]:\n\n{{quote|O [[\u00c2dityas|Adityas]]. run to us while we are still alive, i.e. before we are slain; where are you, the hearers of our invocations? It is known to be the composition of the fish caught in a net. The fish are (so called because) they float in water, or they revel in eating each other. Net is (so called) because it moves in water, or it is set in water, or it lies in water.|source=The Nirukta, translated by  Lakshman Sarup (1967), Chapter 6, Section 27 (pp.108; English section)<ref name=\":16\">{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/TheNighantuAndTheNirukta|title=The Nighantu And The Nirukta|last=Lakshman Sarup|first=|date=1967|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=26, 108 (footnote 3)|language=English}}</ref>}}\n\nSarup, the [[Translation|translator]], elaborates for the above section (6.27; footnote 3), stating 'Matsyah (fish) is derived from [the root word] \u221a''syand'' (to float) and ''madhu'' (water)'. The Monier-Williams [[Sanskrit]] Dictionary does not seem to agree however, as although 'madhu' does mean 'water' (and [[Soma (drink)|'soma']], 'milk', and 'honey'),<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sanskritdictionary.com/?iencoding=iast&q=madhu&lang=sans&action=Search|title=Sanskrit Dictionary|last=|first=|date=|website=sanskritdictionary.com: 'madhu'|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-05}}</ref> 'syand' means 'to trickle or flow'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sanskritdictionary.com/?iencoding=iast&q=syand&lang=sans&action=Search|title=Sanskrit Dictionary: 'syand'|last=|first=|date=|website=sanskritdictionary.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-05}}</ref> The four etymological definitions of 'Matsya' are therefore:\n\n* '''Sanskrit Dictionary:''' 'religion, or religious doctrine'\n* '''Franco:''' 'Union or binding in joy or intoxication'\n* '''The Nirukta:''' 'Floating in water' \n* '''Monier-Williams (Sarup's breakdown):''' 'the trickle or flow of water, Soma, milk, or honey'\n\n=== Horn ===\nMatsya is depicted as possessing a horn (e.g. which the ship of Manu is tied to), and according to the [[Nirukta]]:\n\n{{quote|''Srnga'' (horn) is derived from (the root) ''Sri'' (to rest on), or from ''sr'' (to slay), or from sam (to destroy); or (it is so called because) it grows up to protect, or it comes out of the head.|source=The Nirukta, translated by\u00a0 Lakshman Sarup (1967), Chapter 2, Section 7 (pp. 26, English section)<ref name=\":16\" />|author=|title=}}\n\n== Symbolism ==\n\n'''Cosmogonic creation and dissolution:''' J. Roy states in the [[Rigveda|RigVeda]], water represents 'the first principle of creation [<nowiki/>[[purusha]]]... Thus, the story of deluge and the fish-god, even though of foreign [e.g. [[Enki|Babylonian]] or [[Hatmehit|Egyptian]]] origin, finds a parallel in the [[Vedas|Vedic]] and [[Puranas|Puranic]] [[Cosmogony|cosmogonic]] myth, representing the universe emerging out of waters'. In regards to dissolution, Roy adds that in 'the [[Itihasa|epic]] and [[Puranas|Puranic]] versions of the legend of [[Flood myth|deluge]], the great flood [[Allegory|allegorizes]] dissolution of the world. The Fish incarnation is thus rightly enumerated as the first incarnation, [[Allegory|allegorizing]] [[Brahma]] or [[Narayana]], who creates the world anew after dissolution'.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=lr9pFQPwhXYC&pg=PA95&lpg=PA95&dq=Atharva+Veda+varaha+boar#v=onepage&q=matsya&f=false|title=Theory of Avat\u0101ra and Divinity of Chaitanya|last=Roy|first=Janmajit|date=2002|publisher=Atlantic Publishers & Dist|isbn=978-81-269-0169-2|location=|pages=79\u201385|language=en}}</ref>\n\n'''Astronomy:''' Roy also states that it 'has been suggested that the boat of [[Shraddhadeva Manu|Manu]] and the Fish in the epico-[[Puranas|puranic]] legend [[Allegory|allegorically]] represent the [[constellation]] of [[Ursa Major]] and [[Ursa Minor|Urda Minor]] respectively. The legend is construed as pointing to a remote period of antiquity when [[Thuban|Alpha Draconis]] was the [[Pole star|Pole Star]]'.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n'''Sacrifice:''' N. Aiyangar states that in 'the Rig-veda the idea that [[Yajna|Sacrifice]] is [a] Ship is expressed in many places... As thus Sacrifice is metaphorically called Ship and as [[Manu (Hinduism)|Manu]] means man, the thinker, the story [of Matsya] seems to be a [[parable]] of the Ship of Sacrifice being the means for man's crossing the sea of his duritas, [i.e. his] sins, and troubles'. In regards to Matsya, Auyangar states that the 'Supreme self [<nowiki/>[[\u0100tman (Hinduism)|Atman]]] is found as a small fish... thus cultivated and realised [to a big fish, it] is able to conduct the Ship of Sacrifice across the sea of the Duritas of the selfish world of strife'. Ida is also stated to 'represent here the blessedness of mind-born \u015araddh\u0101, Faith'.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.217324|title=Essays On Indo Aryan Mythology|last=Narayan Aiyangar|date=1901|publisher=|isbn=|location=|pages=121\u2013124}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wisdomlib.org/definition/durita|title=Durita, Dur-ita: 6 definitions|last=www.wisdomlib.org|date=2014-08-03|website=www.wisdomlib.org|access-date=2019-12-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wisdomlib.org/definition/shraddha|title=Shraddha, \u015ar\u0101ddha, \u015araddh\u0101, \u015araddha: 21 definitions|last=www.wisdomlib.org|date=2014-09-09|website=www.wisdomlib.org|access-date=2019-12-29}}</ref>\n\n'''Deluge / Historical Fact:''' T.W. Munro states that the 'deluge, in this land [Dravida country, [[South India]]] is both [[Astronomy|astronomically]] and [[Geology|geologically]] an accomplished fact'. Munro adds that although the accounts of the deluge were considered 'a merely fanciful tissue of imagination from the brains of fanciful men', one of those incorrectly believing the deluge to be 'fanciful', [[William Jones (philologist)|Sir William Jones]], 'very properly corrected his former error' after travelling to [[India]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.123134|title=A Handbook Of Hindu Mythology And Philosophy With Some Biographical Notices|last=Taylor|first=W. Munro|date=1870|publisher=|isbn=|location=|pages=74\u201375}}</ref>\n\n== The Vedas ==\nJ. Roy states that the 'earliest reference to\u00a0the legend of the fish [Matsya] occurs in the [[Shatapatha Brahmana|Satapatha Brahmana]] [White [[Yajurveda|YajurVeda]]] though not as an incarnation of any particular deity... [and is] believed to be of [[Babylon|Babylonian]] origin by many scholars'.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Rig Veda ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! rowspan=\"3\" |[[Rigveda|Rig]]\n!\n!References\n!Notes\n|-\n|Samhita\n|'''Manu:'''  1.76.5,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/rigveda/rv01076.htm|title=Rig Veda: Rig-Veda Book 1: HYMN LXXVI. Agni.|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-08}}</ref> 7.100.4,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/rigveda/rv07100.htm|title=Rig Veda: Rig-Veda, Book 7: HYMN C. Vi\u1e63\u1e47u.|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-21}}</ref> 10.63.7,<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/rigveda/rv10063.htm|title=Rig Veda: Rig-Veda, Book 10: HYMN LXIII. Vi\u015bvedevas.|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-08}}</ref> 10.164.2;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/rigveda/rv10164.htm|title=Rig Veda: Rig-Veda, Book 10: HYMN CLXIV. Dream-charm.|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-08}}</ref> '''Ship:''' 10.44.6,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/rigveda/rv10044.htm|title=Rig Veda: Rig-Veda, Book 10: HYMN XLIV. Indra.|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-08}}</ref> 10.63.10;<ref name=\":4\" />  '''Ida/Ila:''' 1.13.9,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/rigveda/rv01013.htm|title=Rig Veda: Rig-Veda Book 1: HYMN XIII. Agni|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-08}}</ref> (teacher of men) 1.31.11,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/rigveda/rv01031.htm|title=Rig Veda: Rig-Veda Book 1: HYMN XXXI. Agni.|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-10}}</ref> 1.142.8-9,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/rigveda/rv01142.htm|title=Rig Veda: Rig-Veda Book 1: HYMN CXLII. \u0100pr\u012bs.|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-08}}</ref> 3.4.8,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/rigveda/rv03004.htm|title=Rig Veda: Rig-Veda, Book 3: HYMN IV \u0100pr\u012bs.|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-08}}</ref> 7.2.8,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/rigveda/rv07002.htm|title=Rig Veda: Rig-Veda, Book 7: HYMN II. \u0100pr\u012bs.|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-08}}</ref> (foot drops oil) 10.70.8,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/rigveda/rv10070.htm|title=Rig Veda: Rig-Veda, Book 10: HYMN LXX. \u0100pr\u012bs.|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-08}}</ref> 10.95.18<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/rigveda/rv10095.htm|title=Rig Veda: Rig-Veda, Book 10: HYMN XCV. Urvasi. Pur\u016bravas.|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-08}}</ref>, 10.110.8<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/rigveda/rv10110.htm|title=Rig Veda: Rig-Veda, Book 10: HYMN CX. \u0100pr\u012bs.|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-08}}</ref>\n|'''Ida/Ila:''' Most verses are about being invoked at [[Yajna|sacrifice]] by two [[Vedic priesthood|Hotars]]. '''Ship:''' 10.63.10 is quoted by the [[Taittiriya Samhita]].\n|-\n|[[Aitareya Brahmana]]\n|'''Manu:''' 8.2.7 '''Ship:''' 6.4.21<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.281986|title=The Aitareya Brahmanam Of The Rigveda Vol Ii|last=B D Basu|date=1899|publisher=|isbn=|location=|pages=281 (Ship), 347 (Manu)}}</ref>\n|\n|}{{Verse translation|yebhyo hotr\u0101\u1e43 pratham\u0101m\u0101yeje manu\u1e25 samiddh\u0101ghnirmanas\u0101sapta hot\u1e5bbhi\u1e25 {{!}}\nta \u0101dity\u0101 abhaya\u1e43 \u015barma yachata sugh\u0101 na\u1e25karta supath\u0101 svastaye {{!}}{{!}}...\n\n\nsutr\u0101m\u0101\u1e47a\u1e43 p\u1e5bthiv\u012b\u1e43 dy\u0101manehasa\u1e43 su\u015barm\u0101\u1e47amaditi\u1e43supra\u1e47\u012btim {{!}}\ndaiv\u012b\u1e43 n\u0101va\u1e43 svaritr\u0101man\u0101ghasamasravant\u012bm\u0101 ruhem\u0101 svastaye {{!}}{{!}}|Ye to whom Manu, by seven priests, with kindled fire, offered the first oblation with his heart and soul,\nVouchsafe us, ye \u0100dityas, shelter free from fear, and make us good and easy paths to happiness...\n\nMightily-saving Earth, incomparable Heaven the good guide [[Aditi]] who gives secure defence\nThe well-oared heavenly Ship that lets no waters in, free from defect, will we ascend for happiness.|lang=en|attr1=RigVeda [[transliteration]] of Book 10, Hymn 63, Verses 7 and 10<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/rvsan/rv10063.htm|title=RigVeda Book X LXIII 'Vi\u015bvedevas' (Sanskrit and Transliteration)|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-07}}</ref>|attr2=RigVeda [[translation]] by Ralph T.H. Griffith (1896) of Book 10, Hymn 63, Verses 7 and 10<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/rigveda/rv10063.htm|title=RigVeda Book X LXIII 'Vi\u015bvedevas'|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-07}}</ref>}}\n\nV. Mani states that the [[Manu (Hinduism)|'''Manu''']] (\u092e\u0928\u0941)<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://spokensanskrit.org/index.php?tran_input=manu&direct=se&script=hk&link=yes&mode=3|title=Sanskrit Dictionary for Spoken Sanskrit: 'Manu'|last=|first=|date=|website=spokensanskrit.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-07}}</ref> is [[Shraddhadeva Manu|Vaivasvata]] (also known as Satyavrata or Shraddhadeva), son of the sun-god [[Surya|Vivasvan]] (Surya), grandson of [[Kashyapa|Kasyapa]] and [[Aditi]], and the seventh of fourteen total Manus of the current ([[Varaha]]) [[Kalpa (aeon)|Kalpa]].<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/puranicencyclopa00maniuoft|title=Puranic encyclopaedia : a comprehensive dictionary with special reference to the epic and Puranic literature|last=Mani|first=Vettam|date=1975|publisher=Delhi : Motilal Banarsidass|others=Robarts - University of Toronto|isbn=|location=|pages=79}}</ref> M. Dhavamony states that in the [[Rigveda|RigVeda]], the most important hero 'is Manu ('man') the first man, the ancestor of the human race and the first sacrificer... He it was who, having kindled the fire, presented the first offering with seven priests [<nowiki/>[[Saptarishi]]] to the gods [RigVeda 10.3.67]... Thus manu's sacrifice becomes the prototype and exemplary model of all other sacrifices [RigVeda 1.76.5]'.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=DD0w_IMFA8gC&pg=PA114&lpg=PA114&dq=Rig+Veda+ship+manu#v=onepage&q=Rig%20Veda%20ship%20manu&f=false|title=Classical Hinduism|last=Dhavamony|first=Mariasusai|date=1982|publisher=Gregorian Biblical BookShop|isbn=978-88-7652-482-0|location=|pages=112\u2013113|language=en}}</ref>\n\nNotably, the account of Manu's first offering with the [[Saptarishi]] - seven sages - also mentions ascending in a 'well-oared heavenly ship'. The belief of Aiyangar (as above, see Symbolism section) in the metaphorical 'ship of sacrifice'<ref name=\":3\" /> is further supported by the [[Aitareya Brahmana]], an exposition of [[Yajna|sacrificial]] rites attached to the [[Rigveda|RigVeda]] (Book 6, Chapter 4, Section 21):\n\n<nowiki/>{{quote|(The repetition of these [[Tristubh|Tristubhs]] by the minor Hotri-priests is, however, necessary). He ought to know, \u201cthese Tristubhs are the helm (pratipad) of my hymns,\u201d just as (one requires a helm) if crossing the sea. For those who perform a session lasting for a year or the [[Dvadasaha]], are floating like those who cross the sea. Just as those who wish to land on the shore enter a ship having plenty of provisions, in the same manner the sacrificers should enter (i.e., begin with) these Tristubhs.'|source=Aitareya Brahmana translated by B.D. Basu (1899), Sixth Book, Chapter 4 ('The Sampata hymns. The Valakhilyas. TheDurohanam'.)|sign=}}\n\nIt is also stated that 'Over this earth with mighty step strode [[Vishnu|Vi\u1e63\u1e47u]], ready to give it for a home to Manu' (RigVeda 7.100.4). D.M. Knipe states [[Ila (Hinduism)|'''Ida''']] (\u0907\u0921\u093e)<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://spokensanskrit.org/index.php?tran_input=iDA&direct=se&script=hk&link=yes&mode=3|title=Sanskrit Dictionary for Spoken Sanskrit: 'ida'|last=|first=|date=|website=spokensanskrit.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-07}}</ref> is 'a personification of [[Yajna|sacrificial]] remnants'.<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=QedcBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA264&lpg=PA264&dq=Id%C3%A2+veda#v=onepage&q=Id%C3%A2%20veda&f=false|title=Vedic Voices: Intimate Narratives of a Living Andhra Tradition|last=Knipe|first=David M.|date=2015|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-939769-3|location=|pages=264|language=en}}</ref> J. Dowson elaborates that in 'the [[Rigveda|RigVeda]], [[Ila (Hinduism)|Ida]] is primarily food, refreshment, or a libation of milk; thence a stream of praise, personified as the goddess of speech'.<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.83638|title=Classical Dictionary Of Hindu Mythology And Religion Etc|last=John Dowson|date=1903|publisher=|isbn=|location=|pages=122}}</ref> G.M. Williams agrees, stating 'ida was a word for food or refreshment, especially milk... [and] worked metaphorically as the refreshment given to the [[Deva (Hinduism)|devas]] (gods) as praise'.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9791576071068|url-access=registration|quote=Id\u00e2.|title=Handbook of Hindu Mythology|last=Williams|first=George Mason|date=2003|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-1-57607-106-9|location=|pages=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9791576071068/page/155 155]|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the [[Monier Monier-Williams|Monier-Williams]] [[Sanskrit]] Dictionary, '''Ida''' is also [[Synonym|synonymous]] with '''Ila,''' as the daughter of Manu, as the Earth, the cow, praise (to the gods, i.e. prayer), the goddess of speech, and as the [[Yajna|sacrificial]] offering/libation 'consisting of four preparations of milk, poured into a vessel containing water, and then partially drunk by the priest and sacrificers; [Ida/Ila is also] personified in the cow, the symbol of feeding, and nourishment'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sanskritdictionary.com/?q=i%E1%B8%8D%C4%81|title=Sanskrit Dictionary: 'Ida'|last=|first=|date=|website=www.sanskritdictionary.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-08}}</ref><ref name=\":14\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sanskritdictionary.com/?q=i%E1%B8%B7%C4%81&iencoding=&lang=|title=Sanskrit Dictionary: 'Ila'|last=|first=|date=|website=www.sanskritdictionary.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-08}}</ref> Notably, Ida/Ila is also stated in the RigVeda to be the mother of King [[Pururavas]] (10.95.18),<ref name=\":10\" /> from whom the [[Pandavas]] ([[Arjuna]] and his brothers are cousins of [[Krishna]]) and [[Kauravas]] descend. In the following verse, Ida/Ila is associated with sacrifice:{{Verse translation|mandrajihv\u0101 jughurva\u1e47\u012b '''hot\u0101r\u0101''' daivy\u0101 kav\u012b <nowiki>|</nowiki>\n'''yaj\u00f1a\u1e43''' no yak\u1e63at\u0101mima\u1e43 sidhramadya divisp\u1e5b\u015bam <nowiki>||</nowiki>\n\n\u015bucirdeve\u1e63varpit\u0101 hotr\u0101 marutsu bh\u0101rat\u012b <nowiki>|</nowiki>\n'''i\u1e37\u0101''' sarasvat\u012b mah\u012b barhi\u1e25 s\u012bdantu yaj\u00f1iy\u0101\u1e25 <nowiki>||</nowiki>|May the two '''Priests''' Divine, the sage, the sweet-voiced lovers of the hymn,\nComplete this '''sacrifice''' of ours, effectual, reaching heaven to-day.\n\nLet Hotr\u0101 pure, set among Gods, amid the Maruts Bh\u0101rat\u012b, \n'''I\u1e37\u0101''', Sarasvat\u012b, Mah\u012b, rest on the grass, adorable.|lang=en|attr1=RigVeda [[transliteration]] of Book 1, Hymn 142, Verses 8-9<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/rvsan/rv01142.htm|title=RigVeda Book I CXLII '\u0100pr\u012bs' (Sanskrit and Transliteration)|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-07}}</ref>|attr2=RigVeda [[translation]] by Ralph T.H. Griffith (1896) of  Book 1, Hymn 142, Verses 8-9<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/rigveda/rv01142.htm|title=RigVeda Book I CXLII '\u0100pr\u012bs'|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-08}}</ref>}}\n\n=== Sama Veda ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" |[[Samaveda|Sama]]\n!References\n!Notes\n|-\n|'''Manu: Part 1:''' 1.1.5.10, 1.2.4.10; '''Part 2:''' 2.2.18.2, 6.1.1.4<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/sv.htm|title=Hymns of the Samaveda|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-08}}</ref> \n|1.1.5.10 means Book 1, Capter 1, Decade 5, Verse 10.\n|}\n\n=== Yajur Veda ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! rowspan=\"4\" |[[Yajurveda|Yajur]]\n! colspan=\"3\" |References\n!Notes\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |'''[[Yajurveda#Shukla Yajurveda|\u015aukla (White) Shakha]]''' \n|Vajasaneyi Samhita\n|24.21,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/wyv/wyvbk24.htm|title=White Yajur Veda: Book XXIV|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-05}}</ref> 24.21, 24.34<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/wyv/wyvbk24.htm|title=White Yajur Veda: Book XXIV|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-05}}</ref>\n|\n|-\n|[[Shatapatha Brahmana]]\n|'''Matsya:''' 1.8.1;<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/sbr/sbe12/sbe1234.htm|title=Satapatha Brahmana Part 1 (SBE12): First K\u00e2nda: I, 8, 1. Eighth Adhy\u00e2ya. First Br\u00e2hmana|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2019-12-28}}</ref> '''Ida:''' 1.7.4.19,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/sbr/sbe12/sbe1233.htm|title=Satapatha Brahmana Part 1 (SBE12): First K\u00e2nda: I, 7, 4. Fourth Br\u00e2hmana|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-06}}</ref> 1.8.1.16,<ref name=\":1\" /> '''Domestic Offering:''' 2.3.1.21;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/sbr/sbe12/sbe1248.htm|title=Satapatha Brahmana Part 1 (SBE12): Second K\u00e2nda: II, 3, 1. Third Adhy\u00e2ya. First Br\u00e2hmana|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-06}}</ref> '''King Matsya Sammada:''' 13.4.3.12,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/sbr/sbe44/sbe44104.htm|title=Satapatha Brahmana Part V (SBE44): Thirteenth K\u00e2nda: XIII, 4, 3. Third Br\u00e2hmana|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-06}}</ref> (Dhvasan Dvaitavana) 13.5.4.9<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/sbr/sbe44/sbe44109.htm|title=Satapatha Brahmana Part V (SBE44): Thirteenth K\u00e2nda: XIII, 5, 4. Fourth Br\u00e2hmana|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-06}}</ref>\n|Citations other than 1.8.1 refer to King Matsya.\n|-\n|[[Taittiriya Shakha|'''Taittiriya (Black) Shakha''']]\n|[[Taittiriya Samhita]]\n|'''Ship:''' 1.5.11.5,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/yv/yv01.htm|title=Yajur Veda Kanda I|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-07}}</ref> '''Ida:''' 1.7.1,<ref name=\":13\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/yv/yv01.htm|title=Yajur Veda Kanda I|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-06}}</ref> 2.6.7;<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/yv/yv02.htm|title=Yajur Veda Kanda II|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-06}}</ref> '''Fish:''' 2.6.6,<ref name=\":2\" /> 5.5.13<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/yv/yv05.htm|title=Yajur Veda Kanda V|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-06}}</ref>\n|1.5.11.5 quotes [[Rigveda|RigVeda]] 10.63.10\n|}\n\n==== Shukla (White) Yajurveda ====\n{{See also|Shatapatha Brahmana}}{{Quote|<poem>In the morning they brought to [[Manu (Hinduism)|Manu]] water for washing, just as now also they (are wont to) bring (water) for washing the hands. When he was washing himself, a fish came into his hands. \n\nIt spake to him the word, 'Rear me, I will save thee!' 'Wherefrom wilt thou save me?' 'A [[Flood myth|flood]] will carry away all these creatures: from that I will save thee!' 'How am I to rear thee?' \n\nIt said, 'As long as we are small, there is great destruction for us: fish devours fish. Thou wilt first keep me in a jar. When I outgrow that, thou wilt dig a pit and keep me in it. When I outgrow that, thou wilt take me down to the sea, for then I shall be beyond destruction.' \n\nIt soon became a ''ghasha'' (a large fish); for that grows largest (of all fish). Thereupon it said, 'In such and such a year that flood will come. Thou shalt then attend to me (i.e. to my advice) by preparing a ship; and when the flood has risen thou shalt enter into the ship, and I will save thee from it.'...\n\nBeing desirous of offspring, he engaged in worshipping and austerities. During this time he also performed a p\u00e2ka-sacrifice: he offered up in the waters clarified butter, sour milk, whey, and curds. Thence a woman was produced in a year: becoming quite solid she rose; clarified butter gathered in her footprint.</poem>|source=[[Shatapatha Brahmana]], translated by [[Julius Eggeling]] (1900), Kanda I, Adhyaya 8, Brahmana 1 ('The Ida'), Verses 1-4 and 7|sign=}}[[File:The fish avatara of Vishnu saves Manu during the great deluge.jpg|thumb|Matsya pulling Manu's boat|alt=|274x274px]]In this original account, Manu is approached by a small fish requesting his protection, and having reared it to become a ''ghasha'', is warned of an impending flood and instructed to build a ship. After the Earth is flooded, the ship is tied with rope to the horn of Matsya, and 'by that means he passed swiftly up to yonder northern mountain'. As the water subsides, Manu performs the p\u00e2ka-sacrifice, from which \"Ida\" emerges. \"Ida\" identifies herself as 'Manu's daughter' when approached by [[Mitra]] and [[Varuna]], and explains to Manu that 'Those offerings (of) clarified butter, sour milk, whey, and curds, which thou madest in the waters, with them thou hast begotten me. I am the blessing (benediction): make use of me at the sacrifice'. Manu does so to regenerate the human race through sacrifice.\n\nThe legend of Matsya rescuing [[Manu (Hinduism)|Manu]] from the flood, taking the ship to the summit of a mountain, and the birth of \"Ida\" from the p\u00e2ka-sacrifice - consisting of only the first 10 of 44 verses in this Brahmana - is a prelude to explain the symbolic importance of the ''ida,'' the domestic offering in the form of a sacrificial cake (including butter). In the practice of the ritual described in the remaining verses, the daughter of Manu is explicitly stated to be 'essentially the same as the Ida' to attain prosperity from a successful sacrifice in the form of cattle and offspring. Linking to academics' claims of Ida representing libations such as milk in the [[Rigveda|RigVeda]], the domestic offering is stated to be milk in the [[Shatapatha Brahmana]] (e.g. SB 2.3.1.21).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/sbr/sbe12/sbe1248.htm|title=Satapatha Brahmana Part 1 (SBE12): Second K\u00e2nda: II, 3, 1. Third Adhy\u00e2ya. First Br\u00e2hmana|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-07}}</ref> Notably, this first account of the Matsya legend also seems to link directly with the [[Rigveda|RigVeda]] (RV):\n\n* '''SB 1.8.1.7''' 'clarified butter gathered in her [Ida's] footprint' and '''RV 10.70.8''' 'May I\u1e37\u0101, she whose foot drops oil...'\n* '''SB 1.8.1.21''' 'Hither is called (I''d''\u00e2) by that (sacrifice) which is performed by the seven Hot''ri''s [priests]' and '''RV''' '''10.63.7:''' 'Ye to whom Manu, by seven priests, with kindled fire, offered the first oblation with his heart and soul...The well-oared heavenly Ship that lets no waters in, free from defect, will we ascend for happiness'.\n\nY. Bonnefoy states that 'classical India indeed speaks of the \"law of the fishes\" to designate what we could call the \"[[law of the jungle]].\" The law of the fishes is set against the order imposed by a good [[king]], an order in which the weak are protected from the strong and in which [[dharma]] rather than individual force is the organizing principle. Manu, who is in essence the legislator [e.g. [[Manusmriti|the laws of Manu]]] and the father of the traditional royal dynasties, had an obvious connection with royal power'.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=r4I-FsZCzJEC&q=jungle#v=snippet&q=jungle&f=false|title=Asian Mythologies|last=Bonnefoy|first=Yves|date=1993-05-15|publisher=University of Chicago Press|isbn=978-0-226-06456-7|location=|pages=80|language=en}}</ref> These claims are supported in texts such as the [[Ramayana]], as illustrated below.\n\nAs stated by W.J. Wilkins, Matsya in this account is not ascribed to any particular deity.<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/HinduMythologyWilkins_201801|title=Hindu Mythology|last=Wilkins|first=W.J.|publisher=|year=1882|isbn=|location=|pages=113|language=English}}</ref> Aiyangar supposes that the 'Fish that conducts the Ship seems to me to be [[Agni]], the symbol of the all-knowing and all-embracing God... The reason why this Fish is horned may be due to Agni being described as having four horns in [<nowiki/>[[Rigveda|RigVeda]] 4.58.3],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/rigveda/rv04058.htm|title=Rig Veda: Rig-Veda, Book 4: HYMN LVIII. Gh\u1e5bta.|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-13}}</ref> a verse which is repeated daily in Agni-worship.'<ref name=\":3\" /> Eggeling supposes (note 216:3 in the linked version), that in the [[Taittiriya Samhita]] (1.7.1 and 2.6.7)<ref name=\":13\" /><ref name=\":2\" /> 'i''d''\u00e2 is represented as a cow, produced by [[Mitra]] and [[Varuna|Varu''n''a]]. Perhaps it was this version and the symbolical representation of the i''d''\u00e2 as meaning cattle, which suggested the notion of a horned fish, in adapting an older legend'.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==== Krishna (Black) Yajurveda ====\n{{Verse translation|Manuh prthivya yajniyam aichat\nsa ghrtam nisiktam avindat\nso 'bravit\nko 'syesvaro yajne 'pi kartor iti\ntav abrutam mitravarunau\ngor evavam isvarau kartoh sva iti\ntau tato gam sam airayatam {{!}}\nsa yatrayatra nyakramat tato ghrtam apidyata\ntasmad ghrtapady ucyate\ntad asyai janma {{!}}|Manu desired what of earth was sacrificial. He found the poured out ghee. He said, 'Who is able to produce this also at the sacrifice?' [[Mitra]] and [[Varuna]] said, 'We are able to produce the cow.' Then they set the cow in motion. Wherever she stepped, there ghee was pressed out; therefore she is called ghee-footed; that is her origin.|lang=en|attr1=Taittiriya Samhita [[transliteration]] of Kanda I, Prapathaka VI, Chapter VII, Verse 1<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sanskritweb.net/yajurveda/ts-find.pdf|title=Taittiriya Samhita Kanda I, Prapathaka VI, Chapter VII, Verse 1 (Transliteration)|website=www.www.sanskritweb.net|access-date=2020-01-07}}</ref>|attr2=Taittiriya Samhita [[translation]] by Arthur Berriedale Keith (1914) of Kanda I, Prapathaka VI, Chapter VII, Verse 1<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/yv/yv02.htm|title=Taittiriya Samhita Kanda I, Prapathaka VI, Chapter VII, Verse 1|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-07}}</ref>}}This above-quoted verse links directly with the [[Shatapatha Brahmana]] (1.8.1.7; 'clarified butter gathered in her [Ida's] footprint') and the [[Rigveda|RigVeda]] (10.70.8; 'May I\u1e37\u0101, she whose foot drops oil...'). Macdonell adds that in the [[Taittiriya Shakha|Taittiriya Samhita]], 'Ida, or personified [[libation]], is [also] represented as a cow' (i.e. representing prosperity and producing milk).<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/vedicindexofname01macduoft|title=Vedic index of names and subjects|last=Macdonell|first=Arthur Anthony|last2=Keith|first2=Arthur Berriedale|date=1912|publisher=London, Murray|others=Robarts - University of Toronto|isbn=|location=|pages=293 (Jhasa; Eggeling's 'ghasha')}}</ref>\n{{Verse translation|imam su navam aruham sataritram '''satasphyam''' <nowiki>|</nowiki>\nachidram parayisnum <nowiki>||</nowiki>|Happily have I mounted this ship With a hundred oars and a '''hundred spars [satasphyam]''',\nWithout leak, able to convey across.|lang=en|attr1=Taittiriya Samhita [[transliteration]] of Kanda I, Prapathaka V, Chapter XI, Verse 5<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sanskritweb.net/yajurveda/ts-find.pdf|title=Taittiriya Samhita Kanda I, Prapathaka V, Chapter XI, Verse 5 (Transliteration)|website=www.www.sanskritweb.net|access-date=2020-01-07}}</ref>|attr2=Taittiriya Samhita [[translation]] by Arthur Berriedale Keith (1914) of Kanda I, Prapathaka V, Chapter XI, Verse 5<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/yv/yv01.htm|title=Taittiriya Samhita Kanda I, Prapathaka V, Chapter XI, Verse 5|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-07}}</ref>}}Although 'satasphyam' from the above-quoted verse was translated by Keith as 'a hundred [[Spar (sailing)|spars]]', Aiyangar translates it as a hundred ''sphyas'', and explains that a 'Sphya [(\u0938\u094d\u092b\u094d\u092f)] is a wooden sword used as a [[Yajna|sacrificial]] instrument'.<ref name=\":3\" /> Both interpretations are correct.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://spokensanskrit.org/index.php?mode=3&script=hk&tran_input=sphya&direct=se&anz=100|title=Sanskrit Dictionary for Spoken Sanskrit: 'sphya'|last=|first=|date=|website=spokensanskrit.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-07}}</ref> Eggeling adds that the 'sphya is a straight sword (''khadga'') or knife, a [[cubit]] long, carved out of khadira wood... It is used for various purposes calculated to symbolically insure the safe and undisturbed performance of the [[Yajna|sacrifice]]'.<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.38188|title=The Satapatha-brahmana Pt. 1|last=Eggeling|first=Julius|date=1882|publisher=|isbn=|location=|pages=13 (footnote 1)}}</ref> \n\n=== Atharva Veda ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" |[[Atharvaveda|Arharva]]\n! colspan=\"2\" |References\n!Notes\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" |39.7-8<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/sbe42/av007.htm|title=Atharva Veda: I. Charms to Cure Diseases and Possession by Demons of Disease (Bhaishagykni): XIX, 39. Prayer to the kushtha-plant to destroy takman (fever), and other ailments|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-11}}</ref>\n|The Bloomfield translation (39.7-8) is part of an [[anthology]] and is not in numeric order.\n|}\n\n{{quote|<poem>A golden ship with golden tackle moved upon the heavens. There came to sight the [[amrita]], there the kushtha-plant was born.\n\nOn the spot where the ship glided down, on the peak of the [[Himavat|Himavant]], there came to sight the ambrosia, there the kushtha-plant was born. This kushtha, a universal remedy, stands together with [[soma]]. Destroy thou every takman, and all female spooks!</poem>|source=Hymns Of The Atharva-veda, translated by [[Maurice Bloomfield]] (1897), XIX, 39. ('Prayer to the kushtha-plant to destroy takman (fever), and other ailments'), Verses 7-8|sign=}}\n\nIn this commentary to the eighth verse (or stanza) of hymn XIX, where a ship rests at the peak of a mountain, Bloomfield states it 'seems difficult to abstain from comparing with this passage certain features of the well-known legend of Manu and the flood' in the account of the [[Shatapatha Brahmana]] (as above) and the [[Mahabharata]].<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.44825|title=Hymns Of The Atharva-veda|last=Bloomfield|first=Maurice|date=1893|publisher=|isbn=|location=|pages=679}}</ref>  In regards to the Kushtha-plant mentioned, Bloomfield adds that combined with the [[Rigveda|RigVeda]] (2.33.13) which 'speaks of pure, most wholesome, and strengthening remedies which 'Father Manu' chose... it seems altogether likely that the two independent legends [i.e. the flood and discovery of the medicinal Kustha-plant] should blend here [in the [[Atharvaveda|AtharvaVeda]]] in the mind of the poet'.<ref name=\":11\" />  \n\n== Upanishads ==\n\n=== Brihadaranyaka Upanishad ===\n\n{{quote|As a large fish [maha-matsya] glides between both banks, the right and the left one, so glides the [[Purusha]] between both boundaries, the boundary of dream and the boundary of the waking state.|source=Brihadaranyaka Upanishad, translated by Eduard Roer (1856), Chapter 4, Verse 18<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/The_Brihad_aranyaka_upanishad_Sankarabhashya_English|title=The Brihadaranyaka Upanishad|last=Roer|first=Eduard|publisher=Asiatic Society of Bengal|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=226|language=english}}</ref>|sign=}}\n\n== Itih\u0101sa (Epics) ==\n\n=== Mahabharata ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" |[[Ramayana|Mahabharata]]\n!References\n!Notes\n|-\n|'''Matsya:''' Book 3: Markandeya-Samasya Parva - CLXXXVI (186);<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/m03/m03186.htm|title=The Mahabharata, Book 3: Vana Parva: Markandeya-Samasya Parva: Section CLXXXVI|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-12}}</ref> '''Ida:''' Book 2: Rajasuyika Parva - XXXIV (34);<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/m02/m02034.htm|title=The Mahabharata, Book 2: Sabha Parva: Rajasuyika Parva: Section XXXIV|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-12}}</ref>\n\n'''Ship:''' Book 3: Arjunabhigamana Parva - XXXI (31),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/m03/m03031.htm|title=The Mahabharata, Book 3: Vana Parva: Arjunabhigamana Parva: Section XXXI|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-12}}</ref> Markandeya-Samasya Parva: CCX (210)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/m03/m03210.htm|title=The Mahabharata, Book 3: Vana Parva: Markandeya-Samasya Parva: Section CCX|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-12}}</ref>\n|Translation is by [[Kisari Mohan Ganguli|K.M. Ganguli]].\n|}\n\n{{quote|<poem>...[When] the world was thus flooded, none but Manu, the [[Saptarishi|seven Rishis]] and the fish could be seen. And, [[Yudhishthira|O king]], the fish diligently dragged the boat through the flood for many a long year and then, O descendant of Kuru and ornament of Bharata's race, it towed the vessel towards the highest peak of the [[Himavat]]. And, O Bharata, the fish then told those on the vessel to tie it to the peak of the Himavat. And hearing the words of the fish they immediately tied the boat on that peak of the mountain and, O son of [[Kunti]] and ornament of Bharata's race, know that that high peak of the Himavat is still called by the name of Naubandhana (the harbour). Then the fish addressing the associated [[Rishi|Rishis]] told them these words, 'I am [[Brahma]], the Lord of all creatures; there is none greater than myself. Assuming the shape of a fish, I have saved you from this cataclysm. Manu will create (again) all beings--gods, Asuras and men, all those divisions of creation which have the power of locomotion and which have it not. By practicing severe austerities he will acquire this power, and with my blessing, illusion will have no power over him.'\n\n\"So saying the fish vanished instantly. And [[Shraddhadeva Manu|Vaivaswata]] Manu himself became desirous of creating the world. In this work of creation illusion overtook him and he, therefore, practised great asceticism. And endowed with ascetic merit, Manu, O ornament of Bharata's race, again set about his work of creating all beings in proper and exact order.</poem>|source=The Mahabharata, translated by [[Kisari Mohan Ganguli]] (1883-1896), Book 3, Markandeya-Samasya Parva - CLXXXVI (186)}}[[File:BritishMuseumMatsya.jpg|thumb|Matsya, Central India, 9th - 10th century. [[British Museum]].<ref name=\"Dallapiccola2003p19\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AEQovil-HSoC&pg=PA19|title=Hindu Myths|author=A. L. Dallapiccola|publisher=University of Texas Press|year=2003|isbn=978-0-292-70233-2|pages=19\u201320}}</ref>|alt=|200x200px]]\n\nAlthough the [[Matsya Kingdom]] of the [[Vedic period|Vedic Period]] features throughout the [[Mahabharata]], the legend of Matsya the fish occupies a single chapter, narrated by the sage [[Markandeya]] to [[Yudhishthira]] (as narrated by [[Vaisampayana]]). In this account, [[Shraddhadeva Manu|Vaivaswata]] Manu performs austerities for 10,000 years in the '[[jujube]] forest called Visala' before a small-fish, i.e. Matsya, approaches him on the banks of the Chirini river. Outgrowing a tank 'two [[Yojana|yojanas]] in length and one yojana in width', Matsya is deposited in the [[Ganges]] river before outgrowing that and being deposited in the sea, where Manu is warned 'the dissolution of all this mobile and immobile world is nigh at hand' and is instructed to 'build a strong massive ark and have it furnished with a long rope. On that must thou ascend, O great Muni, with the [[Saptarishi|seven Rishis]] and take with thee all the different [[Seed|seeds]] which were enumerated by regenerate [[Brahmin|Brahmanas]] in days of yore'. As noted by Aiyanger,<ref name=\":3\" /> [[Rigveda|RigVeda]] Hymn 10.63 (as above) states 'Manu, by seven priests, with kindled fire, offered the first oblation with his heart and soul'; in the same hymn, mention is also made of the 'well-oared heavenly Ship that lets no waters in'.   \n\nAfter the flood, a rope is used to tie the ark to the horns of Matsya (plural, not singular, as per the original account of the [[Shatapatha Brahmana]]) where it is taken to safety at the peak of the [[Himavat]]. Matsya then identifies itself as [[Brahma]] and states 'Manu will create (again) all beings--gods, ''[[Asura|Asuras]]'' and men' before disappearing. Notably, this account does not mention Ida/Ila. Other details include:  \n\n* A description of a sacrifice performed states 'The gods also were gratified at the sacrifice by the ''Ida'', clarified butter, ''Homa'' and libations poured by the great ''Rishis'' versed in ''mantras'' and pronunciation' (Book 2: Rajasuyika Parva - XXXIV)\n* [[Yudhishthira]] describes religion as 'the only raft for those desirous of going to heaven, like a ship to merchants desirous of crossing the ocean' (Book 3: Arjunabhigamana Parva - XXXI)\n* [[Markandeya]] states that 'a man's mind is overpowered by any one of these senses running wild, he loses his reason, and becomes like a ship tossed by storms upon the high ocean' (Book 3: Markandeya-Samasya Parva: CCX)\n\n=== Ramayana ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! rowspan=\"5\" |[[Ramayana]]\n! colspan=\"2\" |References\n!Notes\n|-\n|'''Valmiki version 1''' (S. Ayyangar translation)\n|'''Fish:''' Ayodhya Kanda - LXVII (67)<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/ramayanaofvalmee035120mbp/page/n701|title=Ramayana Of Valmeeki|last=Sreenivasa Ayyangar|publisher=A L V Press And Guardian Press Madras|others=BRAOU, Digital Library Of India|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=312 (verse 110)}}</ref>\n|Great fish eat small fish in a King-less land.\n|-\n|'''Valmiki version 2''' (H. P. Shastri and R.T.H. Griffith translations)\n|'''Manu:''' Book 2: Ayodhya Kanda - 110<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/The.Ramayana.of.Valmiki.by.Hari.Prasad.Shastri|title=The Ramayana of Valmiki, translated by Hari Prasad Shastri - 3 Volumes Combined - 1709 Pages, with complete Outline|last=Hari Prasad Shastri|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=393\u2013394|language=English}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/rama/ry188.htm|title=Book II: Canto CX.: The Sons of Ikshva'ku.|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-12}}</ref>\n|Father of [[Ikshvaku|Ikshv'aku]]\n|-\n|'''Adhyatma Ramayana''' (R.B.L.B Nath translation)\n|'''Matsya:''' Ayodhya Kanda - V (5.41); Yuddha Kanda - X (10.46), XV (15.58)<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/TheAdhyatmaRamayana|title=The Adhyatma Ramayana|last=Rai Bahadur Lala Baij Nath|date=1979|publisher=|isbn=|location=|pages=40, 163, 184}}</ref>\n|Stated to be an avatar of [[Rama]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" |There are [[Versions of Ramayana|multiple versions]] of the Ramayana. Many are attributed to [[Valmiki]].\n|}\nAs evidenced below, the assertion of Bonnefoy (see [[Yajurveda|YajurVeda]] section, above) that Matsya refers to the \"law of the fishes\" - equivalent to the \"law of the jungle\" - in respect to an absence of a [[monarchy]] (specifically a [[King|kingship]]) to rule a given land,<ref name=\":12\" /> is fully supported by various versions of the [[Ramayana]]. Notably, [[Shraddhadeva Manu|Manu]] in the account of Matsya is the father of [[Ikshvaku]], the first king of the [[Solar dynasty|Solar Dynasty]], of which [[Prithu]] and [[Rama]] are descendants.\n\n==== Valmiki version 1 ====\n\n{{quote|In a kingless land none dares to call anything his own. Like a fish in the ocean, the great feed upon the small and they upon the smaller and so on ''ad infinitum''. Those that were severely punished by the king for falling away from their duties of their rank and order, those who proclaim and live a godless life, this is their day of power and glory. They wreak their hoarded vengeance upon the good and the innocent; and the world will laud them to the skies as great men and holy.|source=Ramayana, translated by S. Ayyangar (1910), Ayodhya Kanda - LXVII (67)|sign=}}\n\n==== Valmiki version 2 ====\n\n{{quote|<poem>And [[Kashyapa|Ka'syap]] was [[Marichi|Mar'ichi's]] child.\nFrom him [[Surya|Vivasvat]] sprang: from him\n[[Shraddhadeva Manu|Manu]], whose fame shall ne'er be dim.\nManu, who life to mortals gave,\nBegot [[Ikshvaku|Ikshv'aku]] good and brave:\nFirst of [[Ayodhya (Ramayana)|Ayodhya]]'s kings was he,\nPride of her famous dynasty.</poem>|source=The Ramayana of Valmiki, translated by R.T.H. Griffith (1870-1874), Book 2, Ayodhya Kanda - 110|sign=}}\n\n==== Adhyatma Ramayana ====\n\n{{quote|Thou [<nowiki/>[[Rama]]] alone art know in [[\u015aruti|Srutis]] and the [[Puranas]] as appearing in the form of the fish [Matsya] and the like. In the same way all this differentiation of [[Sat (Sanskrit)|sat]] and asat (existence and non-existence) art thou. None that appears is without thee.|source=The Adhyatma Ramayana, translated by R.B.L.B. Nath (1979), Yuddha Kanda, Chapters V.17 and X.48|sign=}}\n\n== Maha-Puranas ==\nRoy states that a 'comparison of the Mahabharata account with those of the [[Matsya Purana|Matsya]] and [[Bhagavata Purana|Bhagavata Puranas]]... [makes it] clear that new elements were gradually brought into the legend and slight changes occasioned so as to [[Allegory|allegorize]] the [[Historical Vedic religion|Brahmanical]] ideas', adding that all these versions agree in ascribing a horn to Matsya, which adds a 'religious sacredness'.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Agni Purana ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" |[[Agni Purana|Agni]]\n!References\n!Notes\n|-\n|2, 46.8, 49.1, 63.7-9, 108.29-30, 167.24, 272.20b-21a, 273.7 (Ila), 370.4, 374.29-32a<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/AgniPuranaUnabridgedEnglishMotilal|title=Agni Purana Unabridged English Motilal|last=J. L. Shastri|first=G. P. Bhatt|date=1998-01-01}}</ref>\n|\n|}\n\n{{quote|<poem>\"Who are you, but [[Vishnu|Visnu]]? O [[Narayana]] (Visnu) I salute you. Why do you stupefy me with your illusory power, O [[Janardana]] (Visnu)\".\n\nHaving hear the words of Manu, the Fish replied [to] Manu who had been engaged in the protection (of the world), \"I have manifested for the protection of this universe and for the destruction of the wicked\".\n\n\"On the seventh day, the ocean would flood the earth. Having put the seeds (of creation) etc. in the boat that would approach you, you would spend the night... of [[Brahma]] on it being encircled by the seven sages, (you) bind this boat to my horn with the big [[N\u0101ga|serpent]]\".</poem>|source=Agni Purana (unabridged), translated by J.L. Shastri, G.P. Bhatt, and N. Gangadharan (1998), Chapter 2, Verses 10-13|author=|title=}}\n[[File:Kalighat Matsya avatar.jpg|thumb|250x250px|Matsya.]]\nR. Dalal describes the [[Agni Purana]] as an '[[Encyclopedia|encyclopedic]] work, which is classified as a [[Shaivism|SHAIVITE]] [[Puranas|Purana]], through is begins with a section on [[Vishnu|VISHNU]], and has several other topics'.<ref name=\":15\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=DH0vmD8ghdMC&pg=PA444#v=onepage&q=agni%20purana&f=false|title=Hinduism: An Alphabetical Guide|last=Dalal|first=Roshen|date=2010|publisher=Penguin Books India|isbn=978-0-14-341421-6|location=|pages=10, 250|language=en}}</ref> As narrated by [[Agni]] to the sage [[Vasishtha|Vasistha]] (one of the [[Saptarishi|Saptarishis]]), in this account, as [[Shraddhadeva Manu|Manu]] 'was offering waters of libation in the (river) Krtamala, a small fish came in the waters in his folded palms', seeking protection from crocodiles and others. Growing and being transferred first to a vessel, then to a tank, and then the ocean when finally 'in size extending to a [[lakh]] of [[Yojana|yojanas]]', Manu identifies the fish as [[Vishnu]], who warns of the impending flood and instructs him to board a ship with seeds, etc. Notably, this includes being told that he will spend the 'night of [[Brahma]]' on the ship (i.e. the time of universal dissolution lasting 1000 [[Yuga|yugas]] or 'celestial years' where all creation begins again anew) while 'being encircled by the seven sages', i.e. the [[Saptarishi]].\n\nAfter the flood occurs and Manu is on the ship, a serpent ([[N\u0101ga|Naga]]) - in place of a rope - is used to tie the ship to the horn of Matsya, described as 'one million yojanas in length'. The final verses, rather than narrate the arrival of Manu at the safety at the peak of a mountain or his subsequent sacrificial ritual to produce [[Ila (Hinduism)|Ila]], instead briefly narrate that Manu 'heard from the fish the [[Puranas|Purana]] known as the [[Matsya Purana]], and that '[[Keshava|Kesava]] (Vishnu) killed the demon Hayagriva, the destroyer of the [[Vedas]] of [[Brahmin|Brahman]] and thus protected the Vedic [[Mantra|mantras]]'. Other details include:\n\n* Matsya is listed as the first of the [[Dashavatara]], or ten primary incarnations of [[Vishnu]] (49.1)\n*The Matsya [[Shaligram|salagrama]] is described as 'long and has three dots. It is crystalline-coloured... The Sridhara (stone) has a garland of wild flowers and five lines and is circular' (49.1)\n* Images of [[Vishnu]] as Matsya 'should be installed in waters' (63.7-9)\n* Vishnu resides in '[[Kuru Kingdom|Kurus]] in the form of Matsya' (108.29-30)\n*[[Ila (Hinduism)|Ila]] is mentioned as the daughter of Manu, mother of [[Pururavas]] with [[Budha]], and becoming a male called Sudyumna 'after delivering Pururavas' (273.7)\n* It is stated the [[Purusha]] is 'just like the fish in the water attached and detached' (370.4; similar to the [[Brihadaranyaka Upanishad]], above)\n* Contemplation of [[Vishnu]] should include 'with ear-ring[s] (in the shape of a fish' (374.29-32a)<br />\n\n*  \n\n=== Bhagavata Purana ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" |[[Bhagavata Purana|Bhagavata]]\n!References\n!Notes\n|-\n|1.3.15,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vedabase.io/en/library/sb/1/3/15/|title=\u015aB 1.3.15|website=vedabase.io|language=en|access-date=2020-01-18}}</ref> 1.15.35,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vedabase.io/en/library/sb/1/15/35/|title=\u015aB 1.15.35|website=vedabase.io|language=en|access-date=2020-01-18}}</ref> 2.7.12,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vedabase.io/en/library/sb/2/7/12/|title=\u015aB 2.7.12|website=vedabase.io|language=en|access-date=2020-01-18}}</ref> 6.8.13,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vedabase.io/en/library/sb/6/8/13/|title=\u015aB 6.8.13|website=vedabase.io|language=en|access-date=2020-01-18}}</ref> 8.24,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vedabase.io/en/library/sb/8/24/|title=CHAPTER TWENTY-FOUR|website=vedabase.io|language=en|access-date=2020-01-18}}</ref> 9.1.16,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vedabase.io/en/library/sb/9/1/16/|title=\u015aB 9.1.16|website=vedabase.io|language=en|access-date=2020-01-18}}</ref> 10.2.40<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vedabase.io/en/library/sb/10/2/40/|title=\u015aB 10.2.40|website=vedabase.io|language=en|access-date=2020-01-18}}</ref>\n|\n|}\n\n{{quote|<poem> O King [[Parikshit|Par\u012bk\u1e63it]], at the end of the past millennium, at the end of [[Brahm\u0101]]\u2019s day, because Lord Brahm\u0101 sleeps during the night, annihilation took place, and the three worlds were covered by the water of the ocean.\n\nAt the end of Brahm\u0101\u2019s day, when Brahm\u0101 felt sleepy and desired to lie down, the [[Vedas]] were emanating from his mouth, and the great demon named Hayagr\u012bva stole the Vedic knowledge.\n\nUnderstanding the acts of the great demon Hayagr\u012bva, the Supreme Personality of Godhead, [[Hari]], who is full of all opulences, assumed the form of a fish and saved the Vedas by killing the demon.</poem>|source=Bhagavata Purana, translated by [[A. C. Bhaktivedanta Swami Prabhupada|Swami Prabhupada]], Canto 8, Chapter 24, Verses 7-9|author=|title=}}\n\nThe legend of Matsya in the [[Bhagavata Purana]] consists of two separate accounts. In the first, as quoted above in its entirety, after the [[Vedas]] are stolen by an [[Asura]] called Hayagriva (not to be confused with the horse-headed avatar also called '[[Hayagriva]]'), [[Krishna]] assumes the form of Matsya to destroy the demon and retrieve the stolen Vedas. This account is very similar to those of the [[Naradiya Purana|Narada]] and [[Garuda Purana|Garuda Puranas]]; similar stories involving other demons are also mentioned in the [[Padma Purana|Padma]] and [[Skanda Purana|Skanda Puranas]] (see below). From the second account, following directly from the first:\n\n{{quote|<poem>The Supreme Personality of Godhead [Matsya] said: O [[Shraddhadeva Manu|King]], who can subdue your enemies, on the seventh day from today the three worlds \u2014 Bh\u016b\u1e25, Bhuva\u1e25 and Sva\u1e25 \u2014 will all merge into the water of inundation. When all the three worlds merge into the water, a large boat sent by Me will appear before you.\n\nThereafter, O King, you shall collect all types of herbs and seeds and load them on that great boat. Then, accompanied by the [[Saptarishi|seven \u1e5b\u1e63is]] and surrounded by all kinds of living entities, you shall get aboard that boat, and without moroseness you shall easily travel with your companions on the ocean of inundation, the only illumination being the effulgence of the great [[Rishi|\u1e5b\u1e63is]].\n\nThen, as the boat is tossed about by the powerful winds, attach the vessel to My horn by means of the great serpent [[Vasuki|V\u0101suki]], for I shall be present by your side. Pulling the boat, with you and all the \u1e5b\u1e63is in it, O King, I shall travel in the water of devastation until the night of Lord Brahm\u0101\u2019s slumber is over.</poem>|source=Bhagavata Purana, translated by [[A. C. Bhaktivedanta Swami Prabhupada|Swami Prabhupada]], Canto 8, Chapter 24, Verses 32-37}}\n[[File:Matsya Avatar, ca 1870.jpg|left|thumb|274x274px|Matsya.]]\nThe second account occurs at the end of the [[Chakshusha|C\u0101k\u1e63u\u1e63a]]-[[manvantara]] with King [[Shraddhadeva Manu|Satyavrata]], stated to 'later became the son of [[Surya|Vivasv\u0101n]]... and was [to be] known as \u015ar\u0101ddhadeva. By the mercy of the Supreme Personality of Godhead, he was given the post of [[Manu (Hinduism)|Manu]]'. While performing austerities, a small fish jumps into the King's hands, which he throws back into the river, prompting to fish to request his protection. Doing so, the fish grows as it is first deposited in a water jug, then a well, a lake, and then finally the sea where it expands for 'hundreds of miles'. Recognising the fish as [[Krishna]], Satyavrata is warned of the impending dissolution of the [[Trailokya|three worlds]] and instructed to board a boat built for him, taking 'herbs and seeds... the [[Saptarishi|seven \u1e5b\u1e63is]] and... all kinds of living entities'.\n\nSatyavrata meditates on [[Krishna]] until the 'gigantic clouds pouring incessant water swelled the ocean more and more', boards the boat, and 'while the King constantly meditated upon the Supreme Personality of Godhead, a large golden fish appeared in the ocean of inundation. The fish had one horn and was eight million miles long'. [[Vasuki]] is used as a rope. During the journey, Satyavrata praises [[Krishna]], and Krishna - as Matsya - 'explained to King Satyavrata the spiritual science known as [[Samkhya|s\u0101\u1e45khya]]-yoga, the science by which one distinguishes between matter and spirit, along with the instructions contained in the [[Puranas|Pur\u0101\u1e47as]] and the [[Samhita|sa\u1e41hit\u0101s]]' (8.24).\n\nThe second account is similar to that given in the [[Matsya Purana]], particularly as both [[Puranas]] omit the remainder of the original legend from the [[Shatapatha Brahmana]] (White [[Yajurveda|YajurVeda]], see above), where Manu is taken to safety by Matsya to a mountain where he consequently performs a [[Yajna|sacrifice]] to produce his \"daughter\" [[Ila (Hinduism)|Ila]]. Instead, this sacrifice is described in a separate legend, similar to that of the [[Vishnu Purana]] (see below), where 'Manu had begun that sacrifice for the sake of getting a son, but because the priest was diverted by the request of Manu\u2019s wife, a daughter named Il\u0101 was born' (9.1.16).\n\n=== Brahma Purana ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" |[[Brahma Purana|Brahma]]\n!References\n!Notes\n|-\n|'''Matsya:''' 38.1-63, 56.3, 57.1-3, 68.73; '''Flood:''' 24.19-21; '''Manu:''' 3.4-7; '''Ship:''' 38.85-86; '''Ila:''' 5.3-7, Gautami-Mahaymya: 3.9-12<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/brahma_purana_english_full|title=Brahma Purana - Parts I - IV|last=Motilal Banarsidass|date=1955-01-01}}</ref>\n|The legend of Matsya is not narrated in this [[Puranas|Purana]].\n|}\n\n{{quote|By visiting Svetamadhava and Matsyamadhava by his side and by bowing to the first incarnation of [[Krishna|Madhava]] in the form of a fish [i.e. Matsya-Madhava], one is liberated from all miseries. Lord Matsya [[Krishna|Madhava]] had at the outset assumed the form of [a] [[Rohu|Rohita]] fish. He had been thinking of the earth stationed at the bottom of the nether worlds. He established himself there in order to redeem the [[Vedas]].|source=Brahma Purana, unknown translator (1955), Chapter 57, Verses 1-3|author=|title=}}\n[[File:Varuna makara.jpg|left|thumb|180x180px|[[Varuna]].]]\nThe legend of Matsya is only briefly mentioned in the [[Brahma Purana]], as quoted above. O.M. Starza states that ''Svetamadhava'' 'to the south of the Blue Mountain... On its banks are the two shrines, those of Matsya Avatara [Matsyamadhava] and King Sveta [Svetamadhava]'. He adds that in the [[Skanda Purana]] (Purusottama Mahatmya: 37.55-6), [[Vishnu]] granted Sveta a crystalline image seated in front of Matsya (at Puri, between the blue hill and the sea) as a reward for [[asceticism]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=v4bV3beb0n8C&pg=PA11&lpg=PA11&dq=Svetamadhava#v=onepage&q=Svetamadhava&f=false|title=The Jagannatha Temple at Puri: Its Architecture, Art, and Cult|last=Starza|first=O. M.|date=1993|publisher=BRILL|isbn=978-90-04-09673-8|location=|pages=11|language=en}}</ref>\n\nOtherwise, it is stated that this 'ocean of worldly existence is painful and utterly full of misery... with passions acting like crocodiles' (24.19-21), reminiscent of the account in the [[Agni Purana]] where Matsya seeks protection from crocodiles and others. \n\nThe Brahma Purana also states that a 'son is the exceedingly splendid ship for those who are about to sink in the ocean of misery' (38.85-86). Ila/Ida is also mentioned as emerging after [[Shraddhadeva Manu|Manu]] 'desirous of begetting sons, so performed the sacrifice with [[Mitra]] and [[Varuna]] as deities... It is said in the [[Vedas]] that Ila was born therefrom' (5.3-7). This is consistent of the account of Matsya in the [[Shatapatha Brahmana]] (1.8.1). Notably, [[Ila (Hinduism)|Ila]] is also stated to be synonymous with the Earth, carrying out the function of productivity (Gautami-Mahaymya: 3.9-12).\n\n=== Brahmanda Purana ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" |[[Brahmanda Purana|Brahmanda]]\n!References\n!Notes\n|-\n|'''Part 1:''' --;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/BrahmandaPuranaG.V.TagarePart1|title=Brahmanda Purana - English Translation - Part 1 of 5|last=G.V.Tagare|date=1958}}</ref> '''Part 2:''' --;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/BrahmandaPuranaG.V.TagarePart2|title=Brahmanda Purana - English Translation - Part 2 of 5|last=G.V.Tagare|date=1958}}</ref>  '''Part 3:''' '''Manu:''' 59, '''Ida/Illa:''' 60;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/BrahmandaPuranaG.V.TagarePart3|title=Brahmanda Purana - English Translation - Part 3 of 5|last=G.V.Tagare|date=1958}}</ref>  '''Part 4:''' Lalita-mahatmya: 29.134-136;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/BrahmandaPuranaG.V.TagarePart4|title=Brahmanda Purana - English Translation - Part 4 of 5|last=G.V.Tagare}}</ref>  '''Part 5:''' Lalita-mahatmya: 33.64-66<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/BrahmandaPuranaG.V.TagarePart5|title=Brahmanda Purana - English Translation - Part 5 of 5|last=G.V.Tagare|date=1959}}</ref>\n|The legend of Matsya is not mentioned.\n|}\n\n{{quote|Desirous of getting a son, the Prajapati [<nowiki/>[[Shraddhadeva Manu]]] performed a [[Yajna|sacrifice]]. He dropped Ahuti (ghee-offering) in the fire at the spot allotted to [[Mitra]] and [[Varuna]]. It is mentioned in the [[\u015aruti|Sruti]] [i.e. [[Vedas]], including the [[Brahmana|Brahmanas]]] that Ila [Ida] was born at that spot wearing divine robes, bedecked in divine ornaments and having [a] divine physical body.|source=Brahmanda Purana Part 3, translated by G.V. Tagare  (1958), Chapter 60, Verses 5-6|author=|title=}}\n\nThe legend of Matsya does not seem to be mentioned in the [[Brahmanda Purana]]. However, a detailed [[genealogy]] is provided for [[Shraddhadeva Manu|Vaivasvata]] Manu (chapter 59), as well as an account of producing Ila/Ida through performance of a sacrifice, which is almost identical to the account given in the legend of Matsya in the [[Shatapatha Brahmana]] (chapter 60). Notably, although the name of the \"daughter\" of Manu in the Brahmana was 'Ida', in the Brahmanda it is \"Ila\", thus evidencing claims that Ida and Ila are the same (i.e. synonymous) are indeed correct.<ref name=\":14\" />\n=== Brahmavaivarta Purana ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" |[[Brahma Vaivarta Purana|Brahmavaivarta]]\n!References\n!Notes\n|-\n|Nath Translation: -- ;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.142284|title=The Brahma Vaivarta Puranam (Brahma and Prakrti Khandas)|last=Sen|first=rajendra Nath|date=1920|publisher=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>Nager translation: '''Volume 2:''' 9 (p74)<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/357106450BrahmavaivartaPurana2SanskritTextWithEnglishTranslationPdf|title=Brahmavaivarta Purana (Volume 1: Brahma, Prakrti, and Ganapati Khandas, and Volume 2: Krsna-Janma Khanda)|last=Nager|first=Shanti Lal|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n|Roman numerals indicate the Nath translation; numerical digits indi<nowiki/>cate the Nager translation (two parts), which does not provide verse numbers (some pages of the Nath translation are also missing verse numbers).\n|}\nThe legend of Matsya does not seem to be mentioned in the [[Brahma Vaivarta Purana|Brahmavaivarta Purana]]. A reference to Matsya found states that this avatar - along with [[Varaha]], [[Vamana]], [[Kalki]], [[Gautama Buddha|Buddha]], and [[Kapila]] - is 'the amsa [portion or part] of the lord [<nowiki/>[[Vishnu]]]' (Nager Translation, Volume 2, Chapter 9).<br />\n=== Garuda Purana ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" |[[Garuda Purana|Gaurda]]\n!References\n!Notes\n|-\n|'''Part 1:''' 1.23, 2.42, 13.3-10, 15.3-160, 86.10-11, 87.12, 138.4 (Ila), 142.2-3;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.20541|title=THE GARUDA-PURANA PART. 1|last=N.A.|date=1957|publisher=MOTILAL BANARSIDASS PUBLISHERS PVT. DELHI}}</ref> '''Part 2:''' 194.13, 196.6;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.21508|title=THE GARUDA-PURANA PART. 2|last=N.A.|date=1957|publisher=MOTILAL BANARSIDASS PUBLISHERS PVT. DELHI}}</ref> '''Part 3:''' 25.38 (Ila), 30.37<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.12942|title=THE GARUDA-PURANA PART. 3|last=N.A|date=1957|publisher=MOTILAL BANARSIDASS PUBLISHERS PVT. LTD, DELHI}}</ref>\n|The legend of Matsya is not mentioned. Part 3 (Brahma Moska Kanda) 1.51-52 classifies Puranas.\n|}\n\n{{quote|Svasanti was elected [[Indra]] during this regime and his enemy was the demon [[Pralamba]]. Lord [[Vishnu|Visnu]] in his incarnation as [a] fish killed him.|source=Garuda Purana, translated by 'a board of scholars' (1957), Part 1, Chapter 87, Verse 12}}\n\nThe legend of Matsya does not seem to be mentioned in the [[Garuda Purana]]. In addition to the demon [[Pralamba]] as quoted above, it is also mentioned that Matsya 'fought with the demon Hayagriva in battle, killed him, redeemed the [[Vedas]], and saved [[Shraddhadeva Manu|Manu]] and others' (Part 1: 142.2-3). Notably, [[Hayagriva]] is also the name of the horse-headed avatar of [[Vishnu]] that recovered the stolen [[Vedas]] and returned them to [[Brahma]]. Stated to be the tenth overall incarnation of [[Vishnu]] at the end of the [[Chakshusha|Cakusa]] [[Manvantara]] (i.e. the end of the reign of the sixth [[Manu (Hinduism)|Manu]]) that saved [[Shraddhadeva Manu|Vaivasvata]] Manu, the seventh and current Manu associated with the legend of Matsya (Part 1: 1.23), other details include:\n\n* Matsya is stated as the first in the [[Dashavatara|Dhashavatara]], the ten primary incarnations of [[Vishnu]] (Part 1: 86.10-11 and Part 3: 30.37)\n* 'Matsya' is also one of the 1,000 names of Vishnu ([[Vishnu Sahasranama]]; Part 1: 15.3-160)\n* Ila is mentioned, albeit without reference to the sacrifice of Manu: 'Manu had a daughter Ila of whom [[Budha]] (Mercury) begot three sons: Rajas, Rudra and [[Pururavas]]. Ila was transformed into a man named Sudyumna. Sudyumna begot three sons - Utkala, Vinata, and Gaya' (Part 1: 138.4). The word 'Ila' also signifies the soul (Part 3: 25.38)\n\n=== Kurma Purana ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" |[[Kurma Purana|Kurma]]\n!References\n!Notes\n|-\n|6.18, 19.6-9 (Ila), 21 (Puruvas)<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/kurmapuranaTRkashirajtrust1972|title=K\u016brmapur\u0101\u1e47a (Kashiraj Trust edition with English translation)|last=Gupta|first=Anand Swarup|date=1972}}</ref>\n|The legend of Matsya is not mentioned.\n|}\nAlthough the legend of Matsya does not seem to be mentioned in the [[Kurma Purana]], Ila/Ida from the original legend is, albeit without reference to [[Shraddhadeva Manu|Manu]] or the performance of a [[Yajna|sacrifice]] to produce her. Ila is stated to have bared sons with [[Budha]], the son of [[Soma (deity)|Soma]], and having 'transformed as a stainless man' called Sudyumna, also had another three sons called Utkala, Gaya, and Vinatasya (19.6-9). One of the sons of the female Ila with Budha, King [[Pururavas|Puruavas]], is also mentioned (21).\n\n=== Linga Purana ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" |[[Linga Purana|Linga]]\n!References\n!Notes\n|-\n|'''Part 1:''' 2.38-41, 65.19b-22 (Ila);<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/LingaPuranaJ.L.ShastriPart1|title=Linga Purana - English Translation - Part 1 of 2|last=J.L.Shastri|date=1951}}</ref> '''Part 2:''' 48.30-32, 96.17-22<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/LingaPuranaJ.L.ShastriPart2|title=Linga Purana - English Translation - Part 2 of 2|last=J.L.Shastri|date=1951}}</ref>\n|Part 2 continues up to chapter 108 and then starts at chapter 1 again.\n|}\n\n{{quote|Multitudes of creatures have been saved by you in the form of a fish. You moved about in the vast ocean-like sheet of water formerly, after tying up the boat to your tail.|source=\u2009Linga Purana, translated by J.L.Shastri (1951), Part 2, Chapter 96, Verses 17-22|author=|title=}}\n\nThe legend of Matsya is only briefly mentioned in the [[Linga Purana]], as quoted above, and as stated by [[Virabhadra]] to [[Narasimha|Nrismha]], the man-lion [[avatar]] of [[Vishnu]]. Matsya is also mentioned as one of the 10 primary avatars of Vishnu ([[Dashavatara]]) for the good of the world; other avatars are due to the curse of [[Bhrigu|Bhrgu]] (Part 2: 48.30-32). Ila is also mentioned as becoming a '[[Kinnara Kingdom|Kimpurusa]]' called Sudyumna, alternating between being a man and a woman from one month to another; as a woman she bore children with [[Budha]], the son of [[Soma (deity)|Soma]], including King [[Pururavas]]. No mention is made of being produced by the [[Yajna|sacrifice]] of [[Shraddhadeva Manu|Manu]] (Part 1: 65.19b-22).\n\n=== Markandeya Purana ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" |[[Markandeya Purana|Markandeya]]\n!References\n!Notes\n|-\n|XLVII.7, LIV.31, LVIII.75-78 (star constellations), LIX.22-26<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.163375|title=Markandeya Puranam.|last=Dutt|first=Manmatha Nath|date=1896}}</ref>\n|The legend of Matsya is not mentioned.\n|}\n=== Matsya Purana ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" |[[Matsya Purana|Matsya]]\n!References\n!Notes\n|-\n|'''Matsya:''' 1-2; '''Ila:''' 11<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.135360|title=The Matsya Puranam|last=Taluqdar|first=a|date=1916}}</ref>\n|The legend of Matsya forms the frame in which this [[Puranas|Purana]] was narrated to [[Shraddhadeva Manu|Vaivasvata]] Manu.\n|}\n\n{{quote|May the words of Lord [[Vishnu|Visnu]], embodied in the Vedas and uttered by his Matsya-[[Avatar|avatara]], in which incarnation, at the time of His sallying forth from the region of the [[patala]], the blow of His tail caused the [[Seven Seas|seven seas]] to intermingle with the high heavens and then to fall down, splattering the sphere of the earth, steal away all your evil.|source=Matsya Purana, translated by A. Taluqdar (1916), Chapter I, Verse 2}}\n[[File:Matsya and Manu.jpg|left|thumb|306x306px|Matsya and [[Manu (Hinduism)|Manu]].]]\nAs stated by the [[Agni Purana]] (see above), V. R. R. Dikshitar notes that after the flood, when 'the boat was floating in the dark waters, [[Krishna|Vasudeva]], in the form of a fish, addressed the [[Matsya Purana]] to [[Shraddhadeva Manu|Manu]]'.<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/in.gov.ignca.9097|title=Matsya Purana a study|last=Dikshitar|first=V. R. Ramachandra|date=1935|publisher=|isbn=|location=|pages=4}}</ref> [[Horace Hayman Wilson|H.H. Wilson]] adds that the legend of Matsya 'is told in the [[Mahabharata]], with reference to the Matsya [Purana] as its authority; from which it might be inferred, that the [[Puranas|Purana]] was prior to the poem'.<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.217330|title=Puranas|last=H H Wilson|date=1911|publisher=|isbn=|location=|pages=84}}</ref> Dalal also states about the Matsya Purana that it 'is one of the older Puranas, and was narrated by LOMAHARSHANA [Suta] to the [[Rishi|rishis]] in the [[Naimi\u1e63\u0101ra\u1e47ya (forest)|NAIMISHA]] forest. It begins with the story of [[Shraddhadeva Manu|MANU]]'.<ref name=\":15\" />\n\nIn this account, which consists of the first two chapters, King [[Shraddhadeva Manu|Vaivasvata]], 'after making over his kingdom to his son [<nowiki/>[[Ikshvaku]]], devoted himself to rigid [[asceticism]] [on] the summit of the Malnya mountain'. After a million years, granted a boon by [[Brahma]], the King requested 'power sufficient for the protection of the whole creation, movable and immovable, when the hour of [[Pralaya]] [dissolution] will come'.\n\nAfterwards, while performing [[Tarpana]] (libation of water to [[Manes|deceased ancestors]]) at his [[Hermit|hermitage]], a small [[carp]] jumps into his hands which as it grows, is first deposited in a jar, then a large pitcher, a well, a tank, the [[Ganges]], and then the ocean where 'it very nearly filled the vast expanse of the great ocean'. Identifying the gigantic fish as Krishna, Manu is warned by Matsya that in 'a few days time, O King, the Universe shall be [[Outburst flood|deluged]] with water, along with the mountains and forests', adding that the [[Deva (Hinduism)|Devas]] had created a boat to rescue creation which Manu is to take charge of to 'help the distressed' and to tie to His horn if in danger from strong gusts of wind (Chapter 1).\n[[File:Budha graha.JPG|thumb|200x200px|[[Budha]], husband of Ila.]]\nThe dissolution of the Earth is described to Vaivasvata by Matsya, beginning with no rain for a hundred years, famine as the rays of the sun 'shall become seven times more powerful', and subterranean fire from the thousand mouths of [[Shesha|Sesa]] which will destroy creation, reducing the three worlds to ash. Then 'the seven destructive [<nowiki/>[[pralaya]]] clouds, viz - Samvarta,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wisdomlib.org/definition/samvarta|title=Samvarta, Sa\u1e43varta: 10 definitions|last=www.wisdomlib.org|date=2012-06-29|website=www.wisdomlib.org|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref> Bhimanada,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wisdomlib.org/definition/bhimanada|title=Bhimanada, Bh\u012bman\u0101da, Bhima-nada: 3 definitions|last=www.wisdomlib.org|date=2017-03-31|website=www.wisdomlib.org|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref> Drona,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wisdomlib.org/definition/drona|title=Drona, Dro\u1e47\u0101, Dro\u1e47a: 16 definitions|last=www.wisdomlib.org|date=2012-06-29|website=www.wisdomlib.org|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref> Chanda, Balahaka,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wisdomlib.org/definition/balahaka|title=Balahaka, Bal\u0101haka: 8 definitions|last=www.wisdomlib.org|date=2017-08-03|website=www.wisdomlib.org|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref> Vidyut Pataka,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wisdomlib.org/definition/vidyutpataka|title=Vidyutpataka, Vidyutpat\u0101ka: 1 definition|last=www.wisdomlib.org|date=2017-06-07|website=www.wisdomlib.org|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref> and Sona,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wisdomlib.org/definition/shona|title=Shona, \u015ao\u1e47a, So\u1e47a, Sona, \u015ao\u1e47\u0101, So\u1e47\u0101: 15 definitions|last=www.wisdomlib.org|date=2009-04-12|website=www.wisdomlib.org|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref> would spring up from the vapours arising out of such a head, and would rain in torrents till all the seas become united in one great mass'. Matsya, before disappearing, also states that at the beginning of re-creation, He will bring back [[Vedas|Vedic]] knowledge. Finally, after performing [[Yoga]], Vaivasvata boards the boat at the time of dissolution, [[Shesha|Sesa]] appears in the shape of a rope, and the horned Matsya reappears to narrate the Matsya Purana (Chapter 2).\n\n==== Ila ====\nNotably, the remainder of the legend from the [[Shatapatha Brahmana]] (White [[Yajurveda|YajurVeda]]), where Manu is taken to safety by Matsya to a mountain where he consequently performs a sacrifice to produce his \"daughter\" [[Ila (Hinduism)|Ila]] is not mentioned. Instead it is stated in a separate legend that [[Shraddhadeva Manu|Vaivasvata]] had ten '''sons''', 'the eldest of whom was Ila who was born by the performance of [a] [[Putrakameshti|putresti]] sacrifice'. It was Ila - not [[Solar dynasty|Iskwaku]] - who was made King, who then 'started on an expedition of conquest and visited several countries'. Happening to enter Saravana, the pleasure gardens of [[Shiva]] who was enjoying conjugal love with His consort [[Parvati]], Ila 'was instantly transformed into a woman, and his horse was transformed into a mare'. Ila - as a woman again - later marries [[Budha]], the son of the [[Soma (deity)|Moon]] (Chapter 11).\n\n=== Narada Purana ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" |[[Narada Purana|Narada]]\n!References\n!Notes\n|-\n|'''Part 1:''' 11.52;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.12945|title=THE NARADA-PURANA PART. 1|last=N.A|date=1950|publisher=MOTILAL BANARSIDASS PUBLISHERS PRIVATE LIMITED, DELHI DELHI}}</ref> '''Part 2:''' 62.52;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.20659|title=THE NARADA-PURANA PART. 2|last=N.A.|date=1950|publisher=MOTILAL BANARSIDASS PUBLISHERS PVT. DELHI}}</ref> '''Part 3:''' 65.59, 71.152.153, 71.161;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.21516|title=THE NARADA-PURANA PART. 3|last=N.A.|date=1952|publisher=MOTILAL BANARSIDASS PUBLISHERS PVT. DELHI}}</ref> '''Part 4:''' 114.2, 119.14-19, 125.62-64;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.12976|title=THE NARADA-PURANA PART. 4|last=N.A|date=1952|publisher=MOTILAL BANARSIDASS PUBLISHERS PVT. LTD, DELHI}}</ref> '''Part 5:''' Uttarabhaga - 55.47-48 (flood), 56.14-18, 57.30, 67.45-47<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.12978|title=THE NARADA-PURANA PART. 5|last=N.A|date=1952|publisher=MOTILAL BANARSIDASS PUBLISHERS PVT. LTD, DELHI}}</ref>\n|The Narada Purana focuses on worship and rituals.\n|}\n\n{{quote|O [[Mohini]], listen to another great holy pool here itself. By taking a holy dip here with devotion, the man becomes master of the [[Vedas]]. The [[Asura]] named Hayasiras, a terror to [[Deva (Hinduism)|Devas]] and others, snatched away [[Vedas]] coming out of the mouth of god [[Brahma]].  Thereupon, prayed to by Brahma, [[Vishnu|Visnu]] manifested himself in the form of a divine Fish [Matsya]. The lord killed the demon and handed over the Vedas to Brahma.|source=Narada Purana, unknown translator (1952), Part 5, Chapter 67, Verses 45-47}}\n\n[[File:Matsya Raja Ravi Varma Press.jpg|thumb|Matsya with the [[Vedas]] depicted as infants.|alt=|250x250px]]\n\nIt seems the legend of Matsya rescuing [[Shraddhadeva Manu|Manu]] from the flood is not narrated in the [[Naradiya Purana|Narada Purana]]. Instead, a brief account of Matsya destroying the demon Hayasiras (i.e. Hayagriva) to return the [[Vedas]] to [[Brahma]] is given, similar to the accounts of the [[Agni Purana|Agni]] and [[Garuda Purana|Garuda]] [[Puranas]] (see above). Notably, worldly existence is described as a 'terrible ocean... Miseries constitute its foams; it is turbulent with furious temperament constituting its sharks and crocodiles. The mundane affairs are its flood of waters; the different kinds of ailments are its waves; it is impassable due to the whirlpool of delusion' (Part 5: Uttarabhaga - 55.47-48). Also notably - especially as virtually identical to the account given in the [[Brahma Purana]] (see above) - mention is made of visiting the shrines of Matsya (Matsyamadhava; 'who had at the outset assumed the form of a fish of the [[Rohu|Rohita]] type') and King Sveta (Svetamadhava; Part 5: Uttarabhaga - 56.14-16). Other details include: \n\n* It is stated that the legend of Matsya is narrated in the eighth [[Skandha]] (or canto) of the [[Bhagavata Purana|Srimad Bhagavatam]] (Part 4 96.14-15a),\n* It is stated that the 'Pancami (fifth day) in the bright half of the month of [[Chaitra|Caitra]] is called Matsya Jayanti. On this day, the worship of the incarnation of the Lord as (Divine) fish is to be formed with great festivities, by devotees' (Part 4: 114.2)\n* In ritual worship, 'a beautiful square-shaped put fourteen [[A\u1e45gula|Angulas]] deep should be made and sprinkled with sandal water. After filling it with the milk of cows, the devotee should put in it an image of a fish made of gold and exquisite in every limb, and with eyes constituted of pearls. Uttering the [[Mantra]], 'Obeisance to the great fish' the devotee should worship it with scents and other things and offer it to a [[Brahmin|Brahmana]]' (Part 4: 125.62-64)\n* [[Kama]] (Cupid) has a fish for a banner (Part 4: Uttarabhaga - 2.44b-46 and 19.14)\n* Matsya is listed as the first of the [[Dashavatara]], or ten primary incarnations of [[Vishnu]] (Part 4: 119.14-19)\n\n=== Padma Purana ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" |[[Padma Purana|Padma]]\n!References\n!Notes\n|-\n|'''Part 1:''' 1.44b-50, 3.25b-29, 8.75-77, 8.118-119;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/padma_purana_part1_english|title=Padma Purana Part 1 Srishti Khanda Motilal Banarsidass 1988|last=N. A. Deshpande|date=1988-01-01}}</ref> '''Part 2:''' --;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/padma_purana_part2_english|title=Padma Purana Part 2 Srishti Khanda Motilal Banarsidass 1989|last=N. A. Deshpande|date=1989-01-01}}</ref> '''Part 3:''' 19.60-71, 75.1-6;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.21960|title=THE PADMA-PURANA PART. 3|last=N.A.|date=1951|publisher=MOTILAL BANARSIDASS PUBLISHERS PVT. DELHI}}</ref> '''Part 4:''' --;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.12948|title=THE PADMA-PURANA PART. 4|last=N.A|date=1952|publisher=MOTILAL BANARSIDASS PUBLISHERS PVT. LTD, DELHI}}</ref> '''Part 5:''' 22.28-36;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.21800|title=THE PADMA-PURANA PART. 5|last=N.A|date=1952|publisher=MOTILAL BANARSIDASS PUBLISHERS PVT. DELHI}}</ref> '''Part 6:''' 77.48b-51;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.22055|title=THE PADMA-PURANA PART. 6|last=N.A|date=1952|publisher=MOTILAL BANARSIDASS PUBLISHERS PVT. DELHI}}</ref> '''Part 7:''' 30.11-15, 66.44-54, 71.23-29, 71.169-188, 80.137-146a;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.12949|title=THE PADMA-PURANA PART. 7|last=N.A|date=1952|publisher=MOTILAL BANARSIDASS PUBLISHERS PVT. LTD, DELHI}}</ref> '''Part 8:'''  91.1-11, 95.10-24, 98.2-4, 120.51b-73;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.12952|title=THE PADMA-PURANA PART. 8|last=N.A|date=1952|publisher=MOTILAL BANARSIDASS PUBLISHERS PVT. LTD, DELHI}}</ref> '''Part 9:''' 197.57b-70a, 229.40-44, 230;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.12954|title=THE PADMA-PURANA PART. 9|last=N.A|date=1956|publisher=MOTILAL BANARSIDASS PUBLISHERS PVT. LTD, DELHI}}</ref> '''Part 10:'''  253.71-81, Kritayogasara Khanda - 6.175-190, 11.92b-101, 17.1-3-117<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.21961|title=THE PADMA-PURANA PART.10|last=N.A.|date=1956|publisher=MOTILAL BANARSIDASS PUBLISHERS PVT. DELHI}}</ref>\n|\n|}\n\n{{quote|<poem>...[[Vishnu|Visnu]] taking up the form resembling a small glittering fish fell into the hollow of the hands of [[Kashyapa|Kasyapa]] at his residence on the [[Vindhya Range|Vindhya]] (mountain). The sage kindly and quickly put him into (his) water-pot. When it could not contain itself there, he put it into a well. When it could not contain itself there, he put it into a lake. In this way it was (in the end) put into the sea. It grew there also. Then Vishnu, having the form of a fish, killed Sankha. Then taking him in his hand he came to the Badari-forest. Calling all the sages there, he ordered them (like) this.\n\nRemove the [[Vedas]] dropped into the water. Quickly bring them with the [[Upanishads]] from the interior of the water. Till then I, with the group of deities, shall live and [[Allahabad|Prayaga]]. Then all the sages, endowed with the power of penance, lifted the Vedas with the six [[Vedanga|Vedangas]] and with [[Yajna|sacrifices]]... Then all the sages together went to Prayaga. They presented the Vedas obtained by them to Vishnu with the Creator. [[Brahma]], obtained the Vedas with the sacrifices was delighted; and with the group of deities and sages he performed the horse-sacrifice.</poem>|source=Padma Purana, translated by N.A. Deshpande (1988), Part 8, Chapter 91, Verses 1-11}}[[File:Matsya painting.jpg|thumb|left|Matsya preparing to slay the demon.|alt=|200x200px]]There are two accounts of the Matsya legend in [[Padma Purana]]. In the first, it is [[Kashyapa|Kasyapa]] - a [[Saptarishi]] synonymous with [[Kurma]] - who rears Matsya, not the Manu [[Shraddhadeva Manu|Vaivasvata]]. The story itself is in regards to rescuing the Vedas from the demon Sankha (Hayasiras or Hayagriva in other accounts), not in regards to protection from the deluge or dissolution of the Earth. It is also the sages that return the [[Vedas]] to [[Brahma]], not [[Vishnu]] (i.e. in other accounts, such as that below, it is usually the horse-headed avatar also called '[[Hayagriva]]', or the fish avatar, that returns the Vedas to Brahma; Part 8: 91.1-11).\n\nIn the second account, [[Kashyapa|Kasyapa]] is stated to have had four (i.e. not thirteen) wives: [[Aditi]], [[Diti]], [[Kadru]] and [[Vinata]]. As well as [[Hiranyaksha|Hiranyaksa]] and [[Hiranyakashipu]] ([[Asura|Asuras]] relating to the legends of the [[Varaha]] and [[Narasimha]] avatars, respectively), Diti also gives birth to other demons including Hayagriva and [[Makara]]. \n\nIt is Makara, through performance of severe penances, who enters into the realm of [[Brahma]], steals the [[Vedas]], and enters 'into the great ocean' with them, causing ruin to the world. Reminiscent of the legend of [[Kurma]], Brahma, 'surrounded by the hosts of all gods, went to the [[Samudra manthan|Milky Ocean]], and seeking refuge of god ([[Vishu]])' informs Him of what has happened. Vishnu 'thus addressed by Brahma, resorted to the Fish-form [Matsya] and entered the great ocean' before then adopting the form of a [[crocodile]] to kill Makara and return the Vedas, [[Vedanga|Vedangas]], and Upangas to Brahma. Other details include:\n\n<br />\n\n* [[Ila (Hinduism)|Ila]] was created from a sacrifice by [[Shraddhadeva Manu|Manu]] to produce a son (Part 1: 8.75-77) and alternated between being man for one month (called Sudyumna) and woman in another; made  pregnant by [[Budha]] (Part 1: 8.118-119)\n* Matsya is listed as first in the [[Dashavatara]], the ten primary incarnations of [[Vishnu]] (Part 7: 66.44-54 and 71.23-29 and Part 9: 229.40-44)\n* 'That [<nowiki/>[[Shaligram|salagrama]]] stone which is long, has a golden complexion, and adorned with three lines, is known as 'Matsya', and gives the fruit like enjoyments and salvation' (Part 8: 120.51b-73)\n* It is stated about [[Vishnu]] that 'You are the Fish holding the [[Vedas]]' (Part 9: 197.57b-70a) and that 'taking the form of a Fish, extracted the Vedas' (Part 10: Kritayogasara khanda - 6.175-190)\n* It is stated 'The third auspicious covering [of [[Vaikuntha]]] consists of the worlds of Matsya, Kurma, etc.' (Part 9: 228.59-65)\n\n=== Shiva Purana ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" |[[Shiva Purana|Shiva]]\n!References\n!Notes\n|-\n|'''Part 1:''' Rudra-Samhita II - 2.24-29 ([[Kama]] fish banner and vehicle);<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/SivaPuranaJ.L.ShastriPart1|title=Siva Purana - English Translation - Part 1 of 4|last=J.L.Shastri|date=1950}}</ref> '''Part 2:''' 17.16, Yuddha Khanda - 16.16;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/SivaPuranaJ.L.ShastriPart2|title=Siva Purana - English Translation - Part 2 of 4|last=J.L.Shastri|date=1950}}</ref> '''Part 3:''' Satarudra Samhita - 11.18;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/SivaPuranaJ.L.ShastriPart3|title=Siva Purana - English Translation - Part 3 of 4|last=J.L.Shastri|date=1950}}</ref> '''Part 4:''' Uma Samhita - 36; Vayaviya Samhita - 30.56-58, 31.134-136<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/SivaPuranaJ.L.ShastriPart4|title=Siva Purana - English Translation - Part 4 of 4|last=J.L.Shastri|date=1950}}</ref>\n|\n|}\nThe legend of Matsya does not seem to be narrated in the [[Shiva Purana]]. Matsya is however listed as first in the [[Dashavatara]], the ten principle [[Avatar|avatars]] of [[Vishnu]] (Part 4: Vayaviya Samhita: Chapter 30.56-58 and 31.134-136). it is also mentioned that [[Shraddhadeva Manu|Vaivasvata]] had nine sons, plus a daughter [[Ila (Hinduism)|Ila]] from performance of a sacrifice. Born 'of the parts of [[Mitra]] and [[Varuna]]', these deities inform Ila that she 'alone will become the son establishing the family of Manu. You will be famous in the three worlds as Sudyumna' (Part 4: Uma Samhita - 36).\n\n=== Skanda Purana ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" |[[Skanda Purana|Skanda]]\n!References\n!Notes\n|-\n|'''Part 1:''' --;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.12961|title=THE SKANDA-PURANA PART. 1|last=N.A|date=1950|publisher=MOTILAL BANARSIDASS PUBLISHERS PVT. LTD, DELHI}}</ref> '''Part 2:''' Kaumarkika Khanda - 13.194, 36.25;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.13010|title=THE SKANDA-PURANA PART. 2|last=N.A|date=1950|publisher=MOTILAL BANARSIDASS PUBLISHERS PVT. LTD, DELHI}}</ref> '''Part 3:''' Uttarardha - 8.20, 9.16, 16.18;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.20835|title=THE SKANDA-PURANA PART. 3|last=N.A.|date=1951|publisher=MOTILAL BANARSIDASS PUBLISHERS PVT. DELHI}}</ref> '''Part 4:''' --;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.13009|title=THE SKANDA-PURANA PART. 4|last=N.A|date=1951|publisher=MOTILAL BANARSIDASS PUBLISHERS PVT. LTD, DELHI}}</ref> '''Part 5:''' Purusottama-Ksetra-Mahatmya - 15.30, 22.32.43, 38.113-117;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.20756|title=THE SKANDA-PURANA PART. 5|last=N.A.|date=1951|publisher=MOTILAL BANARSIDASS PUBLISHERS PVT. DELHI}}</ref> '''Part 6:''' Karttikamsa-Mahatmya - 13, 14.1, 16.2, 34.27-28, Margasirsa-Mahatmya - 3.23-25, 14.25-28, Bhagavata-Mahatmyha - 3.29-32;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.20761|title=THE SKANDA-PURANA PART. 6|last=N.A.|date=1951|publisher=MOTILAL BANARSIDASS PUBLISHERS PVT. DELHI}}</ref> '''Part 7:''' Ayidhya-Mahatmya 1.64-67, 18.12-20, 27.32-33;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.13008|title=THE SKANDA-PURANA PART. 7|last=N.A|date=1951|publisher=MOTILAL BANARSIDASS PUBLISHERS PVT. LTD, DELHI}}</ref> '''Part 8:''' Setu-Mahaymya - 3.81-82, 37.15-20, 46.37-43, 48.47-52;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.22054|title=THE SKANDA-PURANA PART. 8|last=N.A.|date=1953|publisher=MOTILAL BANARSIDASS PUBLISHERS PVT. DELHI}}</ref> '''Part 9:'''  Dharmaranya Khanda - 8.53-59;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.21994|title=THE SKANDA-PURANA PART. 9|last=N.A.|date=1953|publisher=MOTILAL BANARSIDASS PUBLISHERS PVT. DELHI}}</ref> '''Part 10:''' Purvardha - 21.7;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.13007|title=THE SKANDA-PURANA PART.10|last=N.A|date=1953|publisher=MOTILAL BANARSIDASS PUBLISHERS PVT. LTD, DELHI}}</ref> '''Part 11:''' Uttarardha - 69.141;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.13006|title=THE SKANDA-PURANA PART.11|last=N.A|date=1955|publisher=MOTILAL BANARSIDASS PUBLISHERS PVT. LTD, DELHI}}</ref> '''Part 12:''' Avantiksetra-Mahatmya - 8.20-26, 63.81;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.22009|title=THE SKANDA-PURANA PART.12|last=N.A.|date=1955|publisher=MOTILAL BANARSIDASS PUBLISHERS PVT. DELHI}}</ref> '''Part 13''': --;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.20764|title=THE SKANDA-PURANA PART.13|last=N.A.|date=1955|publisher=MOTILAL BANARSIDASS PUBLISHERS PVT. DELHI}}</ref> '''Part 14:''' Reva Khanda - 3.23-32, 9;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.100076|title=The Skanda-purana Part.14|last=Not Available|date=1957}}</ref> '''Part 15:''' Reva Khanda - 151.8-17, 151.1-7;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.20778|title=THE SKANDA-PURANA PART.15|last=N.A.|date=1957|publisher=MOTILAL BANARSIDASS PUBLISHERS PVT. DELHI}}</ref> '''Part 16:''' --;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.13005|title=THE SKANDA-PURANA PART.16|last=N.A|date=1958|publisher=MOTILAL BANARSIDASS PUBLISHERS PVT. LTD, DELHI}}</ref> '''Part 17:''' --;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.13004|title=THE SKANDA-PURANA PART.17|last=N.A|date=1958|publisher=MOTILAL BANARSIDASS PUBLISHERS PVT. LTD, DELHI}}</ref> '''Part 18:''' Nagara Khanda - 254.92;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.13003|title=THE SKANDA-PURANA PART.18|last=N.A|date=1960|publisher=MOTILAL BANARSIDASS PUBLISHERS PVT. LTD, DELHI}}</ref> '''Part 19:''' Prabhasa-Ksetra Mahatmya - 2.20-23;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.13002|title=THE SKANDA-PURANA PART.19|last=N.A|date=1960|publisher=MOTILAL BANARSIDASS PUBLISHERS PVT. LTD, DELHI}}</ref> '''Part 20:''' Prabhasa Khanda: 152.4 ('The earth is called Ila')<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.13000|title=THE SKANDA-PURANA PART.20|last=N.A|date=1960|publisher=MOTILAL BANARSIDASS PUBLISHERS PVT. LTD, DELHI}}</ref>\n|\n|}\n\n{{quote|<poem>Formerly there was a [[Daitya]] called [[Panchatantra|Damanaka]]. He had become very powerful due to [[Maya (religion)|Maya]]. He harassed people. He could move through the waters of [the] ocean. The Lord too could wield Maya. At the request of [[Brahma]] the Lord took up the incarnation of [a] Fish and entered the ocean. He searched for and found (the demon). He dragged him to the shore and thrashed him on the surface of the earth. The excellent [[Danava (Hinduism)|Danava]] fell on the fourteenth day in the bright half of the month of Madhu (i.e [[Chaitra|Caitra]]).\n\nBy contact of the hands of the Lord he became a fragrant gross of the same name, i.e. Damanaka (Artemisia indica). The Lord accepted it with a surprised mind. He made a garland of it and wore it on his chest along with the garland of sylvan flowers. He thought that its fragrance should stay as long as the object exists.</poem>|source=Skanda Purana, Unknown translator (1951), Part 5: Purusottama-Ksetra-Mahatmya, Chapter 38, Verses 113-117}}\n\nThere are several accounts of Matsya in the [[Skanda Purana]]. In the first, as quoted above, [[Vishnu]] in the form of Matsya destroys the [[Asura]] called Damanaka in the ocean, who turns into fragrant Damanaka grass. This story is in relation to the Matsya Jayanti which takes place in [[Chaitra|Caitra]], as related by the [[Naradiya Purana|Narada Purana]] (Part 5: Purusottama-Ksetra-Mahatmya: 38.113-117). From the second account:\n\n{{quote|<poem>Formerly there was an [[Asura]] named Sankha. He was the son of Sagara (Ocean). He usurped the powers of [[Indra]] and other Guardians of the Quarters... on seeing [[Vishnu]] asleep, he took away the [[Vedas]] [to weaken the gods] from the primordial self-born Lord [[Brahma]] from [[Brahmaloka|Satyaloka]]. While they were being carried away by him, the Vedas, out of fear of him, escaped and entered the waters along with the seeds of the Yajnamantras. In search of them, Sankha too entered the ocean. Wandering here and there the [[Daitya]] did not find them together anywhere...\n\n[Vishnu said:] All the Vedas carried away by Sankha now lie submerged in the waters. O Devas, I shall bring them all after killing the son of the Ocean... After saying this, Lord Visnu assumed the form of a Saphari fish and plunged into the water from the sky even as Brahma staying on [[Vindhya Range|Vindhya]] was watching. After killing [the] Asura Sankha, Visnu went to the forest of Badari. There the Lord called together all the sages and commanded thus: O you all, do search for the Vedas scattered within the waters. Bring them quickly from the midst of the waters of the sea. Till then I shall remain at [[Prayaga]] accompanied by the groups of [[Deva (Hinduism)|Devas]].</poem>|source=Skanda Purana, Unknown translator (1951), Part 6, Karttikamsa-Mahatmya, Chapter 13|author=|title=}}\n[[File:DASWANTH Birth of Brhma and madhu-kaitabha kill by vishnu.jpg|thumb|250x250px|The deaths of [[Madhu-Kaitabha|Madhu and Kaitabha]].]]\nNotably, the second account, as quoted above, is in many respects almost identical to the account in the [[Padma Purana]] (see above), with the exception of being nurtured by [[Kashyapa|Kasyapa]] (or, in the original account of the [[Shatapatha Brahmana]], [[Shraddhadeva Manu|Vaivasvata]] Manu; Part 6: Karttikamsa-Mahatmya: 13). In the third account, the Asuras [[Madhu-Kaitabha|Madhu and Kaitabha]] steal the [[Vedas]] from [[Brahma]] and enter 'the great ocean'. Mahadeva - i.e. [[Shiva]], not [[Vishnu]] in this account - assumes the form of a Fish, stirs up the ocean, and finds the Vedas in [[Patala]] before destroying the [[Daitya|Daityas]] and returning the Vedas to Brahma (Part 14: Reva Khanda: 9). Notably, in the [[Bhagavata Purana]], it is [[Vishnu]] in the form of [[Hayagriva]] (also the name of another Veda-stealing demon as described above) who retrieves the Vedas from Madhu and Kaitabha.\n\nThe fourth and fifth accounts are brief mentions of Matsya in relation to the legend of the flood and of [[Shraddhadeva Manu|Manu]]. In the fourth account Vishnu states <nowiki>''</nowiki>When you day ends, I shall become a fish and shall support (floating) like a boat, the earth along with its medicinal plants, Manus and others' (Part 7: Ayidhya-Mahatmya: 18.12-20). In the fifth account it is stated 'In order to please [[Brahma]] in a former [[Kalpa (aeon)|Kalpa]], the Lord became a Fish, recovered the [[Vedas]] that were immersed in the great sea and handed them over to Brahma' (Part 15: Reva Khanda - 151.8-17). Elsewhere, it is also stated that at the beginning of a new Kalpa, Vishnu in the form of Matsya taught the Vedas to Brahma (Part 19: Prabhasa-Ksetra Mahatmya - 2.20-23). The accounts of Matsya in this Purana are thus primarily concerned with the retrieval or restoration of the Vedas after being stolen by various demons. Other details include:\n\n* It is stated 'in the morning on [[Dwadashi|Dvadasi]] day, in the bright half of the month of [[Agrahayana|Margasirsa]], the Matsya festival is to be celebrated by the wise' (Part 6: Karttikamsa-Mahatmya: 14.1)\n* Matsya is stated to be the protector of the Vedas (Part 8: Setu-Mahaymya: 46.37-43)\n* Matsya is listed in the [[Dashavatara]], or ten primary incarnations of Vishnu (Part 15: Reva-Khanda, 151.1-7)\n* King [[Pururavas]] was the son of [[Ila (Hinduism)|Ila]] (Part 12: Avantiksetra-Mahatmya - 8.20-26); it is also stated that 'The earth is called Ila' (Part 20: Prabhasa Khanda: 152.4)\n* 'Matsya' is one of the thousand names ([[Vishnu Sahasranama]]) of [[Vishnu]] (Part 12: Avantiksetra-Mahatmya: 63.81)\n* It is stated that the Matsyavahana is the emblem of [[Parvati]] (Part 18: Nagara Khanda - 254.92)\n\n=== Vamana Purana ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" |[[Vamana Purana|Vamana]]\n!References\n!Notes\n|-\n| --<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.313087|title=The Vamana Purana With English Translation|last=Gupta|first=anand Swarup|date=1968}}</ref>\n|No notable mentions.\n|}\n=== Varaha Purana ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" |[[Varaha Purana|Varaha]]\n!References\n!Notes\n|-\n|'''Part 1:''' 1.6, 4.2-3, 7.40, 9, 12.8-9, 15.10, 15.18-19, 40.46-48, 48.17-22, 113.20, 113.42;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.12962|title=THE VARAHA PURANA PART. 1|last=N.A|date=1960|publisher=MOTILAL BANARSIDASS, DELHI}}</ref> '''Part 2:''' 211.69<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.12972|title=THE VARAHA PURANA PART. 2|last=N.A|date=1960|publisher=MOTILAL BANARSIDASS, DELHI}}</ref>\n|}\n\n{{quote|<poem>Night being over, the lotus-eyed God [<nowiki/>[[Narayana]]] got up and thought about the four [[Vedas]] and in them the Goddess of the Vedas. Despite this thinking, he did not get the Vedas because he was illusioned by the sense of sleep. He was in utter confusion. Then seeing them hidden in his own form called water, he thought of entering into it taking the form of a fish. So after meditating for sometime He took the form of a great fish and entered into the water agitating it all around. When the excellent God in the form of a huge fish resembling a big mountain, suddenly entered the ocean, He who uplifted the earth before was extolled...\n\nExtolled thus, the God caught the Vedas with [[Upanishads]] and [[Shastra|Sastras]] out of the water and then took his own form.</poem>|source=Varaha Purana, Unknown translator (1960), Part 1, Chapter 9|author=|title=}}\n\nAs quoted above, the account of Matsya in the [[Varaha Purana]] concerns the retrieval of the [[Vedas]] at the beginning of a new [[Kalpa (aeon)|Kalpa]], where creation begins anew. This occurs after the dissolution (i.e. annihilation) of creation at the end of the previous Kalpa, followed by the 'night' of [[Vishnu]] / [[Narayana]], which lasts 1,000 [[Yuga|Yugas]]. With the exceptions of verses listing Matsya as first in the [[Dashavatara]], the ten primary incarnations of Vishnu (Part 1: 4.2-3, 48.17-22 and Part 2: 211.69), almost all references to this avatar are in respect to retrieving the lost or stolen Vedas from the ocean.\n=== Vayu Purana ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" |[[Vayu Purana|Vayu]]\n!References\n!Notes\n|-\n|'''Part 1:''' --<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.12977|title=THE VAYU PURANA PART. 1|last=N.A|date=1960|publisher=MOTILAL BANARSIDASS PUBLISHERS PVT. LTD, DELHI|isbn=|location=|pages=377\u2013382}}</ref>; '''Part 2:''' 23;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.20638|title=THE VAYU PURANA PART. 2|last=N.A.|date=1960|publisher=MOTILAL BANARSIDASS, DELHI}}</ref>\n|No notable mentions.\n|}\n\n{{quote|Know that formerly [[Shraddhadeva Manu|Manu]], on being urged by [[Brahma]], began to create willingly, but he was unsuccessful. Then [[Prajapati]] [Manu], desirous of sons, performed a great ''Isti'' ([[Yajna]]). Manu offered the oblation (''Ahuti'') in the share of [[Mitra]] and [[Varuna]]. It is heard, that [[Ila (Hinduism)|Ida]] was born thereof. She wore heavenly garments and was bedecked in celestial ornaments. Her body too was divine. It is remembered that Manu, the bearer of the staff of justice, addressed her as 'Ila' and said, \"Welfare unto you, I shall follow you\".|source=Vayu Purana, Unknown translator, (1960), Part 2, Chapter 23, Verses 5-7}}\n\nAlthough there are no notable mentions of Matsya in the [[Vayu Purana]], the account of the birth of Ida at sacrifice of Manu clearly originates from the [[Shatapatha Brahmana]] (Part 2: 23.5-7). The account itself is very similar to that of the [[Brahmanda Purana]] (see above). Part 2 also contains detailed information on the [[Manu (Hinduism)|Manus]] and [[Saptarishi]].\n\n=== Vishnu Purana ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" |[[Vishnu Purana|VIshnu]]\n!References\n!Notes\n|-\n|'''Book 1:''' 4;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/vp/vp038.htm|title=The Vishnu Purana: Book I: Chapter IV|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-18}}</ref> '''Book 2:''' 2;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/vp/vp059.htm|title=The Vishnu Purana: Book II: Chapter II|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-18}}</ref> '''Book 3:''' --; '''Book 4:''' 1;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/vp/vp093.htm|title=The Vishnu Purana: Book IV: Chapter I|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-18}}</ref> '''Book 5:'''  --; '''Book 6:''' --;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/vp/index.htm|title=The Vishnu Purana Index|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-18}}</ref>\n|No notable mentions.\n|}\n\n{{quote|<poem>From the right thumb of [[Brahma|Brahm\u00e1]] was born the patriarch [[Daksha]]; his daughter was [[Aditi]], who was the mother of the sun. The Manu [[Shraddhadeva Manu|Vaivaswata]] was the son of the celestial luminary [<nowiki/>[[Surya]]]; and his sons were [[Ikshvaku|Ikshw\u00e1ku]], Nriga, Dhrisht\u0301a, \u015aary\u00e1ti, Narishyanta, Pr\u00e1n\u015bu, N\u00e1bh\u00e1ga, Nedisht\u0301a, Kar\u00fasha, and Prishadhra. Before their birth, the Manu being desirous of sons, offered a sacrifice for that purpose to [[Mitra]] and [[Varuna|Varu\u0144a]]; but the rite being deranged, through an irregularity of the ministering priest, a daughter, [[Ila (Hinduism)|Il\u00e1]], was produced. Through the favour of the two divinities, however, her sex was changed, and she became a man, named Sudyumna. \n\nAt a subsequent period, in consequence of becoming subject to the effects of a malediction once pronounced by [[Shiva|\u015aiva]], Sudyumna was again transformed to a woman in the vicinity of the hermitage of [[Budha]], the son of the deity of the [[Soma (deity)|moon]]. Budha saw and espoused her, and had by her a son named [[Pururavas|Pur\u00faravas]]. After his birth, the illustrious [[Rishi|Rishis]], desirous of restoring Sudyumna to his sex, prayed to the mighty [[Vishnu|Vish\u0144u]], who is the essence of the four [[Vedas]], of mind, of every thing, and of nothing; and who is in the form of the sacrificial male; and through his favour Il\u00e1 once more became Sudyumna, in which character he had three sons, Utkala, Gaya, and Vinata.</poem>|source=Vishnu Purana, translated by Horace Hayman Wilson (1840), Book IV, Chapter 1}}It seems the legend of Matsya is not narrated in the [[Vishnu Purana]]. As quoted above, the aspect of [[Shraddhadeva Manu|Vaivasvata]] performing a sacrifice and producing a \"daughter\" called Ida/[[Ila (Hinduism)|Ila]] from the original legend in the [[Shatapatha Brahmana]] is mentioned, albeit as a separate legend and in a modified form; it seems to contain elements also found in the [[Matsya Purana|Matsya]], [[Padma Purana|Padma]], and [[Skanda Purana|Skanda Puranas]], although Ila being produced due to a mistake by the ministering priest at the [[sacrifice]] seems to be shared only with the [[Bhagavata Purana]].\n\n== Upa-Puranas ==\n\n=== Vishnudharmottara ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" |[[Vishnudharmottara Purana|Vishnudharmottara]]\n!References\n!Notes\n|-\n|Adhyaya 32, 85.58-59, 106, 118.6;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.127780|title=Shri Vishnudharmottara|last=Shah|first=priyabala}}</ref>\n|This is [[Upapurana]] is a supplement to the [[Vishnu Purana]].\n|}\n\n* The Ardhacandra [[Mudra]] [symbolic hand gesture; palm open, fingers extended together, and thumb up like a fish-fin] signifies Matsya (Adhyaya 32)\n* Images of Matsya should depict Him with a horn (Adhyaya 85.58-59)\n* The Mantra of Matsya is 'I shall invoke god Matsya moving in the sea. O Matsya deva, the sustainer of the lives of the world, O infallible, kindly come' (Adhyaya 106)\n* Men 'desirous of grains' should worship Matsya (Adhyaya 118.6)\n\n==Iconography==\n[[File:Matsya Avatar, ca 1870.jpg|thumb|Matsya pulls Manu's boat after having defeated the demon (circa 1870)|alt=|left]]\n\nMatsya is depicted in two forms: as a [[zoomorphic]] fish or in an [[anthropomorphic]] form. In the latter form, the upper half is that of the four-armed man and the lower half is a fish. The upper half resembles Vishnu and wears the traditional ornaments and the ''kirita-makuta'' (tall conical crown) as worn by Vishnu. He holds in two of his hands the ''[[Sudarshana chakra]]'' (discus) and a ''[[shankha]]'' (conch), the usual weapons of Vishnu. The other two hands make the gestures of ''[[varadamudra]]'', which grants boons to the devotee, and ''[[abhayamudra]]'', which reassures the devotee of protection.<ref>Rao p. 127</ref> In another configuration, he might have all four attributes of Vishnu, namely the ''Sudarshana chakra'', a ''shankha'', a [[gada (weapon)|gada]] (mace) and a lotus.<ref name=\"Dalal2011\">{{cite book|author=Roshen Dalal|title=Hinduism: An Alphabetical Guide|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DH0vmD8ghdMC&pg=PA250|accessdate=12 January 2013|year= 2011|publisher=Penguin Books India|isbn=978-0-14-341421-6|page=250}}</ref> \n\nIn some representations, Matsya is shown with four hands like Vishnu, one holding the chakra, another the shankha, while the front two hands hold a sword and a book signifying the Vedas he recovered from the demon. Over his elbows is an angavastra draped, while a ''dhoti'' like draping covers his hips.<ref name=\"MuseumDallapiccola2010\">{{cite book|author1=British Museum|author2=Anna Libera Dallapiccola|title=South Indian Paintings: A Catalogue of the British Museum Collection|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FIzWapiacQcC&pg=PA78|accessdate=13 January 2013|year=2010|publisher=Mapin Publishing Pvt Ltd|isbn=978-0-7141-2424-7|pages=78, 117, 125}}</ref>\n\nIn rare representations, his lower half is human while the upper body (or just the face) is of a fish. The fish-face version is found in a relief at the [[Chennakesava Temple, Somanathapura]].<ref>[http://www.art-and-archaeology.com/india/mysore/kes09.html Hindu Temple, Somnathpur]</ref>\n\nMatsya may be depicted alone or in a scene depicting his combat with a demon. A demon called Shankhasura emerging from a conch is sometimes depicted attacking Matsya with a sword as Matsya combats or kills him. Both of them may be depicted in the ocean, while the god Brahma and/or manuscripts or four men, symbolizing the Vedas, may be depicted in the background.<ref name=\"MuseumDallapiccola2010\"/>\n\n==Comparative mythology==\n\n{{main|Flood myth}}[[File:15th-16th century Vaishnavism Vitthala temple Matsya avatar, Hampi Hindu monuments Karnataka.jpg|thumb|Matsya temples are relatively rare, but the iconography is found in Hindu temple reliefs. Above: Matsya on a mandapa pillar in [[Hampi]].]]\nThe story of a great deluge is found in many civilizations across the earth. It is often related to the [[Genesis flood narrative|Genesis narrative]] of the flood and [[Noah's Ark]].<ref name=\"Dalal2011\" /> The fish motif reminds readers of the Biblical 'Jonah and the Whale' narrative as well;  this fish narrative, as well as the saving of the scriptures from a demon, are specifically Hindu traditions of this style of the flood narrative.{{sfn|Krishna|2009|p=35}} Similar flood myths also exist in tales from ancient [[Sumerian creation myth|Sumer]] and Babylonia, [[Deucalion|Greece]], the [[Maya peoples|Maya]] of Americas and the [[Yoruba people|Yoruba]] of Africa.<ref name=\"Dalal2011\" />\n\nMatsya is believed to symbolise the aquatic life as the first beings on earth.<ref name = \"Krishna36\">Krishna p. 36</ref> Another symbolic interpretation of the Matsya mythology is, states Bonnefoy, to consider Manu's boat to represent [[moksha]] (salvation), which helps one to cross over. The Himalayas are treated as a boundary between the earthly existence and land of salvation beyond. The protection of the fish and its horn represent the sacrifices that help guide Manu to salvation. Treated as a parable, the tale advises a good king should protect the weak from the mighty, reversing the \"law of fishes\" and uphold [[dharma]], like Manu, who defines an ideal king.{{sfn|Bonnefoy|1993|pp= 79-80}} In the tales where the demon hides the Vedas, dharma is threatened and Vishnu as the divine Saviour rescues dharma, aided by his earthly counterpart, Manu - the king.{{sfn|Bonnefoy|1993|p= 80}}\n\n==Worship and significance==\n===India===\nThere are very few temples dedicated to Matsya. Prominent ones include the Shankhodara temple in [[Bet Dwarka]] and [[Vedanarayana Temple, Nagalapuram|Vedanarayana Temple]] in [[Nagalapuram]].<ref name = \"Krishna36\"/> The [[Koneswaram temple|Koneswaram Matsyakeswaram temple in]] [[Trincomalee]] is now destroyed. [[Matsya Narayana Temple, Bangalore]] also exists.\n\nSome kingdoms have used sacred matsya as their state [[emblem]]. There was a [[Matsya Kingdom]] during [[vedic era]], which was one of the sixteen [[Mahajanapadas]] (great kingdoms) during as described in the hindu epic [[Mahabharta]] and 6th BCE Buddhist text ''Anguttara Nikaya''. After the [[Partition of India|Indian independence]] in 1947, the [[princely state]]s of [[Bharatpur State|Bharatpur]], [[Dholpur State|Dholpur]], [[Alwar State|Alwar]] and [[Karauli State|Karauli]] were temporarily put together from 1947 to 1949 as the ''\"United State of Matsya\"'', and later in March 1949 after these princely states signed the [[Instrument of Accession]] they were merged with the present state of [[Rajasthan]].<ref>[https://nwr.indianrailways.gov.in/uploads/files/1416202359797-Tourist%20Places.pdf NWR tourist places]</ref> '''Matsya Festival''' is held in [[Alwar]] every year in the last week of November to celebrate culture and adventure.<ref>[https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/travel/destinations/all-about-alwar-matsya-festival-2018/as66707230.cms All about Alwar Matsya Festival 2018], [[Times of India]], November 2018.</ref>\n\n===Korea===\n[[Jogyesa]] Buddhist Temple has [[Jogyesa#Layout|colorful matsya relics]].<ref>2011, [http://lib.perdana.org.my/PLF/PLF2/Digital_Content/PLF/000017/1008593.pdf World Mythology], Pustaka Perdana, Parragon, UK</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Apkallu]]\n*[[Dashavatara]]\n*[[Flood myth]]\n*[[Rishabhanatha]]\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|first=Yves|last= Bonnefoy|title=Asian Mythologies|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=r4I-FsZCzJEC|date=15 May 1993|publisher=University of Chicago Press|isbn=978-0-226-06456-7}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|first=Nanditha |last= Krishna|title=The Book of Vishnu|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=f9cSlaLMlgEC |year=2009|publisher=Penguin Books India|isbn=978-0-14-306762-7}}\n* {{cite book|last=Rao|first=T.A. Gopinatha|title=Elements of Hindu iconography |volume=1: Part I|year=1914|publisher=Law Printing House|location=Madras|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|author=George M. Williams|title=Handbook of Hindu Mythology|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=N7LOZfwCDpEC|year=2008|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-533261-2}}\n* {{cite book | last = Mani | first = Vettam | title = Puranic Encyclopaedia: a Comprehensive Dictionary with Special Reference to the Epic and Puranic Literature | url = https://archive.org/details/puranicencyclopa00maniuoft | publisher = Motilal Banarsidass Publishers | year = 1975 <!-- | location = Delhi --> | isbn = 978-0-8426-0822-0 | authorlink = Vettam Mani }}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Matsya}}\n\n{{VishnuAvatars}}\n{{HinduMythology}}\n\n[[Category:Fish gods]]\n[[Category:Forms of Vishnu]]\n[[Category:Flood myths]]\n[[Category:Mythological human hybrids]]\n[[Category:Water and Hinduism]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|fish form of the Hindu god Vishnu}}\n{{other uses}}\n{{EngvarB|date=March 2017}} \n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2017}}\n{{Infobox deity<!--Wikipedia:WikiProject Hindu mythology-->\n| type        = Hindu\n| image       = Matsya avatar.jpg\n| caption     = Half-human and Half-Fish depiction of [[Vishnu]]\n| name        = Matsya\n| Devanagari  = \u092e\u0924\u094d\u0938\u094d\u092f\n| affiliation = [[Vishnu]] (first [[avatar]]) \n| weapon      = None\n| abode = [[Kuru Kingdom]], [[Patala]]\n| mantra  = 'I shall invoke god Matsya moving in the sea. O Matsya Deva, the sustainer of the lives of the world, O infallible, kindly come' ([[Vishnudharmottara Purana]], Adhyaya 106)\n| consort = None \n| god_of= \n| children= None\n| symbols= Three dots (e.g. on a long, crystalline-coloured [[salagrama]])\n| festivals = Matsya Jayanti: Pancami (fifth day) in the bright half of the month of [[Chaitra]]\n}}\n{{Vaishnavism}}\n{{Hindu scriptures and texts}}\n'''Matsya''' ({{lang-sa|\u092e\u0924\u094d\u0938\u094d\u092f}}, lit. ''fish'')<!--Do not remove, WP:INDICSCRIPT doesn't apply to WikiProject Hinduism--> is an [[avatar]] of the [[Rigvedic deities|RigVedic]] god [[Vishnu]]. Originating in the White [[Yajurveda|YajurVeda]] ([[Shatapatha Brahmana]]), Matsya is most commonly associated in post-Vedic literature such as the [[Puranas]] with the legends of rescuing [[Shraddhadeva Manu|Vaivasvata Manu]] from the [[Flood myth|deluge]], and rescuing the [[Vedas]] stolen by various [[Asura|Asuras]]. Matsya is listed as the first incarnation of the [[Dashavatara]], the ten principal avatars of Vishnu. \n\nMatsya iconography sometimes is [[Zoomorphism|zoomorphic]] as a giant fish with a horn, or [[Anthropomorphism|anthropomorphic]] in the form of a human torso connected to the rear half of a fish.<ref>Rao p. 127</ref>{{sfn|Bonnefoy|1993|pp=79-80}}\n\n==Etymology==\n'Mastya' is derived from 'matsa' (\u092e\u0924\u094d\u0938) meaning 'Fish',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://spokensanskrit.org/index.php?mode=3&script=hk&tran_input=matsa&direct=au&anz=100|title=Sanskrit Dictionary for Spoken Sanskrit: 'matsa'|last=|first=|date=|website=spokensanskrit.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-05}}</ref> itself derived from the root 'mad' (or 'mat', \u092e\u0924), meaning 'religion', 'counsel', 'knowledge', and 'religious doctrine'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://spokensanskrit.org/index.php?tran_input=mATha&direct=se&script=hk&link=yes&mode=3|title=Sanskrit Dictionary for Spoken Sanskrit|website=spokensanskrit.org|access-date=2020-01-05}}</ref>  The term 'Matsya' also appears in the ''[[Rigveda]]''.<ref name=mmwmatsya/> It is related to ''maccha'', which also means fish.<ref name=mmwmatsya>Monier Monier-Williams, Sanskrit-English Dictionary and Etymology, Oxford University Press, pages 776-777</ref> R. Franco states that [[Etymology|etymologically]], 'Matsa' means 'gay [joyous] one' or 'Fish', and is derived from (square brackets '[ ]' as per the original author):\n\n* '''<nowiki/>'Mad'''', meaning 'to be excited by joy', 'to savor food and drink [ad] to the absolute limit of their flavour [m]', and 'to get drunk', and\n* '''<nowiki/>'sa'''', meaning 'effect of the action [a] of binding to [s]', 'union', 'with', 'similar', or 'together'..<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=KphVAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA383&lpg=PA383&dq=sanskrit+'mad'+the+gay+one#v=onepage&q=sanskrit%20'mad'%20the%20gay%20one&f=false|title=Comparative etymological Dictionary of classical Indo-European languages: Indo-European - Sanskrit - Greek - Latin|last=Franco|first=Rendich|date=2013-12-14|publisher=Rendich Franco|isbn=|location=|pages=383, 555\u2013556|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe Monier-Williams [[Sanskrit]] Dictionary agrees with Franco.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sanskritdictionary.com/?q=matsya%22&lang=sans&iencoding=iast&action=Search|title=Sanskrit Dictionary:'Matsya'|last=|first=|date=|website=sanskritdictionary.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sanskritdictionary.com/?q=matsa&iencoding=iast&lang=sans|title=Sanskrit Dictionary: 'matsa'|last=|first=|date=|website=sanskritdictionary.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-05}}</ref> According to the [[Nirukta]], an ancient ancillary text to the [[Vedas]]:\n\n{{quote|O [[\u00c2dityas|Adityas]]. run to us while we are still alive, i.e. before we are slain; where are you, the hearers of our invocations? It is known to be the composition of the fish caught in a net. The fish are (so called because) they float in water, or they revel in eating each other. Net is (so called) because it moves in water, or it is set in water, or it lies in water.|source=The Nirukta, translated by  Lakshman Sarup (1967), Chapter 6, Section 27 (pp.108; English section)<ref name=\":16\">{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/TheNighantuAndTheNirukta|title=The Nighantu And The Nirukta|last=Lakshman Sarup|first=|date=1967|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=26, 108 (footnote 3)|language=English}}</ref>}}\n\nSarup, the [[Translation|translator]], elaborates for the above section (6.27; footnote 3), stating 'Matsyah (fish) is derived from [the root word] \u221a''syand'' (to float) and ''madhu'' (water)'. The Monier-Williams [[Sanskrit]] Dictionary does not seem to agree however, as although 'madhu' does mean 'water' (and [[Soma (drink)|'soma']], 'milk', and 'honey'),<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sanskritdictionary.com/?iencoding=iast&q=madhu&lang=sans&action=Search|title=Sanskrit Dictionary|last=|first=|date=|website=sanskritdictionary.com: 'madhu'|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-05}}</ref> 'syand' means 'to trickle or flow'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sanskritdictionary.com/?iencoding=iast&q=syand&lang=sans&action=Search|title=Sanskrit Dictionary: 'syand'|last=|first=|date=|website=sanskritdictionary.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-05}}</ref> The four etymological definitions of 'Matsya' are therefore:\n\n* '''Sanskrit Dictionary:''' 'religion, or religious doctrine'\n* '''Franco:''' 'Union or binding in joy or intoxication'\n* '''The Nirukta:''' 'Floating in water' \n* '''Monier-Williams (Sarup's breakdown):''' 'the trickle or flow of water, Soma, milk, or honey'\n\n=== Horn ===\nMatsya is depicted as possessing a horn (e.g. which the ship of Manu is tied to), and according to the [[Nirukta]]:\n\n{{quote|''Srnga'' (horn) is derived from (the root) ''Sri'' (to rest on), or from ''sr'' (to slay), or from sam (to destroy); or (it is so called because) it grows up to protect, or it comes out of the head.|source=The Nirukta, translated by\u00a0 Lakshman Sarup (1967), Chapter 2, Section 7 (pp. 26, English section)<ref name=\":16\" />|author=|title=}}\n\n== Symbolism ==\n\n'''Cosmogonic creation and dissolution:''' J. Roy states in the [[Rigveda|RigVeda]], water represents 'the first principle of creation [<nowiki/>[[purusha]]]... Thus, the story of deluge and the fish-god, even though of foreign [e.g. [[Enki|Babylonian]] or [[Hatmehit|Egyptian]]] origin, finds a parallel in the [[Vedas|Vedic]] and [[Puranas|Puranic]] [[Cosmogony|cosmogonic]] myth, representing the universe emerging out of waters'. In regards to dissolution, Roy adds that in 'the [[Itihasa|epic]] and [[Puranas|Puranic]] versions of the legend of [[Flood myth|deluge]], the great flood [[Allegory|allegorizes]] dissolution of the world. The Fish incarnation is thus rightly enumerated as the first incarnation, [[Allegory|allegorizing]] [[Brahma]] or [[Narayana]], who creates the world anew after dissolution'.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=lr9pFQPwhXYC&pg=PA95&lpg=PA95&dq=Atharva+Veda+varaha+boar#v=onepage&q=matsya&f=false|title=Theory of Avat\u0101ra and Divinity of Chaitanya|last=Roy|first=Janmajit|date=2002|publisher=Atlantic Publishers & Dist|isbn=978-81-269-0169-2|location=|pages=79\u201385|language=en}}</ref>\n\n'''Astronomy:''' Roy also states that it 'has been suggested that the boat of [[Shraddhadeva Manu|Manu]] and the Fish in the epico-[[Puranas|puranic]] legend [[Allegory|allegorically]] represent the [[constellation]] of [[Ursa Major]] and [[Ursa Minor|Urda Minor]] respectively. The legend is construed as pointing to a remote period of antiquity when [[Thuban|Alpha Draconis]] was the [[Pole star|Pole Star]]'.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n'''Sacrifice:''' N. Aiyangar states that in 'the Rig-veda the idea that [[Yajna|Sacrifice]] is [a] Ship is expressed in many places... As thus Sacrifice is metaphorically called Ship and as [[Manu (Hinduism)|Manu]] means man, the thinker, the story [of Matsya] seems to be a [[parable]] of the Ship of Sacrifice being the means for man's crossing the sea of his duritas, [i.e. his] sins, and troubles'. In regards to Matsya, Auyangar states that the 'Supreme self [<nowiki/>[[\u0100tman (Hinduism)|Atman]]] is found as a small fish... thus cultivated and realised [to a big fish, it] is able to conduct the Ship of Sacrifice across the sea of the Duritas of the selfish world of strife'. Ida is also stated to 'represent here the blessedness of mind-born \u015araddh\u0101, Faith'.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.217324|title=Essays On Indo Aryan Mythology|last=Narayan Aiyangar|date=1901|publisher=|isbn=|location=|pages=121\u2013124}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wisdomlib.org/definition/durita|title=Durita, Dur-ita: 6 definitions|last=www.wisdomlib.org|date=2014-08-03|website=www.wisdomlib.org|access-date=2019-12-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wisdomlib.org/definition/shraddha|title=Shraddha, \u015ar\u0101ddha, \u015araddh\u0101, \u015araddha: 21 definitions|last=www.wisdomlib.org|date=2014-09-09|website=www.wisdomlib.org|access-date=2019-12-29}}</ref>\n\n'''Deluge / Historical Fact:''' T.W. Munro states that the 'deluge, in this land [Dravida country, [[South India]]] is both [[Astronomy|astronomically]] and [[Geology|geologically]] an accomplished fact'. Munro adds that although the accounts of the deluge were considered 'a merely fanciful tissue of imagination from the brains of fanciful men', one of those incorrectly believing the deluge to be 'fanciful', [[William Jones (philologist)|Sir William Jones]], 'very properly corrected his former error' after travelling to [[India]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.123134|title=A Handbook Of Hindu Mythology And Philosophy With Some Biographical Notices|last=Taylor|first=W. Munro|date=1870|publisher=|isbn=|location=|pages=74\u201375}}</ref>\n\n== The Vedas ==\nJ. Roy states that the 'earliest reference to\u00a0the legend of the fish [Matsya] occurs in the [[Shatapatha Brahmana|Satapatha Brahmana]] [White [[Yajurveda|YajurVeda]]] though not as an incarnation of any particular deity... [and is] believed to be of [[Babylon|Babylonian]] origin by many scholars'.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Rig Veda ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! rowspan=\"3\" |[[Rigveda|Rig]]\n!\n!References\n!Notes\n|-\n|Samhita\n|'''Manu:'''  1.76.5,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/rigveda/rv01076.htm|title=Rig Veda: Rig-Veda Book 1: HYMN LXXVI. Agni.|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-08}}</ref> 7.100.4,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/rigveda/rv07100.htm|title=Rig Veda: Rig-Veda, Book 7: HYMN C. Vi\u1e63\u1e47u.|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-21}}</ref> 10.63.7,<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/rigveda/rv10063.htm|title=Rig Veda: Rig-Veda, Book 10: HYMN LXIII. Vi\u015bvedevas.|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-08}}</ref> 10.164.2;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/rigveda/rv10164.htm|title=Rig Veda: Rig-Veda, Book 10: HYMN CLXIV. Dream-charm.|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-08}}</ref> '''Ship:''' 10.44.6,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/rigveda/rv10044.htm|title=Rig Veda: Rig-Veda, Book 10: HYMN XLIV. Indra.|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-08}}</ref> 10.63.10;<ref name=\":4\" />  '''Ida/Ila:''' 1.13.9,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/rigveda/rv01013.htm|title=Rig Veda: Rig-Veda Book 1: HYMN XIII. Agni|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-08}}</ref> (teacher of men) 1.31.11,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/rigveda/rv01031.htm|title=Rig Veda: Rig-Veda Book 1: HYMN XXXI. Agni.|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-10}}</ref> 1.142.8-9,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/rigveda/rv01142.htm|title=Rig Veda: Rig-Veda Book 1: HYMN CXLII. \u0100pr\u012bs.|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-08}}</ref> 3.4.8,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/rigveda/rv03004.htm|title=Rig Veda: Rig-Veda, Book 3: HYMN IV \u0100pr\u012bs.|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-08}}</ref> 7.2.8,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/rigveda/rv07002.htm|title=Rig Veda: Rig-Veda, Book 7: HYMN II. \u0100pr\u012bs.|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-08}}</ref> (foot drops oil) 10.70.8,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/rigveda/rv10070.htm|title=Rig Veda: Rig-Veda, Book 10: HYMN LXX. \u0100pr\u012bs.|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-08}}</ref> 10.95.18<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/rigveda/rv10095.htm|title=Rig Veda: Rig-Veda, Book 10: HYMN XCV. Urvasi. Pur\u016bravas.|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-08}}</ref>, 10.110.8<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/rigveda/rv10110.htm|title=Rig Veda: Rig-Veda, Book 10: HYMN CX. \u0100pr\u012bs.|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-08}}</ref>\n|'''Ida/Ila:''' Most verses are about being invoked at [[Yajna|sacrifice]] by two [[Vedic priesthood|Hotars]]. '''Ship:''' 10.63.10 is quoted by the [[Taittiriya Samhita]].\n|-\n|[[Aitareya Brahmana]]\n|'''Manu:''' 8.2.7 '''Ship:''' 6.4.21<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.281986|title=The Aitareya Brahmanam Of The Rigveda Vol Ii|last=B D Basu|date=1899|publisher=|isbn=|location=|pages=281 (Ship), 347 (Manu)}}</ref>\n|\n|}{{Verse translation|yebhyo hotr\u0101\u1e43 pratham\u0101m\u0101yeje manu\u1e25 samiddh\u0101ghnirmanas\u0101sapta hot\u1e5bbhi\u1e25 {{!}}\nta \u0101dity\u0101 abhaya\u1e43 \u015barma yachata sugh\u0101 na\u1e25karta supath\u0101 svastaye {{!}}{{!}}...\n\n\nsutr\u0101m\u0101\u1e47a\u1e43 p\u1e5bthiv\u012b\u1e43 dy\u0101manehasa\u1e43 su\u015barm\u0101\u1e47amaditi\u1e43supra\u1e47\u012btim {{!}}\ndaiv\u012b\u1e43 n\u0101va\u1e43 svaritr\u0101man\u0101ghasamasravant\u012bm\u0101 ruhem\u0101 svastaye {{!}}{{!}}|Ye to whom Manu, by seven priests, with kindled fire, offered the first oblation with his heart and soul,\nVouchsafe us, ye \u0100dityas, shelter free from fear, and make us good and easy paths to happiness...\n\nMightily-saving Earth, incomparable Heaven the good guide [[Aditi]] who gives secure defence\nThe well-oared heavenly Ship that lets no waters in, free from defect, will we ascend for happiness.|lang=en|attr1=RigVeda [[transliteration]] of Book 10, Hymn 63, Verses 7 and 10<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/rvsan/rv10063.htm|title=RigVeda Book X LXIII 'Vi\u015bvedevas' (Sanskrit and Transliteration)|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-07}}</ref>|attr2=RigVeda [[translation]] by Ralph T.H. Griffith (1896) of Book 10, Hymn 63, Verses 7 and 10<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/rigveda/rv10063.htm|title=RigVeda Book X LXIII 'Vi\u015bvedevas'|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-07}}</ref>}}\n\nV. Mani states that the [[Manu (Hinduism)|'''Manu''']] (\u092e\u0928\u0941)<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://spokensanskrit.org/index.php?tran_input=manu&direct=se&script=hk&link=yes&mode=3|title=Sanskrit Dictionary for Spoken Sanskrit: 'Manu'|last=|first=|date=|website=spokensanskrit.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-07}}</ref> is [[Shraddhadeva Manu|Vaivasvata]] (also known as Satyavrata or Shraddhadeva), son of the sun-god [[Surya|Vivasvan]] (Surya), grandson of [[Kashyapa|Kasyapa]] and [[Aditi]], and the seventh of fourteen total Manus of the current ([[Varaha]]) [[Kalpa (aeon)|Kalpa]].<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/puranicencyclopa00maniuoft|title=Puranic encyclopaedia : a comprehensive dictionary with special reference to the epic and Puranic literature|last=Mani|first=Vettam|date=1975|publisher=Delhi : Motilal Banarsidass|others=Robarts - University of Toronto|isbn=|location=|pages=79}}</ref> M. Dhavamony states that in the [[Rigveda|RigVeda]], the most important hero 'is Manu ('man') the first man, the ancestor of the human race and the first sacrificer... He it was who, having kindled the fire, presented the first offering with seven priests [<nowiki/>[[Saptarishi]]] to the gods [RigVeda 10.3.67]... Thus manu's sacrifice becomes the prototype and exemplary model of all other sacrifices [RigVeda 1.76.5]'.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=DD0w_IMFA8gC&pg=PA114&lpg=PA114&dq=Rig+Veda+ship+manu#v=onepage&q=Rig%20Veda%20ship%20manu&f=false|title=Classical Hinduism|last=Dhavamony|first=Mariasusai|date=1982|publisher=Gregorian Biblical BookShop|isbn=978-88-7652-482-0|location=|pages=112\u2013113|language=en}}</ref>\n\nNotably, the account of Manu's first offering with the [[Saptarishi]] - seven sages - also mentions ascending in a 'well-oared heavenly ship'. The belief of Aiyangar (as above, see Symbolism section) in the metaphorical 'ship of sacrifice'<ref name=\":3\" /> is further supported by the [[Aitareya Brahmana]], an exposition of [[Yajna|sacrificial]] rites attached to the [[Rigveda|RigVeda]] (Book 6, Chapter 4, Section 21):\n\n<nowiki/>{{quote|(The repetition of these [[Tristubh|Tristubhs]] by the minor Hotri-priests is, however, necessary). He ought to know, \u201cthese Tristubhs are the helm (pratipad) of my hymns,\u201d just as (one requires a helm) if crossing the sea. For those who perform a session lasting for a year or the [[Dvadasaha]], are floating like those who cross the sea. Just as those who wish to land on the shore enter a ship having plenty of provisions, in the same manner the sacrificers should enter (i.e., begin with) these Tristubhs.'|source=Aitareya Brahmana translated by B.D. Basu (1899), Sixth Book, Chapter 4 ('The Sampata hymns. The Valakhilyas. TheDurohanam'.)|sign=}}\n\nIt is also stated that 'Over this earth with mighty step strode [[Vishnu|Vi\u1e63\u1e47u]], ready to give it for a home to Manu' (RigVeda 7.100.4). D.M. Knipe states [[Ila (Hinduism)|'''Ida''']] (\u0907\u0921\u093e)<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://spokensanskrit.org/index.php?tran_input=iDA&direct=se&script=hk&link=yes&mode=3|title=Sanskrit Dictionary for Spoken Sanskrit: 'ida'|last=|first=|date=|website=spokensanskrit.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-07}}</ref> is 'a personification of [[Yajna|sacrificial]] remnants'.<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=QedcBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA264&lpg=PA264&dq=Id%C3%A2+veda#v=onepage&q=Id%C3%A2%20veda&f=false|title=Vedic Voices: Intimate Narratives of a Living Andhra Tradition|last=Knipe|first=David M.|date=2015|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-939769-3|location=|pages=264|language=en}}</ref> J. Dowson elaborates that in 'the [[Rigveda|RigVeda]], [[Ila (Hinduism)|Ida]] is primarily food, refreshment, or a libation of milk; thence a stream of praise, personified as the goddess of speech'.<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.83638|title=Classical Dictionary Of Hindu Mythology And Religion Etc|last=John Dowson|date=1903|publisher=|isbn=|location=|pages=122}}</ref> G.M. Williams agrees, stating 'ida was a word for food or refreshment, especially milk... [and] worked metaphorically as the refreshment given to the [[Deva (Hinduism)|devas]] (gods) as praise'.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9791576071068|url-access=registration|quote=Id\u00e2.|title=Handbook of Hindu Mythology|last=Williams|first=George Mason|date=2003|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-1-57607-106-9|location=|pages=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9791576071068/page/155 155]|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the [[Monier Monier-Williams|Monier-Williams]] [[Sanskrit]] Dictionary, '''Ida''' is also [[Synonym|synonymous]] with '''Ila,''' as the daughter of Manu, as the Earth, the cow, praise (to the gods, i.e. prayer), the goddess of speech, and as the [[Yajna|sacrificial]] offering/libation 'consisting of four preparations of milk, poured into a vessel containing water, and then partially drunk by the priest and sacrificers; [Ida/Ila is also] personified in the cow, the symbol of feeding, and nourishment'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sanskritdictionary.com/?q=i%E1%B8%8D%C4%81|title=Sanskrit Dictionary: 'Ida'|last=|first=|date=|website=www.sanskritdictionary.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-08}}</ref><ref name=\":14\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sanskritdictionary.com/?q=i%E1%B8%B7%C4%81&iencoding=&lang=|title=Sanskrit Dictionary: 'Ila'|last=|first=|date=|website=www.sanskritdictionary.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-08}}</ref> Notably, Ida/Ila is also stated in the RigVeda to be the mother of King [[Pururavas]] (10.95.18),<ref name=\":10\" /> from whom the [[Pandavas]] ([[Arjuna]] and his brothers are cousins of [[Krishna]]) and [[Kauravas]] descend. In the following verse, Ida/Ila is associated with sacrifice:{{Verse translation|mandrajihv\u0101 jughurva\u1e47\u012b '''hot\u0101r\u0101''' daivy\u0101 kav\u012b <nowiki>|</nowiki>\n'''yaj\u00f1a\u1e43''' no yak\u1e63at\u0101mima\u1e43 sidhramadya divisp\u1e5b\u015bam <nowiki>||</nowiki>\n\n\u015bucirdeve\u1e63varpit\u0101 hotr\u0101 marutsu bh\u0101rat\u012b <nowiki>|</nowiki>\n'''i\u1e37\u0101''' sarasvat\u012b mah\u012b barhi\u1e25 s\u012bdantu yaj\u00f1iy\u0101\u1e25 <nowiki>||</nowiki>|May the two '''Priests''' Divine, the sage, the sweet-voiced lovers of the hymn,\nComplete this '''sacrifice''' of ours, effectual, reaching heaven to-day.\n\nLet Hotr\u0101 pure, set among Gods, amid the Maruts Bh\u0101rat\u012b, \n'''I\u1e37\u0101''', Sarasvat\u012b, Mah\u012b, rest on the grass, adorable.|lang=en|attr1=RigVeda [[transliteration]] of Book 1, Hymn 142, Verses 8-9<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/rvsan/rv01142.htm|title=RigVeda Book I CXLII '\u0100pr\u012bs' (Sanskrit and Transliteration)|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-07}}</ref>|attr2=RigVeda [[translation]] by Ralph T.H. Griffith (1896) of  Book 1, Hymn 142, Verses 8-9<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/rigveda/rv01142.htm|title=RigVeda Book I CXLII '\u0100pr\u012bs'|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-08}}</ref>}}\n\n=== Sama Veda ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" |[[Samaveda|Sama]]\n!References\n!Notes\n|-\n|'''Manu: Part 1:''' 1.1.5.10, 1.2.4.10; '''Part 2:''' 2.2.18.2, 6.1.1.4<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/sv.htm|title=Hymns of the Samaveda|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-08}}</ref> \n|1.1.5.10 means Book 1, Capter 1, Decade 5, Verse 10.\n|}\n\n=== Yajur Veda ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! rowspan=\"4\" |[[Yajurveda|Yajur]]\n! colspan=\"3\" |References\n!Notes\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |'''[[Yajurveda#Shukla Yajurveda|\u015aukla (White) Shakha]]''' \n|Vajasaneyi Samhita\n|24.21,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/wyv/wyvbk24.htm|title=White Yajur Veda: Book XXIV|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-05}}</ref> 24.21, 24.34<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/wyv/wyvbk24.htm|title=White Yajur Veda: Book XXIV|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-05}}</ref>\n|\n|-\n|[[Shatapatha Brahmana]]\n|'''Matsya:''' 1.8.1;<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/sbr/sbe12/sbe1234.htm|title=Satapatha Brahmana Part 1 (SBE12): First K\u00e2nda: I, 8, 1. Eighth Adhy\u00e2ya. First Br\u00e2hmana|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2019-12-28}}</ref> '''Ida:''' 1.7.4.19,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/sbr/sbe12/sbe1233.htm|title=Satapatha Brahmana Part 1 (SBE12): First K\u00e2nda: I, 7, 4. Fourth Br\u00e2hmana|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-06}}</ref> 1.8.1.16,<ref name=\":1\" /> '''Domestic Offering:''' 2.3.1.21;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/sbr/sbe12/sbe1248.htm|title=Satapatha Brahmana Part 1 (SBE12): Second K\u00e2nda: II, 3, 1. Third Adhy\u00e2ya. First Br\u00e2hmana|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-06}}</ref> '''King Matsya Sammada:''' 13.4.3.12,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/sbr/sbe44/sbe44104.htm|title=Satapatha Brahmana Part V (SBE44): Thirteenth K\u00e2nda: XIII, 4, 3. Third Br\u00e2hmana|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-06}}</ref> (Dhvasan Dvaitavana) 13.5.4.9<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/sbr/sbe44/sbe44109.htm|title=Satapatha Brahmana Part V (SBE44): Thirteenth K\u00e2nda: XIII, 5, 4. Fourth Br\u00e2hmana|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-06}}</ref>\n|Citations other than 1.8.1 refer to King Matsya.\n|-\n|[[Taittiriya Shakha|'''Taittiriya (Black) Shakha''']]\n|[[Taittiriya Samhita]]\n|'''Ship:''' 1.5.11.5,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/yv/yv01.htm|title=Yajur Veda Kanda I|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-07}}</ref> '''Ida:''' 1.7.1,<ref name=\":13\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/yv/yv01.htm|title=Yajur Veda Kanda I|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-06}}</ref> 2.6.7;<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/yv/yv02.htm|title=Yajur Veda Kanda II|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-06}}</ref> '''Fish:''' 2.6.6,<ref name=\":2\" /> 5.5.13<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/yv/yv05.htm|title=Yajur Veda Kanda V|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-06}}</ref>\n|1.5.11.5 quotes [[Rigveda|RigVeda]] 10.63.10\n|}\n\n==== Shukla (White) Yajurveda ====\n{{See also|Shatapatha Brahmana}}{{Quote|<poem>In the morning they brought to [[Manu (Hinduism)|Manu]] water for washing, just as now also they (are wont to) bring (water) for washing the hands. When he was washing himself, a fish came into his hands. \n\nIt spake to him the word, 'Rear me, I will save thee!' 'Wherefrom wilt thou save me?' 'A [[Flood myth|flood]] will carry away all these creatures: from that I will save thee!' 'How am I to rear thee?' \n\nIt said, 'As long as we are small, there is great destruction for us: fish devours fish. Thou wilt first keep me in a jar. When I outgrow that, thou wilt dig a pit and keep me in it. When I outgrow that, thou wilt take me down to the sea, for then I shall be beyond destruction.' \n\nIt soon became a ''ghasha'' (a large fish); for that grows largest (of all fish). Thereupon it said, 'In such and such a year that flood will come. Thou shalt then attend to me (i.e. to my advice) by preparing a ship; and when the flood has risen thou shalt enter into the ship, and I will save thee from it.'...\n\nBeing desirous of offspring, he engaged in worshipping and austerities. During this time he also performed a p\u00e2ka-sacrifice: he offered up in the waters clarified butter, sour milk, whey, and curds. Thence a woman was produced in a year: becoming quite solid she rose; clarified butter gathered in her footprint.</poem>|source=[[Shatapatha Brahmana]], translated by [[Julius Eggeling]] (1900), Kanda I, Adhyaya 8, Brahmana 1 ('The Ida'), Verses 1-4 and 7|sign=}}[[File:The fish avatara of Vishnu saves Manu during the great deluge.jpg|thumb|Matsya pulling Manu's boat|alt=|274x274px]]In this original account, Manu is approached by a small fish requesting his protection, and having reared it to become a ''ghasha'', is warned of an impending flood and instructed to build a ship. After the Earth is flooded, the ship is tied with rope to the horn of Matsya, and 'by that means he passed swiftly up to yonder northern mountain'. As the water subsides, Manu performs the p\u00e2ka-sacrifice, from which \"Ida\" emerges. \"Ida\" identifies herself as 'Manu's daughter' when approached by [[Mitra]] and [[Varuna]], and explains to Manu that 'Those offerings (of) clarified butter, sour milk, whey, and curds, which thou madest in the waters, with them thou hast begotten me. I am the blessing (benediction): make use of me at the sacrifice'. Manu does so to regenerate the human race through sacrifice.\n\nThe legend of Matsya rescuing [[Manu (Hinduism)|Manu]] from the flood, taking the ship to the summit of a mountain, and the birth of \"Ida\" from the p\u00e2ka-sacrifice - consisting of only the first 10 of 44 verses in this Brahmana - is a prelude to explain the symbolic importance of the ''ida,'' the domestic offering in the form of a sacrificial cake (including butter). In the practice of the ritual described in the remaining verses, the daughter of Manu is explicitly stated to be 'essentially the same as the Ida' to attain prosperity from a successful sacrifice in the form of cattle and offspring. Linking to academics' claims of Ida representing libations such as milk in the [[Rigveda|RigVeda]], the domestic offering is stated to be milk in the [[Shatapatha Brahmana]] (e.g. SB 2.3.1.21).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/sbr/sbe12/sbe1248.htm|title=Satapatha Brahmana Part 1 (SBE12): Second K\u00e2nda: II, 3, 1. Third Adhy\u00e2ya. First Br\u00e2hmana|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-07}}</ref> Notably, this first account of the Matsya legend also seems to link directly with the [[Rigveda|RigVeda]] (RV):\n\n* '''SB 1.8.1.7''' 'clarified butter gathered in her [Ida's] footprint' and '''RV 10.70.8''' 'May I\u1e37\u0101, she whose foot drops oil...'\n* '''SB 1.8.1.21''' 'Hither is called (I''d''\u00e2) by that (sacrifice) which is performed by the seven Hot''ri''s [priests]' and '''RV''' '''10.63.7:''' 'Ye to whom Manu, by seven priests, with kindled fire, offered the first oblation with his heart and soul...The well-oared heavenly Ship that lets no waters in, free from defect, will we ascend for happiness'.\n\nY. Bonnefoy states that 'classical India indeed speaks of the \"law of the fishes\" to designate what we could call the \"[[law of the jungle]].\" The law of the fishes is set against the order imposed by a good [[king]], an order in which the weak are protected from the strong and in which [[dharma]] rather than individual force is the organizing principle. Manu, who is in essence the legislator [e.g. [[Manusmriti|the laws of Manu]]] and the father of the traditional royal dynasties, had an obvious connection with royal power'.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=r4I-FsZCzJEC&q=jungle#v=snippet&q=jungle&f=false|title=Asian Mythologies|last=Bonnefoy|first=Yves|date=1993-05-15|publisher=University of Chicago Press|isbn=978-0-226-06456-7|location=|pages=80|language=en}}</ref> These claims are supported in texts such as the [[Ramayana]], as illustrated below.\n\nAs stated by W.J. Wilkins, Matsya in this account is not ascribed to any particular deity.<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/HinduMythologyWilkins_201801|title=Hindu Mythology|last=Wilkins|first=W.J.|publisher=|year=1882|isbn=|location=|pages=113|language=English}}</ref> Aiyangar supposes that the 'Fish that conducts the Ship seems to me to be [[Agni]], the symbol of the all-knowing and all-embracing God... The reason why this Fish is horned may be due to Agni being described as having four horns in [<nowiki/>[[Rigveda|RigVeda]] 4.58.3],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/rigveda/rv04058.htm|title=Rig Veda: Rig-Veda, Book 4: HYMN LVIII. Gh\u1e5bta.|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-13}}</ref> a verse which is repeated daily in Agni-worship.'<ref name=\":3\" /> Eggeling supposes (note 216:3 in the linked version), that in the [[Taittiriya Samhita]] (1.7.1 and 2.6.7)<ref name=\":13\" /><ref name=\":2\" /> 'i''d''\u00e2 is represented as a cow, produced by [[Mitra]] and [[Varuna|Varu''n''a]]. Perhaps it was this version and the symbolical representation of the i''d''\u00e2 as meaning cattle, which suggested the notion of a horned fish, in adapting an older legend'.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==== Krishna (Black) Yajurveda ====\n{{Verse translation|Manuh prthivya yajniyam aichat\nsa ghrtam nisiktam avindat\nso 'bravit\nko 'syesvaro yajne 'pi kartor iti\ntav abrutam mitravarunau\ngor evavam isvarau kartoh sva iti\ntau tato gam sam airayatam {{!}}\nsa yatrayatra nyakramat tato ghrtam apidyata\ntasmad ghrtapady ucyate\ntad asyai janma {{!}}|Manu desired what of earth was sacrificial. He found the poured out ghee. He said, 'Who is able to produce this also at the sacrifice?' [[Mitra]] and [[Varuna]] said, 'We are able to produce the cow.' Then they set the cow in motion. Wherever she stepped, there ghee was pressed out; therefore she is called ghee-footed; that is her origin.|lang=en|attr1=Taittiriya Samhita [[transliteration]] of Kanda I, Prapathaka VI, Chapter VII, Verse 1<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sanskritweb.net/yajurveda/ts-find.pdf|title=Taittiriya Samhita Kanda I, Prapathaka VI, Chapter VII, Verse 1 (Transliteration)|website=www.www.sanskritweb.net|access-date=2020-01-07}}</ref>|attr2=Taittiriya Samhita [[translation]] by Arthur Berriedale Keith (1914) of Kanda I, Prapathaka VI, Chapter VII, Verse 1<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/yv/yv02.htm|title=Taittiriya Samhita Kanda I, Prapathaka VI, Chapter VII, Verse 1|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-07}}</ref>}}This above-quoted verse links directly with the [[Shatapatha Brahmana]] (1.8.1.7; 'clarified butter gathered in her [Ida's] footprint') and the [[Rigveda|RigVeda]] (10.70.8; 'May I\u1e37\u0101, she whose foot drops oil...'). Macdonell adds that in the [[Taittiriya Shakha|Taittiriya Samhita]], 'Ida, or personified [[libation]], is [also] represented as a cow' (i.e. representing prosperity and producing milk).<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/vedicindexofname01macduoft|title=Vedic index of names and subjects|last=Macdonell|first=Arthur Anthony|last2=Keith|first2=Arthur Berriedale|date=1912|publisher=London, Murray|others=Robarts - University of Toronto|isbn=|location=|pages=293 (Jhasa; Eggeling's 'ghasha')}}</ref>\n{{Verse translation|imam su navam aruham sataritram '''satasphyam''' <nowiki>|</nowiki>\nachidram parayisnum <nowiki>||</nowiki>|Happily have I mounted this ship With a hundred oars and a '''hundred spars [satasphyam]''',\nWithout leak, able to convey across.|lang=en|attr1=Taittiriya Samhita [[transliteration]] of Kanda I, Prapathaka V, Chapter XI, Verse 5<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sanskritweb.net/yajurveda/ts-find.pdf|title=Taittiriya Samhita Kanda I, Prapathaka V, Chapter XI, Verse 5 (Transliteration)|website=www.www.sanskritweb.net|access-date=2020-01-07}}</ref>|attr2=Taittiriya Samhita [[translation]] by Arthur Berriedale Keith (1914) of Kanda I, Prapathaka V, Chapter XI, Verse 5<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/yv/yv01.htm|title=Taittiriya Samhita Kanda I, Prapathaka V, Chapter XI, Verse 5|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-07}}</ref>}}Although 'satasphyam' from the above-quoted verse was translated by Keith as 'a hundred [[Spar (sailing)|spars]]', Aiyangar translates it as a hundred ''sphyas'', and explains that a 'Sphya [(\u0938\u094d\u092b\u094d\u092f)] is a wooden sword used as a [[Yajna|sacrificial]] instrument'.<ref name=\":3\" /> Both interpretations are correct.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://spokensanskrit.org/index.php?mode=3&script=hk&tran_input=sphya&direct=se&anz=100|title=Sanskrit Dictionary for Spoken Sanskrit: 'sphya'|last=|first=|date=|website=spokensanskrit.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-07}}</ref> Eggeling adds that the 'sphya is a straight sword (''khadga'') or knife, a [[cubit]] long, carved out of khadira wood... It is used for various purposes calculated to symbolically insure the safe and undisturbed performance of the [[Yajna|sacrifice]]'.<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.38188|title=The Satapatha-brahmana Pt. 1|last=Eggeling|first=Julius|date=1882|publisher=|isbn=|location=|pages=13 (footnote 1)}}</ref> \n\n=== Atharva Veda ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" |[[Atharvaveda|Arharva]]\n! colspan=\"2\" |References\n!Notes\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" |39.7-8<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/sbe42/av007.htm|title=Atharva Veda: I. Charms to Cure Diseases and Possession by Demons of Disease (Bhaishagykni): XIX, 39. Prayer to the kushtha-plant to destroy takman (fever), and other ailments|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-11}}</ref>\n|The Bloomfield translation (39.7-8) is part of an [[anthology]] and is not in numeric order.\n|}\n\n{{quote|<poem>A golden ship with golden tackle moved upon the heavens. There came to sight the [[amrita]], there the kushtha-plant was born.\n\nOn the spot where the ship glided down, on the peak of the [[Himavat|Himavant]], there came to sight the ambrosia, there the kushtha-plant was born. This kushtha, a universal remedy, stands together with [[soma]]. Destroy thou every takman, and all female spooks!</poem>|source=Hymns Of The Atharva-veda, translated by [[Maurice Bloomfield]] (1897), XIX, 39. ('Prayer to the kushtha-plant to destroy takman (fever), and other ailments'), Verses 7-8|sign=}}\n\nIn this commentary to the eighth verse (or stanza) of hymn XIX, where a ship rests at the peak of a mountain, Bloomfield states it 'seems difficult to abstain from comparing with this passage certain features of the well-known legend of Manu and the flood' in the account of the [[Shatapatha Brahmana]] (as above) and the [[Mahabharata]].<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.44825|title=Hymns Of The Atharva-veda|last=Bloomfield|first=Maurice|date=1893|publisher=|isbn=|location=|pages=679}}</ref>  In regards to the Kushtha-plant mentioned, Bloomfield adds that combined with the [[Rigveda|RigVeda]] (2.33.13) which 'speaks of pure, most wholesome, and strengthening remedies which 'Father Manu' chose... it seems altogether likely that the two independent legends [i.e. the flood and discovery of the medicinal Kustha-plant] should blend here [in the [[Atharvaveda|AtharvaVeda]]] in the mind of the poet'.<ref name=\":11\" />  \n\n== Upanishads ==\n\n=== Brihadaranyaka Upanishad ===\n\n{{quote|As a large fish [maha-matsya] glides between both banks, the right and the left one, so glides the [[Purusha]] between both boundaries, the boundary of dream and the boundary of the waking state.|source=Brihadaranyaka Upanishad, translated by Eduard Roer (1856), Chapter 4, Verse 18<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/The_Brihad_aranyaka_upanishad_Sankarabhashya_English|title=The Brihadaranyaka Upanishad|last=Roer|first=Eduard|publisher=Asiatic Society of Bengal|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=226|language=english}}</ref>|sign=}}\n\n== Itih\u0101sa (Epics) ==\n\n=== Mahabharata ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" |[[Ramayana|Mahabharata]]\n!References\n!Notes\n|-\n|'''Matsya:''' Book 3: Markandeya-Samasya Parva - CLXXXVI (186);<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/m03/m03186.htm|title=The Mahabharata, Book 3: Vana Parva: Markandeya-Samasya Parva: Section CLXXXVI|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-12}}</ref> '''Ida:''' Book 2: Rajasuyika Parva - XXXIV (34);<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/m02/m02034.htm|title=The Mahabharata, Book 2: Sabha Parva: Rajasuyika Parva: Section XXXIV|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-12}}</ref>\n\n'''Ship:''' Book 3: Arjunabhigamana Parva - XXXI (31),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/m03/m03031.htm|title=The Mahabharata, Book 3: Vana Parva: Arjunabhigamana Parva: Section XXXI|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-12}}</ref> Markandeya-Samasya Parva: CCX (210)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/m03/m03210.htm|title=The Mahabharata, Book 3: Vana Parva: Markandeya-Samasya Parva: Section CCX|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-12}}</ref>\n|Translation is by [[Kisari Mohan Ganguli|K.M. Ganguli]].\n|}\n\n{{quote|<poem>...[When] the world was thus flooded, none but Manu, the [[Saptarishi|seven Rishis]] and the fish could be seen. And, [[Yudhishthira|O king]], the fish diligently dragged the boat through the flood for many a long year and then, O descendant of Kuru and ornament of Bharata's race, it towed the vessel towards the highest peak of the [[Himavat]]. And, O Bharata, the fish then told those on the vessel to tie it to the peak of the Himavat. And hearing the words of the fish they immediately tied the boat on that peak of the mountain and, O son of [[Kunti]] and ornament of Bharata's race, know that that high peak of the Himavat is still called by the name of Naubandhana (the harbour). Then the fish addressing the associated [[Rishi|Rishis]] told them these words, 'I am [[Brahma]], the Lord of all creatures; there is none greater than myself. Assuming the shape of a fish, I have saved you from this cataclysm. Manu will create (again) all beings--gods, Asuras and men, all those divisions of creation which have the power of locomotion and which have it not. By practicing severe austerities he will acquire this power, and with my blessing, illusion will have no power over him.'\n\n\"So saying the fish vanished instantly. And [[Shraddhadeva Manu|Vaivaswata]] Manu himself became desirous of creating the world. In this work of creation illusion overtook him and he, therefore, practised great asceticism. And endowed with ascetic merit, Manu, O ornament of Bharata's race, again set about his work of creating all beings in proper and exact order.</poem>|source=The Mahabharata, translated by [[Kisari Mohan Ganguli]] (1883-1896), Book 3, Markandeya-Samasya Parva - CLXXXVI (186)}}[[File:BritishMuseumMatsya.jpg|thumb|Matsya, Central India, 9th - 10th century. [[British Museum]].<ref name=\"Dallapiccola2003p19\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AEQovil-HSoC&pg=PA19|title=Hindu Myths|author=A. L. Dallapiccola|publisher=University of Texas Press|year=2003|isbn=978-0-292-70233-2|pages=19\u201320}}</ref>|alt=|200x200px]]\n\nAlthough the [[Matsya Kingdom]] of the [[Vedic period|Vedic Period]] features throughout the [[Mahabharata]], the legend of Matsya the fish occupies a single chapter, narrated by the sage [[Markandeya]] to [[Yudhishthira]] (as narrated by [[Vaisampayana]]). In this account, [[Shraddhadeva Manu|Vaivaswata]] Manu performs austerities for 10,000 years in the '[[jujube]] forest called Visala' before a small-fish, i.e. Matsya, approaches him on the banks of the Chirini river. Outgrowing a tank 'two [[Yojana|yojanas]] in length and one yojana in width', Matsya is deposited in the [[Ganges]] river before outgrowing that and being deposited in the sea, where Manu is warned 'the dissolution of all this mobile and immobile world is nigh at hand' and is instructed to 'build a strong massive ark and have it furnished with a long rope. On that must thou ascend, O great Muni, with the [[Saptarishi|seven Rishis]] and take with thee all the different [[Seed|seeds]] which were enumerated by regenerate [[Brahmin|Brahmanas]] in days of yore'. As noted by Aiyanger,<ref name=\":3\" /> [[Rigveda|RigVeda]] Hymn 10.63 (as above) states 'Manu, by seven priests, with kindled fire, offered the first oblation with his heart and soul'; in the same hymn, mention is also made of the 'well-oared heavenly Ship that lets no waters in'.   \n\nAfter the flood, a rope is used to tie the ark to the horns of Matsya (plural, not singular, as per the original account of the [[Shatapatha Brahmana]]) where it is taken to safety at the peak of the [[Himavat]]. Matsya then identifies itself as [[Brahma]] and states 'Manu will create (again) all beings--gods, ''[[Asura|Asuras]]'' and men' before disappearing. Notably, this account does not mention Ida/Ila. Other details include:  \n\n* A description of a sacrifice performed states 'The gods also were gratified at the sacrifice by the ''Ida'', clarified butter, ''Homa'' and libations poured by the great ''Rishis'' versed in ''mantras'' and pronunciation' (Book 2: Rajasuyika Parva - XXXIV)\n* [[Yudhishthira]] describes religion as 'the only raft for those desirous of going to heaven, like a ship to merchants desirous of crossing the ocean' (Book 3: Arjunabhigamana Parva - XXXI)\n* [[Markandeya]] states that 'a man's mind is overpowered by any one of these senses running wild, he loses his reason, and becomes like a ship tossed by storms upon the high ocean' (Book 3: Markandeya-Samasya Parva: CCX)\n\n=== Ramayana ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! rowspan=\"5\" |[[Ramayana]]\n! colspan=\"2\" |References\n!Notes\n|-\n|'''Valmiki version 1''' (S. Ayyangar translation)\n|'''Fish:''' Ayodhya Kanda - LXVII (67)<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/ramayanaofvalmee035120mbp/page/n701|title=Ramayana Of Valmeeki|last=Sreenivasa Ayyangar|publisher=A L V Press And Guardian Press Madras|others=BRAOU, Digital Library Of India|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=312 (verse 110)}}</ref>\n|Great fish eat small fish in a King-less land.\n|-\n|'''Valmiki version 2''' (H. P. Shastri and R.T.H. Griffith translations)\n|'''Manu:''' Book 2: Ayodhya Kanda - 110<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/The.Ramayana.of.Valmiki.by.Hari.Prasad.Shastri|title=The Ramayana of Valmiki, translated by Hari Prasad Shastri - 3 Volumes Combined - 1709 Pages, with complete Outline|last=Hari Prasad Shastri|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=393\u2013394|language=English}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/rama/ry188.htm|title=Book II: Canto CX.: The Sons of Ikshva'ku.|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-12}}</ref>\n|Father of [[Ikshvaku|Ikshv'aku]]\n|-\n|'''Adhyatma Ramayana''' (R.B.L.B Nath translation)\n|'''Matsya:''' Ayodhya Kanda - V (5.41); Yuddha Kanda - X (10.46), XV (15.58)<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/TheAdhyatmaRamayana|title=The Adhyatma Ramayana|last=Rai Bahadur Lala Baij Nath|date=1979|publisher=|isbn=|location=|pages=40, 163, 184}}</ref>\n|Stated to be an avatar of [[Rama]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" |There are [[Versions of Ramayana|multiple versions]] of the Ramayana. Many are attributed to [[Valmiki]].\n|}\nAs evidenced below, the assertion of Bonnefoy (see [[Yajurveda|YajurVeda]] section, above) that Matsya refers to the \"law of the fishes\" - equivalent to the \"law of the jungle\" - in respect to an absence of a [[monarchy]] (specifically a [[King|kingship]]) to rule a given land,<ref name=\":12\" /> is fully supported by various versions of the [[Ramayana]]. Notably, [[Shraddhadeva Manu|Manu]] in the account of Matsya is the father of [[Ikshvaku]], the first king of the [[Solar dynasty|Solar Dynasty]], of which [[Prithu]] and [[Rama]] are descendants.\n\n==== Valmiki version 1 ====\n\n{{quote|In a kingless land none dares to call anything his own. Like a fish in the ocean, the great feed upon the small and they upon the smaller and so on ''ad infinitum''. Those that were severely punished by the king for falling away from their duties of their rank and order, those who proclaim and live a godless life, this is their day of power and glory. They wreak their hoarded vengeance upon the good and the innocent; and the world will laud them to the skies as great men and holy.|source=Ramayana, translated by S. Ayyangar (1910), Ayodhya Kanda - LXVII (67)|sign=}}\n\n==== Valmiki version 2 ====\n\n{{quote|<poem>And [[Kashyapa|Ka'syap]] was [[Marichi|Mar'ichi's]] child.\nFrom him [[Surya|Vivasvat]] sprang: from him\n[[Shraddhadeva Manu|Manu]], whose fame shall ne'er be dim.\nManu, who life to mortals gave,\nBegot [[Ikshvaku|Ikshv'aku]] good and brave:\nFirst of [[Ayodhya (Ramayana)|Ayodhya]]'s kings was he,\nPride of her famous dynasty.</poem>|source=The Ramayana of Valmiki, translated by R.T.H. Griffith (1870-1874), Book 2, Ayodhya Kanda - 110|sign=}}\n\n==== Adhyatma Ramayana ====\n\n{{quote|Thou [<nowiki/>[[Rama]]] alone art know in [[\u015aruti|Srutis]] and the [[Puranas]] as appearing in the form of the fish [Matsya] and the like. In the same way all this differentiation of [[Sat (Sanskrit)|sat]] and asat (existence and non-existence) art thou. None that appears is without thee.|source=The Adhyatma Ramayana, translated by R.B.L.B. Nath (1979), Yuddha Kanda, Chapters V.17 and X.48|sign=}}\n\n== Maha-Puranas ==\nRoy states that a 'comparison of the Mahabharata account with those of the [[Matsya Purana|Matsya]] and [[Bhagavata Purana|Bhagavata Puranas]]... [makes it] clear that new elements were gradually brought into the legend and slight changes occasioned so as to [[Allegory|allegorize]] the [[Historical Vedic religion|Brahmanical]] ideas', adding that all these versions agree in ascribing a horn to Matsya, which adds a 'religious sacredness'.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Agni Purana ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" |[[Agni Purana|Agni]]\n!References\n!Notes\n|-\n|2, 46.8, 49.1, 63.7-9, 108.29-30, 167.24, 272.20b-21a, 273.7 (Ila), 370.4, 374.29-32a<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/AgniPuranaUnabridgedEnglishMotilal|title=Agni Purana Unabridged English Motilal|last=J. L. Shastri|first=G. P. Bhatt|date=1998-01-01}}</ref>\n|\n|}\n\n{{quote|<poem>\"Who are you, but [[Vishnu|Visnu]]? O [[Narayana]] (Visnu) I salute you. Why do you stupefy me with your illusory power, O [[Janardana]] (Visnu)\".\n\nHaving hear the words of Manu, the Fish replied [to] Manu who had been engaged in the protection (of the world), \"I have manifested for the protection of this universe and for the destruction of the wicked\".\n\n\"On the seventh day, the ocean would flood the earth. Having put the seeds (of creation) etc. in the boat that would approach you, you would spend the night... of [[Brahma]] on it being encircled by the seven sages, (you) bind this boat to my horn with the big [[N\u0101ga|serpent]]\".</poem>|source=Agni Purana (unabridged), translated by J.L. Shastri, G.P. Bhatt, and N. Gangadharan (1998), Chapter 2, Verses 10-13|author=|title=}}\n[[File:Kalighat Matsya avatar.jpg|thumb|250x250px|Matsya.]]\nR. Dalal describes the [[Agni Purana]] as an '[[Encyclopedia|encyclopedic]] work, which is classified as a [[Shaivism|SHAIVITE]] [[Puranas|Purana]], through is begins with a section on [[Vishnu|VISHNU]], and has several other topics'.<ref name=\":15\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=DH0vmD8ghdMC&pg=PA444#v=onepage&q=agni%20purana&f=false|title=Hinduism: An Alphabetical Guide|last=Dalal|first=Roshen|date=2010|publisher=Penguin Books India|isbn=978-0-14-341421-6|location=|pages=10, 250|language=en}}</ref> As narrated by [[Agni]] to the sage [[Vasishtha|Vasistha]] (one of the [[Saptarishi|Saptarishis]]), in this account, as [[Shraddhadeva Manu|Manu]] 'was offering waters of libation in the (river) Krtamala, a small fish came in the waters in his folded palms', seeking protection from crocodiles and others. Growing and being transferred first to a vessel, then to a tank, and then the ocean when finally 'in size extending to a [[lakh]] of [[Yojana|yojanas]]', Manu identifies the fish as [[Vishnu]], who warns of the impending flood and instructs him to board a ship with seeds, etc. Notably, this includes being told that he will spend the 'night of [[Brahma]]' on the ship (i.e. the time of universal dissolution lasting 1000 [[Yuga|yugas]] or 'celestial years' where all creation begins again anew) while 'being encircled by the seven sages', i.e. the [[Saptarishi]].\n\nAfter the flood occurs and Manu is on the ship, a serpent ([[N\u0101ga|Naga]]) - in place of a rope - is used to tie the ship to the horn of Matsya, described as 'one million yojanas in length'. The final verses, rather than narrate the arrival of Manu at the safety at the peak of a mountain or his subsequent sacrificial ritual to produce [[Ila (Hinduism)|Ila]], instead briefly narrate that Manu 'heard from the fish the [[Puranas|Purana]] known as the [[Matsya Purana]], and that '[[Keshava|Kesava]] (Vishnu) killed the demon Hayagriva, the destroyer of the [[Vedas]] of [[Brahmin|Brahman]] and thus protected the Vedic [[Mantra|mantras]]'. Other details include:\n\n* Matsya is listed as the first of the [[Dashavatara]], or ten primary incarnations of [[Vishnu]] (49.1)\n*The Matsya [[Shaligram|salagrama]] is described as 'long and has three dots. It is crystalline-coloured... The Sridhara (stone) has a garland of wild flowers and five lines and is circular' (49.1)\n* Images of [[Vishnu]] as Matsya 'should be installed in waters' (63.7-9)\n* Vishnu resides in '[[Kuru Kingdom|Kurus]] in the form of Matsya' (108.29-30)\n*[[Ila (Hinduism)|Ila]] is mentioned as the daughter of Manu, mother of [[Pururavas]] with [[Budha]], and becoming a male called Sudyumna 'after delivering Pururavas' (273.7)\n* It is stated the [[Purusha]] is 'just like the fish in the water attached and detached' (370.4; similar to the [[Brihadaranyaka Upanishad]], above)\n* Contemplation of [[Vishnu]] should include 'with ear-ring[s] (in the shape of a fish' (374.29-32a)<br />\n\n*  \n\n=== Bhagavata Purana ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" |[[Bhagavata Purana|Bhagavata]]\n!References\n!Notes\n|-\n|1.3.15,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vedabase.io/en/library/sb/1/3/15/|title=\u015aB 1.3.15|website=vedabase.io|language=en|access-date=2020-01-18}}</ref> 1.15.35,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vedabase.io/en/library/sb/1/15/35/|title=\u015aB 1.15.35|website=vedabase.io|language=en|access-date=2020-01-18}}</ref> 2.7.12,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vedabase.io/en/library/sb/2/7/12/|title=\u015aB 2.7.12|website=vedabase.io|language=en|access-date=2020-01-18}}</ref> 6.8.13,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vedabase.io/en/library/sb/6/8/13/|title=\u015aB 6.8.13|website=vedabase.io|language=en|access-date=2020-01-18}}</ref> 8.24,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vedabase.io/en/library/sb/8/24/|title=CHAPTER TWENTY-FOUR|website=vedabase.io|language=en|access-date=2020-01-18}}</ref> 9.1.16,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vedabase.io/en/library/sb/9/1/16/|title=\u015aB 9.1.16|website=vedabase.io|language=en|access-date=2020-01-18}}</ref> 10.2.40<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vedabase.io/en/library/sb/10/2/40/|title=\u015aB 10.2.40|website=vedabase.io|language=en|access-date=2020-01-18}}</ref>\n|\n|}\n\n{{quote|<poem> O King [[Parikshit|Par\u012bk\u1e63it]], at the end of the past millennium, at the end of [[Brahm\u0101]]\u2019s day, because Lord Brahm\u0101 sleeps during the night, annihilation took place, and the three worlds were covered by the water of the ocean.\n\nAt the end of Brahm\u0101\u2019s day, when Brahm\u0101 felt sleepy and desired to lie down, the [[Vedas]] were emanating from his mouth, and the great demon named Hayagr\u012bva stole the Vedic knowledge.\n\nUnderstanding the acts of the great demon Hayagr\u012bva, the Supreme Personality of Godhead, [[Hari]], who is full of all opulences, assumed the form of a fish and saved the Vedas by killing the demon.</poem>|source=Bhagavata Purana, translated by [[A. C. Bhaktivedanta Swami Prabhupada|Swami Prabhupada]], Canto 8, Chapter 24, Verses 7-9|author=|title=}}\n\nThe legend of Matsya in the [[Bhagavata Purana]] consists of two separate accounts. In the first, as quoted above in its entirety, after the [[Vedas]] are stolen by an [[Asura]] called Hayagriva (not to be confused with the horse-headed avatar also called '[[Hayagriva]]'), [[Krishna]] assumes the form of Matsya to destroy the demon and retrieve the stolen Vedas. This account is very similar to those of the [[Naradiya Purana|Narada]] and [[Garuda Purana|Garuda Puranas]]; similar stories involving other demons are also mentioned in the [[Padma Purana|Padma]] and [[Skanda Purana|Skanda Puranas]] (see below). From the second account, following directly from the first:\n\n{{quote|<poem>The Supreme Personality of Godhead [Matsya] said: O [[Shraddhadeva Manu|King]], who can subdue your enemies, on the seventh day from today the three worlds \u2014 Bh\u016b\u1e25, Bhuva\u1e25 and Sva\u1e25 \u2014 will all merge into the water of inundation. When all the three worlds merge into the water, a large boat sent by Me will appear before you.\n\nThereafter, O King, you shall collect all types of herbs and seeds and load them on that great boat. Then, accompanied by the [[Saptarishi|seven \u1e5b\u1e63is]] and surrounded by all kinds of living entities, you shall get aboard that boat, and without moroseness you shall easily travel with your companions on the ocean of inundation, the only illumination being the effulgence of the great [[Rishi|\u1e5b\u1e63is]].\n\nThen, as the boat is tossed about by the powerful winds, attach the vessel to My horn by means of the great serpent [[Vasuki|V\u0101suki]], for I shall be present by your side. Pulling the boat, with you and all the \u1e5b\u1e63is in it, O King, I shall travel in the water of devastation until the night of Lord Brahm\u0101\u2019s slumber is over.</poem>|source=Bhagavata Purana, translated by [[A. C. Bhaktivedanta Swami Prabhupada|Swami Prabhupada]], Canto 8, Chapter 24, Verses 32-37}}\n[[File:Matsya Avatar, ca 1870.jpg|left|thumb|274x274px|Matsya.]]\nThe second account occurs at the end of the [[Chakshusha|C\u0101k\u1e63u\u1e63a]]-[[manvantara]] with King [[Shraddhadeva Manu|Satyavrata]], stated to 'later became the son of [[Surya|Vivasv\u0101n]]... and was [to be] known as \u015ar\u0101ddhadeva. By the mercy of the Supreme Personality of Godhead, he was given the post of [[Manu (Hinduism)|Manu]]'. While performing austerities, a small fish jumps into the King's hands, which he throws back into the river, prompting to fish to request his protection. Doing so, the fish grows as it is first deposited in a water jug, then a well, a lake, and then finally the sea where it expands for 'hundreds of miles'. Recognising the fish as [[Krishna]], Satyavrata is warned of the impending dissolution of the [[Trailokya|three worlds]] and instructed to board a boat built for him, taking 'herbs and seeds... the [[Saptarishi|seven \u1e5b\u1e63is]] and... all kinds of living entities'.\n\nSatyavrata meditates on [[Krishna]] until the 'gigantic clouds pouring incessant water swelled the ocean more and more', boards the boat, and 'while the King constantly meditated upon the Supreme Personality of Godhead, a large golden fish appeared in the ocean of inundation. The fish had one horn and was eight million miles long'. [[Vasuki]] is used as a rope. During the journey, Satyavrata praises [[Krishna]], and Krishna - as Matsya - 'explained to King Satyavrata the spiritual science known as [[Samkhya|s\u0101\u1e45khya]]-yoga, the science by which one distinguishes between matter and spirit, along with the instructions contained in the [[Puranas|Pur\u0101\u1e47as]] and the [[Samhita|sa\u1e41hit\u0101s]]' (8.24).\n\nThe second account is similar to that given in the [[Matsya Purana]], particularly as both [[Puranas]] omit the remainder of the original legend from the [[Shatapatha Brahmana]] (White [[Yajurveda|YajurVeda]], see above), where Manu is taken to safety by Matsya to a mountain where he consequently performs a [[Yajna|sacrifice]] to produce his \"daughter\" [[Ila (Hinduism)|Ila]]. Instead, this sacrifice is described in a separate legend, similar to that of the [[Vishnu Purana]] (see below), where 'Manu had begun that sacrifice for the sake of getting a son, but because the priest was diverted by the request of Manu\u2019s wife, a daughter named Il\u0101 was born' (9.1.16).\n\n=== Brahma Purana ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" |[[Brahma Purana|Brahma]]\n!References\n!Notes\n|-\n|'''Matsya:''' 38.1-63, 56.3, 57.1-3, 68.73; '''Flood:''' 24.19-21; '''Manu:''' 3.4-7; '''Ship:''' 38.85-86; '''Ila:''' 5.3-7, Gautami-Mahaymya: 3.9-12<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/brahma_purana_english_full|title=Brahma Purana - Parts I - IV|last=Motilal Banarsidass|date=1955-01-01}}</ref>\n|The legend of Matsya is not narrated in this [[Puranas|Purana]].\n|}\n\n{{quote|By visiting Svetamadhava and Matsyamadhava by his side and by bowing to the first incarnation of [[Krishna|Madhava]] in the form of a fish [i.e. Matsya-Madhava], one is liberated from all miseries. Lord Matsya [[Krishna|Madhava]] had at the outset assumed the form of [a] [[Rohu|Rohita]] fish. He had been thinking of the earth stationed at the bottom of the nether worlds. He established himself there in order to redeem the [[Vedas]].|source=Brahma Purana, unknown translator (1955), Chapter 57, Verses 1-3|author=|title=}}\n[[File:Varuna makara.jpg|left|thumb|180x180px|[[Varuna]].]]\nThe legend of Matsya is only briefly mentioned in the [[Brahma Purana]], as quoted above. O.M. Starza states that ''Svetamadhava'' 'to the south of the Blue Mountain... On its banks are the two shrines, those of Matsya Avatara [Matsyamadhava] and King Sveta [Svetamadhava]'. He adds that in the [[Skanda Purana]] (Purusottama Mahatmya: 37.55-6), [[Vishnu]] granted Sveta a crystalline image seated in front of Matsya (at Puri, between the blue hill and the sea) as a reward for [[asceticism]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=v4bV3beb0n8C&pg=PA11&lpg=PA11&dq=Svetamadhava#v=onepage&q=Svetamadhava&f=false|title=The Jagannatha Temple at Puri: Its Architecture, Art, and Cult|last=Starza|first=O. M.|date=1993|publisher=BRILL|isbn=978-90-04-09673-8|location=|pages=11|language=en}}</ref>\n\nOtherwise, it is stated that this 'ocean of worldly existence is painful and utterly full of misery... with passions acting like crocodiles' (24.19-21), reminiscent of the account in the [[Agni Purana]] where Matsya seeks protection from crocodiles and others. \n\nThe Brahma Purana also states that a 'son is the exceedingly splendid ship for those who are about to sink in the ocean of misery' (38.85-86). Ila/Ida is also mentioned as emerging after [[Shraddhadeva Manu|Manu]] 'desirous of begetting sons, so performed the sacrifice with [[Mitra]] and [[Varuna]] as deities... It is said in the [[Vedas]] that Ila was born therefrom' (5.3-7). This is consistent of the account of Matsya in the [[Shatapatha Brahmana]] (1.8.1). Notably, [[Ila (Hinduism)|Ila]] is also stated to be synonymous with the Earth, carrying out the function of productivity (Gautami-Mahaymya: 3.9-12).\n\n=== Brahmanda Purana ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" |[[Brahmanda Purana|Brahmanda]]\n!References\n!Notes\n|-\n|'''Part 1:''' --;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/BrahmandaPuranaG.V.TagarePart1|title=Brahmanda Purana - English Translation - Part 1 of 5|last=G.V.Tagare|date=1958}}</ref> '''Part 2:''' --;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/BrahmandaPuranaG.V.TagarePart2|title=Brahmanda Purana - English Translation - Part 2 of 5|last=G.V.Tagare|date=1958}}</ref>  '''Part 3:''' '''Manu:''' 59, '''Ida/Illa:''' 60;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/BrahmandaPuranaG.V.TagarePart3|title=Brahmanda Purana - English Translation - Part 3 of 5|last=G.V.Tagare|date=1958}}</ref>  '''Part 4:''' Lalita-mahatmya: 29.134-136;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/BrahmandaPuranaG.V.TagarePart4|title=Brahmanda Purana - English Translation - Part 4 of 5|last=G.V.Tagare}}</ref>  '''Part 5:''' Lalita-mahatmya: 33.64-66<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/BrahmandaPuranaG.V.TagarePart5|title=Brahmanda Purana - English Translation - Part 5 of 5|last=G.V.Tagare|date=1959}}</ref>\n|The legend of Matsya is not mentioned.\n|}\n\n{{quote|Desirous of getting a son, the Prajapati [<nowiki/>[[Shraddhadeva Manu]]] performed a [[Yajna|sacrifice]]. He dropped Ahuti (ghee-offering) in the fire at the spot allotted to [[Mitra]] and [[Varuna]]. It is mentioned in the [[\u015aruti|Sruti]] [i.e. [[Vedas]], including the [[Brahmana|Brahmanas]]] that Ila [Ida] was born at that spot wearing divine robes, bedecked in divine ornaments and having [a] divine physical body.|source=Brahmanda Purana Part 3, translated by G.V. Tagare  (1958), Chapter 60, Verses 5-6|author=|title=}}\n\nThe legend of Matsya does not seem to be mentioned in the [[Brahmanda Purana]]. However, a detailed [[genealogy]] is provided for [[Shraddhadeva Manu|Vaivasvata]] Manu (chapter 59), as well as an account of producing Ila/Ida through performance of a sacrifice, which is almost identical to the account given in the legend of Matsya in the [[Shatapatha Brahmana]] (chapter 60). Notably, although the name of the \"daughter\" of Manu in the Brahmana was 'Ida', in the Brahmanda it is \"Ila\", thus evidencing claims that Ida and Ila are the same (i.e. synonymous) are indeed correct.<ref name=\":14\" />\n=== Brahmavaivarta Purana ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" |[[Brahma Vaivarta Purana|Brahmavaivarta]]\n!References\n!Notes\n|-\n|Nath Translation: -- ;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.142284|title=The Brahma Vaivarta Puranam (Brahma and Prakrti Khandas)|last=Sen|first=rajendra Nath|date=1920|publisher=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>Nager translation: '''Volume 2:''' 9 (p74)<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/357106450BrahmavaivartaPurana2SanskritTextWithEnglishTranslationPdf|title=Brahmavaivarta Purana (Volume 1: Brahma, Prakrti, and Ganapati Khandas, and Volume 2: Krsna-Janma Khanda)|last=Nager|first=Shanti Lal|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n|Roman numerals indicate the Nath translation; numerical digits indi<nowiki/>cate the Nager translation (two parts), which does not provide verse numbers (some pages of the Nath translation are also missing verse numbers).\n|}\nThe legend of Matsya does not seem to be mentioned in the [[Brahma Vaivarta Purana|Brahmavaivarta Purana]]. A reference to Matsya found states that this avatar - along with [[Varaha]], [[Vamana]], [[Kalki]], [[Gautama Buddha|Buddha]], and [[Kapila]] - is 'the amsa [portion or part] of the lord [<nowiki/>[[Vishnu]]]' (Nager Translation, Volume 2, Chapter 9).<br />\n=== Garuda Purana ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" |[[Garuda Purana|Gaurda]]\n!References\n!Notes\n|-\n|'''Part 1:''' 1.23, 2.42, 13.3-10, 15.3-160, 86.10-11, 87.12, 138.4 (Ila), 142.2-3;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.20541|title=THE GARUDA-PURANA PART. 1|last=N.A.|date=1957|publisher=MOTILAL BANARSIDASS PUBLISHERS PVT. DELHI}}</ref> '''Part 2:''' 194.13, 196.6;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.21508|title=THE GARUDA-PURANA PART. 2|last=N.A.|date=1957|publisher=MOTILAL BANARSIDASS PUBLISHERS PVT. DELHI}}</ref> '''Part 3:''' 25.38 (Ila), 30.37<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.12942|title=THE GARUDA-PURANA PART. 3|last=N.A|date=1957|publisher=MOTILAL BANARSIDASS PUBLISHERS PVT. LTD, DELHI}}</ref>\n|The legend of Matsya is not mentioned. Part 3 (Brahma Moska Kanda) 1.51-52 classifies Puranas.\n|}\n\n{{quote|Svasanti was elected [[Indra]] during this regime and his enemy was the demon [[Pralamba]]. Lord [[Vishnu|Visnu]] in his incarnation as [a] fish killed him.|source=Garuda Purana, translated by 'a board of scholars' (1957), Part 1, Chapter 87, Verse 12}}\n\nThe legend of Matsya does not seem to be mentioned in the [[Garuda Purana]]. In addition to the demon [[Pralamba]] as quoted above, it is also mentioned that Matsya 'fought with the demon Hayagriva in battle, killed him, redeemed the [[Vedas]], and saved [[Shraddhadeva Manu|Manu]] and others' (Part 1: 142.2-3). Notably, [[Hayagriva]] is also the name of the horse-headed avatar of [[Vishnu]] that recovered the stolen [[Vedas]] and returned them to [[Brahma]]. Stated to be the tenth overall incarnation of [[Vishnu]] at the end of the [[Chakshusha|Cakusa]] [[Manvantara]] (i.e. the end of the reign of the sixth [[Manu (Hinduism)|Manu]]) that saved [[Shraddhadeva Manu|Vaivasvata]] Manu, the seventh and current Manu associated with the legend of Matsya (Part 1: 1.23), other details include:\n\n* Matsya is stated as the first in the [[Dashavatara|Dhashavatara]], the ten primary incarnations of [[Vishnu]] (Part 1: 86.10-11 and Part 3: 30.37)\n* 'Matsya' is also one of the 1,000 names of Vishnu ([[Vishnu Sahasranama]]; Part 1: 15.3-160)\n* Ila is mentioned, albeit without reference to the sacrifice of Manu: 'Manu had a daughter Ila of whom [[Budha]] (Mercury) begot three sons: Rajas, Rudra and [[Pururavas]]. Ila was transformed into a man named Sudyumna. Sudyumna begot three sons - Utkala, Vinata, and Gaya' (Part 1: 138.4). The word 'Ila' also signifies the soul (Part 3: 25.38)\n\n=== Kurma Purana ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" |[[Kurma Purana|Kurma]]\n!References\n!Notes\n|-\n|6.18, 19.6-9 (Ila), 21 (Puruvas)<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/kurmapuranaTRkashirajtrust1972|title=K\u016brmapur\u0101\u1e47a (Kashiraj Trust edition with English translation)|last=Gupta|first=Anand Swarup|date=1972}}</ref>\n|The legend of Matsya is not mentioned.\n|}\nAlthough the legend of Matsya does not seem to be mentioned in the [[Kurma Purana]], Ila/Ida from the original legend is, albeit without reference to [[Shraddhadeva Manu|Manu]] or the performance of a [[Yajna|sacrifice]] to produce her. Ila is stated to have bared sons with [[Budha]], the son of [[Soma (deity)|Soma]], and having 'transformed as a stainless man' called Sudyumna, also had another three sons called Utkala, Gaya, and Vinatasya (19.6-9). One of the sons of the female Ila with Budha, King [[Pururavas|Puruavas]], is also mentioned (21).\n\n=== Linga Purana ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" |[[Linga Purana|Linga]]\n!References\n!Notes\n|-\n|'''Part 1:''' 2.38-41, 65.19b-22 (Ila);<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/LingaPuranaJ.L.ShastriPart1|title=Linga Purana - English Translation - Part 1 of 2|last=J.L.Shastri|date=1951}}</ref> '''Part 2:''' 48.30-32, 96.17-22<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/LingaPuranaJ.L.ShastriPart2|title=Linga Purana - English Translation - Part 2 of 2|last=J.L.Shastri|date=1951}}</ref>\n|Part 2 continues up to chapter 108 and then starts at chapter 1 again.\n|}\n\n{{quote|Multitudes of creatures have been saved by you in the form of a fish. You moved about in the vast ocean-like sheet of water formerly, after tying up the boat to your tail.|source=\u2009Linga Purana, translated by J.L.Shastri (1951), Part 2, Chapter 96, Verses 17-22|author=|title=}}\n\nThe legend of Matsya is only briefly mentioned in the [[Linga Purana]], as quoted above, and as stated by [[Virabhadra]] to [[Narasimha|Nrismha]], the man-lion [[avatar]] of [[Vishnu]]. Matsya is also mentioned as one of the 10 primary avatars of Vishnu ([[Dashavatara]]) for the good of the world; other avatars are due to the curse of [[Bhrigu|Bhrgu]] (Part 2: 48.30-32). Ila is also mentioned as becoming a '[[Kinnara Kingdom|Kimpurusa]]' called Sudyumna, alternating between being a man and a woman from one month to another; as a woman she bore children with [[Budha]], the son of [[Soma (deity)|Soma]], including King [[Pururavas]]. No mention is made of being produced by the [[Yajna|sacrifice]] of [[Shraddhadeva Manu|Manu]] (Part 1: 65.19b-22).\n\n=== Markandeya Purana ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" |[[Markandeya Purana|Markandeya]]\n!References\n!Notes\n|-\n|XLVII.7, LIV.31, LVIII.75-78 (star constellations), LIX.22-26<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.163375|title=Markandeya Puranam.|last=Dutt|first=Manmatha Nath|date=1896}}</ref>\n|The legend of Matsya is not mentioned.\n|}\n=== Matsya Purana ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" |[[Matsya Purana|Matsya]]\n!References\n!Notes\n|-\n|'''Matsya:''' 1-2; '''Ila:''' 11<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.135360|title=The Matsya Puranam|last=Taluqdar|first=a|date=1916}}</ref>\n|The legend of Matsya forms the frame in which this [[Puranas|Purana]] was narrated to [[Shraddhadeva Manu|Vaivasvata]] Manu.\n|}\n\n{{quote|May the words of Lord [[Vishnu|Visnu]], embodied in the Vedas and uttered by his Matsya-[[Avatar|avatara]], in which incarnation, at the time of His sallying forth from the region of the [[patala]], the blow of His tail caused the [[Seven Seas|seven seas]] to intermingle with the high heavens and then to fall down, splattering the sphere of the earth, steal away all your evil.|source=Matsya Purana, translated by A. Taluqdar (1916), Chapter I, Verse 2}}\n[[File:Matsya and Manu.jpg|left|thumb|306x306px|Matsya and [[Manu (Hinduism)|Manu]].]]\nAs stated by the [[Agni Purana]] (see above), V. R. R. Dikshitar notes that after the flood, when 'the boat was floating in the dark waters, [[Krishna|Vasudeva]], in the form of a fish, addressed the [[Matsya Purana]] to [[Shraddhadeva Manu|Manu]]'.<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/in.gov.ignca.9097|title=Matsya Purana a study|last=Dikshitar|first=V. R. Ramachandra|date=1935|publisher=|isbn=|location=|pages=4}}</ref> [[Horace Hayman Wilson|H.H. Wilson]] adds that the legend of Matsya 'is told in the [[Mahabharata]], with reference to the Matsya [Purana] as its authority; from which it might be inferred, that the [[Puranas|Purana]] was prior to the poem'.<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.217330|title=Puranas|last=H H Wilson|date=1911|publisher=|isbn=|location=|pages=84}}</ref> Dalal also states about the Matsya Purana that it 'is one of the older Puranas, and was narrated by LOMAHARSHANA [Suta] to the [[Rishi|rishis]] in the [[Naimi\u1e63\u0101ra\u1e47ya (forest)|NAIMISHA]] forest. It begins with the story of [[Shraddhadeva Manu|MANU]]'.<ref name=\":15\" />\n\nIn this account, which consists of the first two chapters, King [[Shraddhadeva Manu|Vaivasvata]], 'after making over his kingdom to his son [<nowiki/>[[Ikshvaku]]], devoted himself to rigid [[asceticism]] [on] the summit of the Malnya mountain'. After a million years, granted a boon by [[Brahma]], the King requested 'power sufficient for the protection of the whole creation, movable and immovable, when the hour of [[Pralaya]] [dissolution] will come'.\n\nAfterwards, while performing [[Tarpana]] (libation of water to [[Manes|deceased ancestors]]) at his [[Hermit|hermitage]], a small [[carp]] jumps into his hands which as it grows, is first deposited in a jar, then a large pitcher, a well, a tank, the [[Ganges]], and then the ocean where 'it very nearly filled the vast expanse of the great ocean'. Identifying the gigantic fish as Krishna, Manu is warned by Matsya that in 'a few days time, O King, the Universe shall be [[Outburst flood|deluged]] with water, along with the mountains and forests', adding that the [[Deva (Hinduism)|Devas]] had created a boat to rescue creation which Manu is to take charge of to 'help the distressed' and to tie to His horn if in danger from strong gusts of wind (Chapter 1).\n[[File:Budha graha.JPG|thumb|200x200px|[[Budha]], husband of Ila.]]\nThe dissolution of the Earth is described to Vaivasvata by Matsya, beginning with no rain for a hundred years, famine as the rays of the sun 'shall become seven times more powerful', and subterranean fire from the thousand mouths of [[Shesha|Sesa]] which will destroy creation, reducing the three worlds to ash. Then 'the seven destructive [<nowiki/>[[pralaya]]] clouds, viz - Samvarta,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wisdomlib.org/definition/samvarta|title=Samvarta, Sa\u1e43varta: 10 definitions|last=www.wisdomlib.org|date=2012-06-29|website=www.wisdomlib.org|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref> Bhimanada,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wisdomlib.org/definition/bhimanada|title=Bhimanada, Bh\u012bman\u0101da, Bhima-nada: 3 definitions|last=www.wisdomlib.org|date=2017-03-31|website=www.wisdomlib.org|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref> Drona,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wisdomlib.org/definition/drona|title=Drona, Dro\u1e47\u0101, Dro\u1e47a: 16 definitions|last=www.wisdomlib.org|date=2012-06-29|website=www.wisdomlib.org|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref> Chanda, Balahaka,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wisdomlib.org/definition/balahaka|title=Balahaka, Bal\u0101haka: 8 definitions|last=www.wisdomlib.org|date=2017-08-03|website=www.wisdomlib.org|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref> Vidyut Pataka,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wisdomlib.org/definition/vidyutpataka|title=Vidyutpataka, Vidyutpat\u0101ka: 1 definition|last=www.wisdomlib.org|date=2017-06-07|website=www.wisdomlib.org|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref> and Sona,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wisdomlib.org/definition/shona|title=Shona, \u015ao\u1e47a, So\u1e47a, Sona, \u015ao\u1e47\u0101, So\u1e47\u0101: 15 definitions|last=www.wisdomlib.org|date=2009-04-12|website=www.wisdomlib.org|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref> would spring up from the vapours arising out of such a head, and would rain in torrents till all the seas become united in one great mass'. Matsya, before disappearing, also states that at the beginning of re-creation, He will bring back [[Vedas|Vedic]] knowledge. Finally, after performing [[Yoga]], Vaivasvata boards the boat at the time of dissolution, [[Shesha|Sesa]] appears in the shape of a rope, and the horned Matsya reappears to narrate the Matsya Purana (Chapter 2).\n\n==== Ila ====\nNotably, the remainder of the legend from the [[Shatapatha Brahmana]] (White [[Yajurveda|YajurVeda]]), where Manu is taken to safety by Matsya to a mountain where he consequently performs a sacrifice to produce his \"daughter\" [[Ila (Hinduism)|Ila]] is not mentioned. Instead it is stated in a separate legend that [[Shraddhadeva Manu|Vaivasvata]] had ten '''sons''', 'the eldest of whom was Ila who was born by the performance of [a] [[Putrakameshti|putresti]] sacrifice'. It was Ila - not [[Solar dynasty|Iskwaku]] - who was made King, who then 'started on an expedition of conquest and visited several countries'. Happening to enter Saravana, the pleasure gardens of [[Shiva]] who was enjoying conjugal love with His consort [[Parvati]], Ila 'was instantly transformed into a woman, and his horse was transformed into a mare'. Ila - as a woman again - later marries [[Budha]], the son of the [[Soma (deity)|Moon]] (Chapter 11).\n\n=== Narada Purana ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" |[[Narada Purana|Narada]]\n!References\n!Notes\n|-\n|'''Part 1:''' 11.52;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.12945|title=THE NARADA-PURANA PART. 1|last=N.A|date=1950|publisher=MOTILAL BANARSIDASS PUBLISHERS PRIVATE LIMITED, DELHI DELHI}}</ref> '''Part 2:''' 62.52;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.20659|title=THE NARADA-PURANA PART. 2|last=N.A.|date=1950|publisher=MOTILAL BANARSIDASS PUBLISHERS PVT. DELHI}}</ref> '''Part 3:''' 65.59, 71.152.153, 71.161;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.21516|title=THE NARADA-PURANA PART. 3|last=N.A.|date=1952|publisher=MOTILAL BANARSIDASS PUBLISHERS PVT. DELHI}}</ref> '''Part 4:''' 114.2, 119.14-19, 125.62-64;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.12976|title=THE NARADA-PURANA PART. 4|last=N.A|date=1952|publisher=MOTILAL BANARSIDASS PUBLISHERS PVT. LTD, DELHI}}</ref> '''Part 5:''' Uttarabhaga - 55.47-48 (flood), 56.14-18, 57.30, 67.45-47<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.12978|title=THE NARADA-PURANA PART. 5|last=N.A|date=1952|publisher=MOTILAL BANARSIDASS PUBLISHERS PVT. LTD, DELHI}}</ref>\n|The Narada Purana focuses on worship and rituals.\n|}\n\n{{quote|O [[Mohini]], listen to another great holy pool here itself. By taking a holy dip here with devotion, the man becomes master of the [[Vedas]]. The [[Asura]] named Hayasiras, a terror to [[Deva (Hinduism)|Devas]] and others, snatched away [[Vedas]] coming out of the mouth of god [[Brahma]].  Thereupon, prayed to by Brahma, [[Vishnu|Visnu]] manifested himself in the form of a divine Fish [Matsya]. The lord killed the demon and handed over the Vedas to Brahma.|source=Narada Purana, unknown translator (1952), Part 5, Chapter 67, Verses 45-47}}\n\n[[File:Matsya Raja Ravi Varma Press.jpg|thumb|Matsya with the [[Vedas]] depicted as infants.|alt=|250x250px]]\n\nIt seems the legend of Matsya rescuing [[Shraddhadeva Manu|Manu]] from the flood is not narrated in the [[Naradiya Purana|Narada Purana]]. Instead, a brief account of Matsya destroying the demon Hayasiras (i.e. Hayagriva) to return the [[Vedas]] to [[Brahma]] is given, similar to the accounts of the [[Agni Purana|Agni]] and [[Garuda Purana|Garuda]] [[Puranas]] (see above). Notably, worldly existence is described as a 'terrible ocean... Miseries constitute its foams; it is turbulent with furious temperament constituting its sharks and crocodiles. The mundane affairs are its flood of waters; the different kinds of ailments are its waves; it is impassable due to the whirlpool of delusion' (Part 5: Uttarabhaga - 55.47-48). Also notably - especially as virtually identical to the account given in the [[Brahma Purana]] (see above) - mention is made of visiting the shrines of Matsya (Matsyamadhava; 'who had at the outset assumed the form of a fish of the [[Rohu|Rohita]] type') and King Sveta (Svetamadhava; Part 5: Uttarabhaga - 56.14-16). Other details include: \n\n* It is stated that the legend of Matsya is narrated in the eighth [[Skandha]] (or canto) of the [[Bhagavata Purana|Srimad Bhagavatam]] (Part 4 96.14-15a),\n* It is stated that the 'Pancami (fifth day) in the bright half of the month of [[Chaitra|Caitra]] is called Matsya Jayanti. On this day, the worship of the incarnation of the Lord as (Divine) fish is to be formed with great festivities, by devotees' (Part 4: 114.2)\n* In ritual worship, 'a beautiful square-shaped put fourteen [[A\u1e45gula|Angulas]] deep should be made and sprinkled with sandal water. After filling it with the milk of cows, the devotee should put in it an image of a fish made of gold and exquisite in every limb, and with eyes constituted of pearls. Uttering the [[Mantra]], 'Obeisance to the great fish' the devotee should worship it with scents and other things and offer it to a [[Brahmin|Brahmana]]' (Part 4: 125.62-64)\n* [[Kama]] (Cupid) has a fish for a banner (Part 4: Uttarabhaga - 2.44b-46 and 19.14)\n* Matsya is listed as the first of the [[Dashavatara]], or ten primary incarnations of [[Vishnu]] (Part 4: 119.14-19)\n\n=== Padma Purana ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" |[[Padma Purana|Padma]]\n!References\n!Notes\n|-\n|'''Part 1:''' 1.44b-50, 3.25b-29, 8.75-77, 8.118-119;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/padma_purana_part1_english|title=Padma Purana Part 1 Srishti Khanda Motilal Banarsidass 1988|last=N. A. Deshpande|date=1988-01-01}}</ref> '''Part 2:''' --;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/padma_purana_part2_english|title=Padma Purana Part 2 Srishti Khanda Motilal Banarsidass 1989|last=N. A. Deshpande|date=1989-01-01}}</ref> '''Part 3:''' 19.60-71, 75.1-6;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.21960|title=THE PADMA-PURANA PART. 3|last=N.A.|date=1951|publisher=MOTILAL BANARSIDASS PUBLISHERS PVT. DELHI}}</ref> '''Part 4:''' --;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.12948|title=THE PADMA-PURANA PART. 4|last=N.A|date=1952|publisher=MOTILAL BANARSIDASS PUBLISHERS PVT. LTD, DELHI}}</ref> '''Part 5:''' 22.28-36;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.21800|title=THE PADMA-PURANA PART. 5|last=N.A|date=1952|publisher=MOTILAL BANARSIDASS PUBLISHERS PVT. DELHI}}</ref> '''Part 6:''' 77.48b-51;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.22055|title=THE PADMA-PURANA PART. 6|last=N.A|date=1952|publisher=MOTILAL BANARSIDASS PUBLISHERS PVT. DELHI}}</ref> '''Part 7:''' 30.11-15, 66.44-54, 71.23-29, 71.169-188, 80.137-146a;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.12949|title=THE PADMA-PURANA PART. 7|last=N.A|date=1952|publisher=MOTILAL BANARSIDASS PUBLISHERS PVT. LTD, DELHI}}</ref> '''Part 8:'''  91.1-11, 95.10-24, 98.2-4, 120.51b-73;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.12952|title=THE PADMA-PURANA PART. 8|last=N.A|date=1952|publisher=MOTILAL BANARSIDASS PUBLISHERS PVT. LTD, DELHI}}</ref> '''Part 9:''' 197.57b-70a, 229.40-44, 230;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.12954|title=THE PADMA-PURANA PART. 9|last=N.A|date=1956|publisher=MOTILAL BANARSIDASS PUBLISHERS PVT. LTD, DELHI}}</ref> '''Part 10:'''  253.71-81, Kritayogasara Khanda - 6.175-190, 11.92b-101, 17.1-3-117<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.21961|title=THE PADMA-PURANA PART.10|last=N.A.|date=1956|publisher=MOTILAL BANARSIDASS PUBLISHERS PVT. DELHI}}</ref>\n|\n|}\n\n{{quote|<poem>...[[Vishnu|Visnu]] taking up the form resembling a small glittering fish fell into the hollow of the hands of [[Kashyapa|Kasyapa]] at his residence on the [[Vindhya Range|Vindhya]] (mountain). The sage kindly and quickly put him into (his) water-pot. When it could not contain itself there, he put it into a well. When it could not contain itself there, he put it into a lake. In this way it was (in the end) put into the sea. It grew there also. Then Vishnu, having the form of a fish, killed Sankha. Then taking him in his hand he came to the Badari-forest. Calling all the sages there, he ordered them (like) this.\n\nRemove the [[Vedas]] dropped into the water. Quickly bring them with the [[Upanishads]] from the interior of the water. Till then I, with the group of deities, shall live and [[Allahabad|Prayaga]]. Then all the sages, endowed with the power of penance, lifted the Vedas with the six [[Vedanga|Vedangas]] and with [[Yajna|sacrifices]]... Then all the sages together went to Prayaga. They presented the Vedas obtained by them to Vishnu with the Creator. [[Brahma]], obtained the Vedas with the sacrifices was delighted; and with the group of deities and sages he performed the horse-sacrifice.</poem>|source=Padma Purana, translated by N.A. Deshpande (1988), Part 8, Chapter 91, Verses 1-11}}[[File:Matsya painting.jpg|thumb|left|Matsya preparing to slay the demon.|alt=|200x200px]]There are two accounts of the Matsya legend in [[Padma Purana]]. In the first, it is [[Kashyapa|Kasyapa]] - a [[Saptarishi]] synonymous with [[Kurma]] - who rears Matsya, not the Manu [[Shraddhadeva Manu|Vaivasvata]]. The story itself is in regards to rescuing the Vedas from the demon Sankha (Hayasiras or Hayagriva in other accounts), not in regards to protection from the deluge or dissolution of the Earth. It is also the sages that return the [[Vedas]] to [[Brahma]], not [[Vishnu]] (i.e. in other accounts, such as that below, it is usually the horse-headed avatar also called '[[Hayagriva]]', or the fish avatar, that returns the Vedas to Brahma; Part 8: 91.1-11).\n\nIn the second account, [[Kashyapa|Kasyapa]] is stated to have had four (i.e. not thirteen) wives: [[Aditi]], [[Diti]], [[Kadru]] and [[Vinata]]. As well as [[Hiranyaksha|Hiranyaksa]] and [[Hiranyakashipu]] ([[Asura|Asuras]] relating to the legends of the [[Varaha]] and [[Narasimha]] avatars, respectively), Diti also gives birth to other demons including Hayagriva and [[Makara]]. \n\nIt is Makara, through performance of severe penances, who enters into the realm of [[Brahma]], steals the [[Vedas]], and enters 'into the great ocean' with them, causing ruin to the world. Reminiscent of the legend of [[Kurma]], Brahma, 'surrounded by the hosts of all gods, went to the [[Samudra manthan|Milky Ocean]], and seeking refuge of god ([[Vishu]])' informs Him of what has happened. Vishnu 'thus addressed by Brahma, resorted to the Fish-form [Matsya] and entered the great ocean' before then adopting the form of a [[crocodile]] to kill Makara and return the Vedas, [[Vedanga|Vedangas]], and Upangas to Brahma. Other details include:\n\n<br />\n\n* [[Ila (Hinduism)|Ila]] was created from a sacrifice by [[Shraddhadeva Manu|Manu]] to produce a son (Part 1: 8.75-77) and alternated between being man for one month (called Sudyumna) and woman in another; made  pregnant by [[Budha]] (Part 1: 8.118-119)\n* Matsya is listed as first in the [[Dashavatara]], the ten primary incarnations of [[Vishnu]] (Part 7: 66.44-54 and 71.23-29 and Part 9: 229.40-44)\n* 'That [<nowiki/>[[Shaligram|salagrama]]] stone which is long, has a golden complexion, and adorned with three lines, is known as 'Matsya', and gives the fruit like enjoyments and salvation' (Part 8: 120.51b-73)\n* It is stated about [[Vishnu]] that 'You are the Fish holding the [[Vedas]]' (Part 9: 197.57b-70a) and that 'taking the form of a Fish, extracted the Vedas' (Part 10: Kritayogasara khanda - 6.175-190)\n* It is stated 'The third auspicious covering [of [[Vaikuntha]]] consists of the worlds of Matsya, Kurma, etc.' (Part 9: 228.59-65)\n\n=== Shiva Purana ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" |[[Shiva Purana|Shiva]]\n!References\n!Notes\n|-\n|'''Part 1:''' Rudra-Samhita II - 2.24-29 ([[Kama]] fish banner and vehicle);<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/SivaPuranaJ.L.ShastriPart1|title=Siva Purana - English Translation - Part 1 of 4|last=J.L.Shastri|date=1950}}</ref> '''Part 2:''' 17.16, Yuddha Khanda - 16.16;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/SivaPuranaJ.L.ShastriPart2|title=Siva Purana - English Translation - Part 2 of 4|last=J.L.Shastri|date=1950}}</ref> '''Part 3:''' Satarudra Samhita - 11.18;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/SivaPuranaJ.L.ShastriPart3|title=Siva Purana - English Translation - Part 3 of 4|last=J.L.Shastri|date=1950}}</ref> '''Part 4:''' Uma Samhita - 36; Vayaviya Samhita - 30.56-58, 31.134-136<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/SivaPuranaJ.L.ShastriPart4|title=Siva Purana - English Translation - Part 4 of 4|last=J.L.Shastri|date=1950}}</ref>\n|\n|}\nThe legend of Matsya does not seem to be narrated in the [[Shiva Purana]]. Matsya is however listed as first in the [[Dashavatara]], the ten principle [[Avatar|avatars]] of [[Vishnu]] (Part 4: Vayaviya Samhita: Chapter 30.56-58 and 31.134-136). it is also mentioned that [[Shraddhadeva Manu|Vaivasvata]] had nine sons, plus a daughter [[Ila (Hinduism)|Ila]] from performance of a sacrifice. Born 'of the parts of [[Mitra]] and [[Varuna]]', these deities inform Ila that she 'alone will become the son establishing the family of Manu. You will be famous in the three worlds as Sudyumna' (Part 4: Uma Samhita - 36).\n\n=== Skanda Purana ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" |[[Skanda Purana|Skanda]]\n!References\n!Notes\n|-\n|'''Part 1:''' --;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.12961|title=THE SKANDA-PURANA PART. 1|last=N.A|date=1950|publisher=MOTILAL BANARSIDASS PUBLISHERS PVT. LTD, DELHI}}</ref> '''Part 2:''' Kaumarkika Khanda - 13.194, 36.25;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.13010|title=THE SKANDA-PURANA PART. 2|last=N.A|date=1950|publisher=MOTILAL BANARSIDASS PUBLISHERS PVT. LTD, DELHI}}</ref> '''Part 3:''' Uttarardha - 8.20, 9.16, 16.18;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.20835|title=THE SKANDA-PURANA PART. 3|last=N.A.|date=1951|publisher=MOTILAL BANARSIDASS PUBLISHERS PVT. DELHI}}</ref> '''Part 4:''' --;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.13009|title=THE SKANDA-PURANA PART. 4|last=N.A|date=1951|publisher=MOTILAL BANARSIDASS PUBLISHERS PVT. LTD, DELHI}}</ref> '''Part 5:''' Purusottama-Ksetra-Mahatmya - 15.30, 22.32.43, 38.113-117;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.20756|title=THE SKANDA-PURANA PART. 5|last=N.A.|date=1951|publisher=MOTILAL BANARSIDASS PUBLISHERS PVT. DELHI}}</ref> '''Part 6:''' Karttikamsa-Mahatmya - 13, 14.1, 16.2, 34.27-28, Margasirsa-Mahatmya - 3.23-25, 14.25-28, Bhagavata-Mahatmyha - 3.29-32;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.20761|title=THE SKANDA-PURANA PART. 6|last=N.A.|date=1951|publisher=MOTILAL BANARSIDASS PUBLISHERS PVT. DELHI}}</ref> '''Part 7:''' Ayidhya-Mahatmya 1.64-67, 18.12-20, 27.32-33;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.13008|title=THE SKANDA-PURANA PART. 7|last=N.A|date=1951|publisher=MOTILAL BANARSIDASS PUBLISHERS PVT. LTD, DELHI}}</ref> '''Part 8:''' Setu-Mahaymya - 3.81-82, 37.15-20, 46.37-43, 48.47-52;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.22054|title=THE SKANDA-PURANA PART. 8|last=N.A.|date=1953|publisher=MOTILAL BANARSIDASS PUBLISHERS PVT. DELHI}}</ref> '''Part 9:'''  Dharmaranya Khanda - 8.53-59;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.21994|title=THE SKANDA-PURANA PART. 9|last=N.A.|date=1953|publisher=MOTILAL BANARSIDASS PUBLISHERS PVT. DELHI}}</ref> '''Part 10:''' Purvardha - 21.7;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.13007|title=THE SKANDA-PURANA PART.10|last=N.A|date=1953|publisher=MOTILAL BANARSIDASS PUBLISHERS PVT. LTD, DELHI}}</ref> '''Part 11:''' Uttarardha - 69.141;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.13006|title=THE SKANDA-PURANA PART.11|last=N.A|date=1955|publisher=MOTILAL BANARSIDASS PUBLISHERS PVT. LTD, DELHI}}</ref> '''Part 12:''' Avantiksetra-Mahatmya - 8.20-26, 63.81;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.22009|title=THE SKANDA-PURANA PART.12|last=N.A.|date=1955|publisher=MOTILAL BANARSIDASS PUBLISHERS PVT. DELHI}}</ref> '''Part 13''': --;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.20764|title=THE SKANDA-PURANA PART.13|last=N.A.|date=1955|publisher=MOTILAL BANARSIDASS PUBLISHERS PVT. DELHI}}</ref> '''Part 14:''' Reva Khanda - 3.23-32, 9;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.100076|title=The Skanda-purana Part.14|last=Not Available|date=1957}}</ref> '''Part 15:''' Reva Khanda - 151.8-17, 151.1-7;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.20778|title=THE SKANDA-PURANA PART.15|last=N.A.|date=1957|publisher=MOTILAL BANARSIDASS PUBLISHERS PVT. DELHI}}</ref> '''Part 16:''' --;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.13005|title=THE SKANDA-PURANA PART.16|last=N.A|date=1958|publisher=MOTILAL BANARSIDASS PUBLISHERS PVT. LTD, DELHI}}</ref> '''Part 17:''' --;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.13004|title=THE SKANDA-PURANA PART.17|last=N.A|date=1958|publisher=MOTILAL BANARSIDASS PUBLISHERS PVT. LTD, DELHI}}</ref> '''Part 18:''' Nagara Khanda - 254.92;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.13003|title=THE SKANDA-PURANA PART.18|last=N.A|date=1960|publisher=MOTILAL BANARSIDASS PUBLISHERS PVT. LTD, DELHI}}</ref> '''Part 19:''' Prabhasa-Ksetra Mahatmya - 2.20-23;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.13002|title=THE SKANDA-PURANA PART.19|last=N.A|date=1960|publisher=MOTILAL BANARSIDASS PUBLISHERS PVT. LTD, DELHI}}</ref> '''Part 20:''' Prabhasa Khanda: 152.4 ('The earth is called Ila')<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.13000|title=THE SKANDA-PURANA PART.20|last=N.A|date=1960|publisher=MOTILAL BANARSIDASS PUBLISHERS PVT. LTD, DELHI}}</ref>\n|\n|}\n\n{{quote|<poem>Formerly there was a [[Daitya]] called [[Panchatantra|Damanaka]]. He had become very powerful due to [[Maya (religion)|Maya]]. He harassed people. He could move through the waters of [the] ocean. The Lord too could wield Maya. At the request of [[Brahma]] the Lord took up the incarnation of [a] Fish and entered the ocean. He searched for and found (the demon). He dragged him to the shore and thrashed him on the surface of the earth. The excellent [[Danava (Hinduism)|Danava]] fell on the fourteenth day in the bright half of the month of Madhu (i.e [[Chaitra|Caitra]]).\n\nBy contact of the hands of the Lord he became a fragrant gross of the same name, i.e. Damanaka (Artemisia indica). The Lord accepted it with a surprised mind. He made a garland of it and wore it on his chest along with the garland of sylvan flowers. He thought that its fragrance should stay as long as the object exists.</poem>|source=Skanda Purana, Unknown translator (1951), Part 5: Purusottama-Ksetra-Mahatmya, Chapter 38, Verses 113-117}}\n\nThere are several accounts of Matsya in the [[Skanda Purana]]. In the first, as quoted above, [[Vishnu]] in the form of Matsya destroys the [[Asura]] called Damanaka in the ocean, who turns into fragrant Damanaka grass. This story is in relation to the Matsya Jayanti which takes place in [[Chaitra|Caitra]], as related by the [[Naradiya Purana|Narada Purana]] (Part 5: Purusottama-Ksetra-Mahatmya: 38.113-117). From the second account:\n\n{{quote|<poem>Formerly there was an [[Asura]] named Sankha. He was the son of Sagara (Ocean). He usurped the powers of [[Indra]] and other Guardians of the Quarters... on seeing [[Vishnu]] asleep, he took away the [[Vedas]] [to weaken the gods] from the primordial self-born Lord [[Brahma]] from [[Brahmaloka|Satyaloka]]. While they were being carried away by him, the Vedas, out of fear of him, escaped and entered the waters along with the seeds of the Yajnamantras. In search of them, Sankha too entered the ocean. Wandering here and there the [[Daitya]] did not find them together anywhere...\n\n[Vishnu said:] All the Vedas carried away by Sankha now lie submerged in the waters. O Devas, I shall bring them all after killing the son of the Ocean... After saying this, Lord Visnu assumed the form of a Saphari fish and plunged into the water from the sky even as Brahma staying on [[Vindhya Range|Vindhya]] was watching. After killing [the] Asura Sankha, Visnu went to the forest of Badari. There the Lord called together all the sages and commanded thus: O you all, do search for the Vedas scattered within the waters. Bring them quickly from the midst of the waters of the sea. Till then I shall remain at [[Prayaga]] accompanied by the groups of [[Deva (Hinduism)|Devas]].</poem>|source=Skanda Purana, Unknown translator (1951), Part 6, Karttikamsa-Mahatmya, Chapter 13|author=|title=}}\n[[File:DASWANTH Birth of Brhma and madhu-kaitabha kill by vishnu.jpg|thumb|250x250px|The deaths of [[Madhu-Kaitabha|Madhu and Kaitabha]].]]\nNotably, the second account, as quoted above, is in many respects almost identical to the account in the [[Padma Purana]] (see above), with the exception of being nurtured by [[Kashyapa|Kasyapa]] (or, in the original account of the [[Shatapatha Brahmana]], [[Shraddhadeva Manu|Vaivasvata]] Manu; Part 6: Karttikamsa-Mahatmya: 13). In the third account, the Asuras [[Madhu-Kaitabha|Madhu and Kaitabha]] steal the [[Vedas]] from [[Brahma]] and enter 'the great ocean'. Mahadeva - i.e. [[Shiva]], not [[Vishnu]] in this account - assumes the form of a Fish, stirs up the ocean, and finds the Vedas in [[Patala]] before destroying the [[Daitya|Daityas]] and returning the Vedas to Brahma (Part 14: Reva Khanda: 9). Notably, in the [[Bhagavata Purana]], it is [[Vishnu]] in the form of [[Hayagriva]] (also the name of another Veda-stealing demon as described above) who retrieves the Vedas from Madhu and Kaitabha.\n\nThe fourth and fifth accounts are brief mentions of Matsya in relation to the legend of the flood and of [[Shraddhadeva Manu|Manu]]. In the fourth account Vishnu states <nowiki>''</nowiki>When you day ends, I shall become a fish and shall support (floating) like a boat, the earth along with its medicinal plants, Manus and others' (Part 7: Ayidhya-Mahatmya: 18.12-20). In the fifth account it is stated 'In order to please [[Brahma]] in a former [[Kalpa (aeon)|Kalpa]], the Lord became a Fish, recovered the [[Vedas]] that were immersed in the great sea and handed them over to Brahma' (Part 15: Reva Khanda - 151.8-17). Elsewhere, it is also stated that at the beginning of a new Kalpa, Vishnu in the form of Matsya taught the Vedas to Brahma (Part 19: Prabhasa-Ksetra Mahatmya - 2.20-23). The accounts of Matsya in this Purana are thus primarily concerned with the retrieval or restoration of the Vedas after being stolen by various demons. Other details include:\n\n* It is stated 'in the morning on [[Dwadashi|Dvadasi]] day, in the bright half of the month of [[Agrahayana|Margasirsa]], the Matsya festival is to be celebrated by the wise' (Part 6: Karttikamsa-Mahatmya: 14.1)\n* Matsya is stated to be the protector of the Vedas (Part 8: Setu-Mahaymya: 46.37-43)\n* Matsya is listed in the [[Dashavatara]], or ten primary incarnations of Vishnu (Part 15: Reva-Khanda, 151.1-7)\n* King [[Pururavas]] was the son of [[Ila (Hinduism)|Ila]] (Part 12: Avantiksetra-Mahatmya - 8.20-26); it is also stated that 'The earth is called Ila' (Part 20: Prabhasa Khanda: 152.4)\n* 'Matsya' is one of the thousand names ([[Vishnu Sahasranama]]) of [[Vishnu]] (Part 12: Avantiksetra-Mahatmya: 63.81)\n* It is stated that the Matsyavahana is the emblem of [[Parvati]] (Part 18: Nagara Khanda - 254.92)\n\n=== Vamana Purana ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" |[[Vamana Purana|Vamana]]\n!References\n!Notes\n|-\n| --<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.313087|title=The Vamana Purana With English Translation|last=Gupta|first=anand Swarup|date=1968}}</ref>\n|No notable mentions.\n|}\n=== Varaha Purana ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" |[[Varaha Purana|Varaha]]\n!References\n!Notes\n|-\n|'''Part 1:''' 1.6, 4.2-3, 7.40, 9, 12.8-9, 15.10, 15.18-19, 40.46-48, 48.17-22, 113.20, 113.42;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.12962|title=THE VARAHA PURANA PART. 1|last=N.A|date=1960|publisher=MOTILAL BANARSIDASS, DELHI}}</ref> '''Part 2:''' 211.69<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.12972|title=THE VARAHA PURANA PART. 2|last=N.A|date=1960|publisher=MOTILAL BANARSIDASS, DELHI}}</ref>\n|}\n\n{{quote|<poem>Night being over, the lotus-eyed God [<nowiki/>[[Narayana]]] got up and thought about the four [[Vedas]] and in them the Goddess of the Vedas. Despite this thinking, he did not get the Vedas because he was illusioned by the sense of sleep. He was in utter confusion. Then seeing them hidden in his own form called water, he thought of entering into it taking the form of a fish. So after meditating for sometime He took the form of a great fish and entered into the water agitating it all around. When the excellent God in the form of a huge fish resembling a big mountain, suddenly entered the ocean, He who uplifted the earth before was extolled...\n\nExtolled thus, the God caught the Vedas with [[Upanishads]] and [[Shastra|Sastras]] out of the water and then took his own form.</poem>|source=Varaha Purana, Unknown translator (1960), Part 1, Chapter 9|author=|title=}}\n\nAs quoted above, the account of Matsya in the [[Varaha Purana]] concerns the retrieval of the [[Vedas]] at the beginning of a new [[Kalpa (aeon)|Kalpa]], where creation begins anew. This occurs after the dissolution (i.e. annihilation) of creation at the end of the previous Kalpa, followed by the 'night' of [[Vishnu]] / [[Narayana]], which lasts 1,000 [[Yuga|Yugas]]. With the exceptions of verses listing Matsya as first in the [[Dashavatara]], the ten primary incarnations of Vishnu (Part 1: 4.2-3, 48.17-22 and Part 2: 211.69), almost all references to this avatar are in respect to retrieving the lost or stolen Vedas from the ocean.\n=== Vayu Purana ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" |[[Vayu Purana|Vayu]]\n!References\n!Notes\n|-\n|'''Part 1:''' --<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.12977|title=THE VAYU PURANA PART. 1|last=N.A|date=1960|publisher=MOTILAL BANARSIDASS PUBLISHERS PVT. LTD, DELHI|isbn=|location=|pages=377\u2013382}}</ref>; '''Part 2:''' 23;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.20638|title=THE VAYU PURANA PART. 2|last=N.A.|date=1960|publisher=MOTILAL BANARSIDASS, DELHI}}</ref>\n|No notable mentions.\n|}\n\n{{quote|Know that formerly [[Shraddhadeva Manu|Manu]], on being urged by [[Brahma]], began to create willingly, but he was unsuccessful. Then [[Prajapati]] [Manu], desirous of sons, performed a great ''Isti'' ([[Yajna]]). Manu offered the oblation (''Ahuti'') in the share of [[Mitra]] and [[Varuna]]. It is heard, that [[Ila (Hinduism)|Ida]] was born thereof. She wore heavenly garments and was bedecked in celestial ornaments. Her body too was divine. It is remembered that Manu, the bearer of the staff of justice, addressed her as 'Ila' and said, \"Welfare unto you, I shall follow you\".|source=Vayu Purana, Unknown translator, (1960), Part 2, Chapter 23, Verses 5-7}}\n\nAlthough there are no notable mentions of Matsya in the [[Vayu Purana]], the account of the birth of Ida at sacrifice of Manu clearly originates from the [[Shatapatha Brahmana]] (Part 2: 23.5-7). The account itself is very similar to that of the [[Brahmanda Purana]] (see above). Part 2 also contains detailed information on the [[Manu (Hinduism)|Manus]] and [[Saptarishi]].\n\n=== Vishnu Purana ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" |[[Vishnu Purana|VIshnu]]\n!References\n!Notes\n|-\n|'''Book 1:''' 4;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/vp/vp038.htm|title=The Vishnu Purana: Book I: Chapter IV|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-18}}</ref> '''Book 2:''' 2;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/vp/vp059.htm|title=The Vishnu Purana: Book II: Chapter II|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-18}}</ref> '''Book 3:''' --; '''Book 4:''' 1;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/vp/vp093.htm|title=The Vishnu Purana: Book IV: Chapter I|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-18}}</ref> '''Book 5:'''  --; '''Book 6:''' --;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/vp/index.htm|title=The Vishnu Purana Index|website=www.sacred-texts.com|access-date=2020-01-18}}</ref>\n|No notable mentions.\n|}\n\n{{quote|<poem>From the right thumb of [[Brahma|Brahm\u00e1]] was born the patriarch [[Daksha]]; his daughter was [[Aditi]], who was the mother of the sun. The Manu [[Shraddhadeva Manu|Vaivaswata]] was the son of the celestial luminary [<nowiki/>[[Surya]]]; and his sons were [[Ikshvaku|Ikshw\u00e1ku]], Nriga, Dhrisht\u0301a, \u015aary\u00e1ti, Narishyanta, Pr\u00e1n\u015bu, N\u00e1bh\u00e1ga, Nedisht\u0301a, Kar\u00fasha, and Prishadhra. Before their birth, the Manu being desirous of sons, offered a sacrifice for that purpose to [[Mitra]] and [[Varuna|Varu\u0144a]]; but the rite being deranged, through an irregularity of the ministering priest, a daughter, [[Ila (Hinduism)|Il\u00e1]], was produced. Through the favour of the two divinities, however, her sex was changed, and she became a man, named Sudyumna. \n\nAt a subsequent period, in consequence of becoming subject to the effects of a malediction once pronounced by [[Shiva|\u015aiva]], Sudyumna was again transformed to a woman in the vicinity of the hermitage of [[Budha]], the son of the deity of the [[Soma (deity)|moon]]. Budha saw and espoused her, and had by her a son named [[Pururavas|Pur\u00faravas]]. After his birth, the illustrious [[Rishi|Rishis]], desirous of restoring Sudyumna to his sex, prayed to the mighty [[Vishnu|Vish\u0144u]], who is the essence of the four [[Vedas]], of mind, of every thing, and of nothing; and who is in the form of the sacrificial male; and through his favour Il\u00e1 once more became Sudyumna, in which character he had three sons, Utkala, Gaya, and Vinata.</poem>|source=Vishnu Purana, translated by Horace Hayman Wilson (1840), Book IV, Chapter 1}}It seems the legend of Matsya is not narrated in the [[Vishnu Purana]]. As quoted above, the aspect of [[Shraddhadeva Manu|Vaivasvata]] performing a sacrifice and producing a \"daughter\" called Ida/[[Ila (Hinduism)|Ila]] from the original legend in the [[Shatapatha Brahmana]] is mentioned, albeit as a separate legend and in a modified form; it seems to contain elements also found in the [[Matsya Purana|Matsya]], [[Padma Purana|Padma]], and [[Skanda Purana|Skanda Puranas]], although Ila being produced due to a mistake by the ministering priest at the [[sacrifice]] seems to be shared only with the [[Bhagavata Purana]].\n\n== Upa-Puranas ==\n\n=== Vishnudharmottara ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" |[[Vishnudharmottara Purana|Vishnudharmottara]]\n!References\n!Notes\n|-\n|Adhyaya 32, 85.58-59, 106, 118.6;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.127780|title=Shri Vishnudharmottara|last=Shah|first=priyabala}}</ref>\n|This is [[Upapurana]] is a supplement to the [[Vishnu Purana]].\n|}\n\n* The Ardhacandra [[Mudra]] [symbolic hand gesture; palm open, fingers extended together, and thumb up like a fish-fin] signifies Matsya (Adhyaya 32)\n* Images of Matsya should depict Him with a horn (Adhyaya 85.58-59)\n* The Mantra of Matsya is 'I shall invoke god Matsya moving in the sea. O Matsya deva, the sustainer of the lives of the world, O infallible, kindly come' (Adhyaya 106)\n* Men 'desirous of grains' should worship Matsya (Adhyaya 118.6)\n\n==Iconography==\n[[File:Matsya Avatar, ca 1870.jpg|thumb|Matsya pulls Manu's boat after having defeated the demon (circa 1870)|alt=|left]]\n\nMatsya is depicted in two forms: as a [[zoomorphic]] fish or in an [[anthropomorphic]] form. In the latter form, the upper half is that of the four-armed man and the lower half is a fish. The upper half resembles Vishnu and wears the traditional ornaments and the ''kirita-makuta'' (tall conical crown) as worn by Vishnu. He holds in two of his hands the ''[[Sudarshana chakra]]'' (discus) and a ''[[shankha]]'' (conch), the usual weapons of Vishnu. The other two hands make the gestures of ''[[varadamudra]]'', which grants boons to the devotee, and ''[[abhayamudra]]'', which reassures the devotee of protection.<ref>Rao p. 127</ref> In another configuration, he might have all four attributes of Vishnu, namely the ''Sudarshana chakra'', a ''shankha'', a [[gada (weapon)|gada]] (mace) and a lotus.<ref name=\"Dalal2011\">{{cite book|author=Roshen Dalal|title=Hinduism: An Alphabetical Guide|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DH0vmD8ghdMC&pg=PA250|accessdate=12 January 2013|year= 2011|publisher=Penguin Books India|isbn=978-0-14-341421-6|page=250}}</ref> \n\nIn some representations, Matsya is shown with four hands like Vishnu, one holding the chakra, another the shankha, while the front two hands hold a sword and a book signifying the Vedas he recovered from the demon. Over his elbows is an angavastra draped, while a ''dhoti'' like draping covers his hips.<ref name=\"MuseumDallapiccola2010\">{{cite book|author1=British Museum|author2=Anna Libera Dallapiccola|title=South Indian Paintings: A Catalogue of the British Museum Collection|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FIzWapiacQcC&pg=PA78|accessdate=13 January 2013|year=2010|publisher=Mapin Publishing Pvt Ltd|isbn=978-0-7141-2424-7|pages=78, 117, 125}}</ref>\n\nIn rare representations, his lower half is human while the upper body (or just the face) is of a fish. The fish-face version is found in a relief at the [[Chennakesava Temple, Somanathapura]].<ref>[http://www.art-and-archaeology.com/india/mysore/kes09.html Hindu Temple, Somnathpur]</ref>\n\nMatsya may be depicted alone or in a scene depicting his combat with a demon. A demon called Shankhasura emerging from a conch is sometimes depicted attacking Matsya with a sword as Matsya combats or kills him. Both of them may be depicted in the ocean, while the god Brahma and/or manuscripts or four men, symbolizing the Vedas, may be depicted in the background.<ref name=\"MuseumDallapiccola2010\"/>\n\n==Comparative mythology==\n{{main|Flood myth}}[[File:15th-16th century Vaishnavism Vitthala temple Matsya avatar, Hampi Hindu monuments Karnataka.jpg|thumb|Matsya temples are relatively rare, but the iconography is found in Hindu temple reliefs. Above: Matsya on a mandapa pillar in [[Hampi]].]]\nThe story of a great Deluge is found in many civilizations across the earth. It is often related to the [[Genesis flood narrative|Genesis narrative]] of the flood and [[Noah's Ark]].<ref name=\"Dalal2011\" /> The fish motif reminds readers of the Biblical 'Jonah and the Whale' narrative as well;  this fish narrative, as well as the saving of the scriptures from a demon, are specifically Hindu traditions of this style of the flood narrative.{{sfn|Krishna|2009|p=35}} Similar flood myths also exist in tales from ancient [[Sumerian creation myth|Sumer]] and Babylonia, [[Deucalion|Greece]], the [[Maya peoples|Maya]] of Americas and the [[Yoruba people|Yoruba]] of Africa.<ref name=\"Dalal2011\" />\n\nMatsya is believed to symbolise the aquatic life as the first beings on earth.<ref name = \"Krishna36\">Krishna p. 36</ref> Another symbolic interpretation of the Matsya mythology is, states Bonnefoy, to consider Manu's boat to represent [[moksha]] (salvation), which helps one to cross over. The Himalayas are treated as a boundary between the earthly existence and land of salvation beyond. The protection of the fish and its horn represent the sacrifices that help guide Manu to salvation. Treated as a parable, the tale advises a good king should protect the weak from the mighty, reversing the \"law of fishes\" and uphold [[dharma]], like Manu, who defines an ideal king.{{sfn|Bonnefoy|1993|pp= 79-80}} In the tales where the demon hides the Vedas, dharma is threatened and Vishnu as the divine Saviour rescues dharma, aided by his earthly counterpart, Manu - the king.{{sfn|Bonnefoy|1993|p= 80}}\n\n==Worship and significance==\n===India===\nThere are very few temples dedicated to Matsya. Prominent ones include the Shankhodara temple in [[Bet Dwarka]] and [[Vedanarayana Temple, Nagalapuram|Vedanarayana Temple]] in [[Nagalapuram]].<ref name = \"Krishna36\"/> The [[Koneswaram temple|Koneswaram Matsyakeswaram temple in]] [[Trincomalee]] is now destroyed. [[Matsya Narayana Temple, Bangalore]] also exists.\n\nSome kingdoms have used sacred matsya as their state [[emblem]]. There was a [[Matsya Kingdom]] during [[vedic era]], which was one of the sixteen [[Mahajanapadas]] (great kingdoms) during as described in the hindu epic [[Mahabharta]] and 6th BCE Buddhist text ''Anguttara Nikaya''. After the [[Partition of India|Indian independence]] in 1947, the [[princely state]]s of [[Bharatpur State|Bharatpur]], [[Dholpur State|Dholpur]], [[Alwar State|Alwar]] and [[Karauli State|Karauli]] were temporarily put together from 1947 to 1949 as the ''\"United State of Matsya\"'', and later in March 1949 after these princely states signed the [[Instrument of Accession]] they were merged with the present state of [[Rajasthan]].<ref>[https://nwr.indianrailways.gov.in/uploads/files/1416202359797-Tourist%20Places.pdf NWR tourist places]</ref> '''Matsya Festival''' is held in [[Alwar]] every year in the last week of November to celebrate culture and adventure.<ref>[https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/travel/destinations/all-about-alwar-matsya-festival-2018/as66707230.cms All about Alwar Matsya Festival 2018], [[Times of India]], November 2018.</ref>\n\n===Korea===\n[[Jogyesa]] Buddhist Temple has [[Jogyesa#Layout|colorful matsya relics]].<ref>2011, [http://lib.perdana.org.my/PLF/PLF2/Digital_Content/PLF/000017/1008593.pdf World Mythology], Pustaka Perdana, Parragon, UK</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Apkallu]]\n*[[Dashavatara]]\n*[[Flood myth]]\n*[[Rishabhanatha]]\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|first=Yves|last= Bonnefoy|title=Asian Mythologies|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=r4I-FsZCzJEC|date=15 May 1993|publisher=University of Chicago Press|isbn=978-0-226-06456-7}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|first=Nanditha |last= Krishna|title=The Book of Vishnu|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=f9cSlaLMlgEC |year=2009|publisher=Penguin Books India|isbn=978-0-14-306762-7}}\n* {{cite book|last=Rao|first=T.A. Gopinatha|title=Elements of Hindu iconography |volume=1: Part I|year=1914|publisher=Law Printing House|location=Madras|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|author=George M. Williams|title=Handbook of Hindu Mythology|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=N7LOZfwCDpEC|year=2008|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-533261-2}}\n* {{cite book | last = Mani | first = Vettam | title = Puranic Encyclopaedia: a Comprehensive Dictionary with Special Reference to the Epic and Puranic Literature | url = https://archive.org/details/puranicencyclopa00maniuoft | publisher = Motilal Banarsidass Publishers | year = 1975 <!-- | location = Delhi --> | isbn = 978-0-8426-0822-0 | authorlink = Vettam Mani }}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Matsya}}\n\n{{VishnuAvatars}}\n{{HinduMythology}}\n\n[[Category:Fish gods]]\n[[Category:Forms of Vishnu]]\n[[Category:Flood myths]]\n[[Category:Mythological human hybrids]]\n[[Category:Water and Hinduism]]\n", "name_user": "Nittawinoda", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eComparative mythology", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Matsya"}
