14\n| 321\n| 0.0\n| {{nochange}}\n|-\n\n|style=\"background:silver;\" | &nbsp;\n| align=left| Others\n| 0\n| 0\n|0\n|{{nochange}}\n|\u2014\n| 151,054\n| 0.6\n| {{increase}}0.4\n|-\n\n! colspan=\"2\" |Total\n!533\n!\n!\n!\n!\n! style=\"text-align: right;\" |  27,165,789\n! align=left| Turnout\n! style=\"text-align: right;\" | 69.1\n|}\n\n{{bar box\n| title=Popular vote\n| titlebar=#ddd\n| width=600px\n| barwidth=410px\n| bars=\n {{bar percent|'''Conservative'''|{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}|45.4}}\n {{bar percent|Labour|{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}|41.9}}\n {{bar percent|Liberal Democrats|{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}|7.8}}\n {{bar percent|UKIP|{{UK Independence Party/meta/color}}|2.1}}\n {{bar percent|Green|{{Green Party of England and Wales/meta/color}}|1.9}}\n {{bar percent|Other|#777777|0.9}}\n}}\n\n{{bar box\n| title=Parliament seats\n| titlebar=#ddd\n| width=600px\n| barwidth=410px\n| bars=\n {{bar percent|'''Conservative'''|{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}|55.5}}\n {{bar percent|Labour|{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}|42.6}}\n {{bar percent|Liberal Democrats|{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}|1.5}}\n {{bar percent|Green|{{Green Party of England and Wales/meta/color}}|0.2}}\n {{bar percent|Speaker|black|0.2}}\n}}\n\n==Analysis==\n\nThe [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservatives]] retained a majority of seats in England, though with a net loss of 23 seats. They also increased their share of the vote to their highest since [[1987 United Kingdom general election|1987]].\n\nThe [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] substantially increased their share of the vote and made gains for the first time since [[2001 United Kingdom general election|2001]], but did not overtake the Conservatives. Labour received its highest share of the vote in England since [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]].\n\nThe [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]], led by [[Tim Farron]] saw their previous leader [[Nick Clegg]] lose his seat; as [[Sheffield Hallam (UK Parliament constituency)|Sheffield Hallam]] was gained by the Labour candidate, [[Jared O'Mara]]. They also lost their [[2016 Richmond Park by-election|by-election]] gain at [[Richmond Park (UK Parliament constituency)|Richmond Park]] to [[Zac Goldsmith]] of the Conservatives; whose resignation on 25 October 2016 triggered the by-election initially. They also gained some seats, including the recovery of [[Twickenham (UK Parliament constituency)|Twickenham]] by former Business Secretary [[Sir Vince Cable]] who had lost it to the Conservatives [[2015 United Kingdom general election|two years previously]]. Cable succeeded Farron as party leader on 20 July 2017.\n\nUKIP saw their share of the vote collapse to almost negligible levels. They failed to gain any new seats and their one success from 2015, [[Clacton (UK Parliament constituency)|Clacton]], returned to Conservative control. [[Paul Nuttall]] resigned as party leader on 9 June 2017 after finishing in third place at [[Boston and Skegness (UK Parliament constituency)|Boston and Skegness]].\n\nThe [[Green Party of England and Wales|Green Party]] decreased its share of the vote and failed to make any gains, but retained [[Brighton Pavilion (UK Parliament constituency)|Brighton Pavilion]]. The party deliberately chose not to contest many seats, in order to give Labour an increased chance of winning over Conservative candidates.\n\n==Regional results==\n\nRegional vote shares and changes are sourced from [https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1SGkPQqosDbVL9tSX_uMNaXPGiW2z02z2fchDezlyNss/edit#gid=1413119988 Britain Elects].\n\n===East Midlands===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:right; font-size:95%;\"\n|+\n! colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"2\" |Party\n! colspan=\"5\" |Seats\n! colspan=\"3\" |Votes\n|-\n! Total !! Gains !! Losses\n!Net +/-\n!% seats\n!Total votes\n!% votes\n!Change\n|-\n{{Party name with colour|Conservative Party (UK)}}\n| 31\n| 2\n| 3\n| {{decrease}}1\n|67.4\n| 1,195,983\n| 50.8\n| {{increase}}7.3\n|-\n{{Party name with colour|Labour Party (UK)}}\n| 15\n| 3\n| 2\n| {{increase}}1\n|32.6\n| 952,295\n| 40.5\n| {{increase}}8.9\n|-\n{{Party name with colour|Liberal Democrats (UK)}}\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n| {{nochange}}\n|\u2014\n| 101,612\n| 4.3\n| {{decrease}}1.3\n|-\n{{Party name with colour|UKIP}}\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n| {{nochange}}\n|\u2014\n| 56,358\n| 2.4\n| {{decrease}}13.4\n|-\n{{Party name with colour|Green Party of England and Wales}}\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n| {{nochange}}\n|\u2014\n| 34,355\n| 1.5\n| {{decrease}}1.5\n|-\n|style=\"background:silver;\" | &nbsp;\n| align=left| Others\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n| {{nochange}}\n|\u2014\n| 13,247\n| 0.6\n| \u2014\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"background:#f2f2f2\" | Total\n|style=\"background:#f2f2f2;\" | '''46'''\n|style=\"background:#f2f2f2;\" |\n|style=\"background:#f2f2f2;\" |\n|style=\"background:#f2f2f2;\" |\n|style=\"background:#f2f2f2;\" |\n|style=\"background:#f2f2f2;\" | '''2,353,850'''\n|style=\"background:#f2f2f2;\" | '''69.0'''\n|style=\"background:#f2f2f2;\" | '''{{increase}}2.5'''\n|}\n\n<gallery perrow=\"5\" widths=\"150\" heights=\"150\">File:United Kingdom General Election 2017 Results Map (East Midlands).svg|East Midlands</gallery>\n\n===East of England===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:right; font-size:95%;\"\n|+\n! colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"2\" |Party\n! colspan=\"5\" |Seats\n! colspan=\"3\" |Votes\n|-\n! Total !! Gains !! Losses\n!Net +/-\n!% seats\n!Total votes\n!% votes\n!Change\n|-\n{{Party name with colour|Conservative Party (UK)}}\n| 50\n| 1\n| 3\n| {{decrease}}2\n|86.2\n| 1,690,813\n| 54.7\n| {{increase}}5.7\n|-\n{{Party name with colour|Labour Party (UK)}}\n| 7\n| 3\n| 0\n| {{increase}}3\n|12.1\n| 1,012,359\n| 32.8\n| {{increase}}10.8\n|-\n{{Party name with colour|Liberal Democrats (UK)}}\n| 1\n| 0\n| 0\n| {{nochange}}\n| 1.7\n| 244,064\n| 7.9\n| {{decrease}}0.3\n|-\n{{Party name with colour|UKIP}}\n| 0\n| 0\n| 1\n| {{decrease}}1\n| \u2014\n| 77,793\n| 2.5\n| {{decrease}}13.7\n|-\n{{Party name with colour|Green Party of England and Wales}}\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n| {{nochange}}\n| \u2014\n| 58,684\n| 1.9\n| {{decrease}}2.0\n|-\n|style=\"background:silver;\" | &nbsp;\n| align=left| Others\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n| {{nochange}}\n| \u2014\n| 6,262\n| 0.2\n| {{decrease}}0.3\n|-\n\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"background:#f2f2f2\" | Total\n|style=\"background:#f2f2f2;\" | '''58'''\n|style=\"background:#f2f2f2;\" |\n|style=\"background:#f2f2f2;\" |\n|style=\"background:#f2f2f2;\" |\n|style=\"background:#f2f2f2;\" |\n|style=\"background:#f2f2f2;\" | '''3,089,966'''\n|style=\"background:#f2f2f2;\" | \n|style=\"background:#f2f2f2;\" | \n|}\n\n<gallery perrow=\"5\" widths=\"150\" heights=\"150\">File:United Kingdom General Election 2017 Results Map (East of England).svg|East of England</gallery>\n\n===London===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:right; font-size:95%;\"\n|+\n! colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"2\" |Party\n! colspan=\"5\" |Seats\n! colspan=\"3\" |Votes\n|-\n! Total !! Gains !! Losses\n!Net +/-\n!% seats\n!Total votes\n!% votes\n!Change\n|-\n{{Party name with colour|Labour Party (UK)}}\n| 49\n| 4\n| 0\n| {{increase}}4\n| 67.1\n| 2,087,010\n| 54.6\n| {{increase}}10.9\n|-\n{{Party name with colour|Conservative Party (UK)}}\n| 21\n| 0\n| 6\n| {{decrease}}6\n| 28.8\n| 1,268,800\n| 33.2\n| {{decrease}}1.7\n|-\n{{Party name with colour|Liberal Democrats (UK)}}\n| 3\n| 2\n| 0\n| {{increase}}2\n| 4.1\n| 336,680\n| 8.8\n| {{increase}}1.1\n|-\n{{Party name with colour|Green Party of England and Wales}}\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n| {{nochange}}\n| \u2014\n| 67,579\n| 1.8\n| {{decrease}}3.1\n|-\n{{Party name with colour|UKIP}}\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n| {{nochange}}\n| \u2014\n| 49,369\n| 1.3\n| {{decrease}}6.8\n|-\n|style=\"background:silver;\" | &nbsp;\n| align=left| Others\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n| {{nochange}}\n| \u2014\n| 11,795\n| 0.3\n| {{decrease}}0.5\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"background:#f2f2f2\" | Total\n|style=\"background:#f2f2f2;\" | '''73'''\n|style=\"background:#f2f2f2;\" |\n|style=\"background:#f2f2f2;\" |\n|style=\"background:#f2f2f2;\" |\n|style=\"background:#f2f2f2;\" |\n|style=\"background:#f2f2f2;\" | '''3,821,233'''\n|style=\"background:#f2f2f2;\" | \n|style=\"background:#f2f2f2;\" | \n|}\n\n<gallery perrow=\"5\" widths=\"150\" heights=\"150\">File:United Kingdom General Election 2017 Results Map (London).svg|London</gallery>\n\n===North East England===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:right; font-size:95%;\"\n|+\n! colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"2\" |Party\n! colspan=\"5\" |Seats\n! colspan=\"3\" |Votes\n|-\n! Total !! Gains !! Losses\n!Net +/-\n!% seats\n!Total votes\n!% votes\n!Change\n|-\n{{Party name with colour|Labour Party (UK)}}\n| 26\n| 1\n| 1\n| {{nochange}}\n| 89.7\n| 709,838\n| 55.6\n| {{increase}}8.7\n|-\n{{Party name with colour|Conservative Party (UK)}}\n| 3\n| 1\n| 1\n| {{nochange}}\n| 10.3\n| 440,613\n| 34.5\n| {{increase}}9.2\n|-\n{{Party name with colour|Liberal Democrats (UK)}}\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n| {{nochange}}\n| \u2014\n| 58,409\n| 4.6\n| {{decrease}}1.9\n|-\n{{Party name with colour|UKIP}}\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n| {{nochange}}\n| \u2014\n| 49,348\n| 3.9\n| {{decrease}}12.8\n|-\n{{Party name with colour|Green Party of England and Wales}}\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n| {{nochange}}\n| \u2014\n| 16,080\n| 1.3\n| {{decrease}}2.3\n|-\n|style=\"background:silver;\" | &nbsp;\n| align=left| Others\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n| {{nochange}}\n| \u2014\n| 2,053\n| 0.2\n| {{decrease}}0.7\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"background:#f2f2f2\" |\n|style=\"background:#f2f2f2;\" | '''29'''\n|style=\"background:#f2f2f2;\" |\n|style=\"background:#f2f2f2;\" |\n|style=\"background:#f2f2f2;\" |\n|style=\"background:#f2f2f2;\" |\n|style=\"background:#f2f2f2;\" |'''1,276,341'''\n|style=\"background:#f2f2f2;\" |\n|style=\"background:#f2f2f2;\" |\n|}\n\n<gallery perrow=\"5\" widths=\"150\" heights=\"150\">File:United Kingdom General Election 2017 Results Map (North East England).svg|North East England</gallery>\n\n===North West England===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:right; font-size:95%;\"\n|+\n! colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"2\" |Party\n! colspan=\"5\" |Seats\n! colspan=\"3\" |Votes\n|-\n! Total !! Gains !! Losses\n!Net +/-\n!% seats\n!Total votes\n!% votes\n!Change\n|-\n{{Party name with colour|Labour Party (UK)}}\n| 54\n| 4\n| 1\n| {{increase}}3\n| 72.0\n| 1,972,682\n| 55.0\n| {{increase}}10.4\n|-\n{{Party name with colour|Conservative Party (UK)}}\n| 20\n| 2\n| 4\n| {{decrease}}2\n| 26.7\n| 1,301,562\n| 36.3\n| {{increase}}5.1\n|-\n{{Party name with colour|Liberal Democrats (UK)}}\n| 1\n| 0\n| 1\n| {{decrease}}1\n| 1.3\n| 193,197\n| 5.4\n| {{decrease}}1.1\n|-\n{{Party name with colour|UKIP}}\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n| {{nochange}}\n| \u2014\n| 68,946\n| 1.9\n| {{decrease}}11.7\n|-\n{{Party name with colour|Green Party of England and Wales}}\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n| {{nochange}}\n| \u2014\n| 39,169\n| 1.1\n| {{decrease}}2.1\n|-\n|style=\"background:silver;\" | &nbsp;\n| align=left| Others\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n| {{nochange}}\n| \u2014\n| 11,283\n| 0.3\n| {{decrease}}0.4\n|-\n|style=\"background:#f2f2f2;\" colspan=\"2\" |\n|style=\"background:#f2f2f2;\" |'''75'''\n|style=\"background:#f2f2f2;\" |\n|style=\"background:#f2f2f2;\" |\n|style=\"background:#f2f2f2;\" |\n|style=\"background:#f2f2f2;\" |\n|style=\"background:#f2f2f2;\" |'''3,586,839'''\n|style=\"background:#f2f2f2;\" |\n|style=\"background:#f2f2f2;\" | \n|}\n\n<gallery perrow=\"5\" widths=\"150\" heights=\"150\">File:United Kingdom General Election 2017 Results Map (North West England).svg|North West England</gallery>\n\nIn [[Cheshire]] the 2015 result was reversed, with Labour winning seven seats and the Conservatives four. [[Crewe and Nantwich]] was a gain for Labour, with tutor and activist [[Laura Smith (politician)|Laura Smith]] defeating children and families minister [[Edward Timpson]]. In [[Tatton (UK Parliament constituency)|Tatton]], former chancellor [[George Osborne]] did not seek re-election, having become editor of the [[London Evening Standard]]. He was succeeded by [[Esther McVey]], who had been a junior DWP minister in the [[Cameron-Clegg coalition]] prior to her defeat in [[Wirral West]] in 2015. In [[Warrington South]] the care and support minister [[David Mowat]] was defeated by the borough's former mayor [[Faisal Rashid]]. City councillor and trade unionist [[Mike Amesbury]] gained [[Weaver Vale (UK Parliament constituency)|Weaver Vale]] from [[Graham Evans]].\n\n===South East England===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:right; font-size:95%;\"\n|+\n! colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"2\" |Party\n! colspan=\"5\" |Seats\n! colspan=\"3\" |Votes\n|-\n! Total !! Gains !! Losses\n!Net +/-\n!% seats\n!Total votes\n!% votes\n!Change\n|-\n{{Party name with colour|Conservative Party (UK)}}\n| 72\n| 0\n| 6\n| {{decrease}}6\n| 85.7\n| 2,529,574\n| 54.8\n| {{increase}}3.2\n|-\n{{Party name with colour|Labour Party (UK)}}\n| 8\n| 4\n| 0\n| {{increase}}4\n| 9.5\n| 1,326,279\n| 28.6\n| {{increase}}10.4\n|-\n{{Party name with colour|Liberal Democrats (UK)}}\n| 2\n| 2\n| 0\n| {{increase}}2\n| 2.4\n| 487,243\n| 10.6\n| {{increase}}1.2\n|-\n{{Party name with colour|Green Party of England and Wales}}\n| 1\n| 0\n| 0\n| {{nochange}}\n| 1.2\n| 145,171\n| 3.1\n| {{decrease}}2.1\n|-\n{{Party name with colour|UKIP}}\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n| {{nochange}}\n| \u2014\n| 103,509\n| 2.2\n| {{decrease}}12.5\n|-\n{{Party name with colour|Speaker of the British House of Commons}}\n| 1\n| 0\n| 0\n| {{nochange}}\n| 1.2\n| 11,283\n| 0.3\n| {{nochange}}\n|-\n\n|style=\"background:silver;\" | &nbsp;\n| align=left| Others\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n| {{nochange}}\n| \u2014\n| 23,914\n| 0.5\n| {{decrease}}0.2\n|-\n|style=\"background:#f2f2f2;\" colspan=\"2\" |\n|style=\"background:#f2f2f2;\" |'''84'''\n|style=\"background:#f2f2f2;\" |\n|style=\"background:#f2f2f2;\" |\n|style=\"background:#f2f2f2;\" |\n|style=\"background:#f2f2f2;\" |\n|style=\"background:#f2f2f2;\" |'''4,610,052'''\n|style=\"background:#f2f2f2;\" |\n|style=\"background:#f2f2f2;\" | \n|}\n\n<gallery perrow=\"5\" widths=\"150\" heights=\"150\">File:United Kingdom General Election 2017 Results Map (South East England).svg|South East England</gallery>\n\nOf the eight constituencies in [[Berkshire]] six were held by the Conservatives. The party leader and prime minister [[Theresa May]] was re-elected, as were justice minister [[Phillip Lee (politician)|Dr Phillip Lee]], Asia minister [[Alok Sharma]] and former trade secretary [[John Redwood|Dr John Redwood]]. Labour held [[Slough (UK Parliament constituency)|Slough]] for [[Tan Dhesi]]. Labour also gained [[Reading East]], with former civil servant [[Matt Rodda]] defeating civil society minister [[Rob Wilson]].\n\nNo seats changed allegiance in [[Buckinghamshire]]. Commons leader [[David Lidington|Dr David Lidington]], veterans minister [[Mark Lancaster|Lieutenant Colonel Mark Lancaster]] and former attorney-general [[Dominic Grieve]] were re-elected. [[John Bercow]], speaker of the House of Commons, returned in [[Buckingham (UK Parliament constituency)|Buckingham]] uncontested by the main political parties.\n\nIn [[Hampshire]] the Conservatives were successful in sixteen seats. DWP ministers [[Damian Hinds]] and [[Penny Mordaunt]], May's own PPS [[George Hollingbery]], Cabinet Office undersecretary [[Caroline Nokes]] and assistant whip [[Steve Brine]] were re-elected. Labour won two seats, with shadow energy minister [[Alan Whitehead]] holding [[Southampton Test]] and city councillor [[Stephen Morgan (U.K. politician)|Stephen Morgan]] gaining [[Portsmouth South]] from [[Flick Drummond]] (giving that constituency its first Labour MP in its ninety-nine year history).\n\nLabour gained [[Canterbury (UK Parliament constituency)|Canterbury]], with former teaching assistant [[Rosie Duffield]] defeating [[Sir Julian Brazier]]. This ended the monopoly which the Conservatives had enjoyed across [[Kent]] since 2010. The rest of the seats held, with work & pensions secretary [[Damian Green]] securing re-election alongside sport minister [[Tracey Crouch]], defence secretary [[Sir Michael Fallon]] and business secretary [[Greg Clark]].\n\nIn [[Oxfordshire]] the Conservatives held four of the six seats including [[Witney (UK Parliament constituency)|Witney]], which had elected [[David Cameron]] two years prior. Labour held [[Oxford East]], while [[Oxford West and Abingdon]] was a gain for the Liberal Democrats, with former teacher [[Layla Moran]] defeating public health undersecretary [[Nicola Blackwood]].\n\nFor the fourth general election in a row the Conservatives made a clean sweep of [[Surrey]]. Prisons undersecretary [[Sam Gyimah]], transport secretary [[Chris Grayling]], deputy chief whip [[Anne Milton]], chancellor [[Philip Hammond]], health secretary [[Jeremy Hunt]] and former lord chancellor [[Michael Gove]] all held their seats here.\n\n===South West England===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:right; font-size:95%;\"\n|+\n! colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"2\" |Party\n! colspan=\"5\" |Seats\n! colspan=\"3\" |Votes\n|-\n! Total !! Gains !! Losses\n!Net +/-\n!% seats\n!Total votes\n!% votes\n!Change\n|-\n{{Party name with colour|Conservative Party (UK)}}\n| 47\n| 0\n| 4\n| {{decrease}}4\n| 85.5\n| 1,539,618\n| 51.5\n| {{increase}}5.0\n|-\n{{Party name with colour|Labour Party (UK)}}\n| 7\n| 3\n| 0\n| {{increase}}3\n| 12.7\n| 870,561\n| 29.1\n| {{increase}}11.4\n|-\n{{Party name with colour|Liberal Democrats (UK)}}\n| 1\n| 1\n| 0\n| {{increase}}1\n| 1.8\n| 446,181\n| 14.9\n| {{decrease}}0.2\n|-\n{{Party name with colour|Green Party of England and Wales}}\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n| {{nochange}}\n| \u2014\n| 66,176\n| 2.2\n| {{decrease}}3.7\n|-\n{{Party name with colour|UKIP}}\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n| {{nochange}}\n| \u2014\n| 32,944\n| 1.1\n| {{decrease}}12.5\n|-\n|style=\"background:silver;\" | &nbsp;\n| align=left| Others\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n| {{nochange}}\n| \u2014\n| 32,649\n| 1.1\n| {{decrease}}0.1\n|-\n|style=\"background:#f2f2f2;\" colspan=\"2\" |\n|style=\"background:#f2f2f2;\" |'''55'''\n|style=\"background:#f2f2f2;\" |\n|style=\"background:#f2f2f2;\" |\n|style=\"background:#f2f2f2;\" |\n|style=\"background:#f2f2f2;\" |\n|style=\"background:#f2f2f2;\" |'''2,988,129'''\n|style=\"background:#f2f2f2;\" |\n|style=\"background:#f2f2f2;\" | \n|}\n\n<gallery perrow=\"5\" widths=\"150\" heights=\"150\">File:United Kingdom General Election 2017 Results Map (South West England).svg|South West England</gallery>\n\nThe combined representation of Labour and the Liberal Democrats doubled compared to 2015, but the Conservatives still had a landslide and also increased their vote share to an outright majority.\n\nIn [[Cornwall]] the Conservatives held all six constituencies, re-electing junior ministers [[George Eustice]] and [[Sarah Newton]].\n\nIn [[Devon]] Labour made one gain in [[Plymouth Sutton and Devonport]], trade unionist [[Luke Pollard]] defeating [[Oliver Colvile]]. They also held [[Exeter (UK Parliament constituency)|Exeter]] for the sixth consecutive time. The other ten constituencies were held by the Conservatives, including treasury minister [[Mel Stride]] and former [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office|FCO]] minister [[Sir Hugo Swire]], who defeated a challenge by independent candidate [[Claire Wright (politician)|Claire Wright]] in his [[East Devon (UK Parliament constituency)|East Devon constituency]]. The former armed forces minister [[Sir Nick Harvey]] attempted to regain the constituency of [[North Devon]] but the Conservative [[Peter Heaton-Jones]] held it by a margin of 4,332.\n\nIn [[Dorset]] all eight Conservative MPs were re-elected, including the counter-terrorism minister [[Tobias Ellwood]] and former [[Chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster|Lancaster chancellor]] [[Sir Oliver Letwin]].\n\nThe Conservatives held five seats in [[Gloucestershire]], returning former chief whip [[Mark Harper]]. Labour gained [[Stroud (UK Parliament constituency)|Stroud]], where [[Forest Green Rovers]] chairman [[David Drew (politician)|David Drew]] defeated [[Neil Carmichael (Conservative politician)|Neil Carmichael]].\n\nThe five [[Somerset]] constituencies were all held by the Conservatives. [[Tessa Munt]] attempted unsuccessfully to regain [[Wells (UK Parliament constituency)|Wells]] from [[James Heappey]].\n\nThe Conservatives also held all seven seats in [[Wiltshire]]: Climate change minister [[Claire Perry]] was re-elected, as were [[Department for Work and Pensions|DWP]] minister [[Justin Tomlinson]] and [[Solicitor-General for England and Wales|solicitor-general]] [[Robert Buckland]].\n\n===West Midlands===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:right; font-size:95%;\"\n|+\n! colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"2\" |Party\n! colspan=\"5\" |Seats\n! colspan=\"3\" |Votes\n|-\n! Total !! Gains !! Losses\n!Net +/-\n!% seats\n!Total votes\n!% votes\n!Change\n|-\n{{Party name with colour|Conservative Party (UK)}}\n| 35\n| 2\n| 1\n| {{increase}}1\n| 59.3\n| 1,355,468\n| 49.1\n| {{increase}}7.3\n|-\n{{Party name with colour|Labour Party (UK)}}\n| 24\n| 1\n| 2\n| {{decrease}}1\n| 40.7\n| 1,175,075\n| 42.6\n| {{increase}}9.7\n|-\n{{Party name with colour|Liberal Democrats (UK)}}\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n| {{nochange}}\n| \u2014\n| 122,287\n| 4.4\n| {{decrease}}1.1\n|-\n{{Party name with colour|UKIP}}\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n| {{nochange}}\n| \u2014\n| 50,106\n| 1.8\n| {{decrease}}13.9\n|-\n{{Party name with colour|Green Party of England and Wales}}\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n| {{nochange}}\n| \u2014\n| 45,208\n| 1.6\n| {{decrease}}1.7\n|-\n\n|style=\"background:silver;\" | &nbsp;\n| align=left| Others\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n| {{nochange}}\n| \u2014\n| 13,236\n| 0.5\n| {{decrease}}0.3\n|-\n|style=\"background:#f2f2f2;\" |\n|style=\"background:#f2f2f2;\" |\n|style=\"background:#f2f2f2;\" |'''59'''\n|style=\"background:#f2f2f2;\" |\n|style=\"background:#f2f2f2;\" |\n|style=\"background:#f2f2f2;\" |\n|style=\"background:#f2f2f2;\" |\n|style=\"background:#f2f2f2;\" |'''2,761,380'''\n|style=\"background:#f2f2f2;\" |\n|style=\"background:#f2f2f2;\" |\n|}\n\n<gallery perrow=\"5\" widths=\"150\" heights=\"150\">File:United Kingdom General Election 2017 Results Map (West Midlands).svg|West Midlands</gallery>\n\nThe Conservatives increased their majority and Labour fell back slightly. Both parties increased their share of the popular vote. The Liberal Democrats and Greens failed to make any improvement on the 2015 result, while UKIP saw its support collapse.\n\nIn the ceremonial county of West Midlands Labour won twenty seats and the Conservatives won eight. [[Gisela Stuart]] retired and was succeeded in [[Birmingham Edgbaston (UK Parliament constituency)|Birmingham Edgbaston]] by Sandwell councillor [[Preet Gill]], making her the first female [[Sikh]] in the House of Commons. Work & Pensions spokesman [[Jack Dromey]] (husband of [[Harriet Harman]]) was re-elected in [[Birmingham Erdington (UK Parliament constituency)|Birmingham Erdington]]. Shadow Europe minister [[Khalid Mahmood (British politician)|Khalid Mahmood]] achieved a fifth term as MP for [[Birmingham Perry Barr]]. Second Church Estates Commissioner [[Dame Caroline Spelman]] was returned im [[Meriden (UK Parliament constituency)|Meriden]]. Business minister [[Margot James]] won a third term in [[Stourbridge (UK Parliament constituency)|Stourbridge]]. Former Chief Whip Andrew Mitchell held [[Sutton Coldfield (UK Parliament constituency)|Sutton Coldfield]]. Walsall councillor Eddie Hughes defeated the long-serving Labour backbencher [[David Winnick]] on a 12-point swing. [[Tom Watson (Labour politician)|Tom Watson]], deputy Labour leader, was re-elected in [[West Bromwich East]] and [[Valerie Vaz]], shadow leader of the Commons, held [[Walsall South]].\n\nThe Conservatives made a clean sweep of [[Worcestershire]] for the third consecutive election. Their six MPs included communities secretary [[Sajid Javid]] and three junior ministers ([[Harriet Baldwin]], [[Robin Walker]] and [[Mark Garnier]]).\n\nThe Conservatives also maintained their sweep of [[Shropshire]] from 2015. Five MPs were elected, including [[Philip Dunne (Ludlow MP)|Philip Dunne]] (incumbent Minister of State for Health) and [[Owen Paterson]] (who had headed the [[Northern Ireland Office]] and [[Defra]] under the [[First Cameron ministry|coalition]]).\n\nIn [[Staffordshire]] the Conservatives won nine seats and Labour the remaining three. Junior whips [[Andrew Griffiths (politician)|Andrew Griffiths]] and [[Christopher Pincher]] secured re-election, as did their predecessor [[Michael Fabricant]] in [[Lichfield (UK Parliament constituency)|Lichfield]], while Chief Whip [[Gavin Williamson]] increased his majority by two thousand. The [[Staffordshire Moorlands (UK Parliament constituency)|Moorlands]] gave a third term to culture secretary [[Karen Bradley]]. Conservative [[Jack Brereton]] defeated [[Rob Flello]], ending sixty-seven years of Labour representation in [[Stoke-on-Trent South]].\n\nIn [[Warwickshire]] the Labour party gained [[Warwick and Leamington]] (county councillor [[Matt Western]] defeated [[Chris White (politician)|Christ White]], ending seven years of Conservative ascendancy.) The Conservatives held the five other seats, electing attorney-general [[Jeremy Wright]], DCLG minister [[Marcus Jones (politician)|Marcus Jones]] and [[Parliamentary Private Secretary|PPS]] [[Mark Pawsey]].\n\nIn [[Herefordshire]] [[Jesse Norman]] and [[Bill Wiggin]] were both returned to Parliament.\n\n===Yorkshire and the Humber===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:right; font-size:95%;\"\n|+\n! colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"2\" |Party\n! colspan=\"5\" |Seats\n! colspan=\"3\" |Votes\n|-\n! Total !! Gains !! Losses\n!Net +/-\n!% seats\n!Total votes\n!% votes\n!Change\n|-\n{{Party name with colour|Labour Party (UK)}}\n| 37\n| 4\n| 0\n| {{increase}}4\n| 59.3\n| 1,275,800\n| 49.1\n| {{increase}}10.0\n|-\n{{Party name with colour|Conservative Party (UK)}}\n| 17\n| 0\n| 2\n| {{decrease}}2\n| 40.7\n| 1,054,099\n| 40.6\n| {{increase}}8.0\n|-\n{{Party name with colour|Liberal Democrats (UK)}}\n| 0\n| 0\n| 2\n| {{decrease}}2\n| \u2014\n| 129,637\n| 5.0\n| {{decrease}}2.1\n|-\n{{Party name with colour|UKIP}}\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n| {{nochange}}\n| \u2014\n| 67,801\n| 2.6\n| {{decrease}}13.4\n|-\n{{Party name with colour|Green Party of England and Wales}}\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n| {{nochange}}\n| \u2014\n| 32,743\n| 1.3\n| {{decrease}}2.2\n|-\n|style=\"background:silver;\" | &nbsp;\n| align=left| Others\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n| {{nochange}}\n| \u2014\n| 36,507\n| 1.4\n| {{decrease}}0.2\n|- \n|style=\"background:#f2f2f2;\"  colspan=\"2\" |\n|style=\"background:#f2f2f2;\" | '''54'''\n|style=\"background:#f2f2f2;\" | \n|style=\"background:#f2f2f2;\" | \n|style=\"background:#f2f2f2;\" | \n|style=\"background:#f2f2f2;\" | \n|style=\"background:#f2f2f2;\" | '''2,596,587'''\n|style=\"background:#f2f2f2;\" | \n|style=\"background:#f2f2f2;\" |  \n|}\n\n<gallery perrow=\"5\" widths=\"150\" heights=\"150\">File:United Kingdom General Election 2017 Results Map (Yorkshire and the Humber).svg|Yorkshire and the Humber</gallery>\n\nAll seats in the region went to the two main parties: Labour increasing their dominance, the Conservatives falling back slightly, and the Liberal Democrats being swept away. UKIP had polled strongly in 2015 but this year declined to insignificance. The Green Party continued to have negligible presence.\n\nAll three [[Kingston-upon-Hull]] constituencies were held by Labour: [[Diana Johnson]] and [[Karl Turner (British politician)|Karl Turner]] were re-elected by large majorities, while former [[Home Secretary]] [[Alan Johnson]] retired and was replaced by [[Hessle]] town councillor [[Emma Hardy (politician)|Emma Hardy]].\n\nIn the [[East Riding of Yorkshire]], the four Conservative MPs ([[David Davis (British politician)|David Davis]], [[Graham Stuart (politician)|Graham Stuart]], [[Greg Knight]] and [[Andrew Percy]]) were all re-elected with substantially increased shares of the vote.\n\nLabour made a clean sweep across [[South Yorkshire]], holding the thirteen which they had already (including [[Doncaster North]] for former leader [[Ed Miliband]] and [[Doncaster Central]] for former Chief Whip [[Dame Rosie Winterton]]) as well as gaining [[Sheffield Hallam (UK Parliament constituency)|Sheffield Hallam]] from the former Deputy Prime Minister [[Nick Clegg]].\n\nIn [[West Yorkshire]] five Conservatives ([[Craig Whittaker]], [[Alec Shelbrooke]], [[Andrea Jenkyns]], [[Stuart Andrew]] and [[Philip Davies]]) were re-elected. Two others ([[Jason McCartney (politician)|Jason McCartney]] and [[Kris Hopkins]]) were defeated by Labour, as was the only Liberal Democrat [[Greg Mulholland]]. Labour held the fourteen seats it had won in 2015, returning shadow Lord Chancellor [[Richard Burgon]] and leadership contender [[Yvette Cooper]] as well as actress [[Tracy Brabin]] who had been elected [[2016 Batley and Spen by-election|the previous autumn]] following the murder of [[Jo Cox]].\n\nNo constituencies changed allegiance in [[North Yorkshire]]: Labour's [[Rachael Maskell]] was re-elected in [[York Central]] while all seven other seats were held by the Conservatives, including [[Vice-Chamberlain of the Household|vice-chamberlain]] and junior whip [[Julian Smith (politician)|Julian Smith]] and transport minister [[Andrew Jones (British politician)|Andrew Jones]].\n\nIn [[North Lincolnshire|North]] and [[North East Lincolnshire]] [[Nick Dakin]] and [[Martin Vickers]] were both re-elected. [[Melanie Onn]] also won re-election in [[Great Grimsby (UK Parliament constituency)|Great Grimsby]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000716#election2015-logo |title=Great Grimsby parliamentary constituency - Election 2017 |publisher=BBC News |date= |accessdate=2018-04-23}}</ref>\n\n== Donations ==\n\nElectoral commission data shows that in 2017 Q2, total donations for each major political party, over \u00a37,500, are as follows:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.electoralcommission.org.uk/who-we-are-and-what-we-do/financial-reporting/donations-and-loans/view-donations-and-loans/donations-accepted|title=Donations accepted|website=Electoral Commission|language=en|accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:right; font-size:95%;\"\n! colspan=\"2\" |Party\n!Donations\n|-\n{{Party name with colour|Conservative Party (UK)}}\n|\u00a325,346,680\n|-\n{{Party name with colour|Labour Party (UK)}}\n|\u00a39,745,745\n|-\n{{Party name with colour|Liberal Democrats (UK)}}\n|\u00a35,058,175\n|}\n\n==Endorsements==\n{{Main|Endorsements in the 2017 United Kingdom general election}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{2017 United Kingdom general election|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:2017 United Kingdom general election|#England]]\n[[Category:2017 in England|United Kingdom General Election Results In England, 2017]]\n[[Category:General elections in England to the Parliament of the United Kingdom|2017]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2012}}\n{{Infobox election\n| election_name   = 2017 United Kingdom general election in England<ref name=BBCRes>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/election/2017/results/ Election 2017 United Kingdom - National Results] BBC News</ref>\n| country         = England\n| type            = parliamentary\n| ongoing         = no\n| previous_election = 2015 United Kingdom general election in England\n| turnout = 69.1% ({{increase}}3.2%)\n| previous_year   = 2015\n| previous_mps    = List of MPs for constituencies in England 2015\u201317\n| next_election   = 2019 United Kingdom general election in England\n| next_year       = 2019\n| next_mps        = <!-- MPs elected in the United Kingdom general election, 58th -->\n| seats_for_election = All 533 English seats to the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]]<br/>267 seats needed for [[English Votes for English Laws|English majority]]\n| elected_mps        = List of MPs for constituencies in England 2017\u2013present\n| election_date   = {{Start date|2017