||[[Wendell Rodricks]]|| Fashion designer and choreographer \n|-\n|30||[[Ashok Row Kavi]]|| Founder of Humsafur Trust and LGBT activist\n|-\n|31||[[Aishwarya Rutuparna Pradhan]]|| First openly transgender civil servant and Odisha Financial Services officer \n|-\n|32||Nishit Saran|| Filmmaker and gay rights activist\n|-\n|33||Dr Mukul Kr Sarma|| LGBT activist, has written several pieces in the ''[[The Assam Tribune]]'' in an effort to raise awareness of LGBT people and mobilise the LGBT community in Assam\n|-\n|34||[[Vikram Seth]]|| Writer\n|-\n|35||[[Parmesh Shahani]]|| Author\n|-\n|36||[[Gopi Shankar Madurai]] || [[Genderqueer]] activist, recipient of the [[Commonwealth of Nations|Commonwealth]] Youth Worker Asia Finalist Award and founder of [[Srishti Madurai]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-tamilnadu/intersex-person-to-contest-from-madurai-north/article8539185.ece|title=Intersex person to contest from Madurai North|date=30 April 2016|publisher=|newspaper=The Hindu|last1=Reporter|first1=Staff}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/elections-2016/tamil-nadu-elections-2016/news/3rd-gender-gets-a-new-champion-in-Tamil-Nadu-poll-ring/articleshow/51935940.cms|title=3rd gender gets a new champion in Tamil Nadu poll ring - Times of India|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/Intersex-candidate-alleges-harassment/articleshow/52197962.cms|title=Intersex candidate alleges harassment - Times of India|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenewsminute.com/article/intersex-person-contesting-tn-polls-ze-wants-change-your-mind-sexual-minorities-42103|title=This intersex person is contesting TN polls, 'ze' wants to change your mind on sexual minorities|date=24 April 2016|publisher=}}</ref>\n|-\n|37||[[Parvez Sharma]]|| Writer and documentary filmmaker\n|-\n|38||[[Manvendra Singh Gohil]]|| Hereditary Prince of Rajpipla\n|-\n|39||[[Ramchandra Siras]]|| Linguist and author\n|-\n|40||[[Living Smile Vidya]] || Actor, artist, writer, and theater activist \n|-\n|41||[[Kalki Subramaniam]]|| Transgender activist, actor, artist, writer and founder of [[Sahodari Foundation]]\n|-\n|42||[[Manil Suri]]|| Indian-American mathematician and writer\n|-\n|43||[[S. Swapna]]|| First transwoman to clear [[Tamil Nadu Public Service Commission]] exam and first transgender I.A.S aspirant\n|-\n|44||[[Laxmi Narayan Tripathi]]|| Transgender activist\n|-\n|45||[[Ruth Vanita]]|| Writer and academician\n|-\n|46||[[Abhinav Vats]]|| Equal rights activist and India's first openly gay actor; featured in a music video from [[Euphoria (Indian band)|Euphoria]] in 1996 in a first ever gay character shown on Indian media\n|-\n|47||[[Rose Venkatesan]]|| First transgender TV host in India\n|-\n|48||[[Riyad Vinci Wadia]]|| Filmmaker\n|}\n\n== Summary table ==\n{{LGBT rights summary\n| legality = [[File:Yes check.svg|15px|Yes]] (Since 2018)<br/> \n| equal_aoc = [[File:Yes check.svg|15px|Yes]] (Since 2018)<ref name=\"bbc\"/>\n| antidiscrimination = \n| antidiscrimination_employment = [[File: Yes check.svg|15px|Yes]]/[[File:X mark.svg|15px|No]] (Only extends to discrimination from the state or government bodies)\n| antidiscrimination_goods = [[File:Yes check.svg|15px|Yes]]\n| antidiscrimination_genderid = [[File:Yes check.svg|15px|Yes]]\n| antidiscrimination_other = [[File:Yes check.svg|15px|Yes]]/[[File:X mark.svg|15px|No]] (Only extends to discrimination from the state or government bodies)\n| hate crimes law including sexual orientation and gender identity = \n| hate speech law including sexual orientation and gender identity = \n| marriage = [[File:X mark.svg|15px|No]] (Proposed) \n| recognition = [[File:X mark.svg|15px|No]] (Proposed)\n| step_adoption = [[File:X mark.svg|15px|No]] (Proposed)\n| single_adoption = [[File:Yes check.svg|15px|Yes]]\n| joint_adoption = [[File:X mark.svg|15px|No]] (Proposed)\n| military_service = [[File:X mark.svg|15px|No]] (Pending)<ref name=\"military\">{{cite news |last1=Dutta |first1=Amrita |title=Indian Army is worried now that men can legally have sex with other men |url=https://theprint.in/security/indian-army-is-worried-now-that-men-can-legally-have-sex-with-other-men/113644|work=The Print |date=7 September 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"military1\">{{cite news |title=Parliament winter session: Bills seek ban on non-veg food at official events, rights to LGBT to serve in armed forces|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/nation/2018/dec/28/parliament-winter-session-bills-seek-ban-on-non-veg-food-at-official-events-rights-to-lgbt-to-serv-1917748.amp|work=The New Indian Express |date=28 December 2018}}</ref>\n| gender_change = [[File:Yes check.svg|15px|Yes]] (Since 2014; sex reassignment surgery required since 2019)<ref>{{cite news |title=Transgender Person Act passed in Parliament|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/despite-massive-protests-trans-bill-gets-president-s-assent-becomes-law-113643}}</ref>\n| conversion_therapy = [[File:X mark.svg|15px|No]]\n| intersex_surgeries = [[File:Yes check.svg|15px|Yes]]/[[File:X mark.svg|15px|No]] (Banned in Tamil Nadu)<ref name=\"Live Law.in\"/><ref name=\"The News Minute\"/><ref name=\"The Times of India\"/><ref name=\"Kyle Knight - Human Rights Watch\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2019/08/29/indian-state-bans-unnecessary-surgery-intersex-children|title=Indian State Bans Unnecessary Surgery on Intersex Children - Human Rights Watch|accessdate=2019-08-30}}</ref><ref name=\"Human Rights Watch\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2019/04/29/indian-court-decides-favor-informed-consent-rights-intersex-people|title=Indian Court Decides In Favor of Informed Consent Rights for Intersex People - Human Rights Watch|accessdate=2019-07-15}}</ref>\n| reassignment surgery = [[File:Yes check.svg|15px|Yes]] (Since 2014)\n| third_gender = [[File:Yes check.svg|15px|Yes]] (Since 2014)\n| Automatic parenthood = [[File:X mark.svg|15px|No]] (Proposed) \n| homosexuality_declassified = [[File:Yes check.svg|15px|Yes]]\n| ivf_access = [[File:Yes check.svg|15px|Yes]]<ref>{{cite news |last=Radha |first=Sharma |title=IVF bundle of 'Anand' for US lesbian couple |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/IVF-bundle-of-Anand-for-US-lesbian-couple/articleshow/45085039.cms |work=The Times of India |date=9 November 2014}}</ref>\n| anti-bullying = [[File:X mark.svg|15px|No]] \n| surrogacy = [[File:X mark.svg|15px|No]] (Explicit ban pending regardless of sexual orientation)<ref>{{cite news |title=Surrogacy Regulation Bill Passed In Lok Sabha: 10 Points|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/surrogacy-regulation-bill-passed-in-lok-sabha-10-points-1965215|work=NDTV |date=19 December 2018}}</ref> \n| blood_donation = [[File:X mark.svg|15px|No]]<ref>{{cite news |last1=Power |first1=Shannon |title=No LGBTI person can donate blood in India\n|url=https://www.gaystarnews.com/article/no-lgbti-person-can-donate-blood-india|work=GayStarNews |date=20 July 2017}}</ref>\n| other_title1 = \n| other1 = \n| other_title2 =\n| other2 = \n}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Human rights in India]]\n* [[LGBT rights in Asia]]\n* [[LGBT culture in India]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{LGBT in India}}\n{{Asia topic|LGBT rights in}}\n{{India topics}}\n{{Social issues in India}}\n\n[[Category:LGBT rights in India]]\n[[Category:LGBT rights in Asia]]\n[[Category:Human rights in India]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Rights of LGBT people in India}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=July 2015}} \n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2015}}\n{{Infobox LGBT rights\n| location_header = India\n| image = India (orthographic projection).svg\n| caption = Area controlled by India shown in dark green;<br/>claimed but uncontrolled regions shown in light green.\n| legal_status = Legal since 2018<ref name=\"toi-judgement2018\">{{cite news |last1=Mahapatra |first1=Dhananjay |last2=Choudhary |first2=Amit Anand |title=SC decriminalises Section 377, calls 2013 ruling 'arbitrary and retrograde'|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/sc-decriminalises-section-377-calls-2013-ruling-arbitrary-and-retrograde/articleshow/65712063.cms |work=The Times of India |date=7 September 2018}}</ref>\n| gender_identity_expression =  Transgender people have a constitutional right to change their legal gender and a [[third gender]] is recognised\n| recognition_of_relationships = No recognition of same-sex relationships<br/>Transgender women may marry under the ''[[Hindu Marriage Act, 1955]]''\n| adoption     = Adoption by single LGBT people recognized, but not by same-sex couples\n| military = No, bill pending to allow LGBT people to serve openly\n| discrimination_protections = Discrimination based on sexual orientation and gender identity from the state or government bodies is prohibited\n}}\n{{LGBT rights}}\n'''Lesbian, gay, bisexual and transgender (LGBT)''' people in [[India]] may face legal and social difficulties not experienced by non-[[LGBT]] persons. The country has repealed its colonial-era laws that directly discriminated against gay sex and transgender identification, but many legal protections have not been provided for including [[Anti-discrimination law|anti-discrimination laws]] and [[same-sex marriage]].<ref name=\"Times of India\" />\n\nSince 2014, [[transgender]] people in India have been allowed to change their gender without [[sex reassignment surgery]], and have a constitutional right to register themselves under a third gender. Additionally, some states protect ''[[Hijra (Indian subcontinent)|hijras]]'', a traditional [[third gender]] population in [[South Asia]], through housing programmes, and offer welfare benefits, pension schemes, free operations in government hospitals, as well as other programmes designed to assist them. There are approximately 4.8 million transgender people in India.<ref name=\"bill\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2010/07/18/india-prosecute-rampant-honor-killings|title=India: Prosecute Rampant 'Honor' Killings|date=18 July 2010|work=Human Rights Watch|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.livemint.com/Sundayapp/sAYrieZdZKEybKzhP8FDbP/Being-LGBT-in-India-Some-home-truths.html|title=Being LGBT in India: Some home truths|last1=Patel|first1=Rashmi|date=27 August 2016|work=[[Mint (newspaper)|Livemint.com]]}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, the [[Supreme Court of India]] decriminalised homosexuality by declaring [[Section 377 of the Indian Penal Code]] unconstitutional in respect of consensual homosexual sex between adults.<ref name=\"toi-judgement2018\" /> Homosexuality was never illegal or a criminal offence in ancient Indian and traditional codes but was criminalised by the British during their rule in India.\n\nDespite recent political movements in favour of LGBT rights, there remains a significant amount of homophobia present among the Indian populace, with around half of Indians objecting to same-sex relationships according to a 2019 opinion poll. Acceptance of the LGBT community was found to be highest among Hindu respondents in the same poll.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=2019|title=Politics and Society Between Elections|url=http://azimpremjiuniversity.edu.in/SitePages/pdf/politics-and-society-between-elections-2019-report.pdf|journal=Regional Political Democracy|volume=2 - Social Identity|pages=88\u201392|via=}}</ref> In the 2010s, LGBT people in India increasingly gained tolerance and acceptance, especially in large cities.<ref name=\"delhi\">{{cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/amp/International/wireStory/hundreds-join-pride-march-india-gay-sex-illegal-51095191|title=Hundreds of gay rights activists join pride march in Delhi|publisher=}}</ref> Nonetheless, most LGBT people in India remain closeted, fearing discrimination from their families, who might see homosexuality as shameful.<ref name=\"delhi\" />\n\n==Law regarding same-sex sexual activity==\n\n===History===\n{{Main|LGBT history in India}}\n{{See also|Homosexuality in India}}\n[[File:Homosexuality in Khajuraho sculpture.jpg|thumb|right|Erotic sculptures of two men (centre) at the Khajuraho temples.]]\nThe Hindu [[Khajuraho Group of Monuments|Khajuraho temples]], famous for their erotic sculptures, contain several depictions of homosexual activity. Historians have long argued that pre-colonial Indian society did not criminalise same-sex relationships, nor did it view such relations as immoral or sinful. [[Hinduism]] has [[Hinduism and LGBT topics|traditionally portrayed homosexuality]] as natural and joyful, though some texts do contain injunctions against homosexuality namely among priests (who are also nominally required to refrain from sex altogether).\n\nHinduism also acknowledges a third gender and has a strong tradition of portraying them positively; there are multiple characters in the [[Mahabharata]] who change genders, such as [[Shikhandi]], who is born female but identifies as male and eventually marries a woman. [[Bahuchara Mata]] is the goddess of fertility, worshipped by ''hijras'' as their patroness.\n\nThe [[N\u0101radasm\u1e5bti]] and the [[Sushruta Samhita]], two important [[Hindu texts|scriptures from ancient India]] relating to [[dharma]] and medicine, respectively, declare homosexuality to be unchangeable and forbid homosexuals from marrying a partner of the opposite sex. The N\u0101radasm\u1e5bti lists fourteen types of ''panda'' (men who are impotent with women); among these are the ''mukhebhaga'' (men who have oral sex with other men), the ''sevyaka'' (men who are sexually enjoyed by other men) and the ''irshyaka'' (the voyeur who watches other men engaging in sex). The [[Kama Sutra]], a [[Sanskrit]] text on human sexual behaviour, uses the term ''tritiya-prakriti'' to define men with homosexual desires and describes their practices in great detail. Likewise, the Kama Sutra describes lesbians (''svairini'', who engage in aggressive lovemaking with other women), bisexuals (referred to as ''kami'' or ''paksha''), transgender and intersex people. The Sushruta Samhita and the [[Charaka Samhita]] delve further into the issue of homosexuality, stating that homosexuals are conceived when the father's semen is scanty and transgender people are conceived when the father and mother reverse roles during intercourse (''purushayita'', \"woman on top\").<ref>[https://www.galva108.org/single-post/2014/05/15/Homosexuality-Hinduism-the-Third-Gender-A-Summary Homosexuality, Hinduism & the Third Gender (A Summary)]</ref><ref>[https://www.newstatesman.com/blogs/the-faith-column/2009/04/gay-homosexuality-vaishnavism Vaishnavism and homosexuality]</ref>\n\nDuring the [[Mughal Empire]], a number of the preexisting [[Delhi Sultanate]] laws were combined into the [[Fatawa-e-Alamgiri]], mandating a common set of punishments for [[zina]] (unlawful intercourse).<ref>{{cite book|last1=Kugle|first1=Scott A|title=Sufis and Saints' Bodies: Mysticism, Corporeality, and Sacred Power in Islam|date=1 Sep 2011|publisher=Univ of North Carolina Press|location=Chapter 4 - Note 62-63|isbn=9780807872772|page=309|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HJ1vpC_SeLcC&pg=PA309&lpg=PA309|accessdate=20 September 2017}}</ref> These could include 50 lashes for a slave, 100 for a free infidel, or death by stoning for a Muslim.<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/digestmoohummud00bailgoog#page/n57/mode/2up A digest of the Moohummudan law] pp. 1-3 with footnotes, Neil Baillie, Smith Elder, London</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://history.stackexchange.com/questions/42157/how-did-the-mughals-view-homosexuality|title=How did the Mughals view homosexuality?|website=History Stack Exchange}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://scroll.in/article/810007/from-bulleh-shah-and-shah-hussain-to-amir-khusro-same-sex-references-abound-in-islamic-sufi-poetry|title=From Bulleh Shah and Shah Hussain to Amir Khusro, same-sex references abound in Islamic poetry|work=Scroll.in|date=17 June 2016|accessdate=7 September 2018|last=Khalid|first=Haroon|language=English}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.diarna.org/site/detail/public/1931/|title=Sarmad Kashani Tomb in Jami Masjid, New Delhi, India - Archive - Diarna.org|website=archive.diarna.org}}</ref><ref>{{citation|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=b7-bAwAAQBAJ&pg=PT32|title=Maulana Abul Kalam Azad and Sarman|author=V. N. Datta|quote=Walderman Hansen doubts whether sensual passions played any part in their love [sic]; puri doubts about their homosexual relationship|isbn=9788129126627|date=2012-11-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://jewishstudies.washington.edu/global-judaism/sarmad-kashani-sufi-jewish/|title=Of Genizahs, Sufi Jewish Saints, and Forgotten Corners of History - UW Stroum Center for Jewish Studies|date=1 March 2016|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n=== Colonialism ===\nModern societal homophobia was introduced to India by the [[European colonialism|European colonisers]] and the subsequent enactment of [[Section 377]] by the British, which stood for more than 70 years after [[Indian independence movement|Indian independence]].<ref name=\"aljazeera\">{{cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2018/09/india-decriminalises-gay-sex-landmark-verdict-180906051219637.html|title=India decriminalises gay sex in landmark verdict|date=6 September 2018|website=Al Jazeera}}</ref> The [[Goa Inquisition]] once prosecuted the capital crime of [[sodomy]] in [[Portuguese India]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.deccanherald.com/content/66330/xavier-aware-brutality-inquisition.html|title=Xavier was aware of the brutality of the Inquisition|date=27 April 2010|work=Deccan Herald|accessdate=18 September 2017|publisher=Deccan Herald}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://indiafacts.org/the-portuguese-inquisition-in-goa-a-brief-history/|title=The Portuguese Inquisition in Goa: A brief history|last1=Sharma|first1=Jai|date=2015-04-09|website=Indiafacts.org|accessdate=18 September 2017}}</ref> but not lesbian activity,<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LxqzbYdSeuYC&pg=PA45&lpg=PA45|title=Ambiguous Gender in Early Modern Spain and Portugal: Inquisitors, Doctors and the Transgression of Gender Norms|last1=Soyer|first1=Francois|date=2012|isbn=9789004225299|page=45|accessdate=18 September 2017}}</ref> whereas the [[British Raj]] criminalised [[anal sex]] and [[oral sex]] (for both heterosexuals and homosexuals) under [[Section 377 of the Indian Penal Code]], which entered into force in 1861, and made it an offence for a person to voluntarily have \"carnal intercourse against the order of nature.\" Scholars have also argued that the original intention of Section 377 was to act as a means by which the British Raj could further police and control the body of the colonial subject. In colonial Victorian era morality, these subjects were seen as erotically perverse and in need of the imposition.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite journal|last=Nagar|first=Ila|last2=DasGupta|first2=Debanuj|date=December 2015|title=Public koti and private love: Section 377, religion, perversity and lived desire|journal=Contemporary South Asia|volume=23|issue=4|pages=426|doi=10.1080/09584935.2015.1056092}}</ref><ref name=\":42\">{{Cite journal|last=Sathyanarayana Rao|first=T. S.|last2=Jacob|first2=K S|date=2014|title=The reversal on Gay Rights in India|journal=Indian Journal of Psychiatry|volume=56|issue=1|pages=1\u20132|doi=10.4103/0019-5545.124706|issn=0019-5545|pmc=3927237|pmid=24574551}}</ref>\n\nIn 1884, a court in north India, ruling on the prosecution of a ''hijra'', commented that a physical examination of the accused revealed she \"had the marks of a habitual [[catamite]]\" and commended the police's desire to \"check these disgusting practices\".<ref name=\"guardian\">{{cite news |last1=Suresh |first1=Mayur |title=This is the start of a new era for India's LGBT communities {{!}} Mayur Suresh |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2018/sep/06/india-lgbt-homophobia-section-377 |work=The Guardian |date=6 September 2018 |language=en}}</ref> In 1871, the British labeled the ''hijra'' population as a \"criminal tribe\".<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite journal|last=Nussbaum|first=Martha|date=2016|title=Disgust or Equality? Sexual Orientation and Indian Law|url=http://docs.manupatra.in/newsline/articles/Upload/7A93092D-3017-413A-AB4E-4D7A1752A854.%20Nussbaum.pdf|journal=Journal of Indian Law and Society|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref>\n<gallery widths=\"220\" heights=\"220\">\nFile:Ardhanari Gangaikonda.jpg|[[Ardhanarishvara]] in [[Gangaikonda Cholapuram]]\nFile:Two women embracing and using carrots as dildoes. Gouache Wellcome L0033073.jpg|Two women using carrots as dildos, 20th century [[gouache]] painting.\n</gallery>\n\n===Post independence===\n{{see also|Navtej Singh Johar v. Union of India}}\nThe Delhi High Court decision in ''[[Naz Foundation v. Govt. of NCT of Delhi]]'' of 2009 found Section 377 and other legal prohibitions against private, adult, consensual, and non-commercial same-sex conduct to be in direct violation of fundamental rights provided by the Indian Constitution. Section 377 stated that: \"Whoever voluntarily has carnal intercourse against the order of nature with any man, woman or animal, shall be punished with [imprisonment for life], or with imprisonment of either description for a term which may extend to ten years, and shall also be liable to fine,\" with the added explanation that: \"Penetration is sufficient to constitute the carnal intercourse necessary to the offence described in this section.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=India: The Indian Penal Code |url=http://www.wipo.int/wipolex/en/text.jsp?file_id=201592 |website=www.wipo.int |publisher=World Intellectual Property Organization |language=en}}</ref>\n\nAccording to a previous ruling by the Indian Supreme Court, decisions of a high court on the constitutionality of a law apply throughout India, and not just to the state over which the high court in question has jurisdiction.<ref name=\"Kusum Ingots v 2004\">''Kusum Ingots v. Union of India'', (2004) 6 SCC 254: \"An order passed on a writ petition questioning the constitutionality of a Parliamentary Act, whether interim or final, keeping in view the provisions contained in Clause (2) of Article 226 of the Constitution of India, will have effect throughout the territory of India subject of course to the applicability of the Act.\"</ref>\n\nThere have been incidents of harassment of LGBT groups by authorities under the law.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Crackdown-on-gay-party-in-Saharanpur-13-held/articleshow/7175530.cms|title=Crackdown on gay party in Saharanpur, 13 held|first=|date=28 December 2010|work=The Times of India|via=|author=Pervez Iqbal Siddiqui|accessdate=20 January 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 February 2012, the [[Ministry of Home Affairs (India)|Ministry of Home Affairs]] expressed its opposition to the decriminalisation of homosexual activity, stating that in India, homosexuality is seen as being immoral.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2012-02-23/news/31091001_1_decriminalisation-judgement-hc|title=Centre opposes decriminalisation of homosexuality in SC|last=Mahapatra|first=Dhananjay|date=23 February 2012|work=Economic Times|publisher=[[Times Internet]]|accessdate=9 September 2014}}</ref> The Central Government reversed its stance on 28 February 2012, asserting that there was no legal error in decriminalising homosexual activity. The shift in stance resulted in two judges of the Supreme Court reprimanding the Central Government for frequently changing its approach to the issue.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://archive.indianexpress.com/news/supreme-court-pulls-up-centre-for-flipflop-on-homosexuality/917743|title=Supreme Court pulls up Centre for flip-flop on homosexuality|date=28 February 2012|work=[[The Indian Express]]|accessdate=9 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 December 2013, the Supreme Court set aside the 2009 Delhi High Court order decriminalising consensual homosexual activity within its jurisdiction.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://barandbench.com/comment/44159#.UqifDPRDtrA|title=Supreme Court sets aside Delhi High Court judgment in Naz Foundation; Declares S.377 to be constitutional|access-date=11 December 2013|archive-url=https://archive.today/20131211173739/http://barandbench.com/comment/44159%23.UqifDPRDtrA|archive-date=11 December 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=India's top court upholds law criminalising gay sex|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/india/10509952/Indias-top-court-upholds-law-criminalising-gay-sex.html|publisher=The Telegraph|accessdate=11 December 2013|location=London|first=Dean|last=Nelson|date=11 December 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Supreme Court makes gay sex punishable offence, again; Twitter war breaks out between those for and against the verdict|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-blow-to-gay-rights-activists-as-supreme-court-upholds-article-377-makes-gay-sex-punishable-offence-1933110|publisher=DNA India|accessdate=11 December 2013|date=2013-12-11}}</ref><ref name=\"court1\">{{cite news |last=Mahapatra |first=Dhananjay |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Supreme-Court-makes-homosexuality-a-crime-again/articleshow/27230690.cms |work=The Times Of India |title=Supreme Court makes homosexuality a crime again |date=12 December 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/190889099/Sc-Verdict-on-Article-377|title=Sc Verdict on Article 377 - Homosexuality - Virtue|website=Scribd}}</ref>\n\n[[Human Rights Watch]] expressed concerns that the Supreme Court ruling would render same-sex couples and individuals that had become open about their sexuality following the High Court's ruling vulnerable to police harassment and blackmail,<ref name=\":42\"/><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ians/apex-court-ruling-disappointing-rights-body-113121100338_1.html|title=Apex court ruling disappointing: rights body|last=IANS|date=2013-12-11|work=Business Standard India|access-date=2017-09-14}}</ref> stating that \"the Supreme Court's ruling is a disappointing setback to human dignity, and the basic rights to privacy and non-discrimination\"<ref>{{cite news|author=Harmit Shah Singh|url=http://www.cnn.com/2013/12/11/world/asia/india-same-sex-relationship/|title=India's Supreme Court declares homosexual sex illegal | work=CNN|date=11 December 2013}}</ref> The [[Naz Foundation (India) Trust|Naz Foundation]] stated that it would file a [[petition for review]] of the court's decision.<ref>{{cite news|title=Naz Foundation to file review petition against SC order on section 377|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-naz-foundation-to-file-review-petition-against-sc-order-on-section-377-1933374}}</ref> Activist group Kavi's Humsafar Trust have reported that two-fifths of homosexuals in the country had faced blackmail after the 2013 ruling.<ref name=\"aljazeera\"/>\n\nOn 28 January 2014, the [[Supreme Court of India]] dismissed the review petition filed by the [[Central government of India|Central Government]], the [[Naz Foundation (India) Trust|Naz Foundation]] and several others against its 11 December verdict on Section 377.<ref>{{cite web|title=Supreme Court refuses overruling its Verdict on Section 377 and Homosexuality|url=http://news.biharprabha.com/2014/01/supreme-court-refuses-overruling-its-verdict-on-article-377-and-homosexuality/|work=IANS|publisher=Biharprabha News|accessdate=28 January 2014}}</ref> The bench explained the ruling by claiming that: \"While reading down Section 377, the High Court overlooked that a minuscule fraction of the country\u2019s population constitutes lesbians, gays, bisexuals or transgender people, and in the more than 150 years past, less than 200 persons have been prosecuted for committing offence under Section 377, and this cannot be made a sound basis for declaring that Section ultra vires Articles 14, 15 and 21.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/supreme-court-sets-aside-delhi-hc-verdict-decriminalising-gay-sex/article5446939.ece?homepage=true|title=Supreme Court sets aside Delhi HC verdict decriminalising gay sex|author=J Venkatesan|accessdate=2013-12-12|location=Chennai, India|work=The Hindu|date=11 December 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 December 2015, [[Shashi Tharoor]], a member of the [[Indian National Congress]] party, introduced a bill for the repeal of [[Section 377]], but it was rejected in the House by a vote of 71-24.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com/world/regions/south-central-asia/116433-india-blocks-mp-vote-decriminalize-gay-sex|title=India parliament blocks MP's bill to decriminalize gay sex|work=Rappler}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 February 2016, the Supreme Court decided to review the criminalisation of homosexual activity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/indias-top-court-examine-gay-rights-36659702|title=ABC News|author=ABC News}}</ref> In August 2017, the Supreme Court unanimously ruled that the right to individual privacy is an intrinsic and fundamental right under the Indian Constitution. The Court also ruled that a person's sexual orientation is a privacy issue, giving hopes to LGBT activists that the Court would soon strike down Section 377.<ref>[https://www.hrw.org/news/2017/08/24/indias-supreme-court-upholds-right-privacy India\u2019s Supreme Court Upholds Right to Privacy] ''Human Rights Watch''</ref>\n\nIn January 2018, the Supreme Court agreed to refer the question of Section 377's validity to a large bench,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/asia/india-homosexuality-legalise-law-gay-lgbt-couples-supreme-court-ruling-a8148896.html |title=India's supreme court could be about to decriminalise gay sex in major victory for LGBT rights |publisher=independent.co.uk |date=8 January 2018}}</ref> and heard several petitions on 1 May 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.livelaw.in/six-new-petitioners-in-sc-seeking-scrapping-of-section-377ipc-hearing-on-tuesday/ |title=Six New Petitioners In SC Seeking Scrapping Of Section 377IPC: Hearing On Tuesday |publisher=Live Law |date=27 April 2018}}</ref> In response to the court's request for its position on the petitions,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thequint.com/news/india/20-iitians-from-the-lgbt-community-move-sc-challenging-section-377|title=SC Seeks Govt's Reply on IITians' Petition Scrapping Homosexuality|publisher=|date=14 May 2018}}</ref> the Government announced that it would not oppose the petitions, and would leave the case \"to the wisdom of the court\".<ref name=\"independent\">{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/asia/india-gay-rights-lgbt-homosexuality-supreme-court-decision-section-377-a8447361.html |title=India on brink of biggest gay rights victory as Supreme Court prepares to rule on gay sex ban |publisher=Independent.co.uk |date=14 July 2018}}</ref> A hearing began on 10 July 2018,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dhruv |first1=Rushabh |title=Just In: Supreme Court to start hearing section 377 case from July 10 |url=https://www.in.com/news/other-news/just-in-supreme-court-to-start-hearing-section-377-case-from-july-10-153545.htm |work=In.com |date=5 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=SC to hear petition against Section 377 next week |url=https://www.aninews.in/news/national/general-news/sc-to-hear-petition-against-section-377-next-week201807060353070001/ |work=www.aninews.in |agency=Asian News International |date=6 July 2018 |language=en}}</ref> with a verdict expected before October 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://paperdabba.com/2018/07/17/section-377-sc-reserves-order-verdict-on-constitutional-validity-likely-before-october/|title=Section 377: SC reserves order, verdict on constitutional validity likely before October|work=Paperdabba|date=17 July 2018|access-date=17 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180717183432/https://paperdabba.com/2018/07/17/section-377-sc-reserves-order-verdict-on-constitutional-validity-likely-before-october/|archive-date=17 July 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> Activists view the case as the most significant and \"greatest breakthrough for gay rights since the country's independence\", and it could have far-reaching implications for other [[Commonwealth of Nations|Commonwealth]] countries that still outlaw homosexuality.<ref name=\"independent\"/>\n\n[[File:Bhopal pride Queermitra 11.jpg|thumb|Participants of a 2018 [[Bhopal]] parade celebrating the ruling of the Supreme Court]]\nOn 6 September 2018, the Supreme Court issued its verdict.<ref name=\"toi-judgement2018\"/> The Court unanimously ruled that Section 377 is unconstitutional as it infringed on the fundamental rights of autonomy, intimacy, and identity, thus legalising homosexuality in India.<ref>{{cite web |title=NAVTEJ SINGH JOHAR v. UNION OF INDIA MINISTRY OF LAW AND JUSTICE SECRETARY. [2018] INSC 746 (6 September 2018) |url=http://www.liiofindia.org/in/cases/cen/INSC/2018/746.html |publisher=Legal Information Institute of India |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Section 377 verdict: Here are the highlights |url=https://indianexpress.com/article/india/section-377-supreme-court-verdict-gay-lgbtq-5343225/ |work=The Indian Express |date=6 September 2018}}</ref> The Court explicitly overturned its 2013 judgement.\n{{quote|Criminalising carnal intercourse is irrational, arbitrary and manifestly unconstitutional.|author=Chief Justice [[Dipak Misra]]<ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-45429664|title=India court legalises gay sex in landmark ruling|website=BBC News|date=6 September 2018}}</ref>}}\n{{quote|History owes an apology to these people and their families. Homosexuality is part of human sexuality. They have the right of dignity and free of discrimination. Consensual sexual acts of adults are allowed for [the] LGBT community.|author=Justice [[Indu Malhotra]]}}\n{{quote|It is difficult to right a wrong by history. But we can set the course for the future. This case involves much more than decriminalizing homosexuality. It is about people wanting to live with dignity.|author=Justice [[Dhananjaya Y. Chandrachud]]}}\n\nFurthermore, it ruled that any discrimination on the basis of sexual orientation is a violation of the Indian Constitution:<ref name=\"thehindu\">{{cite web |last1=Misra |first1=Dipak |title=Navtej Singh Johar and Ors. vs Union Of India Ministry Of Law and Justice |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/article24880700.ece/binary/Sec377judgment.pdf |page=160 |website=The Hindu |accessdate=6 September 2018}}</ref>\n{{quote|Sexual orientation is one of the many biological phenomena which is natural and inherent in an individual and is controlled by neurological and biological factors. The science of sexuality has theorized that an individual exerts little or no control over who he/she gets attracted to. Any discrimination on the basis of one\u2018s sexual orientation would entail a violation of the fundamental right of freedom of expression.}}\n\nThe Supreme Court also directed the Government to take all measures to properly broadcast the fact that homosexuality is not a criminal offence, to create public awareness and eliminate the stigma members of the LGBT community face, and to give the police force periodic training to sensitise them about the issue.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://edition-m.cnn.com/2018/09/06/asia/india-gay-sex-ruling-intl/index.html?r=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.google.ch%2F&rm=1|title=India's top court decriminalizes gay sex in landmark ruling|website=CNN|date=6 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://m.timesofindia.com/india/sc-verdict-on-section-377-all-you-need-to-know/articleshow/65695884.cms|title=Supreme Court decriminalises Section 377: All you need to know|website=The Times of India|date=6 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/sep/06/indian-supreme-court-decriminalises-homosexuality|title=Indian supreme court decriminalises homosexuality|website=The Guardian|date=6 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe judgement also included an inbuilt safeguard to ensure that it cannot be revoked again under the \"Doctrine of Progressive Realisation of Rights\".<ref name=\"The Hindu\">{{cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/377-verdict-has-inbuilt-firewall/article24914104.ece|title= 377 verdict has inbuilt firewall|newspaper=The Hindu|date=10 September 2018|last1= Rajagopal|first1= Krishnadas}}</ref>\n\nLegal experts have urged the Government to pass legislation reflecting the decision, and frame laws to allow same-sex marriage, adoption by same-sex couples and inheritance rights.<ref name=\"livemint\">{{cite news |last1=Das |first1=Shaswati |title=Historic verdict holds hope for same-sex marriages, adoption |url=https://www.livemint.com/Politics/fEiZSRM7ng7Ja4ssTyfl8J/Historic-verdict-holds-hope-for-samesex-marriages-adoption.html |work=[[Mint (newspaper)|Livemint.com]] |date=7 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nNon-consensual sex (rape) and bestiality remain criminal offences. Initially, it was unknown whether the Supreme Court ruling extended to the former state of [[Jammu and Kashmir (state)|Jammu and Kashmir]], which was governed by its own criminal law, the [[Ranbir Penal Code]] (RPC). Legal opinion was divided on whether the Supreme Court judgment applied to the state or not. Per a 1995 judgment of the state [[Jammu and Kashmir High Court|High Court]], when an IPC (Indian Penal Code) provision is struck down on grounds of violating the Constitution, its corresponding provision in the Ranbir Penal Code too would be struck down.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/high-courts-1995-ruling-offers-hope-to-jammu-and-kashmirs-lgbt-community/articleshow/65727555.cms|title=High Court's 1995 ruling offers hope to Jammu and Kashmir's LGBT community|newspaper=The Economic Times|date=10 September 2018|last1=Singh|first1=Dalip|last2=Rautray|first2=Samanwaya}}</ref> On 31 October 2019, the state was split into the union territories of [[Jammu and Kashmir (union territory)|Jammu and Kashmir]] and [[Ladakh]], which apply the IPC. The RPC was abolished.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.firstpost.com/india/jammu-and-kashmir-reorganised-into-uts-of-jk-ladakh-security-centres-ambit-state-constitution-ranbir-penal-code-abolished-7579091.html|title=J&K reorganised into UTs of Jammu and Kashmir, Ladakh: Security under Centre's ambit; state constitution, Ranbir Penal Code abolished|work=First Post|date=31 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Recognition of same-sex relationships==\n{{Main|Recognition of same-sex unions in India}}\n[[File:Bangalore Gay Pride Parade (15).jpg|right|thumb|[[Gay]] [[Pride parade]] in [[Bangalore]], [[Karnataka]] (2013)]]\nSame-sex marriages are not legally recognised in India nor are same-sex couples offered limited rights such as a [[civil union]] or a domestic partnership. In 2011, a [[Haryana]] court granted legal recognition to a same-sex marriage, involving two women.<ref name=\"Times of India\">{{Cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/gurgaon/In-a-first-Gurgaon-court-recognizes-lesbian-marriage/articleshow/9401421.cms|title=In a first, Gurgaon court recognizes lesbian marriage - Times of India|newspaper=The Times of India|access-date=2017-01-31}}</ref> After marrying, the couple began to receive threats from friends and relatives in their village. The couple eventually won family approval.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/gurgaon/Lesbian-couples-parents-accept-their-relationship/articleshow/9630216.cms|title=Lesbian couple's parents accept their relationship - The Times of India|last=|first=|date=17 August 2011|work=The Times Of India|access-date=|via=}}</ref>\n<blockquote>Their lawyer said the court had served notice on 14 of Veena's relatives and villagers who had threatened them with \"dire consequences\". Haryana has been the centre of widespread protests by villagers who believe their village councils or [[khap]]s should be allowed to impose their own punishments on those who disobey their rulings or break local traditions \u2013 mainly honour killings of those who marry within their own [[gotra]] or sub-caste, regarded in the state as akin to incest. Deputy Commissioner of Police Dr. Abhe Singh told ''The Daily Telegraph'': \"The couple has been shifted to a safe house and we have provided adequate security to them on the court orders. The security is provided on the basis of threat perception and in this case the couple feared that their families might be against the relationship.\"<ref name=\"Telegraph\">{{cite news |last1=Nelson |first1=Dean |title=India's first married lesbian couple given 24-hour protection |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/india/8662082/Indias-first-married-lesbian-couple-given-24-hour-protection.html |work=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]] |date=26 July 2011}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nIn October 2017, a group of citizens proposed a draft of a new [[Uniform Civil Code]] that would legalise same-sex marriage to the [[Law Commission of India]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Chishti |first1=Seema |title=Drafting change: What the new 'progressive' intervention in Uniform Civil Code debate entails |url=https://indianexpress.com/article/explained/drafting-change-what-the-new-progressive-intervention-in-uniform-civil-code-debate-entails/ |work=The Indian Express |date=18 October 2017}}</ref>\n<blockquote>It defines marriage as \"the legal union as prescribed under this Act of a man with a woman, a man with another man, a woman with another woman a transgender with another transgender or a transgender with a man or a woman. All married couples in partnership entitled to adopt a child. Sexual orientation of the married couple or the partners not to be a bar to their right to adoption. Non-heterosexual couples will be equally entitled to adopt a child\".<ref name=\"Catch News\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.catchnews.com/india-news/a-new-ucc-for-a-new-india-progressive-draft-ucc-allows-for-same-sex-marriages-85386.html|title=A new UCC for a new India? Progressive draft UCC allows for same sex marriages|newspaper=Catchnews|access-date=2017-10-12}}</ref> </blockquote>\n\nThere are currently several same-sex marriage petitions pending with the courts.<ref name=\"livemint\"/>\n\n==Discrimination protections==\nArticle 15 of the [[Constitution of India]] states that:<ref>{{cite web |title=Article 15 in The Constitution Of India 1949 |url=https://indiankanoon.org/doc/609295/ |website=indiankanoon.org}}</ref>\n\n15. Prohibition of discrimination on grounds of religion, race, caste, sex or place of birth<br />\n:(1) The State shall not discriminate against any citizen on grounds only of religion, race, caste, sex, place of birth or any of them\n:(2) No citizen shall, on grounds only of religion, race, caste, sex, place of birth or any of them, be subject to any disability, liability, restriction or condition with regard to\n::(a) access to shops, public restaurants, hotels and palaces of public entertainment; or\n::(b) the use of wells, tanks, bathing ghats, roads and places of public resort maintained wholly or partly out of State funds or dedicated to the use of the general public\n\nIn the case of ''Navtej Singh Johar v. Union of India'', the Supreme Court ruled that the Indian Constitution bans discrimination based on sexual orientation via the category of \"sex\". Similarly in the case of ''[[National Legal Services Authority v. Union of India]]'', the Supreme Court ruled that discrimination on the basis of [[gender identity]] is constitutionally prohibited.\n{{quote|Gender identity, in our view, is an integral part of sex and no citizen can be discriminated on the ground of gender identity, including those who identify as third\ngender. We, therefore, conclude that discrimination on the basis of sexual orientation or gender identity includes any discrimination, exclusion, restriction or preference, which has the effect of nullifying or transposing equality by the law or the equal protection of laws guaranteed under our Constitution.|author=Supreme Court Judge [[K. S. Panicker Radhakrishnan]]}}\n{{quote|Sex as it occurs in Article 15, is not merely restricted to the biological attributes of an individual, but also includes their \"sexual identity and character\".|author=Supreme Court of India}}\n\nDespite these constitutional interpretations, no explicit law has been enacted to ban discrimination on the basis of both sexual orientation and gender identity. Indeed, India does not possess comprehensive anti-discrimination laws for discrimination and harassment in private employment, except for sexual harassment. Article 15 only extends to discrimination from the state or government bodies.<ref>[https://knowledge.leglobal.org/anti-discrimination-laws-in-india/ Anti-Discrimination Laws in India]</ref>\n\nAdopted in 2019, the ''Transgender Persons (Protection of Rights) Bill, 2019'' bans discrimination against transgender people in areas such as private employment, education and healthcare.\n\nLGBT activists are encouraging people who have faced discrimination because of their sexual orientation or gender identity in private employment or other non-state areas to mount challenges in court,<ref name=\"livemint\"/> seeking to [[Legal tests|test]] the jurisprudence set by the two rulings. They are also campaigning for an explicit anti-discrimination law that would extend to private discrimination.\n\n===Military service===\nLGBT people are banned from openly serving in the [[Indian Armed Forces]].<ref name=\"military\"/> In late December 2018, MP [[Jagdambika Pal]] ([[Bharatiya Janata Party|BJP]]) introduced a bill to the Indian Parliament to amend the ''Army Act, 1950'', the ''Navy Act, 1957'' and the ''Air Force Act, 1950'' that would allow LGBT people to serve in the Armed Forces.<ref name=\"military1\"/>\n\n===Incidents===\nActor [[Kamal Rashid Khan]] was processed by the police on 9 December 2018 for making obscene comments against the LGBT community.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://m.timesofindia.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/kamaal-r-khan-booked-for-passing-vulgar-remarks-against-the-lgbtq-community/articleshow/67010098.cms|title=Kamaal R Khan booked for passing 'vulgar' remarks against the LGBTQ community|date=2018-09-12}}</ref>\n\n==Transgender rights==\n[[File:Hidras of Panscheel Park-New Delhi-1994-2.jpg|thumb|right|Three ''hijras'' in [[New Delhi]]]]\nIndia has traditionally recognised a third gender population, considered by society as neither male or female. Such individuals are known as ''[[Hijra (Indian subcontinent)|hijra]]s'' or alternatively ''hijadas'' ([[Hindi]], [[Maithili language|Maithili]] and [[Dogri language|Dogri]]: [[:hi:\u0939\u093f\u091c\u0921\u093c\u093e|\u0939\u093f\u091c\u0921\u093c\u093e]];<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.khandbahale.com/dogri-dictionary-translation-of-\u0939\u093f\u091c\u0921\u093c\u093e|title=Dogri translation of \u0939\u093f\u091c\u0921\u093c\u093e|work=[[Khandbahale.com]]}}</ref><ref>Thakur, Gajendra, ''Videha English-maithili Dictionary''. page 306</ref> {{lang-bn|[[:bn:\u09b9\u09bf\u099c\u09a1\u09bc\u09be (\u09a6\u0995\u09cd\u09b7\u09bf\u09a3 \u098f\u09b6\u09bf\u09af\u09bc\u09be)|\u09b9\u09bf\u099c\u09a1\u09bc\u09be]]}}; [[Nepali language|Nepali]]: [[:ne:\u0939\u093f\u091c\u0921\u093e|\u0939\u093f\u091c\u0921\u093e]]; [[Marathi language|Marathi]]: [[:mr:\u0939\u093f\u091c\u0921\u093e|\u0939\u093f\u091c\u0921\u093e]]). In [[Telugu language|Telugu]], they are referred to as {{lang|te|napunsakudu}} ([[:te:\u0c28\u0c2a\u0c41\u0c02\u0c38\u0c15\u0c41\u0c21\u0c41|\u0c28\u0c2a\u0c41\u0c02\u0c38\u0c15\u0c41\u0c21\u0c41]]) or {{lang|te|hijr\u0101}} (\u0c39\u0c3f\u0c1c\u0c4d\u0c30\u0c3e), in [[Urdu]] as {{lang|ur|khwaja sara}} ([[:ur:\u06c1\u06cc\u062c\u0691\u0627|\u06c1\u06cc\u062c\u0691\u0627]]), in [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]] as {{lang|gu|pavaiyaa}} (\u0aaa\u0abe\u0ab5\u0ac8\u0aaf\u0abe) or {{lang|gu|h\u012bjad\u0101}} ([[:gu:\u0ab9\u0ac0\u0a9c\u0aa1\u0abe|\u0ab9\u0ac0\u0a9c\u0aa1\u0abe]]), in [[Tamil language|Tamil]] as ''[[Iravan|aravani]]'' ({{lang|ta|\u0b85\u0bb0\u0bb5\u0bbe\u0ba3\u0bbf}}), in [[Punjabi language|Punjabi]] as {{lang|pa|khusra}} ([[:pa:\u0a39\u0a3f\u0a1c\u0a5c\u0a3e|\u0a16\u0a41\u0a38\u0a30\u0a3e]]), in [[Odia language|Odia]] as {{lang|or|hinjada}} (\u0b39\u0b3f\u0b02\u0b1c\u0b21\u0b3e), in [[Sindhi language|Sindhi]] as {{lang|sd|khadra}} ([[:sd:\u06a9\u062f\u0699\u0627|\u06a9\u062f\u0699\u0627]]), in [[Malayalam]] as {{lang|ml|sandan}} (\u0d37\u0d23\u0d4d\u200c\u0d21\u0d28\u0d4d\u200d) or {{lang|ml|hijada}} ([[:ml:\u0d39\u0d3f\u0d1c\u0d21|\u0d39\u0d3f\u0d1c\u0d21]]), in [[Kannada]] as {{lang|kn|chhakka}} ([[:kn:\u0cae\u0c82\u0c97\u0cb3\u0cae\u0cc1\u0c96\u0cbf|\u0c9a\u0c95\u0ccd\u0c95]]), in [[Konkani language|Konkani]] as ''khojji'' ({{lang|kok|\u0916\u094b\u091c\u094d\u091c\u093f}}), in [[Meitei language|Manipuri]] as {{lang|mni|nupi manbi}}, in [[Kashmiri language|Kashmiri]] as ''napumsakh'' ({{lang|ks|\u0928\u092a\u0941\u0902\u0938\u0916\u094d}}), in [[Assamese language|Assamese]] as ''npunnsk'' ({{lang|as|\u09a8\u09aa\u09c1\u0982\u09b8\u0995}}), in [[Santali language|Santali]] as ''cakra'' ({{lang|sat|\u1c6a\u1c5f\u1c60\u1c68\u1c5f}}), in [[Sanskrit]] as ''kl\u012bba'' ({{lang|sa|\u0915\u094d\u0932\u0940\u092c}}), ''napumsa'' ({{lang|sa|\u0928\u092a\u0941\u0902\u0938}}) or ''shandha'' ({{lang|sa|\u0937\u0923\u094d\u0922}}), and in [[Mizo language|Mizo]] as {{lang|lus|mil tilreh}}.<ref>Dacho Furtad, ''Konkani-English dictionary''. Asian Educational Services, 1999</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Sinha |first1=Chandrani |title=Manipur Elections 2017: Why is the transgender community of the state backing Irom Sharmila |url=https://www.inuth.com/elections/manipur-assembly-elections-2017/manipur-elections-2017-transgender-community-of-the-state-backs-prja-says-irom-will-bring-change/ |work=InUth |date=2 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Grierson |first1=George Abraham |title=A dictionary of the Kashmiri language |url=https://dsalsrv04.uchicago.edu/cgi-bin/app/grierson_query.py?qs=napumsakh&searchhws=yes |website=Digital Dictionaries of South Asia |date=1932}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Bronson |first1=Miles |title=A dictionary in Assamese and English |date=1867 |publisher=Sibsagor, American Baptist mission press |page=311 |url=https://archive.org/stream/adictionaryinas00brongoog#page/n322/search/eunuch}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=A Santali-English dictionary |date=1899 |publisher=Santal Mission Press |page=86 |url=https://archive.org/stream/asantalienglish00campgoog#page/n98/search/eunuch |language=Santali}}</ref> In English language publications, these terms are given to [[eunuch]]s, [[intersex]] people or [[transgender]] people.\n\n''Hijras'' were legally granted voting rights as a [[Third gender|third sex]] in 1994.<ref>{{cite news | last=Shackle | first=Samira | title=Politicians of the third gender: the \"shemale\" candidates of Pakistan | url=http://www.newstatesman.com/world-affairs/2013/05/politicians-third-gender-shemale-candidates-pakistan | accessdate=2013-05-11 | newspaper=New Statesman}}</ref> Due to alleged legal ambiguity of the procedure, Indian transgender individuals have difficulties accessing safe medical facilities for surgery.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Crystallising Queer Politics-The Naz Foundation Case and Its Implications For India's Transgender Communities|journal=NUJS Law Review|year=2009|url=http://www.manupatra.co.in/newsline/articles/Upload/F643E753-F822-4FE8-9B38-11279EB7B342.pdf|access-date=11 May 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305092221/http://www.manupatra.co.in/newsline/articles/Upload/F643E753-F822-4FE8-9B38-11279EB7B342.pdf|archive-date=5 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> On 15 April 2014, the [[Supreme Court of India]] declared transgender people a socially and economically backward class entitled to reservations in education and jobs, and also directed union and state governments to frame welfare schemes for them.<ref>{{cite web|title=Supreme Court's Third Gender Status to Transgenders is a landmark|url=http://news.biharprabha.com/2014/04/supreme-courts-third-gender-status-to-transgenders-is-a-landmark/|work=IANS|publisher=news.biharprabha.com|accessdate=15 April 2014}}</ref> The Court ruled that transgender people have a fundamental constitutional right to change their gender without any sort of surgery, and called on the Government to ensure equal treatment for transgender people. The Court also ruled that the Indian Constitution mandates the recognition of a third gender on official documents, and that Article 15 bans discrimination based on gender identity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://iasscore.in/national-issues/transgender-rights-in-india|title=Transgender rights in India|website=iasscore.in}}</ref> In light of the ruling, government documents, such as voter ID cards, passports and bank forms, have started providing a third gender option alongside male (M) and female (F), usually designated \"other\" (O), \"third gender\" (TG) or \"transgender\" (T).<ref name=\"O\">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/states/odisha/state-s-first-transgender-passport/cid/1391219|title=State's first transgender passport|work=The Telegraph|date=4 November 2017|last=Mallick|first=Lelin}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, transgender and gender activists [[S. Swapna]] and [[Gopi Shankar Madurai]] from [[Srishti Madurai]] staged a protest in the [[Madurai]] collectorate on 7 October 2013 demanding reservation and to permit alternate genders to appear for examinations conducted by [[TNPSC]], [[Union Public Service Commission|UPSC]], SSC and Bank exams.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/madurai/Transgenders-protest-demanding-name-change-in-certificates/articleshow/34351467.cms | work=The Times Of India | title=Transgenders protest demanding name change in certificates - The Times of India}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2013-10-08/madurai/42828401_1_transgenders-gender-variants-collectorate | work=The Times Of India | title=Transgenders stage protest at collectorate - The Times of India | date=8 October 2013}}</ref> Swapna, incidentally, had successfully moved the [[Madras High Court]] in 2013 seeking permission to write the TNPSC Group II exam as a female candidate. Swapna is the first transgender person to clear TNPSC Group IV exams.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil_nadu/Transgender-Clears-TNPSC-Group-IV-Exam/2014/02/09/article2046310.ece#.Uvc-CPmSycw|title=Transgender Clears TNPSC Group IV Exam|work=The New Indian Express}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 April 2015, the [[Rajya Sabha]] unanimously passed the ''[[Rights of Transgender Persons Bill, 2014]]'' guaranteeing rights and entitlements, reservations in education and jobs (2% reservation in government jobs), legal aid, pensions, unemployment allowances and skill development for transgender people. It also contains provisions to prohibit discrimination in employment as well as prevent abuse, violence and exploitation of transgender people. The bill also provides for the establishment of welfare boards at the centre and state level as well as for transgender rights courts. The bill was introduced by DMK MP [[Tiruchi Siva]], and marked the first time the upper house had passed a private member's bill in 45 years. However, the bill contained several anomalies and a lack of clarity on how various ministries would coordinate to implement its provisions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-others/rajya-sabha-passes-private-bill-to-protect-the-rights-of-transgenders/99/|title=Rajya Sabha passes historic private bill to promote transgender rights|date=25 April 2015|work=The Indian Express}}</ref> The bill was never brought to a vote in the lower house.\n\nSocial Justice and Empowerment Minister Thaawar Chand Gehlot stated on 11 June 2015 that the Government would introduce a new comprehensive bill for transgender rights in the Monsoon session of Parliament. The bill would be based on the study on transgender issues conducted by a committee appointed on 27 January 2014. According to Gehlot, the Government intends to provide transgender people with all rights and entitlements currently enjoyed by scheduled castes and scheduled tribes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newkerala.com/news/2015/fullnews-72086.html|title=Bills on transgenders, disabled in monsoon session: Gehlot|access-date=11 June 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170930222518/http://www.newkerala.com/news/2015/fullnews-72086.html|archive-date=30 September 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe ''Transgender Persons (Protection of Rights) Bill, 2016'', which was initially introduced to Parliament in August 2016, was re-introduced to Parliament in late 2017.<ref name=\"bill\">{{cite news |last1=Abraham |first1=Rohan |title=All you need to know about the Transgender Persons Bill, 2016 |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/all-you-need-to-know-about-the-transgender-persons-bill-2016/article21226710.ece |work=The Hindu |date=30 November 2017 |language=en-IN}}</ref> Some transgender activists have opposed the bill because it does not address issues such as marriage, adoption and divorce for transgender people. [[Akkai Padmashali]] criticised the bill's definition of transgenderism, which states that transgender people are \"based on the underlying assumption of biological determinism\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.deccanchronicle.com/nation/in-other-news/211117/centres-transgender-bill-ridiculous-laments-activist-akkai-padmashali.html|title=Centre's Transgender Bill ridiculous, laments activist Akkai Padmashali|last=|first=|date=2017-11-21|work=www.deccanchronicle.com/|access-date=2018-04-25|language=en}}</ref> The bill passed the [[Lok Sabha]] on 17 December 2018 with 27 amendments, including a controversial clause prohibiting transgender people from begging.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/lok-sabha-passes-transgender-rights-bill-1411420-2018-12-17|title=Lok Sabha passes transgender rights Bill|date=17 December 2018|work=India Today}}</ref> The bill was sent to a parliamentary committee, but lapsed with the dissolution of the 16th Lok Sabha.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://m.hindustantimes.com/delhi-news/transgender-rights-bill-might-be-reintroduced-this-parliament-session-say-mps/story-xeDqVuWnQ4Q8sAQYYGrqlJ.html|title=Transgender rights bill might be reintroduced this Parliament session, say MPs|work=Hindustan Times|date=22 June 2019|location=New Delhi}}</ref>\n\nA government bill, the ''[[Transgender Persons (Protection of Rights) Bill, 2019]]'', was reintroduced to Parliament after the [[2019 Indian general election|2019 general election]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gaystarnews.com/article/controversial-transgender-bill-to-be-reintroduced-to-indias-parliament/|title=Controversial transgender bill to be reintroduced to India's parliament|work=Gay Star News|date=6 June 2019|last=Glauert|first=Rik}}</ref> The bill was approved on 10 July by the [[Cabinet of India]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/india/cabinet-approves-transgender-bill-5824338/|title=Cabinet approves transgender bill|work=Indian Express|date=11 July 2019|location=New Delhi}}</ref><ref name=\"indiatoday\">{{cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/union-cabinet-approves-transgender-bill-protection-of-rights-2019-1566257-2019-07-10|title=Union Cabinet approves Transgender Rights Bill|work=India Today|date=10 July 2019|location=New Delhi}}</ref> The bill defines transgender persons as those \"whose gender does not match the gender assigned to that person at birth and includes trans-men or trans-women, persons with intersex variations, gender-queers, and persons having socio-cultural identities such as kinnar, hijras, aravani and jogta\". According to the bill, a person would have the right to choose to be identified as a man, woman or transgender, irrespective of [[sex reassignment surgery]] and hormonal therapy. However, it requires transgender persons to go through a district magistrate to obtain a certificate of identity and the district magistrate shall issue to the applicant an identity certificate on the basis of the rules which will be formed once the bill becomes an act, which was criticised by transgender activists who argue that it violates a Supreme Court verdict in 2014 which gave transgender people the right of self-identification.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mynation.com/india-news/begging-by-transgender-community-no-more-a-crime-bill-amended-puochd|title=Begging by transgender community no more a crime; Bill amended|work=My Nation|date=15 July 2019}}</ref> The bill prohibits discrimination against transgender people in nine fields, such as education, employment and healthcare. However, transgender activists criticised that the bill is silent on a real remedy or mechanism to integrate transgender people into public spaces and improve the quality of their lives, or on how the State intends to enforce this, or about what the State will do, if and when such discrimination does occur.<ref name=\"indiatoday\"/> The bill was also criticised for not taking into account any of the suggestions made by transgender activists; namely that it only provides for transgender persons to receive identity certificates recognising them as \"transgender\" and therefore, excludes other gender identities. Although it includes terms such as \"trans-men\", \"trans-women\", \"persons with intersex variations\" and \"gender-queers\" in its definition of transgender persons, these terms are not defined.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/analysis/the-transgender-bill-must-focus-on-equity-and-dignity/story-NHGer1jef0E6UdZhZzVirO.html|title=The transgender bill must focus on equity and dignity|work=Hindustan Times|date=14 July 2019|last=Reddy|first=Apsara}}</ref> The bill aims to set up a \"National Council for Transgender\" that would comprise a host of government and community representatives, and is meant to advise the [[Government of India|Union Government]] on formulation of policies with respect to transgender persons, monitor and evaluate the impact of said policies, coordinate the activities of all departments dealing with these matters and redress the grievances of transgender persons. A controversial clause that would have criminalised begging by transgender people has been removed from the bill. Another controversial clause that would have made transgender people subject themselves to certification by a district screening committee to be acknowledged as transgender has also been struck out.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/transgender-beggary-bill-1568764-2019-07-14|title=Provision that criminalised beggary by transgender people from bill|work=India Today|date=14 July 2019|location=New Delhi}}</ref> The bill was passed by the Lok Sabha on 5 August 2019 by a [[voice vote]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.moneycontrol.com/news/india/lok-sabha-passes-transgender-persons-protection-of-rights-bill-4291561.html|title=Lok Sabha passes Transgender persons protection of rights bill|work=Moneycontrol|date=5 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/lok-sabha-passes-transgender-persons-protection-of-rights-bill/article28822526.ece|title=Lok Sabha passes transgender protection Bill|work=The Hindu|date=5 August 2019}}</ref> and by the Rajya Sabha on 25 November 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://qz.com/india/1756897/indias-transgender-rights-bill-disappoints-the-lgbtq-community/|title=What next for transgender people, as India clears a bill that activists call \"murder of gender justice\"?|work=QuartzIndia|date=27 November 2019|last=Lalwani|first=Vijayta}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 April 2019, the Madras High Court, the high court of [[Tamil Nadu]], ruled that the term \"bride\" under the ''[[Hindu Marriage Act, 1955]]'' includes transwomen. Specifically, it directed the authorities to register a marriage between a man and a transgender woman.<ref name=\"Live Law.in\" /><ref name=\"The News Minute\" /><ref name=\"The Times of India\" />\n\n===State laws===\n{{See also|Transgender rights in Tamil Nadu|LGBT rights in Kerala#Transgender rights}}\nThe states of [[Tamil Nadu]] and [[Kerala]] were the first [[States and union territories of India|Indian states]] to introduce a transgender welfare policy. According to the policy, transgender people can access free [[sex reassignment surgery]] (SRS) in government hospitals (only for male-to-female), free housing, various citizenship documents, admission in government colleges with full scholarship for higher studies, alternative sources of livelihood through formation of self-help groups (for savings) and initiating income-generation programmes (IGP). Tamil Nadu was also the first state to form a transgender welfare board with representatives from the transgender community.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.firstpost.com/india/tamil-nadu-once-a-pioneering-state-for-welfare-of-transgenders-now-shuns-the-third-gender-3476538.html|title=Tamil Nadu, once a pioneering state for welfare of transgenders, now shuns the third gender|work=Firspost|date=25 May 2017|last=Karthikeyan|first=Divya}}</ref> Kerala started providing free surgery in government hospitals in 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://scroll.in/article/804496/why-keralas-free-sex-change-surgeries-will-offer-a-new-lifeline-for-the-transgender-community|title=Why Kerala's free sex-change surgeries will offer a new lifeline for the transgender community|last=Devasia|first=TK|website=Scroll.in|language=en-US|access-date=2016-03-19}}</ref><ref name=\"dnaindia.com\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-how-kerala-left-the-country-behind-on-transgender-rights-2145017|title=How Kerala left the country behind on transgender rights|website=dna|language=en-US|access-date=2016-03-19|date=2015-11-14}}</ref>\n\nThe state of [[West Bengal]] set up a transgender welfare board in 2015 to coordinate all policy decisions and development work pertaining to the transgender population in the state.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://clpr.org.in/blog/the-transgender-welfare-development-board-west-bengal-a-wasted-potential-2/|title=The Transgender Welfare Development Board, West Bengal \u2013 A Wasted Potential|website=Centre for Law & Policy Research|date=13 April 2017}}</ref> The board, however, has been labelled an \"all-around failure\" by several transgender activists. Supposed to meet once every month with representatives from numerous state government departments, the board has only met five times as of July 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/kolkata/bengal-s-transgender-development-board-all-around-failure-alleges-member/story-8YZ4xiM8DMkd9DBYRj5FVI.html|title=Hindustan Times|date=4 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2016, the state of [[Odisha]] enacted welfare benefits for transgender people, giving them the same benefits as those living below the poverty line. This was aimed at improving their overall social and economic status, according to the Odisha Department of Social Security.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dash |first1=Jatindra |title=Odisha becomes first state to give welfare to transgender community |url=https://in.reuters.com/article/india-odisha-lgbt-poverty/odisha-becomes-first-state-to-give-welfare-to-transgender-community-idINKCN0YO1S7 |work=Reuters |date=2 June 2016 |language=en-IN}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Government of Himachal Pradesh]] has set up medical boards at the district and state level for assisting transgender people. The state has also enacted various schemes providing pension, skill development, scholarship and financial support for parents of transgender people.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-news-india/himachal-pradesh-to-bring-transgenders-under-social-security-net-3018937/|title=Himachal Pradesh to bring transgenders under social security net|website=The Indian Express|date=7 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://himachal.nic.in/index1.php?lang=1&dpt_id=9&level=0&linkid=2835&lid=7696|title=Welfare of Transgender|website=himachal.nic.in}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2017, the [[Ministry of Drinking Water and Sanitation]] instructed states to allow transgender people to use the public toilet of their choice.<ref>{{cite news |last=Sharma |first= Kuheena |date=6 April 2017 |title=Sanitation ministry allows transgender people use public toilets, wants them recognised as equal citizens |url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/transgender-public-toilets-ministry-of-drinking-water-and-sanitation/1/922557.html |work=[[India Today]] |location=[[New Delhi]] |access-date=2 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nA transgender board was established in [[Chandigarh]] on 22 August 2017. The board comprises members from the police department, the social welfare department, the education department and the law department, health professionals, and representatives of [[Panjab University]], and others.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/india/chandigarh-gets-its-first-transgender-welfare-board-with-14-members-4820148/|title=Chandigarh gets its first Transgender Welfare Board with 14 members|website=Indian Express|date=30 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2017, the [[Karnataka]] Government issued the \"State Policy for Transgenders, 2017\", with the aim of raising awareness of transgender people within all educational institutions in the state. Educational institutions will address issues of violence, abuse and discrimination against transgender people. It also established a monitoring committee designed with investigating reports of discrimination.<ref>{{cite news |title=Transgender policy cleared by Karnataka cabinet |url=https://indianexpress.com/article/india/transgender-policy-cleared-by-karnataka-cabinet-4909196/ |work=The Indian Express |agency=Press Trust of India |date=27 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 November 2017, [[N. Chandrababu Naidu]], the [[Chief Minister]] of [[Andhra Pradesh]], announced the enactment of pension plans for transgender people.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.abplive.in/india-news/cm-naidu-announces-pension-scheme-for-state-s-transgenders-609165/amp|title=CM Naidu announces pension scheme for state's transgenders|last=ANI|website=ABP Live|date=2017-11-28}}</ref> On 16 December 2017, the Andhra Cabinet passed the policy. According to the policy, the State Government will provide an amount of \u20b91,500 per month to each transgender person above the age of 18 for social security pensions. The Government will also construct special toilets in public places, such as malls and cinema halls, for transgender people.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Apparasu |first1=Srinivasa Rao |title=Transgenders to get pension, ration and more in Andhra; govt clears welfare policy |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/transgenders-to-get-pension-ration-education-in-andhra-govt-clears-welfare-policy/story-ZZ92gJGL0gvP9ZZFlFEvgJ.html |work=Hindustan Times |date=17 December 2017 |language=en}}</ref> In addition, the state has also established a transgender welfare board.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/andhra-pradesh-launches-welfare-board-transgender-persons-community-welcomes-move-60742|title=Andhra Pradesh launches welfare board for transgender persons, community welcomes move|website=The News Minute|date=26 April 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2018, the Kashmiri Finance Minister introduced a proposal to the [[Jammu and Kashmir Legislative Assembly]] that would grant transgender people free life and medical insurance, and a monthly sustenance pension for those aged 60+ and registered with the Social Welfare Department. Transgender activists have criticised aspects of the bill, including its requirement to establish medical boards to issue \"transgender certificates\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Naqash |first1=Rayan |title=For the first time, Kashmir government recognises needs of transgender community. But is it enough? |url=https://scroll.in/article/865317/for-the-first-time-government-recognises-needs-of-kashmirs-transgender-community-is-it-enough |work=Scroll.in |date=4 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-jammu-and-kashmir-transgender-community-welcomes-steps-taken-by-mehbooba-mufti-government-2574903|title=Jammu and Kashmir: Transgender community welcomes steps taken by Mehbooba Mufti government|date=12 January 2018|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Government of Delhi]] announced its intention in May 2018 to establish a seven-member committee to review issues surrounding the transgender community, including concerns of sexual abuse, discrimination at work as well as other societal problems. \"We will have a dedicated cell for transgender people, which will be headed by a representative from the community. The commission receives a lot of complaints of abuse against them. The cell will enable us to focus on issues faced by [transgender people] and providing members greater support and safety.\", said Swati Maliwal, chief of the Delhi Commission for Women. However, as of May 2019, the board has not yet been set up.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/delhi-news/delhi-commission-for-women-to-have-a-dedicated-transgender-cell/story-qOsSY7Rpey21J8KyHlmU3J.html|title=Delhi Commission for Women to have a dedicated transgender cell|website=Hindustan Times|date=8 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2018, the [[Rajasthan]] Transgender Welfare Board (RTWB) announced it would begin issuing \"multi-purpose identity cards\" to about 75,000 transgender people in the state to help them access government schemes and benefits.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/jaipur/in-rajasthan-transgenders-to-get-identity-cards-soon-to-avail-of-scheme-benefits/story-p5PpZy10QUX5eHoHLBwleM.html|title=In Rajasthan, transgenders to get identity cards soon to avail of scheme benefits|website=Hindustan Times|date=13 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Uttarakhand]] High Court directed the [[Government of Uttarakhand|State Government]] in late September 2018 to provide reservation for transgender people in educational institutions. The court also asked the Government to frame social welfare programmes for the betterment of transgender people.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jagranjosh.com/current-affairs/uttarakhand-hc-directs-state-to-provide-reservation-to-transgenders-in-educational-institutions-1538381858-1|title=Uttarakhand HC directs state to provide reservation to transgenders in educational institutions|website=Jagran Josh|date=1 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn early 2019, the Social Welfare Department of [[Assam]] published a draft \"transgender policy\" with numerous objectives, including providing transgender people access to educational institutions, providing shelter and sanitation for the homeless, raising awareness, and issuing self-identification identity cards.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://socialwelfare.assam.gov.in/sites/default/files/swf_utility_folder/departments/sw_webcomindia_org_oid_3/menu/document/draft_transgender.pdf|title=Draft Policy for Transgender.|website=Social Welfare Department of Assam|date=3 February 2019}}</ref> The All Assam Transgender Association has criticised certain aspects of the policy, namely its definition of the term \"transgender\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nenow.in/north-east-news/assam/assam-government-criticized-giving-bad-definition-transgender.html|title=Assam government criticized for giving a bad definition of transgender|website=Ne Now News|date=14 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2019, the [[Maharashtra]] Government set up a \"Transgender Welfare Board\" to conduct health programmes and provide formal education and employment opportunities to transgender people. The board provides skill development programmes to help transgender people find a job and free accommodation for those seeking scholarships.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/maharashtra-government-sets-up-transgender-welfare-board-1998189|title=Maharashtra Government Sets Up Transgender Welfare Board|website=NDTV|date=23 February 2019}}</ref> A similar board was also set up in the neighbouring state of [[Gujarat]] that same month. The Gujarat board provides various welfare programmes for employment and education, and coordinates with state departments to ensure that the transgender community is able to take advantage of government schemes. An educational campaign was also established in order to sensitise the public.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thelogicalindian.com/news/gujarat-transgender-board/|title=Gujarat Govt Establishes Transgender Welfare Board; Housing, Education & Other Issues To Be Taken Care Of|website=The Logical Indian|date=19 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2019, the [[Bihar]] Government announced the creation of a transgender welfare board, which would investigate and report on social and legal challenges faced by transgender people in the state and provide financial assistance of up to \u20b91.5 [[lakh]] for [[sex reassignment surgery]]. In addition, those who refuse house on rent or medical facilities to transgender individuals would be eligible for imprisonment ranging between six months to two years.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thelogicalindian.com/get-inspired/bihar-transgender-rights/|title=Bihar Govt Establishes Transgender Welfare Board, To Give Rs 1.5 Lakh For Sex Change Operation|website=The Logical Indian|date=18 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/nation/2019/jul/16/bihar-to-help-transgenders-with-rs-15-lakh-for-sex-change-operation-2004729.html|title=Bihar to help transgenders with Rs 1.5 lakh for sex change operation|website=The New Indian Express|date=16 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2019, the state of [[Madhya Pradesh]] announced its intention to set up a welfare board for the transgender community in the near future. Issues will include a monthly allowance to parents of intersex children, provisions for job reservations for transgender persons in government and separate public toilets.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/bhopal/madhya-pradesh-to-roll-out-welfare-policy-for-transgenders/story-dewBj0EdfPaokkokMy1vzN.html|title=Madhya Pradesh to roll out welfare policy for transgenders|website=Hindustan Times|date=5 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Third gender literature and studies===\n''Vaadamalli'' by novelist [[Su. Samuthiram]] is the first [[Tamil language|Tamil]] novel about the local ''[[aravani]]'' community in Tamil Nadu, published in 1994. Later, transgender activist [[A. Revathi]] became the first ''[[Hijra (South Asia)|hijra]]'' to write about ''hijra'' issues and gender politics in Tamil. Her works have been translated into more than eight languages and act as a primary resource on gender studies in Asia. Her book is part of a research project for more than 100 universities. She is the author of ''Unarvum Uruvamum'' (Feelings of the Entire Body), the first of its kind in English from a member of the ''hijra'' community.<ref>[http://dspace.flinders.edu.au/jspui/bitstream/2328/27270/1/Revathi_Prabhu.pd Writing'a'Life'Between'Gender'Lines Conversations'with'A.'Revathi'about'Her'Autobiography' The Truth About Me: A Hijra Life Story]</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.thehindu.com/books/hope-floats/article802665.ece | location=Chennai, India | work=The Hindu | first=S. M. | last=Umair | title=Hope floats | date=29 September 2010}}</ref> She also acted and directed several stage plays on gender and sexuality issues in Tamil and [[Kannada language|Kannada]]. ''The Truth about Me: A Hijra Life Story'' by A. Revathi is part of the syllabus for final year students of [[The American College in Madurai]]. The American College is the first college in India to introduce [[third gender]] literature and studies with research-oriented seminars.<ref>{{cite book |title=Maraikkappatta Pakkangal: \u0bae\u0bb1\u0bc8\u0b95\u0bcd\u0b95\u0baa\u0bcd\u0baa\u0b9f\u0bcd\u0b9f \u0baa\u0b95\u0bcd\u0b95\u0b99\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bb3\u0bcd|last=Winter|first=Gopi Shankar|year=2014 |publisher=Srishti Madurai |isbn=9781500380939 |oclc=703235508 |page= |pages=}}</ref> Later, Naan Saravanan's ''Alla'' (2007) and Vidya's ''I Am Vidya'' (2008) were among early transwoman autobiographies.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/metroplus/society/my-life-my-way/article3978249.ece | location=Chennai, India | work=The Hindu | first=Pushpa | last=Achanta | title=My life, my way | date=9 October 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deccanherald.com/content/89595/doraiswamy-revathi-tamil-writer-activists.html|title=Doraiswamy to Revathi: A Tamil writer-activist's alternative journey|work=Deccan Herald|date=2010-08-18}}</ref> [[Kalki Subramaniam]]'s '' Kuri Aruthean'' (Phallus, I cut) is a collection of Tamil poems about transgender lives.\n\nThe American College in Madurai also introduced ''Maraikappatta Pakkangal (Hidden Pages)'' as a course book for \"Genderqueer and Intersex Human Rights studies\" as part of the curriculum for Tamil and English department students in 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/madurai-colleges-intersex-course-to-cover-58-genders/articleshow/65537361.cms|title=Madurai college's 'intersex' course to cover 58 genders|work=Times of India|accessdate=2018-02-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.out.com/popnography/2018/8/28/students-will-study-58-distinct-gender-identities-college-india|title=Students Will Study 58 Distinct Gender Identities at College in India|work=Out Magazine|accessdate=2018-02-10}}</ref> It is the first book on the LGBT community in the Tamil language, launched by [[Gopi Shankar Madurai]] and [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] leader [[Vanathi Srinivasan]] in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mumbaimirror.com/news/india/BJP-leader-launches-LGBT-rights-book-in-TN/articleshow/38157614.cms|title=BJP leader launches LGBT rights book in TN|work=Mumbai Mirror|accessdate=2017-12-28}}</ref><ref name=\"thehindu5\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/metroplus/no-more-under-siege/article5247859.ece|publisher=thehindu.com|title=No more under siege - The Hindu|accessdate=2017-12-28|newspaper=The Hindu|date=18 October 2013|last1=Shrikumar|first1=A.}}</ref><ref name=\"indiatimes2\">{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/madurai/Madurai-student-pens-book-on-gender-variants/articleshow/20419621.cms|publisher=timesofindia.indiatimes.com|title=Madurai student pens book on gender variants - Times of India|accessdate=2017-12-28}}</ref>\n\n==Conversion therapy==\nIn February 2014, the [[Indian Psychiatric Society]] (IPS) issued a statement, in which it stated that there is no evidence to prove that homosexuality is unnatural: \"Based on existing scientific evidence and good practice guidelines from the field of psychiatry, the Indian Psychiatric Society would like to state that there is no evidence to substantiate the belief that homosexuality is a mental illness or a disease.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Iyer |first1=Malathy |title=Homosexuality is not a disease, psychiatrists say |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Homosexuality-is-not-a-disease-psychiatrists-say/articleshow/29965430.cms |work=The Times of India |date=7 February 2014}}</ref> In June 2018, IPS reiterated its stance on homosexuality saying: \"Certain people are not cut out to be heterosexual and we don\u2019t need to castigate them, we don't need to punish them, to ostracize them\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gaystarnews.com/article/indias-biggest-psychiatric-body-declares-homosexuality-is-not-an-illness/|title=India's biggest psychiatric body declares homosexuality is not an illness|last1=Power|first1=Shannon|date=8 June 2018|website=Gay Star News}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/mumbai-news/stop-treating-homosexuality-as-an-illness-says-indian-psychiatric-society/story-EqoFV1KjFE0mxAxOimX8oN.html|title=Stop treating homosexuality as an illness, says Indian Psychiatric Society|last1=Pratap|first=Aayushi|date=6 June 2018|work=[[Hindustan Times]]|accessdate=2 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nDespite this statement from the IPS, conversion therapies are still performed in India. These practices usually involve [[electroconvulsive therapy]] (which may lead to memory loss), hypnosis, the administration of nausea-inducing drugs, or more commonly talk therapy where the individual is told that homosexuality is caused by \"insufficient male affirmation in childhood\" or \"an uncaring father and an overbearing mother\". Conversion therapy can lead to depression, anxiety, seizures, drug use and suicidal tendencies for the individuals involved.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Singh |first1=Amrita |title=From Shock Treatment To Yoga, Conversion Therapy Is A Disturbing Reality Around The World |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.in/youth-ki-awaaz-/how-therapy-to-convert-qu_b_10201948.html |work=HuffPost India |date=1 June 2016 |language=en-IN}}</ref>\n\n==Sexual violence==\nIn July 2019, lawmaker [[K. T. S. Tulsi]] introduced the ''Criminal Law (Amendment) Bill, 2018'' in the [[Rajya Sabha]] to amend the [[Indian Penal Code]], the Criminal Procedure Code and the ''Indian Evidence Act, 1872'' in order to make sexual crimes gender-neutral by including men and transgender people in addition to women. If passed the bill allows for recognition of not only transgender persons defined as the \"other\" gender under Indian law, but would potentially leave the door open for the recognition of other gender identities.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/bill-to-make-sexual-crimes-gender-neutral-introduced-in-parliament-1568504-2019-07-13|title=Bill to make sexual crimes gender neutral introduced to Parliament|work=India Today|date=13 July 2019|last=Mathur|first=Aneesha|location=New Delhi}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timesofindia.com/india/kts-tulsi-introduces-bill-in-rajya-sabha-to-make-sexual-crimes-gender-neutral-full-text-of-the-bill/articleshow/70202016.cms|title=Bill in Parliament to make sexual crimes gender neutral: Read full text|work=The Times of India|date=13 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Living conditions==\n[[File:Anjali gopalan.jpg|thumb|Asia's first Genderqueer Pride Parade in [[Madurai]], [[Tamil Nadu]] (2012). [[Anjali Gopalan]] is seen in the foreground.<ref name=\"One Who Fights For an Other\">{{cite web|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/education/edex/One-Who-Fights-For-an-Other/2015/04/13/article2756559.ece|title=One Who Fights For an Other|work=The New Indian Express}}</ref>]]\n[[File:Bhopal pride Queermitra 04.jpg|thumb|right|Participants at the 2018 [[Bhopal]] Pride parade, in [[Madhya Pradesh]]]]\nThere are many avenues for the LGBT community in metro cities for meeting and socialising, although not very openly. These include GayBombay ([[Mumbai]]), Good as You ([[Bangalore]]), HarmlessHugs ([[Delhi]]), Orinam ([[Chennai]]), Queerala ([[Kochi]]), Queerhythm ([[Thiruvananthapuram]]), Mobbera ([[Hyderabad]]), Parichay Collective ([[Bhubaneswar]]), and Sahodaran (Chennai). Groups focused on LGBT women include ASQ (Bangalore), Labia (Mumbai), Sappho for Equality ([[Kolkata]]), Chennai Queer Cafe, among others. Trans-specific groups that are focused on support and advocacy include Sampoorna, Tweet Foundation, Telangana Hijra Trans Intersex Samiti, and many others. Recently, a queer dating platform named \"Amour Queer Dating\" was launched to help LGBT people find long-term partners.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sawant |first1=Anagha |title=Now, a dating platform for LGBT community |url=https://www.dnaindia.com/mumbai/report-now-a-dating-platform-for-lgbt-community-2236832 |work=Daily News and Analysis |date=22 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nThere have many reports of abuse, harassment and violence over the years directed against LGBT people. In 2003, a ''hijra'' was gang-raped in [[Bangalore]], and then gang-raped by the police. Testimonies provided to the Delhi High Court in 2007 documented how a gay man abducted by the police in [[Delhi]] was raped by police officials for several days and forced to sign a \"confession\" saying \"I am a gandu [a derogatory term, meaning one who has anal sex]\". In 2011, a [[Haryana]] lesbian couple was murdered by their nephews for being in an \"immoral\" relationship.<ref name=\"guardian\"/> According to reports from activist group Kavi's Humsafar Trust, two-fifths of homosexuals in the country had faced blackmail after the 2013 Supreme Court ruling.<ref name=\"aljazeera\"/> [[Suicide]] attempts are common. In early 2018, a lesbian couple committed suicide and left a note reading: \"We have left this world to live with each other. The world did not allow us to stay together.\"<ref name=\"guardian\"/>\n\nIn February 2017, the [[Ministry of Health and Family Welfare]] unveiled resource material relating to health issues to be used as a part of a nationwide adolescent peer-education plan called ''Saathiya''. Among other subjects, the material discusses homosexuality. The material states, \"Yes, adolescents frequently fall in love. They can feel attraction for a friend or any individual of the same or opposite sex. It is normal to have special feelings for someone. It is important for adolescents to understand that such relationships are based on mutual consent, trust, transparency and respect. It is alright to talk about such feelings to the person for whom you have them but always in a respectful manner.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Same-sex attraction is OK, boys can cry, girl's no means no|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/same-sex-attraction-is-ok-boys-can-cry-girls-no-means-no-health-ministry-sex-education-4535410/|website=The Indian Express|accessdate=21 February 2017|language=en|date=21 February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Homosexual attraction is OK; 'NO' means no: Health Ministry rises above Indian stereotypes|url=http://www.financialexpress.com/jobs/homosexual-attraction-is-ok-no-means-no-health-ministry-rises-above-indian-stereotypes/560227/|website=The Financial Express|accessdate=21 February 2017|date=21 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, [[Delhi]] held its tenth pride parade, attended by hundreds of people.<ref name=\"delhi\"/> [[Chennai]] has held pride parades since 2009,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Menon |first1=Priya |title=A decade of Pride in Chennai |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/a-decade-of-pride-in-chennai/articleshow/64421312.cms |work=The Times of India |date=2 June 2018}}</ref> while [[Goa]] held its first pride parade in October 2017.<ref>{{cite news |title=A walk to remember for the LGBT community - Times of India |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/goa/a-walk-to-remember-for-the-lgbt-community/articleshow/61313127.cms |work=The Times of India |date=29 October 2017}}</ref> [[Bhubaneswar]] organised its first in September 2018,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/gdpr-consent/?destination=%2fworld%2fasia_pacific%2fas-india-awaits-a-historic-gay-rights-ruling-a-city-holds-its-first-pride-march%2f2018%2f09%2f05%2fe7a14ce4-b0fa-11e8-a810-4d6b627c3d5d_story.html%3f |title=As India awaits a historic gay rights ruling, a city holds its first pride march|website=The Washington Post|date=5 September 2018}}</ref> and [[Guwahati]] held its first [[Queer Pride Guwahati|pride event]] in February 2014. The first such event in [[Sikkim]] was held in January 2019 in the city of [[Gangtok]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.northeasttoday.in/first-queer-pride-walk-of-sikkim-on-january-27/|title=First Queer Pride Walk of Sikkim on January 27|website=Northeast Today|date=4 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 May 2018, the International Day Against Homophobia, activities were held throughout the country, including in [[Bhopal]], Delhi, [[Mumbai]], [[Kolhapur]], [[Thiruvananthapuram]] and [[Lucknow]]. Numerous foreign embassies ([[Australia]], [[Austria]], [[Belgium]], [[Brazil]], [[Canada]], [[Costa Rica]], [[Croatia]], the [[Czech Republic]], [[Denmark]], [[Finland]], [[France]], [[Germany]], [[Greece]], [[Iceland]], [[Ireland]], [[Italy]], [[Japan]], [[Latvia]], [[Lithuania]], [[Luxembourg]], [[Malta]], [[Mexico]], [[New Zealand]], the [[Netherlands]], [[Norway]], [[Portugal]], [[Serbia]], [[Slovenia]], [[Spain]], [[Sweden]], [[Switzerland]], the [[United Kingdom]] and the [[United States]]) expressed support for LGBT rights in India, and reaffirmed their countries' commitment to promote human rights.<ref>[https://dayagainsthomophobia.org/india-idahotb-2018-country-page India \u2013 IDAHOTB 2018 Country Page], ''Erasing 76 Crimes''</ref>\n\nAccording to a 2018 survey, a third of Indian gay men are married to women who are unaware that they are secretly gay.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gaystarnews.com/article/indian-men-gay/|title=A third of Indian gay men are married to women who have no idea they're gay|work=Gay Star News|date=25 October 2018|last=Besanvalle|first=James}}</ref>\n\n===Politics===\nThe All India Hijra Kalyan Sabha fought for over a decade to get voting rights, which they finally got in 1994. In 1996, Kali stood for office in [[Patna]] under the then Judicial Reform Party. Munni ran in the elections as well for [[South Mumbai]] that year. They both lost.<ref>{{cite news |title=Accept history and move on |url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/magazine/2009/may/16/accept-history-and-move-on-49825.html |work=The New Indian Express}}</ref>\n\nAfter the defeat of Kali and Munni, three years later, Kamla Jaan ran and won the position of the Mayor of [[Katni]]. Later, Shabnam Mausi was elected to the Legislative Assembly of [[Madhya Pradesh]] in 2002. Over the next few years, multiple other transgender candidates won office. These include Heera who won a seat at the City Council of [[Jabalpur]] and Gulshan who was elected to the City Council in [[Bina Etawa]]. In December 2000, Asha Devi became the Mayor of [[Gorakhpur]], and Kallu Kinnar was elected to the City Council in [[Varanasi]].\n\n[[Shabnam Mausi]] is the first transgender Indian to be elected to public office. She was an elected member of the Madhya Pradesh State Legislative Assembly from 1998 to 2003. In 2000, Shabnam Mausi became India's first [[eunuch]] MP. Transgender people were granted voting rights in 1994. In 2003, ''hijras'' in Madhya Pradesh announced the establishment of their own political party called \"Jeeti Jitayi Politics\" (JJP), which literally means \"politics that has already been won\". The party also has released an eight-page election manifesto which it claims outlines why it is different from mainstream political parties.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/668042.stm | work=BBC News | title=Eunuch MP takes seat | date=6 March 2000}}</ref>\n\nKalki Subramaniam is a transgender rights activist, writer and an actor. In the [[2011 Tamil Nadu Legislative Assembly election|2011 assembly elections in Tamil Nadu]], Kalki tried in vain to get a [[Dravida Munnetra Kazhagam|DMK]] ticket.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil_nadu/article452450.ece?service=print|title=Transgender activist Kalki to seek DMK ticket|publisher=}}</ref> In March 2014, Kalki announced in [[Puducherry]] that she would contest a seat in an election in the [[Villupuram]] constituency in neighbouring Tamil Nadu.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/transgender-kalki-in-poll-race/article5840745.ece | location=Chennai, India | work=The Hindu | first1=C. | last1=Jaisankar | first2=A. V. | last2=Raghunathan | title=Transgender Kalki in poll race}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 January 2015, independent transgender candidate Madhu Bai Kinnar was elected as the Mayor of [[Raigarh]], [[Chhattisgarh]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://time.com/3656348/india-transgender-mayor/ | work=Time | first=Charlotte | last=Alter | title=India's First Openly Transgender Mayor Elected | date=6 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://blogs.wsj.com/indiarealtime/2015/01/07/indias-first-openly-transgender-mayor-in-her-own-words/ | work=The Wall Street Journal | title=India's First Openly Transgender Mayor in Her Own Words | date=7 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2015/01/05/us-india-transgender-idUSKBN0KE0MT20150105 | work=Reuters | title=First transgender mayor elected in central India: media | date=5 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/jan/05/transgender-woman-elected-mayor-india-chhattisgarh|title=Transgender woman is elected district mayor in Indian state of Chhattisgarh|newspaper=the Guardian|date=2015-01-05|last1=France-Presse|first1=Agence}}</ref>\n\n[[Manabi Bandopadhyay]] became India's first transgender college principal on 9 June 2015 when she assumed the role of principal of the Krishnagar Women's College in Nadia district, [[West Bengal]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ians/india-s-first-transgender-college-principal-starts-work-115060901323_1.html|title=India's first transgender college principal starts work|author=IANS|date=9 June 2015|publisher=|newspaper=Business Standard India}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 November 2015, K. Prithika Yashini became the first out transgender police officer in the state of Tamil Nadu. At the time, the Tamil Nadu police had three transgender constables, but Yashini became the first transgender person to hold the rank of officer in the state.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-news-india/madras-hc-orders-appointment-of-a-transgender-as-sub-inspector/|title=With a little help from Madras HC, Tamil Nadu gets its first transgender police officer|date=7 November 2015|work=The Indian Express}}</ref> Transgender men are an integral part of the police force in many states of India. Many of them remain in the women police force and fear changing their legal name and gender as this could pose a risk to their employment.\n\nOn 12 February 2017, two transgender people were appointed by the [[Kolhapur]] District Legal Services Authority (KDLSA) as panel members for the local Lok Adalat (People's Court). 30 panels were appointed to settle general local disputes that arise within the community. Members of the KDLSA have stated this appointment was their \"main achievement.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Lok Adalat makes history, appointed two transgenders as panelist|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/kolhapur/lok-adalat-makes-history-appointed-two-transgenders-as-panelist/articleshow/57102434.cms|accessdate=12 April 2017|agency=The Times of India|date=12 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2017, [[Joyita Mondal]] was appointed to the [[Islampur, Uttar Dinajpur|Islampur]] [[Lok Adalat]], becoming [[West Bengal]]'s first transgender judge.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/nation/2017/jul/22/indias-first-transgender-judge-joyita-mondal-wants-jobs-for-her-community-1632169--1.html|title=India's first transgender judge Joyita Mondal wants jobs for her community|publisher=The New Indian Express}}</ref> In 2018, Swati Bidham Baruah became the first transgender judge in [[Assam]]. Swati, founder of the All Assam Transgender Association, was appointed to the [[Guwahati]] [[Lok Adalat]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Assam gets its first transgender judge |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/assam-gets-its-first-transgender-judge/articleshow/64994335.cms |work=The Economic Times |agency=Asian News International |date=15 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nTransgender representation was particularly noticeable in the [[2019 Indian general election|Lok Sabha elections of 2019]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://orinam.net/resources-for/lgbt/queering-india-elections-2019/|title=Queering the Indian Elections 2019|work=Orinam|date=}}</ref> with many candidates running in [[Andhra Pradesh]], [[Gujarat]], [[Kerala]], [[Maharashtra]], [[Odisha]], [[Tamil Nadu]] and [[Uttar Pradesh]]. Most major parties mentioned LGBT rights in their election manifestos. The [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] (BJP) ran on a platform of greater rights for the transgender community, adding that it \"will ensure self-employment and skill development avenues for transgender youth.\" The [[Indian National Congress]]' manifesto states that the party \"recognises the sexual diversity among people and promises equality and equal protection of the laws to people with different sexual identities\", specifically advocating for a transgender bill drafted in consultation with LGBT groups and gender sensitivity training in all government departments.\n\n==Intersex rights==\n[[File:Protection of intersex children from harmful practices.svg|thumb|right|260px|\n{{legend|#002255|Legal prohibition of non-consensual [[Intersex medical interventions|medical interventions]]}}\n{{legend|#0066FF|Regulatory suspension of non-consensual medical interventions}}]]\n{{further|Intersex human rights|Intersex medical interventions}}\n[[File:Inclusion of sex characteristics in anti-discrimination law.svg|thumb|right|260px|\n{{legend|#002255|Explicit protection from [[Discrimination against intersex people|discrimination]] on grounds of [[sex characteristics]]}}\n{{legend|#0066FF|Explicit protection on grounds of intersex status}}\n{{legend|#9FCFFF|Explicit protection on grounds of intersex within attribute of sex}}]]\n\nIntersex issues in India may often be perceived as [[third gender]] issues. The most well-known third gender groups in India are the ''[[Hijra (South Asia)|hijras]]''. After interviewing and studying ''hijras'' for many years, [[Serena Nanda]] writes in her book, ''Neither Man Nor Woman: The hijras of India'', as follows: \"There is a widespread belief in India that hijras are born [[hermaphrodite]]s [intersex] and are taken away by the hijra community at birth or in childhood, but I found no evidence to support this belief among the hijras I met, all of whom joined the community voluntarily, often in their teens.\"<ref>Nanda, Serena. Neither Man Nor Woman: The hijras of India, p. xx. Canada: Wadsworth Publishing Company, 1999</ref> [[Sangam literature]] uses the word ''pedi'' to refer to people born intersex, but the indigenous gender minorities in India were clear about intersex people and referred to them as ''mabedi usili'' and gave a distinct identity to denote them.<ref name=\"Indian Women Blog\">{{cite web|url=http://www.indianwomenblog.org/read-why-gopi-shankar-calls-attention-of-arundhati-roy-to-intersex-community/|publisher= Indian Women Blog.Org|title=Read Why Gopi Shankar Calls Attention Of Arundhati Roy To Intersex Community|accessdate=2018-02-03|date= 2017-11-24}}</ref>\n\n=== Physical integrity and bodily autonomy ===\nIntersex persons are not protected from violations to physical integrity and bodily autonomy.\n\nCases of infanticide have been reported involving infants with obvious intersex conditions at birth, along with a failure to thrive by infants assigned female.<ref name=\"warne2008\">{{Cite journal| doi = 10.1007/s11154-008-9084-2| issn = 1389-9155| volume = 9| issue = 3| pages = 227\u2013236| last1 = Warne| first1 = Garry L.| last2 = Raza| first2 = Jamal| title = Disorders of sex development (DSDs), their presentation and management in different cultures| journal = Reviews in Endocrine and Metabolic Disorders| date = September 2008| pmid=18633712| citeseerx = 10.1.1.469.9016}}</ref> Medical reports suggest that parents in India prefer to assign infants with intersex conditions as male, with [[intersex medical interventions|surgical interventions]] taking place when parents can afford them.<ref name=\"rajendran1995\">{{Cite journal| volume = 32| last1 = Rajendran| first1 = R| last2 = Hariharan| first2 = S| title =  Profile of Intersex Children in South India| journal = Indian Pediatrics| date = 1995}}</ref><ref name=\"sharma2014\">{{Cite news| last = Sharma| first = Radha| title = Parents prefer male child in intersex operations in Gujarat| work = Times of India| date = February 5, 2014| url = http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2014-02-05/india/47048496_1_dr-aniruddha-shah-male-child-organs}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal| doi = 10.4103/2230-8210.102994| pmid = 23226638| pmc = 3510963| issn = 2230-8210| volume = 16| issue = 6| pages = 935\u20138| last1 = Gupta| first1 = Devendra| last2 = Sharma| first2 = Shilpa| title = Male genitoplasty for 46 XX congenital adrenal hyperplasia patients presenting late and reared as males| journal = Indian Journal of Endocrinology and Metabolism|date = 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn a reply to a letter from an intersex rights activist [[Gopi Shankar Madurai]], the [[Ministry of Health and Family Welfare]], India replied that \"Any kind of invasive medical procedure including sex reassignment operations are done only after thorough assessment of the patient, obtaining justification for the procedure planned to be conducted with the help of appropriate diagnostic test and only after taking a written consent of the patient/guardian\".<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.thenewsminute.com/article/activists-say-surgical-correction-intersex-babies-birth-wrong-govt-doesnt-listen-56739 | title = Activists say surgical 'correction' of intersex babies at birth wrong, govt doesn't listen | first = Ragamalika | last = Karthikeyan | work = The News Minute | date = February 3, 2017}}</ref>\n\nBesides male and female, [[Indian passport]]s are available with an [[Legal recognition of non-binary gender|\"O\"]] sex descriptor (for \"Other\").<ref name=\"O\"/>\n\nOn 22 April 2019, the [[Madras High Court]] issued a landmark judgment, in which it upheld the marriage rights of transgender women,<ref name=\"Live Law.in\">{{cite web|url=https://www.livelaw.in/news-updates/transwoman-regarded-as-bride-madras-hc-bans-sex-re-assignment-surgeries-intersex-children-144467|title=\"Transwoman A 'Bride' Under Hindu Marriage Act\": Madras HC; Also Bans Sex Re-Assignment Surgeries On Intersex Children [Read Judgment]|accessdate=2019-04-24|date=23 April 2019}}</ref> and directed the state of [[Tamil Nadu]] to ban sex-selective surgeries on intersex infants. Based on the works of intersex activist Gopi Shankar,<ref name=\"The News Minute\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/ban-sex-reassignment-surgeries-intersex-infants-madras-hc-tells-tn-govt-100565|title=\"Ban sex reassignment surgeries on intersex infants Madras High Court tells Tamil Nadu Govt\" - The News Minute|accessdate=2019-04-24}}</ref> the Court took note of the rampant practice of compulsory [[Intersex medical interventions|medical interventions]] performed on intersex infants and children.<ref name=\"The Times of India\">{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/madurai/ruling-on-intersex-infants-madurai-activist-comes-in-for-praise-by-hc/articleshow/69016201.cms|title=Ruling on intersex infants: Madurai activist comes in for praise by High Court|accessdate=2019-04-24}}</ref> The court further cited examples from Hindu mythology in its ruling, namely the story of [[Iravan]].\n\n===Protection from discrimination===\n{{main|Discrimination against intersex people}}\nMultiple Indian athletes have been subjected to humiliation, discrimination and loss of work and medals following sex verification.<ref name=\"kaira2012\">{{Cite journal| doi = 10.4103/2230-8210.102980| pmid = 23226629| pmc = 3510954| issn = 2230-8210| volume = 16| issue = 6| pages = 873\u20135| last1 = Kalra| first1 = Sanjay| last2 = Kulshreshtha| first2 = Bindu| last3 = Unnikrishnan| first3 = Ambika Gopalakrishnan| title = We care for intersex: For Pinky, for Santhi, and for Anamika| journal = Indian Journal of Endocrinology and Metabolism|date = 2012}}</ref> Middle-distance runner [[Santhi Soundarajan]], who won the silver medal in [[800 metres|800 m]]  at the [[2006 Asian Games]] in [[Doha]], [[Qatar]], was stripped of her medal,<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2006/12/18/asia/AS_SPT_ATH_India_Medalist_Challenged.php| title=Indian silver medalist female runner at Asian Games fails gender test| date=18 December 2006|publisher=International Herald Tribune}}</ref> and later attempted suicide.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/oly/trackandfield/news/story?id=2701018 |title=Indian runner fails gender test, loses medal |website=Sports.espn.go.com |date=2006-12-18 |accessdate=2016-08-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1061218/asp/sports/story_7153292.asp | location=Calcutta, India | work=The Telegraph | title=Shanti fails Doha gender test | date=18 December 2006}}</ref> Track athlete [[Pinki Pramanik]] was accused by a female roommate of rape and later charged, gender tested and declared male, though she and other medical experts dispute these claims.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-11-14/athletics/35111300_1_pinki-pramanik-medical-experts-medical-report|title=Medical experts doubt Pinki Pramanik can rape|publisher=[[Times of India]]|date=14 November 2012|accessdate=15 November 2012}}</ref> Indian athlete [[Dutee Chand]] won a case against the [[IAAF]] in 2015, enabling women athletes with high testosterone levels to compete as women, on the basis that there is no clear evidence of performance benefits.<ref name=\"cas2015\">{{cite web| publisher = [[Court of Arbitration for Sport]]| last = Court of Arbitration for Sport| title = CAS 2014/A/3759 Dutee Chand v. Athletics Federation of India (AFI) & The International Association of Athletics Federations (IAAF)| date = July 2015| url = http://www.tas-cas.org/fileadmin/user_upload/award_internet.pdf| access-date = 3 February 2018| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20170704221029/http://www.tas-cas.org/fileadmin/user_upload/award_internet.pdf| archive-date = 4 July 2017| url-status = dead}}</ref> In 2016, some sports clinicians stated: \"One of the fundamental recommendations published almost 25 years ago ... that athletes born with a disorder of sex development and raised as females be allowed to compete as women remains appropriate\".<ref>{{Cite journal| doi = 10.1001/jama.2016.11850| pmid = 27490137| issn = 0098-7484| last1 = Genel M| last2 = Simpson J| last3 = de la Chapelle A| title = The olympic games and athletic sex assignment| journal = JAMA|  date = August 4, 2016| volume=316| issue = 13| pages = 1359\u20131360}}</ref>\n\n===Intersex people in Indian politics===\n[[Gopi Shankar Madurai]] was one of the youngest, and the first openly [[intersex]] and [[genderqueer]], candidate to run in an Indian election, contesting a seat in the [[2016 Tamil Nadu Legislative Assembly election]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-tamilnadu/intersex-person-to-contest-from-madurai-north/article8539185.ece|title=Intersex person to contest from Madurai North|date=30 April 2016|publisher=|newspaper=The Hindu}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/elections-2016/tamil-nadu-elections-2016/news/3rd-gender-gets-a-new-champion-in-Tamil-Nadu-poll-ring/articleshow/51935940.cms|title=3rd gender gets a new champion in Tamil Nadu poll ring \u2013 Times of India|publisher=}}</ref><ref name=\"bodahub\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bodahub.com/third-gender-genderqueer/|publisher=bodahub.com|title=Meet and Understand The First Genderqueer Candidate in Indian Politics|accessdate=2017-05-12|date=23 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190415151724/http://www.bodahub.com/third-gender-genderqueer/|archive-date=15 April 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"thenewsminute.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thenewsminute.com/article/intersex-person-contesting-tn-polls-ze-wants-change-your-mind-sexual-minorities-42103|title=This intersex person is contesting TN polls, 'ze' wants to change your mind on sexual minorities - The News Minute|date=24 April 2016|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Public opinion==\n{{Pie chart\n| thumb = right\n| caption = Should same-sex marriage be legal? (2016)<ref name=ILGA/>\n| label1 =Yes\n| value1 =35\n| color1 = green\n| label2 =Against\n| value2 =35\n| color2 = red\n| label3 =Don't know\n| value3 =30\n| color3 =lightgrey\n}}\n\nPublic opinion regarding LGBT rights in India is complex. According to a 2016 poll by the [[International Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual, Trans and Intersex Association]], 35% of Indian people were in favor of legalising same-sex marriage, with a further 35% opposed.<ref name=ILGA>{{cite web|title=ILGA/RIWI Global Attitudes Survey on LGBTI People|url=http://ilga.org/downloads/Ilga_Riwi_Attitudes_LGBTI_survey_Logo_personal_political.pdf|website=www.ilga.org|publisher=International Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual, Trans and Intersex Association|date=31 December 2016}}</ref> A survey by the [[Varkey Foundation]] found that support for same-sex marriage was higher among 18-21 year olds at 53%.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.economist.com/blogs/graphicdetail/2017/02/daily-chart-10?fsrc=scn/tw/te/bl/ed/youngpeopleandfreespeech | work=The Economist | title=Young people and free speech | date=15 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nAccording to a 2017 poll carried out by [[International Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual, Trans and Intersex Association|ILGA]], 58% of Indians agreed that gay, lesbian and bisexual people should enjoy the same rights as straight people, while 30% disagreed. Additionally, 59% agreed that they should be protected from workplace discrimination. 39% of Indians, however, said that people who are in same-sex relationships should be charged as criminals, while a plurality of 44% disagreed. As for transgender people, 66% agreed that they should have the same rights, 62% believed they should be protected from employment discrimination and 60% believed they should be allowed to change their legal gender.<ref>{{cite web |title=ILGA-RIWI Global attitudes survey |url=https://ilga.org/what-we-do/ilga-riwi-global-attitudes-survey/ |website=igla.org |publisher=The International Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual, Trans and Intersex Association |date=October 2017 |access-date=7 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180523101715/https://ilga.org/what-we-do/ilga-riwi-global-attitudes-survey/ |archive-date=23 May 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nAcceptance toward LGBT people is reportedly far higher in top government institutes, such as [[Indian Institutes of Technology|IIT]]s. According to a poll conducted at [[Indian Institute of Technology Delhi|IIT Delhi]] in 2015, 72% of respondents agreed that \"being homosexual is normal as being heterosexual\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/delhi/Gay-is-normal-for-72-in-IIT-D/articleshow/49428540.cms|title=Gay is 'normal' for 72% in IIT-D {{!}} Delhi News - Times of India|last=Oct 17|first=Shreya Roy Chowdhury {{!}} TNN {{!}} Updated|last2=2015|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2019-08-17|last3=Ist|first3=13:13}}</ref> Many IITs have their own LGBT clubs, namely \"Saathi\" (English: Friend) at [[IIT, Bombay|IIT Bombay]], \"[[Indradhanu: IIT Delhi|Indradhanu]]\" at IIT Delhi, \"Ambar\" at [[IIT KGP|IIT Kharagpur]], \"Unmukt\" at [[IITK |IIT Kanpur]] and more.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://homegrown.co.in/article/53174/8-schools-and-colleges-in-india-with-in-campus-lgbt-support-groups|title=8 Schools And Colleges In India With In-Campus LGBTQ Support Groups|last=Homegrown|website=homegrown.co.in|language=en|access-date=2019-08-17}}</ref>\n\nAccording to a 2019 survey, the Indian states/union territories which showed the highest acceptance of the LGBT community were [[Uttar Pradesh]] (36%), followed by [[Tamil Nadu]] (30%) and [[Delhi]] (30%). The states which showed the highest rejection to same-sex relationships were [[Mizoram]] (87%), followed by [[Nagaland]] (63%), [[Jammu and Kashmir]] (63%) and [[Kerala]] (58%). The states with the most undecided respondents were [[West Bengal]] (60%), followed by [[Assam]] (40%), [[Punjab]] (39%) and [[Tripura]] (37%).<ref name=\"indiatodaysurvey\">{{cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/diu/story/section-377-anniversary-same-sex-relationships-1596408-2019-09-06|title=Section 377 anniversary: Half of country still doesn't approve of same-sex relationships|work=India Today|date=6 September 2019|last=Rampal|first=Nikhil}}</ref> Acceptance of same-sex relationships was highest in the Hindu community. Around 22% of Hindus, while only 13% of Muslims and Christians, expressed acceptance of same-sex relationships. Opposition was highest among Christian respondents (70%), followed by Muslims (50%) and both Hindus and Sikhs at 40%.<ref name=\"indiatodaysurvey\" />\n\n==Notable Indian LGBTI rights activists==\n[[File:Painting of Manvendra Singh Gohil.JPG|thumb|upright|Since coming out in 2006, Prince [[Manvendra Singh Gohil]] (pictured), heir of the [[Maharaja]] of [[Rajpipla]], has worked on reducing HIV/AIDS infections and homelessness among LGBT youth.]]\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n! S. No.!! Name !! Details\n|-\n|1||Anjali Ameer||Malayalam film actress\n|-\n|2||[[Nakshatra Bagwe]]|| Award-winning filmmaker, actor, and India's first gay brand ambassador\n|-\n|3||[[Manabi Bandyopadhyay]]|| India's first openly transgender college principal and first transgender person to hold a PhD\n|-\n|4|| [[Vinay Chandran]]|| Gay and human rights activist\n|-\n|5|| [[Bobby Darling]]|| Transgender actress and vocal supporter of LGBT rights\n|-\n|6||[[Tista Das]]|| Transgender activist \n|-\n|7||[[Sushant Divgikar]] || [[Mr Gay India|Mr. India Gay]] 2014\n|-\n|8||[[Pablo Ganguli]]|| Cultural entrepreneur, artist, director and impresario\n|-\n|9||[[Rituparno Ghosh]]|| Popular filmmaker, winner of 11 Indian National Film Awards\n|-\n|10||[[Anjali Gopalan]]|| Human rights activist \n|-\n|11||[[Andrew Harvey (religious writer)|Andrew Harvey]]|| Author, religious scholar and teacher of mystic traditions\n|-\n|12|| [[Harish Iyer]]|| Activist, columnist and blogger\n|-\n|13||[[Celina Jaitley ]]|| [[Femina Miss India|Miss India 2001]]\n|-\n|14||[[Firdaus Kanga]]|| Writer and actor\n|-\n|15||[[Karpaga]]|| First transgender person in India to perform a leading role in a mainstream movie\n|-\n|16||[[Saleem Kidwai]]|| Writer\n|-\n|17||[[Agniva Lahiri]] || Social activist (PLUS Kolkata)\n|-\n|18||Nolan Lewis || [[Mr Gay India|Mr. India Gay]] 2013\n|-\n|19||[[Leena Manimekalai]]|| Poet, writer and film maker\n|-\n|20||[[Shabnam Mausi]]|| First openly transgender person to participate in Indian elections\n|-\n|21||[[Hoshang Merchant]]|| Teacher, poet and critic\n|-\n|22||[[Ismail Merchant]]|| Film producer and director\n|-\n|23||Raul Patil|| [[Mr Gay India|Mr. India Gay]] 2011\n|-\n|24||Zoltan Parag|| [[Mr Gay India|Mr. India Gay]] 2008\n|-\n|25||[[Onir]]|| Award-winning film director\n|-\n|26||[[Sridhar Rangayan]]|| Filmmaker, and founder and festival director of Kasish Mumbai International Queer Film Festival\n|-\n|27||[[R. Raj Rao]]|| Writer, professor of literature\n|-\n|28||[[A. Revathi]] || Actor, artist, writer and theater activist \n|-\n|29||[[Wendell Rodricks]]|| Fashion designer and choreographer \n|-\n|30||[[Ashok Row Kavi]]|| Founder of Humsafur Trust and LGBT activist\n|-\n|31||[[Aishwarya Rutuparna Pradhan]]|| First openly transgender civil servant and Odisha Financial Services officer \n|-\n|32||Nishit Saran|| Filmmaker and gay rights activist\n|-\n|33||Dr Mukul Kr Sarma|| LGBT activist, has written several pieces in the ''[[The Assam Tribune]]'' in an effort to raise awareness of LGBT people and mobilise the LGBT community in Assam\n|-\n|34||[[Vikram Seth]]|| Writer\n|-\n|35||[[Parmesh Shahani]]|| Author\n|-\n|36||[[Gopi Shankar Madurai]] || [[Genderqueer]] activist, recipient of the [[Commonwealth of Nations|Commonwealth]] Youth Worker Asia Finalist Award and founder of [[Srishti Madurai]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-tamilnadu/intersex-person-to-contest-from-madurai-north/article8539185.ece|title=Intersex person to contest from Madurai North|date=30 April 2016|publisher=|newspaper=The Hindu|last1=Reporter|first1=Staff}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/elections-2016/tamil-nadu-elections-2016/news/3rd-gender-gets-a-new-champion-in-Tamil-Nadu-poll-ring/articleshow/51935940.cms|title=3rd gender gets a new champion in Tamil Nadu poll ring - Times of India|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/Intersex-candidate-alleges-harassment/articleshow/52197962.cms|title=Intersex candidate alleges harassment - Times of India|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenewsminute.com/article/intersex-person-contesting-tn-polls-ze-wants-change-your-mind-sexual-minorities-42103|title=This intersex person is contesting TN polls, 'ze' wants to change your mind on sexual minorities|date=24 April 2016|publisher=}}</ref>\n|-\n|37||[[Parvez Sharma]]|| Writer and documentary filmmaker\n|-\n|38||[[Manvendra Singh Gohil]]|| Hereditary Prince of Rajpipla\n|-\n|39||[[Ramchandra Siras]]|| Linguist and author\n|-\n|40||[[Living Smile Vidya]] || Actor, artist, writer, and theater activist \n|-\n|41||[[Kalki Subramaniam]]|| Transgender activist, actor, artist, writer and founder of [[Sahodari Foundation]]\n|-\n|42||[[Manil Suri]]|| Indian-American mathematician and writer\n|-\n|43||[[S. Swapna]]|| First transwoman to clear [[Tamil Nadu Public Service Commission]] exam and first transgender I.A.S aspirant\n|-\n|44||[[Laxmi Narayan Tripathi]]|| Transgender activist\n|-\n|45||[[Ruth Vanita]]|| Writer and academician\n|-\n|46||[[Abhinav Vats]]|| Equal rights activist and India's first openly gay actor; featured in a music video from [[Euphoria (Indian band)|Euphoria]] in 1996 in a first ever gay character shown on Indian media\n|-\n|47||[[Rose Venkatesan]]|| First transgender TV host in India\n|-\n|48||[[Riyad Vinci Wadia]]|| Filmmaker\n|}\n\n== Summary table ==\n{{LGBT rights summary\n| legality = [[File:Yes check.svg|15px|Yes]] (Since 2018)<br/> \n| equal_aoc = [[File:Yes check.svg|15px|Yes]] (Since 2018)<ref name=\"bbc\"/>\n| antidiscrimination = \n| antidiscrimination_employment = [[File: Yes check.svg|15px|Yes]]/[[File:X mark.svg|15px|No]] (Only extends to discrimination from the state or government bodies)\n| antidiscrimination_goods = [[File:Yes check.svg|15px|Yes]]\n| antidiscrimination_genderid = [[File:Yes check.svg|15px|Yes]]\n| antidiscrimination_other = [[File:Yes check.svg|15px|Yes]]/[[File:X mark.svg|15px|No]] (Only extends to discrimination from the state or government bodies)\n| hate crimes law including sexual orientation and gender identity = \n| hate speech law including sexual orientation and gender identity = \n| marriage = [[File:X mark.svg|15px|No]] (Proposed) \n| recognition = [[File:X mark.svg|15px|No]] (Proposed)\n| step_adoption = [[File:X mark.svg|15px|No]] (Proposed)\n| single_adoption = [[File:Yes check.svg|15px|Yes]]\n| joint_adoption = [[File:X mark.svg|15px|No]] (Proposed)\n| military_service = [[File:X mark.svg|15px|No]] (Pending)<ref name=\"military\">{{cite news |last1=Dutta |first1=Amrita |title=Indian Army is worried now that men can legally have sex with other men |url=https://theprint.in/security/indian-army-is-worried-now-that-men-can-legally-have-sex-with-other-men/113644|work=The Print |date=7 September 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"military1\">{{cite news |title=Parliament winter session: Bills seek ban on non-veg food at official events, rights to LGBT to serve in armed forces|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/nation/2018/dec/28/parliament-winter-session-bills-seek-ban-on-non-veg-food-at-official-events-rights-to-lgbt-to-serv-1917748.amp|work=The New Indian Express |date